<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTENDER PROVES NO MATCH FOR JONES
</HEADLINE>
   (n) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENSACOLA, Fla. _ Roy Jones Jr. did his civic dutyfor his
hometown crowd here at the Pensacola Civic Center on Saturday
night. Unfortunately it involved battering a police officer - an
overmatched 39-year-old New York City policeman named Richard
Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   Jones (39-1) stopped Frazier (8-4-1) at 2 minutes 59 seconds of
the second round, after crashing a left hook to Frazier's temple
and then catching him with a right blast as he headed for the
canvas. Frazier got up at the count of eight, but his legs were
unsteady. Referee Armando Garcia mercifully stopped it.
</P>
<P>
   In the co-featured bout of the evening Shane Mosley (31-0)
retained his International Boxing Federation lightweight
championship by stopping Golden Johnson (15-3-2) at 2:59 of the
seventh round. It was also a mismatch. In a 4-minute span between
the fifth and sixth round, Johnson didn't land a punch. He didn't
land a punch at all in the sixth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't very satisfying,'' Jones said of his stoppage of
Frazier. ``I'm sorry the fight got stopped early. But I don't stop
them. I just fight. I don't pick the guys. He was the No.1
contender. It's not my job to tell those people what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was referring to the World Boxing Council and the World
Boxing Association. He holds the light heavyweight titles for both
organizations and they were sanctioning this fight. It was a fight
that no one wanted to be associated with.
</P>
<P>
   ``This the kind of fight that the boxing organizations has
mandated,'' said Kery Davis, the director of programming for HBO,
which broadcast the bouts. ``The question is how does this guy
belong in the ring with Roy Jones? I'm sure he gave it his all. But
he had no business being in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier was the WBC mandatory opponent for Jones and the bout
was Exhibit A in what is wrong with the sanctioning organizations
of boxing. Frazier definitely didn't belong in the ring against
Jones, who is arguably the best boxer in the sport today, fighting
for a world title. But he was rated the No. 1 contender thanks in
large part to the diligence of his manager, Grant Phillips, and his
promoter, Don King.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier, who earned $350,000 for the fight, landed just four of
29 punches during the two rounds, according to CompuBox punch
statistics. Jones, who earned $3.6 million, landed 39 of 92
punches.
</P>
<P>
   Jones could be faced with another odorous match in his next bout
in order to satisfy the WBA title requirement. Although it
sanctioned the bout against Frazier, the WBA did not consider Jones
having satisfied its mandatory requirement. The WBA's No.1
contender is Dario Matteoni and the WBA may insist that Jones fight
Matteoni in order to keep the title.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Di Bella, senior vice president of programming for HBO and
TVKO, said the Frazier fight was forced on the cable network. Di
Bella said he is not inclined to broadcast another mismatch like
the Frazier bout. He said the network might be more inclined to put
up the money for a Jones-Reggie Johnson bout, even if that means
Jones would be stripped of the WBA title. Johnson holds the
International Boxing Federation light heavyweight championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``These boxing organizations are hurting the sport by pushing
for fights that are mismatches,'' Di Bella said. ``They're running
the risk that a fighter could get hurt in a bout where he is
overmatched.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
