<SLUG> BC-CHOIR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX BOYS CHOIR TO BE GETTING MAJOR NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH LAFAVE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Half a millennium of musical tradition meets 50 years of
innovation July 1, when Georg Stangelberger arrives from the Vienna
Boys Choir to become the next artistic director of the Phoenix Boys
Choir.
</P>
<P>
   Stangelberger, a Vienna Boys Choir conductor since 1986 and
currently its deputy artistic director, will replace Harvey Smith,
Phoenix Boys Choir artistic director since 1960. The Vienna Boys
Choir, the most prestigious name in the field, was founded in 1496.
The Phoenix Boys Choir is in the middle of its 50th anniversary
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am thrilled that the choir will be guided to the next level
by someone with the knowledge, experience and compassion of Georg
Stangelberger,'' said Smith, who will step down after a boys choir
tour of Australia and New Zealand this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Stangelberger's appointment is the third major change of Valley
artistic leadership in as many years. The Phoenix Symphony named
German-born Hermann Michael music director in 1997, and Arizona
Opera last year appointed Canadian David Speers general director.
</P>
<P>
   Stangelberger, 38, speaks fluent English as well as German and
French. The son of a diplomat, the Austrian native attended the
Vienna Musikhochschule where he studied conducting and piano. He
has conducted major scores by Bach, Beethoven, Brahms, Wagner and
Britten with the Vienna Boys Choir and as conductor of the church
choir of St. Paul, Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been with the Vienna Boys Choir for 13 years and for
me, personally, it is a time for change and for new impressions,''
Stangelberger said by phone from Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Boys Choir came highly recommended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two friends in Europe and many colleagues in America told me
of the fine reputation of the Phoenix Boys Choir and Harvey Smith.
When I came for my interview in December, I heard them and was
quite impressed with their volume and their pitch. Especially in
the Biltmore hotel, where they sang, the acoustics were not that
good, but they managed to stay in tune and that was quite an
achievement,'' Stangelberger said.
</P>
<P>
   Stangelberger said that during his December visit an event
happened that made him feel certain he was receiving special
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It snowed, just like in Austria. It was nice of Arizona to
make me feel at home with the snow,'' Stangelberger said with a
chuckle. ``But no more will be necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Stangelberger said his decision to leave the Vienna Boys Choir
had nothing to do with the recent, widely publicized resignation of
that choir's artistic director, Agnes Grossmann. Grossmann resigned
in November, objecting to what she said were emotional and physical
burdens put on the boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grossmann's complaints were with the board of directors, and a
couple of her points were ones I respect. But my decision to leave
was made long before that. I have been in touch with Phoenix since
last spring,'' Stangelberger said.
</P>
<P>
   Stangelberger admitted that various artistic and administrative
differences between the two choirs will pose some challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest change for me has to do with different cultures. I
am very much looking forward to working with boys from different
backgrounds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, Vienna Boys Choir is a boarding school, where the boys
live together and rehearse every day. Phoenix Boys Choir is not a
boarding school,'' requiring different rehearsal schedules and
practice techniques.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest single artistic difference, he says, is one of
sound:
</P>
<P>
   ``Vienna has been known throughout the years to have a
dark-bodied touch. There is a lot of chest voice, which is why we
have those profound altos here. Phoenix is a more elegant, lighter
sound. But the common thing between us is the most important, and
that is seeking the best quality in performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Stangelberger will relocate to Phoenix with his wife, Aurelia, a
musician and teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking forward to this very much. We have a lot of
travel guides,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
