<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6623 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-FALU-TRANSCRIPT-H     01-10 3790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FALU-TRANSCRIPT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Houston Waltrip star boasts undeniable talent but unbelievable
transcript &QL; 
 &QL; 
By DANNY ROBBINS &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOUSTON _ At the end of last summer, a handful of college
basketball coaches closely studied the transcript of Antonio Falu,
the point guard from Puerto Rico who had entered Waltrip High
School as a junior the previous fall and had helped the Rams win
the 1998 Class 4A state championship.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to find that Falu had the grades to match his game, which
turned heads during Waltrip's title run and in the summer
tournaments and camps that followed, the coaches were not
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   In a sport populated by marginal students and unstable
characters, Falu's transcript was the shorthand version of a
rousing success story, the kind any coach would quickly embrace.
</P>
<P>
   A rousing success story, that is, had it been true.
</P>
<P>
   An examination of Falu's background by the Chronicle reveals
that much of what has been presented as fact about the player,
including the transcript sent to college coaches in his name, is
fiction.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 18 months, Falu has gone from virtual obscurity as a
college basketball prospect to a spot among the upper echelon of
high school seniors.
</P>
<P>
   When he enrolled at Waltrip as a junior in the summer of 1997,
he was unknown even to those who immerse themselves in the minutiae
of college basketball recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, he was named the Chronicle's 1998-99 preseason
Player of the Year and was ranked 37th on The Sporting News' list
of the top 100 high school seniors in the nation. In November, he
signed with the University of Houston, one of three players in
Clyde Drexler's first recruiting class.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his past, Falu has described how, having
outgrown the basketball programs in Puerto Rico, he decided to move
to Houston to get the exposure he would need to obtain a college
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   That story is supported by his transcript. According to the
document, obtained recently by the Chronicle, Falu spent his ninth-
and 10th-grade years, 1995-96 and 1996-97, at a Puerto Rican
school, Defensores Academy, before entering Waltrip as a junior in
1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   But interviews and other documents show he has traveled a far
different path, one that took him to prep schools in Florida and
Virginia before his arrival in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   During much of 1995-96 and 1996-97, the years Falu purportedly
was in Puerto Rico as a ninth- and 10th-grader, he was in fact
enrolled at Florida Air Academy in Melbourne, Fla., and Oak Hill
Academy in Mouth of Wilson, Va.
</P>
<P>
   And interviews with the men who coached him at those schools
indicate that 1995-96 and 1996-97 were actually his 10th- and
11th-grade years.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Dunne, the former basketball coach and athletic director
at Florida Air Academy, said Falu was a sophomore when he attended
the school during the 1995-96 academic year.
</P>
<P>
   According to Steve Smith, the basketball coach and athletic
director at Oak Hill, Falu was a junior when he was enrolled at the
Virginia school during the 1996 fall semester.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario described by Dunne and Smith would mean that Falu
should have been classified as a senior when he entered Waltrip in
1997 and has been playing for the Rams as a senior this season
when, in fact, his high school eligibility ran out last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antonio Falu should be a freshman in college, unless he just
totally sat out a year or whatever,'' Dunne said.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes at Texas public high schools are subject to the
University Interscholastic League's so-called ``four-year'' rule.
Under the rule, a student's high school eligibility is limited to
four consecutive years, starting at the time the student enters the
ninth grade.
</P>
<P>
   The UIL grants waivers to give students additional years of high
school eligibility, usually as a result of illness or other
extenuating circumstances. Such a waiver was not sought by Falu,
according to Sam Harper, the UIL's waiver officer.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip coach Fred Smith declined to make Falu available for an
interview with the Chronicle last week. Smith said Houston
Independent School District policy required him to refer all
questions from the media to HISD press secretary Terry Abbott.
Citing the same policy, Smith also declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott said Falu was attending Defensores Academy when he sought
a transfer to Waltrip. He said a transcript was faxed to Waltrip
from Puerto Rico on July 26, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Falu transferred, Abbott said, his transcript showed
he had the credits to be classified as a junior academically.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott said he had no other information regarding Falu's
background or academic history.
</P>
<P>
   Under HISD guidelines, Waltrip would only have been required to
request a transcript from the last school Falu had attended.
</P>
<P>
   UIL athletic director Charles Breithaupt said a student found to
be competing improperly in a fifth year would be ruled ineligible.
He said such a ruling also could cause the student's school to
forfeit its wins from that season.
</P>
<P>
   Additional sanctions could be imposed on the school if there was
reason to believe coaches or administrators were aware of the
deception, he said.
</P>
<P>
   With Falu averaging 30 points a game, Waltrip has compiled a
12-5 record this season.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler, who returned to his alma mater as coach last year after
a 15-year NBA career, said he knew only that Falu had come to
Houston from Puerto Rico. He said he had no idea Falu had attended
Florida Air Academy or Oak Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Having seen Falu's transcript, Drexler said, he had no reason to
think the player had been anywhere other than Puerto Rico and
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the discrepancy caused him to be concerned about
bringing Falu into the UH program, Drexler said: ``I only want him
if his character is good. I consider this (job) to be a volunteer
position, and I don't need any headaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Four other NCAA Division I schools contacted by the Chronicle
acknowledged receiving an unofficial transcript for Falu that made
no mention of his having attended Florida Air Academy or Oak Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficial transcripts are used by college coaches and
administrators during the recruiting process to gauge whether
prospective student-athletes have done the kind of work that would
allow them to meet NCAA initial-eligibility standards. The NCAA
bases initial eligibility on a formula that includes a student's
grade-point average in certain high school ``core'' courses and
standardized-test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficial transcripts are typically faxed or mailed to colleges
by high school administrative personnel or coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, a student-athlete's initial eligibility must be
determined by the NCAA's initial-eligibility clearinghouse. Among
the information required by the clearinghouse is an official
transcript from each high school attended by the student-athlete.
To be considered official, a transcript must include a raised seal
and must be sent by mail directly from the student's high school.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bob Oliver, a director of membership services at
the NCAA, the clearinghouse must scrutinize a transcript from every
high school attended by a prospective student-athlete because
courses often vary from school to school and misinterpretation can
result when a transcript prepared by one school includes courses
from another.
</P>
<P>
   He said the clearinghouse would have no way of knowing what
schools a prospective student-athlete had previously attended
unless those schools were listed by the student-athlete on his
clearinghouse registration form or were identified on his final
transcript.
</P>
<P>
   An attempt to gain college eligibility for a prospective
student-athlete using a transcript that does not reflect the
student-athlete's true academic record could be considered academic
fraud, Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   If a prospective student-athlete were knowingly involved in such
a scheme, he said, the student-athlete could be cited by the NCAA
for unethical conduct, a finding that could result in the
student-athlete losing all or a portion of his college eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   When Falu first surfaced in Houston in 1997, his name had not
made it onto the radar of college basketball recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Falu played that summer for the Houston Jaguars, a
Nike-sponsored all-star team. Another Jaguars player at the time
was forward Cedric Taylor, then entering his senior year at
Waltrip. At the end of the summer, Falu joined Taylor at Waltrip.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Falu and the 6-7 Taylor, the Rams won the Class 4A state
championship _ the first state basketball title in 10 years for an
HISD team _ and finished the season 33-3. Falu averaged 22.1
points, 8.7 assists, 6.1 rebounds and 3.3 steals per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had not heard of him before then (last year),'' said David
Benezra, a Los Angeles-based college basketball recruiting analyst
who publishes a newsletter on the subject, Recruiting USA. ``Then,
all of a sudden, boom, it was just out there how good this kid
was.''
</P>
<P>
   By playing well last season and in tournaments and camps last
summer, Benezra said, Falu was able to enter the current season
with the kind of reputation that would make college coaches take a
closer look.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (recruiting) is a very insecure process if a kid doesn't
have a rep going already,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Falu made a verbal commitment to attend the University of
Alabama last January, but switched to UH in August following the
dismissal of David Hobbs as Alabama's head coach and UH's hiring of
Drexler.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his commitment to UH, Falu continued to solicit interest
from other schools _ including Louisville, Oregon State and Florida
International University _ before signing with the Cougars during
the November signing period.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Eaves, the Louisville assistant coach who recruited Falu,
said he first encountered Falu during a scouting trip to the
Caribbean for the New Jersey Nets in the mid-'90s and found a
``little bitty skinny kid'' who desperately wanted to leave Puerto
Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he was trying to go to school somewhere in the
States,'' Eaves said.
</P>
<P>
   Eaves said he was surprised to find Falu in Houston last spring.
Checking on Falu's background, he said, he learned from Smith, the
Waltrip coach, that Falu had been involved in some way with Oak
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I started recruiting him, I asked about where he'd been,
what he'd been doing,'' Eaves said. ``The coach (Smith) said, `I
think he was going to do something with Oak Hill, didn't do it,
came down here, played AAU (summer basketball), and I ended up
getting him.'''
</P>
<P>
   Eaves said he had no idea Falu had been at Oak Hill for an
entire semester. Told that Falu had also spent a season at Florida
Air Academy, Eaves expressed shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``No! I never heard that,'' he said. ``That's a new one on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Ramos, an assistant coach at Florida International, said
Falu's connection to Oak Hill had come up in conversations with
other coaches.
</P>
<P>
   He said the fact that Oak Hill did not appear on Falu's
transcript was one of several issues that raised questions about
the player and caused Florida International, a Sun Belt Conference
school located in Miami, to lose interest in recruiting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got in there (recruiting Falu) because we need a guy like
him desperately,'' he said. ``But once you get in there and really
research everything, sometimes it's really not worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that Falu had attended Florida Air Academy as well, Ramos
said: ``Oh, I didn't know that.''
</P>
<P>
   In two separate interviews with Chronicle reporters last fall,
Falu gave varying accounts of why he moved to Houston and what his
living arrangements were. In both interviews, he volunteered no
information about his past other than the fact he had grown up in
Puerto Rico and had played basketball there.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the interviews, he said he came to Houston to play for
the Houston Jaguars on the recommendation of Taylor and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called me to play on their AAU team,'' he said. ``I guess
they heard I was scoring 35 points a night (in Puerto Rico). Cedric
said, `Why don't you play here (for the Jaguars) and you could play
at Waltrip?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for a higher level. Everybody in Puerto Rico
said I could play at a higher level, even the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Falu said he lived with an uncle during his first year in
Houston and that his mother remained in Puerto Rico until she moved
to Houston last summer.
</P>
<P>
   In the other interview, he said he came to Houston initially to
live with an aunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``She (his aunt) told me, `Come here, stay for a week. If you
like it, we'll find you an AAU team or something like that,''' he
said. ``So they told me to play with the Jaguars.''
</P>
<P>
   In that interview, he indicated his mother lives in Puerto Rico
but had visited him twice.
</P>
<P>
   Asked during the interview if he had played high school
basketball in Puerto Rico and on what level, he responded: ``Yeah,
I played my 11th, my 10th and 11th grade. In Puerto Rico, I played
my 10th grade, yeah. It was like I was scoring 50, 55 points (a
game). I said, `Damn, I don't see any colleges coming down here to
see me play,' so I had to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The organizer of the Houston Jaguars, Elaine Jones, said she
heard about Falu from Waltrip's Smith after the player had moved to
Houston. She said she knew little about Falu's background other
than he had spent some time at Oak Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antonio, from my understanding, was already in the United
States when he came here (Houston),'' she said. ``He went to Oak
Hill. We had nothing to do with that (his move to Houston). Because
of some misunderstandings or whatever, problems that he had there
(Oak Hill), he decided to move.''
</P>
<P>
   The copy of Falu's transcript obtained by the Chronicle shows he
was in ninth grade during the 1995-96 academic year at Defensores
Academy, a school in Bayamon, Puerto Rico; 10th grade in 1996-97 at
the same Puerto Rican school, and 11th grade at Waltrip in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, however, Falu's academic career has followed a more
circuitous route.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Dunne, the former Florida Air Academy coach and athletic
director, was emphatic in saying Falu spent all but the final month
of the 1995-96 academic year at the school as a 10th-grader.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should see Florida Air Academy (on Falu's transcript) as
the 10th grade,'' he said, ``unless the transcript was altered.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunne, who spent five years at Florida Air Academy before
becoming headmaster at a private elementary school near Orlando
last year, said he is certain 1995-96 was Falu's sophomore year
because the player had spent the previous year at a Puerto Rican
school, Bayamon Military Academy, as a ninth-grader.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be frank with you, if it had been possible for him to have
been a freshman at our school, I'm sure he would have been placed
as a freshman at our school, because of the language difference and
all that,'' he said. ``But he had a transcript that said he was a
freshman at Bayamon Military, and so he was placed as a sophomore
(at Florida Air Academy).''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1995-96 edition of the Florida Air Academy yearbook, the
Falcon, Falu's photograph appears with the Class of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A private boarding school with an enrollment of 400 on Florida's
east coast, Florida Air Academy attracts numerous students from
Puerto Rico and Caribbean countries.
</P>
<P>
   Dunne said Falu was among a group of Puerto Rican basketball and
baseball players who entered Florida Air Academy at roughly the
same time. One of the students in Falu's class, he said, was
Antonio Latimer, a forward from Puerto Rico who signed with DePaul
in November 1997 and currently is attending Independence (Kan.)
Community College.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Latimer, Florida Air Academy was 21-4 in 1995-96, winning
its district title and ending the season with a loss in the Class
4A regional quarterfinals. Falu filled a backup role on that team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had basically an eight-man rotation, and he was right there
in it,'' Dunne said. ``In our district championship game, he hit a
key 3(-pointer) with about two minutes to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Falu appeared in 14 games for Florida Air Academy during the
1995-96 season and averaged 8.6 points, according to box scores
published during that season in Florida Today, the major daily
newspaper in the Melbourne area.
</P>
<P>
   Dunne said he taught world history and had Falu in his class,
but such a course does not appear on Falu's transcript that was
sent to the colleges recruiting him.
</P>
<P>
   That transcript also shows no record of Falu having taken
aerospace science, a mandatory class each year at Florida Air
Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Dunne remembered Falu as a good student and highly motivated
player, almost fanatically so. He described Falu as being
``obsessed'' with Latimer, his more-publicized Puerto Rican
teammate, and unable to accept the fact Latimer had a bigger role
on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Dunne said Falu, upset over his lack of playing time and other
issues, left Florida Air Academy with a month or so remaining in
the 1996 spring semester and did not return.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's from a family situation where the father isn't around,''
Dunne said. ``I don't know what happened, but he was very driven to
succeed and make a good life for his mother and show his father.
Anybody who stood in his way be damned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would stay until you turned the lights out in the gym. He
would go into the weight room. He was always asking, `Can I take
(diet) supplements? What can I do to get stronger?' I'd say, `Falu,
with your body type, you're just never going to be a big, bulky
guy.' If I had told him, `Eat three dozen raw eggs every day,' he
would have done it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But his whole thing is very individualized _ to make himself
better. His whole thing is for himself, and I think the team is
kind of secondary. He and I had more than a few confrontations.''
</P>
<P>
   The following fall, the beginning of the 1996-97 school year,
Falu moved on to Oak Hill.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny prep school of 140 students in southwest Virginia, Oak
Hill is nationally known as a sort of finishing school for elite
high school basketball players. Its list of graduates reads like a
Who's Who of college and NBA players, including Jerry Stackhouse,
the former North Carolina star now with the Detroit Pistons, and
Ron Mercer, the ex-Kentucky star currently with the Boston Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Smith, Oak Hill's basketball coach and athletic director,
said Falu was enrolled at the school for the 1996 fall semester and
was ``definitely'' a junior.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that semester should show up on Falu's transcript
``unless he, for some reason, didn't want it. He definitely
finished the semester. He definitely got credits.''
</P>
<P>
   Falu was included in the Oak Hill team picture taken before the
opening of the 1996-97 season. When the photo was published by two
local newspapers, the Galax (Va.) Gazette and The Declaration in
Independence, Va., he was identified as Tony Allende.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Falu was known as ``Tony'' Falu among Oak Hill
players and coaches but was identified as Antonio Falu Allende on
school records.
</P>
<P>
   Falu's name appears as Antonio Falu on his Waltrip transcript.
The document lists his mother's name as Gracie Allende Andrades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here called him Tony _ Tony Falu,'' Smith said.
``But I thought Tony Allende was his real name.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Falu was held out of Oak Hill's games during the fall
of 1996 because of poor grades, but his playing time would have
been limited under any circumstances. Oak Hill's senior class that
season included two point guards then rated among the country's
premier recruits, William Avery and Jermaine Medley. Avery is now
starting as a sophomore at Duke; Medley is a sophomore at
Villanova.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Falu became discouraged and left Oak Hill at the
semester break.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was playing behind William Avery and Jermaine Medley,''
Smith said. ``He was like a third-string guard, so he wasn't going
to play much. That affected his attitude. He wasn't making good
grades. He wasn't going to wait his turn and wait for the next
year. So we just kind of parted ways at Christmas after the first
semester.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Smith, the most memorable thing about Falu's stay
at Oak Hill was the persistence he showed in getting there. While
most players are directed to the school by coaches or others with
ties to basketball, Smith said, Falu had no advocate other than
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I remember correctly, he just called me personally,'' Smith
said. ``I answered the phone, and it was this guy Antonio Falu. He
kept calling. I didn't really pursue it. He just kept calling and
calling, wanting to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he made a point of telling Falu about the players
already on the Oak Hill roster and the high cost of attending the
school, but those things didn't deter him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His whole thing was, `I've got to get out of Puerto Rico to
play Division I basketball,''' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he lost touch with Falu until last spring, when the
player called to say he would be attending the Nike All-America
Camp in July. The camp, held annually in Indianapolis, is a
recruiting showcase for high school players entering their senior
seasons or younger.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he was surprised by the call because he assumed Falu
had concluded his high school career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when he said he was going to Nike, I said, `Well,
you should have been a senior this year (1998), right?''' Smith
said, ``and he said something like, `Well, I repeated (a year),
because when I left Oak Hill, I didn't finish the year.'''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he got another surprise when, on the first day of the
camp, the team he was coaching played a team that included Falu.
The day after facing Smith's team, Falu, citing a family emergency,
left the camp.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Smith said he saw enough of Falu's game to be
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised he'd improved as much as he had,'' he said,
``because he really didn't work hard (at Oak Hill). Kids like that
usually don't get better, but he had definitely improved from when
I saw him last.''
</P>
<P>
   A less charitable opinion of Falu's progress was offered by
Kevin Dunne, the former Florida Air Academy coach.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly unsettling to Dunne was seeing Falu as the
Chronicle's preseason Player of the Year for the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he comes from a tough family situation,'' he said. ``He
had to cope with a lot of issues at our place, things going on with
his family back home and so forth. I know he has made some
sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you're good enough, you'll get a chance to play. You
make it. I just have a tough time with him being Player of the Year
when he should be a freshman in college.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
