u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WITNESS-SLAY-300&AMP;ADD-     01-10 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WITNESS-SLAY-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY, A WITNESS IN MURDER CASE, AND MOTHER SLAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Conn.) 
(nk) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An 8-year-old boy who was a witness in a pending murder case was
found shot to death on Friday, along with his mother, in their
Bridgeport, Conn., home, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, Leroy Browne Jr., and his mother, Karen Clarke, 30,
were found after Ms. Clarke's co-workers became concerned that she
had not shown up for work, said Lt. Mathew Cuminotto Jr. of the
Bridgeport police detective bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Leroy, whose nickname was B.J., was a third-grader at Read
School in Bridgeport. His mother sometimes brought him to her job
at a U-Haul dealer in Orange, Conn., where she had worked for six
years in the traffic department.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an outgoing kid,'' said Ann, a co-worker of Ms.
Clarke's who declined to give her last name.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved his mama,'' she said. ``She loved him.''
</P>
<P>
   Leroy was a witness in the state's case against Russell Peeler,
26, who is charged with murder in the May 29 killing of Rudolph
Snead Jr., 28, The Connecticut Post, citing unnamed law enforcement
officials, reported Saturday. The boy apparently had witnessed a
previous attempt by Peeler to kill Snead, the law enforcement
officials told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler is free on $900,000 bail, but Cuminotto said that the
police had not questioned him about the double homicide. ``At this
point he's not tied into this case,'' the lieutenant said of
Peeler.
</P>
<P>
   He added that there was no sign of a robbery or other
indications of a motive at the scene, and the police found no
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler's lawyer, Gary N. Mastronardi, told The Connecticut Post
that his client wears a security bracelet so his whereabouts can be
monitored daily. Neither Mastronardi nor the Fairfield County
state's attorney, which is prosecuting the case against Peeler,
could be reached for comment Saturday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Connecticut Post reported that Snead was shot eight times in
the legs, left arm and back while he was at a barber shop, and he
identified Peeler as his killer before he died at Bridgeport
Hospital. At the time of the slaying, Peeler was free while
awaiting trial on a charge of attempted murder in the previous
attack on Snead, the paper said. The paper did not explain the
circumstances of the first attack, or how Leroy had come to be a
witness in the case.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Clarke and Leroy might have been neighbors of Snead.
Until his death, Snead had lived on Garfield Avenue, the newspaper
said. Saturday, neighbors of Ms. Clarke said that she and her son
had recently moved to Earl Avenue from Garfield Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   A judge recently ordered prosecutors to turn over statements and
other information about the boy, including his current address, to
Mastronardi, according to the newspaper's account.
</P>
<P>
   Mastronardi told the newspaper that he had not shared any of
that information with his client, adding that Peeler had known the
boy's address for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was going to kill him, he had plenty of time to do it
before now,'' The Post quoted Mastronardi as saying.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Clarke, a reliable worker, did not show up at work on
Friday, and did not call, five colleagues became concerned, said
Ann, the co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   She said they called another U-Haul employee who knew Ms.
Clarke, and he went to her home on Earl Avenue. A two-family
cedar-shingled home on a short street in a working-class
neighborhood, it abuts a patch of woods.
</P>
<P>
   He found the door unlocked, and inside he found Ms. Clarke and
her son.
</P>
<P>
   Leroy was dead on the floor outside a bedroom, and his mother
was dead on the bedroom floor, Cuminotto said Saturday. Groceries
were spilled over the floor, suggesting they had just returned from
shopping, he said, adding that both had been shot at least once.
</P>
<P>
   The man called the police, Cuminotto said.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport, Connecticut's largest city, has had its share of
trouble with crime. With a population of 137,000, the city reported
35 murders in 1997 _ down significantly from a high of 63 in 1991,
yet still giving the city a homicide rate more than double that of
New York City, according to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the city put up 38 concrete barriers on its east side
to cut off access to notorious drug dealing areas. The barriers
were removed last year after community protests.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Clarke's multiracial, blue-collar neighborhood was
quiet, neighbors said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you'll hear a gunshot, but it will be off in the
Terrace,'' said Norman Williams, 73, a retired General Electric
employee who lives across the street from where the killings took
place. The Terrace is a nearby public housing project.
</P>
<P>
   Tatiana Bholanath, 17, who lives a few blocks away, said B.J.
was friends with her little sister and cousin. ``He was nice,'' she
said. ``They would ride bikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Clarke was a ``good person, trying hard,'' her co-worker Ann
said. ``She'll be sadly missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Ms. Clarke's white Honda Accord was still parked in
her driveway, next to a basketball hoop. Planted in the front yard
was a sign reading ``24 Hour Protection One Alarm Service'' with a
phone number: (800) GET-HELP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 0011EST &QL; 
