<DOCNO> NYT19990110.0005 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6626 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PENSIONS-AZR &LR;      01-10 2156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENSIONS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENSION FUNDS PUT $88 MILLION IN SPECULATIVE LAND DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Valley land speculators have borrowed millions of dollars from
government worker pension funds in deals that involve potentially
high risks.
</P>
<P>
   An ``Arizona Republic'' &UR; review of public records shows that
three retirement funds currently have more than $88 million
invested in real estate ventures.
</P>
<P>
   And at least two of the many loans involve developers who helped
wipe out Arizona thrifts a decade ago when the land market
nose-dived.
</P>
<P>
   All told, pension real estate deals account for just 2 percent
of a $5 billion pool, and there is no evidence that the retirement
plans are in financial danger. Managers, in fact, boast of the high
return on pension-fund investments.
</P>
<P>
   But loan records raise questions about a conflict of interest in
one transaction and resurrect a decade-old controversy about the
use of public trust money for land investments.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, one loan went to a developer who was indicted
nearly eight years ago for bribery and left a trail of bankrupt
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Another involves a notorious Buckeye project and a borrower
working with Wm. Robert Burns, whose record is littered with bad
debts, failed projects and lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The cash comes from more than 21,000 government workers,
retirees and employers who have contributed to the Public Safety
Personnel Retirement Fund, the Corrections Officer Retirement Plan
and the Elected Official Retirement Plan.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Cross, administrator for all three funds, said real estate
investments are carefully secured and have proved extremely
profitable over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the $88 million in property investments, Cross
added, ``These are very, very small amounts. . . . I don't think
they (retirees) should be concerned. I think we're taking the
proper precautions.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Lieberman, an attorney for the pensions, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's possible for us to lose money on these
deals,'' he said, adding that only one pension loan has gone into
default, and the retirement funds lost no money on that deal.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is not uncommon for retirement plans to invest in
real estate, financial analysts said vacant land deals are so risky
that most Arizona banks and credit unions no longer issue such
loans.
</P>
<P>
   Developers and politicians have created a furor in the past by
trying to get at the state's largest pension plan for similar
investments. But the $20 billion Arizona Retirement System, which
serves teachers and other government workers, shuns undeveloped
property deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raw land is a higher risk investment,'' explained LeRoy
Gilbertson, who oversees the fund.
</P>
<P>
   The pension loans in question net about 20 percent return on
real estate investments, compared with stock and bond portfolios,
which have a 15 percent annual average return.
</P>
<P>
   Investment experts say the hefty return rates on land deals
suggest that developers cannot get money elsewhere, either because
the deals are questionable or the borrowers are suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a $1.6 million loan issued to DMS Holding Co. Inc.,
which lists Donald M. Switzenberg as president, chief executive and
treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, a federal grand jury indicted Switzenberg for fraud and
conspiracy in connection with real estate loans from Sentinel
Savings &AMP; Loan Association. Switzenberg reputedly made payoffs to
officials at the thrift, which subsequently failed.
</P>
<P>
   A loan officer pleaded guilty. Sentinel's president died while
charges were pending. Federal court records on Switzenberg, who did
not return phone calls, were sealed in 1994 before a scheduled
sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hart, an attorney for Switzenberg, said that his client
pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor tax charge, and that the sentencing
was secret because Switzenberg agreed to cooperate with
authorities. The file was unsealed last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``'' In 1992, the Resolution Trust Corporation, a federal agency
created to clean up America's failed thrifts, sued Switzenberg and
others for fraud and racketeering in connection with loans from
Western Savings and Loan. That case was settled. Taxpayers lost an
estimated $2 billion when Western folded.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, Switzenberg has been listed as the principal in at
least five Arizona corporations or partnerships that filed for
bankruptcy protection. Among them was DMS Investment Group Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, DMS Holding was able to obtain more than $1
million from the retirement systems this year to finance 41
undeveloped acres at Cooper and Pecos roads in Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a shock to me,'' said Steve Barnes, president of
an association representing Maricopa County sheriff's deputies.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Gerberry, secretary treasurer of another deputies
association, praised Cross' management of pension funds but said
borrowers should be carefully scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me that money's being loaned to people whose
integrity is in question,'' Gerberry added. ``I'm retired. It's
important that the funds stay healthy.'' &QL; 
HOW IT WORKS
</P>
<P>
   Cross, pension fund administrator for 11 years, said he did not
know about Switzenberg's past when the loan was approved.
</P>
<P>
   But he insisted that all pension investments are safe because of
the way each deal is structured.
</P>
<P>
   Cross said that overall retirement assets exceed the amount
needed for pension payouts by 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, he added, the three retirement accounts have
performed among the top 4 percent of large, public pension plans
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've added a billion dollars to these funds,'' Cross said.
``I'm pretty proud of what we've done here.''
</P>
<P>
   Retirement system investment policies are set by a five-member
board of fund managers, with appointments by the governor and
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The board has capped real estate financing at 10 percent of the
total fund. To date, Cross said, 98 percent of the money is
invested in stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Cross approves loans based on recommendations from Bridge
Financial Services Inc., a private firm that has an exclusive
agreement with the pensions.
</P>
<P>
   Bridge finds borrowers, screens them, researches the collateral,
puts up 20 percent of the loan, and stands to be the first loser if
a default occurs.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical one-year loan, the retirement plans earn a 17
percent profit while Bridge gets a 23 percent return. That includes
an instant share of fees _ $212,800, for example _ on one loan of
$3.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all of the deals involve short-term financing of six
months to three years. Loan amounts are kept at least one-third
below the appraised value of property that serves as collateral.
</P>
<P>
   Cross said that strategy insulates the pension funds from
losses.
</P>
<P>
   But Arizona's land market has a roller-coaster history. Some
property values dropped by more than half during the real estate
crash a decade ago, failing in part due to dishonest borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Sargent, president of Bridge, said he is scrupulous in
checking out loan proposals and borrower backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``We're very careful on the deals we get into,'' Sargent added.
</P>
<P>
   As for Switzenberg's checkered past, he said, ``I think there's
another side to that story.''
</P>
<P>
   Sargent said dozens of legitimate developers and financial
institutions failed when Arizona real estate values collapsed in
the late 1980s. He said it is unfair to judge retirement-fund
investments based on that catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the era's key players continue doing land deals,
including Conley Wolfswinkel, who was convicted of felonies, and
Burns, who was sued for thrift fraud by the Resolution Trust Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Sargent said, Wolfswinkel and Burns have courted the
pension funds for cash, only to be denied. &QL; 
Burns again
</P>
<P>
   But there is a Burns connection to one loan.
</P>
<P>
   Records show nearly $3 million in retirement funds went to
Spurlock Land LLC, which is working with Burns to develop 13,000
acres along Sun Valley Parkway in Buckeye.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix attorney Michael Tiffany set up that loan and did the
paperwork. Tiffany represents Bridge Financial, the lender. He also
represents Spurlock Land, the borrower, and has an ownership
interest in the Sun Valley project.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he could be on both sides of the deal, Tiffany said,
``You've found things that would really cause you to be concerned
and suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Tiffany, the conflict was resolved when
representatives of Bridge Financial and Spurlock Land signed a
waiver.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurlocks hired a separate lawyer to handle the loan.
Tiffany said he was not obliged to inform retirement system
administrators of the conflict, although they put up most of the
money, because Bridge Financial was the official lender.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pension fund is not really involved in any loan,'' he
asserted. ``They're just purchasing an undivided interest. We don't
involve them in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross and Lieberman, who oversee the retirement fund, said they
were unaware of Tiffany's entanglement with the borrower.
</P>
<P>
   After discovering that loan papers contain a disclosure of
Tiffany's conflict, Lieberman said he simply forgot about it.
</P>
<P>
   Pension administrators also said they were unaware of Burns'
role in the Sun Valley project _ a ``joint effort'' with Spurlock
Land that includes shared planning fees and legal representation.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany said the relationship was irrelevant because Burns did
not obtain any pension money.  &QL; 
SUN VALLEY SAGA
</P>
<P>
   Burns was among the original developers of Sun Valley, one of
the biggest land boondoggles in recent Arizona history.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1980s, he acquired thousands of acres in a
controversial transaction with Canadian land speculator Huddie
Bell.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 investors poured money into the planned community.
When the deal crashed, they were left with about $83 million in
bond debts for construction of Sun Valley Parkway, dubbed the
``Road to Nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns, who declined to comment for this story, was among the
defendants in three RTC lawsuits seeking more than $1 billion. The
federal agency also issued a criminal referral in 1993 for fraud,
forgery, theft, false statements and money laundering. Prosecutors
declined to press charges.
</P>
<P>
   Several sources confirmed this month that attorneys for the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., which now pursues RTC debtors, are
continuing to investigate Burns in connection with millions of
dollars in unpaid judgments.
</P>
<P>
   Buckeye officials said Burns represents about 10,000 acres in
Sun Valley through an entity known as Phoenix Holdings. Burns has
previously denied control of that company. In November, a Maricopa
County Superior Court judge fined Burns $25,000 for lying under
oath about a trust that controls Phoenix Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, the pension fund lawyer, said, ``If we had known
Robert Burns was involved, we probably wouldn't have written that
loan.'' &QL; 
`REALLY BOTHERING ME'
</P>
<P>
   The labyrinth of connections goes deeper.
</P>
<P>
   Among the investors in Burns' development is SunChase Holdings
Inc., which has a 10 percent interest.
</P>
<P>
   SunChase is the major shareholder in New Mexico and Arizona Land
Co., which owns Bridge Financial, which set up the pension fund
loan.
</P>
<P>
   Sargent, Bridge's president, said he was not familiar with
SunChase's involvement with Burns.
</P>
<P>
   William Pope, chief executive at SunChase, said he didn't know
that Bridge Financial had retirement loans to Spurlock land.
</P>
<P>
   Both men said the loans were issued before Bridge Financial
became linked with SunChase.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really bothering me,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Some of the real estate deals appear too complex to unravel
using public records.
</P>
<P>
   Among those: a $12.5 million loan issued last year for 6,530
acres of vacant land known as Lake Pleasant Heights.
</P>
<P>
   The Peoria property was acquired by a network of companies
involving Bell, the Canadian land speculator. Pension funds went to
Group Three Properties, represented by Noranda Properties Inc.
Collateral includes first and second liens and an ``unsecured
guarantee'' from Noranda Properties.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Torjhelm, who signed for the loan as president of Noranda
Properties, did not return phone calls. His financial statement
contains this warning:
</P>
<P>
   ``Prepared without audit. . . . Few of the assets are readily
convertible to cash and, therefore, under distressed sale
conditions there is no assurance that the asset values referenced
herein could be realized.''
</P>
<P>
   One month later, a loan of $3.8 million was issued with pension
funds to W.P. Properties LLC for 3,285 acres of vacant land near
Lake Pleasant. This deal also involved Noranda Properties. The
collateral includes a second lien and another unsecured guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Sargent declined to explain the borrower relationships or
details of the collateral. But everyone says they are confident the
loans are secure. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 0024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
