<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6627 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-AZR &LR;      01-10 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS FEELING WEIGHT OF HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nothing can prepare senators for the immense,
conflicting pressures they face in convening the first presidential
impeachment trial of their lifetimes.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just the weight of history on each of them.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't only their oath to render ``impartial justice.''
</P>
<P>
   And it isn't merely political pressure, although there is plenty
of that.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it is the combination of all of these powerful forces
that makes this moment almost unique in history and at the same
time so politically volatile.
</P>
<P>
   As they struggled to lay the ground rules for President
Clinton's trial last week, senators sensed that their collective
reputations were riding on how well they could reconcile these
forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an awful lot at stake as an institution,'' said Sen.
Fred Thompson, R-Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   And there may be no safe middle ground.
</P>
<P>
   How, for example, do Republicans balance what they consider
their constitutional duty to hold a complete trial against the
wishes of many Americans to get it all over with as quickly as
possible? How do lawmakers keep their objectivity in judging a
president whom many of the Republicans have scorned and many of the
Democrats have reflexively defended?
</P>
<P>
   The House has approved two articles of impeachment accusing
Clinton of perjury and obstruction of justice in connection with
his concealing a sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky. Senators
were sworn in as jurors last week, and the trial is expected to get
under way on Thursday. A two-thirds Senate majority is required to
oust a president from office.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., considers the proceedings momentous
enough that he has begun keeping a daily diary ``for my
grandchildren.'' Excerpts will appear in ``The'' ``Arizona
Republic'' beginning today.
</P>
<P>
   The gravity of the occasion was evident Friday during a rare,
private meeting of all 100 senators ``that just dripped with
history,'' Kyl said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, to decide upon trial rules, was convened in the old
Senate chamber, where statesman Daniel Webster had once cried,
``Liberty and Union, now and forever, one and inseparable!''
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, noted that Webster
``had said from this desk that he spoke not as a New Englander, but
as an American,'' Kyl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat Leahy said that got Ted Kennedy all dewy-eyed,'' Kyl said.
Leahy is a Democrat from Vermont and Kennedy is a Massachusetts
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   To further illustrate the high stakes, Sen. Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va., told his colleagues during the meeting of the fate that
befell three greedy men in Geoffrey Chaucer's ``The Canterbury
Tales.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Pardoner's Tale,'' three men come upon a pot of gold
and must decide how to divide it. One decides to poison the others'
wine and keep the bounty for himself. Unaware of the plot, the
other two kill him and then drink the poisoned wine and die. ``O
gluttony, lechery and hazardry!'' Chaucer wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd hoped the cautionary tale would help Democrats and
Republicans unite in common purpose. More so than the House, the
Senate has a historic mandate to be civil. With passions running
high, one of the body's most daunting challenges during the trial
will simply be to keep its members cool-headed, as the framers of
the Constitution envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's House impeachment debate was marked by bitterness
and angry words from both sides. Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., said
the impeachment effort was characterized by ``unbridled hatred and
meanness.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the founding fathers believed the Senate would be
more detached because they face the voters every six years,
compared with every two years in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Many veteran senators, including Byrd, pride themselves on their
knowledge of _ and deference to _ Senate rules and precedents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took an oath to do impartial justice,'' Thompson said in an
interview after the swearing-in, ``and we all take that very
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the particular problems in this country has to do with
the way people view their government institutions,'' Thompson said.
``We have an opportunity to do something positive with regard to
that if we conduct ourselves in an appropriate manner.''
</P>
<P>
   But senators are not just jurors, they are politicians. And
political pressures are certain to blend with the constitutional
ones, complicating senators' decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a gut level, not very many Republicans in Congress really
like Bill Clinton as president very much,'' Kyl said. ``And, of
course, most Democrats in Congress, while they may not necessarily
like him much as a person, have an inclination to defend him as
their president because he supports what they're trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyl also described ``a second level of politics'' he expects to
be at play.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that drives the desire to have a trial that
ends very quickly, and doesn't become a circus, is, frankly, the
political realization that the American people don't want that,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sabato, a University of Virginia political scientist, says
many senators will be able to act and vote impartially _ but still
vote largely along party lines. That is because, he said, Democrats
and Republicans tend to see the world quite differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll give you an example,'' Sabato said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some (state) judges swear they are impartial, and they believe
that they are. There's just one problem: You can almost completely
distinguish between the decisions of Republican judges and
Democratic judges. They're reflecting their values.''
</P>
<P>
   One-third of senators, Kyl among them, are up for re-election in
2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
