<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 00:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6628 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-MAPLELEAFS     01-10 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-MAPLE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAPLE LEAFS TURN OUT LIGHTS ON BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
 LEAFS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Well, what did you expect?
</P>
<P>
   As long shots go, this one might have stacked up at 25 to 1, if
you're an optimist. Yes, we know. On any given night any team can
beat any other team, blah, blah, blah.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, with seven regular players out of their lineup,
including their best defenseman _ Ray Bourque _ and several others
battling the flu, the Bruins were vulnerable to a pretty
significant beating and that's just what they received Saturday
night as they fell to the Maple Leafs, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns said he had a two-tiered strategy heading into
Saturday night's contest, the final one for Boston in Maple Leaf
Gardens. One was to pray, the other to try to bore the Maple Leafs
into such a state of catatonia that the Bruins would be able to
sneak in a few goals.
</P>
<P>
   Good survival tactic perhaps, but the only team that appeared to
be sleeping in the early going was the Bruins, who surrendered
three goals on three shots in the first 10:17. When it ballooned to
4-0 at the 14-minute mark and the Leafs were getting one odd-man
rush after another, Burns pulled goalie Byron Dafoe in favor of Rob
Tallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know which was worse,'' said Dafoe, ``my save
percentage or my goals against, seven shots and four goals or four
goals in 10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston, which had its win streak snapped at three, hasn't had a
great deal of success here in recent years. The last win for the
Bruins in Toronto was Jan. 22, 1992. In their final six visits to
the old barn, they were 0-3-3.
</P>
<P>
   The first period was a big-time train wreck for the Bruins. Just
1:19 in, Todd Warriner, in the right circle, dished the puck down
to Derek King, who redirected it past Dafoe. Only 33 seconds later,
shot No. 2 became goal No. 2. With the Bruins running around in
their own end, Igor Korolev got the puck in front on a pass from
Garry Valk. Dafoe, trying to stop Valk, left a wide-open net and
Korolev had time to switch from forehand to backhand and easily pop
the puck home at 1:52. Burns called a timeout and the bleeding
stopped, momentarily.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Bruins squandered a two-on-one chance with Ken
Baumgartner missing the net wide, the Maple Leafs made it a
three-goal lead.
</P>
<P>
   Valk blocked a wrist shot by Hal Gill (who was on the ice for
all four goals during the barrage) and then took off up the ice. He
teed up a slapper that sailed under the glove of Dafoe. At 14
minutes even, Sergei Berezin made it a four-goal bulge on a goal
the Bruins disputed. With Dafoe well out of the net, a shot from
the point bounced off Berezin and then Dafoe and popped high in the
air, sailing over the goalie and into the net. The Bruins argued
that Berezin interfered with Dafoe and although there was
incidental contact, it occurred when Dafoe was several feet in
front of the crease with the puck already in flight.
</P>
<P>
   Tallas came in and Dafoe, who went into the game with three
straight wins and a stingy 1.00 goals against average in that span,
headed to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins fought the good fight and managed to chip away with
Shawn Bates scoring his third of the year at 15:33 to make it 4-1.
Bates, who was calling for the puck in the right circle, took a
pass from Steve Heinze and snapped a shot past Curtis Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins made a game of it in the middle period and Joseph was
nothing short of outstanding as the Leafs' defense completely
collapsed. Bruins rookie Andre Savage, playing only his second NHL
game, had four shots in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Boston outshot Toronto, 12-7, in the period and 25-14 in the
first 40 minutes and climbed to within two at 17:53 on Joe
Thornton's seventh of the season, on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   But a shorthanded strike by Mike Johnson at 7:48 of the third
and another Johnson tally on the power play at 14:14 proved to be
lights out. Boston's Kyle McLaren ended the scoring with a
power-play tally at 17:32 on assists from Dmitri Khristich and
Steve Heinze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew this Leafs team was going to come at us (after losing,
2-1, to the Bruins Thursday night). In this league, 2-0 in the
first five minutes of a game you can forget it,'' said Burns.
``It's really tough to come back. I thought we had a chance maybe
to come back at the end of the second period, in all honesty I
thought we could have been tied with them, but that first Johnson
goal, that cut us off at the knees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
