<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6629 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-JONES-FRAZIER-BOS     01-10 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JONES-FRAZIER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES FOUGHT LAW, AND WON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENSACOLA, Fla. _ HBO premiered a new documentary Saturday
night. It was called ``Anatomy of a Mismatch.''
</P>
<P>
   From the first bell to the final 10-count, Golden Johnson and
Ricky Frazier no more belonged in a boxing ring with ``Sugar''
Shane Mosley and Roy Jones than did Magic Johnson and Walt Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   Neither encounter was much to watch, but by far the worse was
Jones's battering of the 39-year-old New York City police officer
in less than two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier entered the ring at the Pensacola Civic Center in full
police garb, including service revolver. With him were a bevy of
cornermen wearing NYPD windbreakers. The only thing missing from
the station house look was a box of donuts.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier would have been wise to have kept the revolver with him
after the bell sounded because with it he might have gone the
distance with the World Boxing Council-World Boxing Association
light heavyweight champion. Without it he went to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   That first happened from two right hands and a sweeping left
hook late in the first round. None landed flush but none had to.
Frazier (18-4-1) got up but had no chance to survive this onslaught
unless he was taken into protective custody.
</P>
<P>
   That was not an option to him because the WBC had mandated this
fight after naming Frazier its No. 1 contender, so he had no choice
but to come out for the second round. Mercifully, it was his last.
</P>
<P>
   Jones (39-1, 33 knockouts) stalked Frazier and finally dropped
him with a left hand to the temple that sent him into a squat and a
following right that knocked him to the floor. When he got up,
Frazier was on wobbly legs and referee Armando Garcia stepped in
and made a citizen's arrest, ending the bout at 2:59 of the round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't very satisfying,'' Jones admitted. ``I don't pick
these guys. He was the No. 1 contender. It's not my job to tell
these people what to do. I just fight.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Mosley, unfortunately for Golden Johnson, who stayed
around a lot longer but with the same result when he went down for
the fourth time late in the seventh round and refused to rise until
referee Tommy Kimmons counted him out. Frankly, it was the smartest
thing he did all night.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley first dropped Johnson with two left hooks to the body in
the third round that sent him to his knees. When he got up, Mosley
methodically stalked him until, with only seconds left in the
round, the champion landed another perfect left to the ribs that
sent Johnson down again on one knee. It would become a familiar
position.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Johnson did what he could to fight back, but for
the most part Mosley was paying far too much attention to his
business, all at his challenger's expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised he fought back the way he did, but
this was a championship fight and he wanted the belt,'' Mosley
said. ``He was swinging with desperation shots. He let me know he
was trying to win. He's a durable, strong kid with a hard head.''
</P>
<P>
   Would that his ribs had been as hard because after carrying
Johnson for several more rounds, Mosley (31-0, 29) went back to
work in the seventh and hurt his challenger with a sweeping right
hook, followed by two more blistering punches that sent him down
for the third time.
</P>
<P>
   This was now becoming a habit but not something Johnson found
habit forming. Just a round earlier, Johnson (15-3-2) did not land
a single punch, according to CompuBox. Although this limited his
opportunity for victory, it also kept him upright for a round,
something that soon would not be the case again after a fierce
flurry by Mosley ended with a left to the body that sent Johnson to
one knee for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   As he stared directly at his cornermen, Johnson squatted as if
he were waiting to have a team picture taken with his basketball
buddies. His arms were across his knee as Kimmons counted him out,
his cornermen not encouraging him to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't injured at all,'' Johnson admitted. ``Those body
shots just took a toll.''
</P>
<P>
   Fights like Saturday night's do, too, on anyone who has to watch
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
