<HEADER>
A6630 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KYL-DIARY-AZR &LR;      01-10 2599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KYL-DIARY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KYL RECORDS HISTORY IN MAKING
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SEN. JON KYL 
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
Following are excerpts from Sen. Jon Kyl's personal diary of the
impeachment trial of President William Jefferson Clinton. Kyl, an
Arizona Republican, is keeping the diary for his grandchildren. The
excepts will appear in The Arizona Republic. 
 Tuesday, Jan. 5, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, an opportunity to discuss the impeachment case with
colleagues face to face. It's not been easy by phone over the
holidays; though I've been impressed that everyone with whom I've
spoken has obviously been giving the matter serious thought.
</P>
<P>
   First is a meeting with Majority Leader Trent Lott and eight
other Republican senators with extensive legal backgrounds.
Everyone has thought through some preliminary positions, and all
are thoughtfully presented. The Gorton-Lieberman proposal is
obviously dead, though elements of it may still be embodied in
procedural agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The key question is whether it is possible to reach any
bipartisan agreement with Democrats about the way the trial is to
be conducted. The Senate Rules on Impeachment control, but they are
fairly general and do not lay out a day-to-day process. So, for
example, will the Senate permit witnesses to be called? Will we
limit the time of the trial?
</P>
<P>
   When will it start? What procedural motions should we expect?
Etc.
</P>
<P>
   The leader (Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.) notes that the
House managers believe they need to call a few witnesses. All agree
that a reasonable request of the White House lawyers to call
witnesses in the president's defense could not be denied. Which, to
most, seems to answer the first question as well. But all agree the
Senate has the right to put constraints on the trial (number of
witnesses, time,
</P>
<P>
   etc.), and that we should try to keep it as short as possible,
consistent with fairness and justice. &QL; 
 &UR; Wednesday, Jan. 6, 1999
</P>
<P>
   The full GOP Senate Conference convenes at 9:30 a.m., recesses
at noon to swear in newly elected senators and reconvenes at 3 p.m.
Senate lawyers review the Constitutional provisions and applicable
rules. The special rules for impeachment do not spell out in detail
how to proceed, and most of the discussion centers on how to
establish procedures for completing the trial quickly, but with due
regard for the needs of the House and the president.
</P>
<P>
   The concern expressed by some is that Senate Democrats appear
unanimous in support of the president's position that there should
be no witnesses. Since the Senate (under the rules) has to vote to
hear each witness, it is obvious there could be a series of
party-line votes; and that could lead to charges that the process
is not bipartisan.
</P>
<P>
   Most strongly desire (for both institutional and political
reasons) to try to reach bipartisan consensus. But at what cost?
Undercutting the House's equally strong desire to present its case
as its managers deem necessary? Most hope for a middle ground _
limiting the witnesses and procedural motions to the bare minimum
through a bipartisan consensus. Even that may be impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma is how to prevent the ``process'' from becoming the
issue, while doing justice to the House, the president and the
Constitutional imperatives. While I totally agree that the time
issue is extremely important, I express the view that it is even
more important to do it right, even if it takes a few days longer.
History will remember what we did in impeachment, but not what we
do in the two weeks following the impeachment proceedings. I
conclude by saying that we should take the long view, not the
expedient.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, the leader will meet with three senior
members from both parties, the minority leader and the House
managers to try to work out a process _ at least for beginning the
trial. He presents a notional plan to us, with time frames and
dates certain for each aspect of the trial, ending around Feb. 5
unless witnesses are called. It would require the case to be
presented on the record, after which the Senate could decide
whether to call any witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that we will better know at that point whether
they are needed. It finesses the witness issue in order to get an
agreement. Some argue it sets up a presumption against having
witnesses. Probably. Others say it makes it more likely the
president's lawyers would not contest some facts (and maybe even
would stipulate to certain things) to avoid having witnesses
called.
</P>
<P>
   After extensive discussion and numerous suggestions, it is
agreed by most that the leader should refine the plan and present
it to the House leadership and thereafter to the Senate Democrats. &QL; 
 &UR; Thursday, Jan. 7, 1999
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment trial of President Clinton begins at 10 a.m.
with the escort of the House managers, led by Rep. Henry Hyde, to
the well of the Senate. With no fanfare, Hyde reads the two
impeachment counts approved by the House, the managers retire and
the Senate stands in recess until 1 p.m. for the administration of
the impeachment oaths. Though I have read both counts, I am struck
by the implications, especially of the second count, as I hear it
read.
</P>
<P>
   The severity of the charges and the seriousness of the event
linger after President Pro Tempore Strom Thurmond gavels us to
recess _ and most senators linger as well. In twos and threes, and
larger groups, Democrats and Republicans remain in the Senate
chamber, most discussing the subject that will consume the day _
how to proceed with the case.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats support the president's position that the House
managers should not be able to call any witnesses at the trial.
Most Republicans believe it would be unfair to both sides to
determine in advance that no witnesses can be called under any
circumstances. But the informal discussions reveal potential ways
to bridge the differences, and I leave optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Our hopes are dashed by a report of the Republican leader at our
11 a.m. conference. He reports that the Democratic leader
instructed the three Democratic members of the bipartisan team
(which had been working to devise a process for the trial) to cease
their participation; and that Sen. (Tom) Daschle had publicly said,
``All bets are off,'' unless the Republicans agree to preclude the
House from calling any witnesses. Yet, Lott and others perceive
that many rank-and-file Democrats may be willing to consider a
bipartisan agreement on how the trial should proceed, and the
majority leader instructs Senators (Phil) Gramm and (Slade) Gorton
(who asks me to join the effort) to draft a compromise proposal. We
draft until just before the Senate reconvenes at 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The basis for the proposal is an idea the leader had surfaced
yesterday, that ` `splits the baby'' by forcing the House to make
its case on the record (i.e. the public material the House had
considered) and then, if it still felt it necessary to call
witnesses, to make specific requests to the Senate, which would
then vote on each one requested. In the meantime, to satisfy one of
the Democrats' desires, the president's lawyers could move to
dismiss the case before any ruling on witnesses. (The president's
lawyers would be bound by the same rules in the presentation of
their case and requesting any witnesses.)
</P>
<P>
   The Chief Justice of the Supreme Court, William Rehnquist, is
escorted into the Senate chamber at 1:20 p.m. and immediately takes
his oath, after which we all rise and he administers the oath (to
do `` impartial'' justice) to the Senate as a group. Then the
formal signing of the impeachment register by each senator in turn.
When I return to my desk, I write a short note on my copy of the
Impeachment Resolution with the pen I used to sign the register.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:40 p.m., after the official Proclamation of Impeachment is
read by the Sergeant-at-Arms, the majority leader asks the chief
Justice to recess subject to the call of the chair (there being no
agreement yet on how to proceed).
</P>
<P>
   For the next hour I continue meetings with Lott, Gorton and
others refining our proposal.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:50 p.m. the GOP Conference reconvenes, with Lott announcing
that Daschle has rejected any agreement, any further negotiations
and even a proposed bipartisan conference _ that he proposed to
Lott that each side move its suggested procedure with a vote on
each (but no debate) at 5 p.m. Unfortunately, that would mean that
the very first act of the impeachment trial would be a partisan
vote. Bad!
</P>
<P>
   After description and discussion of the specifics of our
proposal,the Republican Conference asks Lott to try one more time
to get Daschle and the other Democrats to attend a bipartisan
conference.
</P>
<P>
   I join Gorton and Gramm reworking the proposal in the cloakroom
and do a TV interview.
</P>
<P>
   When the Conference reconvenes at 5:50 p.m. Lott announces
Daschle has agreed to meet, and the entire Senate will convene in
the old Senate chambers for a joint conference at 9:30 a.m. This
will be historic, since I am unaware of the two parties ever
meeting in joint conference; but, then, we are not just senators
now, we are also serving under a separate oath as impeachment
jurors.
</P>
<P>
   This news is leavened by a warning that some House managers have
indicated they intended to use the entire time allotted for the
making of their case, to argue for the calling of witnesses. That
would be a huge mistake _ as irresponsible as some White House
threats to delay the case for months if the House is allowed to
call any witnesses. There is obviously a need for cooler heads to
prevail, hopefully at tomorrow's conference, and later, when we
reconvene as the impeachment jury at 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the office for an HBO interview on my Internet gambling
legislation. I'm done at 7:45 p.m., and at 8 p.m. head for home for
dinner with two of our grandchildren, who quickly distract me from
today's momentous events. &QL; 
 &UR; Friday, Jan. 8, 1999
</P>
<P>
   There is an old saying that first impressions matter. If the
very first vote in the impeachment trial is partisan, it will not
only be hard to change public perception, but it will also be hard
to reverse the momentum of partisanship in the trial itself. So
today's meeting of all senators in a closed-door conference is
critical. It will determine for all of history whether Republicans
and Democrats could agree on a procedure for the conduct of the
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   The setting of the conference will help. It is the old Senate
chambers, steeped with history and tradition, some of which was
recalled in presentations this morning.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:50 a.m., Senator Lott calls on Danny Akaka, D-Hawaii, for
an opening prayer. Its simple message of love, by a colleague loved
by all, seems to get the conference started off on a positive note.
Lott and Daschle follow with gracious and constructive remarks. And
then a tour de force by the Senate's pre-eminent orator, Robert
Byrd, D-W.V., who emphasizes the importance of bipartisanship to
establish credibility for the proceedings and dignity for the
institution of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The speakers who follow each argue for either the Democratic
position that there should be no witnesses allowed in the trial or
the Republican position that the Senate should not preclude either
side from requesting witnesses (they still must each be approved by
majority vote under the Senate rules). While each speaker stresses
the desirability of working together (and one senses a
psychological tug toward a bipartisan solution), no practical
resolution is offered.
</P>
<P>
   And time is running out. If we cannot agree, the parties' two
resolutions will be voted on at 1 p.m., and the votes are likely to
be along mostly partisan lines. I can see the majority leader
getting very nervous as the last speaker, Phil Gramm, R-Texas,
speaks. But his is the home run in the bottom of the ninth!
</P>
<P>
   His argument is simple. Republicans, he says, are not holding
out for the possibility of witnesses at the urging of our House
Republican colleagues, as Democrats have thought, but, rather,
because of our view of the oath we took to do impartial justice.
(This is certainly my approach, and I'm glad someone is finally
saying it.) He concludes by stating the obvious: If the president
wanted to call some witnesses in his defense, every Senator would
agree to let him. Impartial justice requires that we accord the
other side the same right. Or, at least, that we not absolutely
deny the possibility that the House managers could call witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was the simple logic of Gramm's short statement or
his quotation of Daniel Webster (``I speak not as a New Englander
but as an American''), Ted Kennedy, D-Mass., was ready to meet
Gramm halfway. He urged that, while we may not have a plan to cover
all the bases, let's get to first base and second base together and
try to work out the rest of the trial as we go. In other words, get
the trial started as Republicans had suggested and leave the issue
of witnesses to be worked out under the Senate rules. Thus was born
the Gramm-Kennedy compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Trent Lott seized on the offer; and with almost no time to
spare,it was agreed that we would proceed in that bipartisan way.
Drafters were appointed to write the resolution we would vote on
after the trial commenced at 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   It was an incredible moment. Partisans being influenced by the
setting, history, each others' words and, I believe, a genuine
sense of duty to the Constitution and the institution. The Senate
is a bit like a boisterous family that has its internal fights; but
on historic occasions, can pull together in unity.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nothing is easy in the Senate. So, instead of a vote
at 1 p.m. (which might have allowed Caryll and me to get back to
Phoenix for the Governor's Ball), there turned out to be some
devils in the details; and the final language was not ready for a
vote until 4:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Leader Lott had asked a delegation of four of
us to communicate with the House managers to inform them of the
proposal and discuss how they intended to proceed so that we could
begin laying the groundwork for a final resolution of the witness
issue before we have to face it in a couple of weeks. We met with
Chairman Hyde and his managers team until about 4 p.m., all of us
conscious of the limitations imposed by our respective roles, but
concluding that the communication was constructive.
</P>
<P>
   The formal trial session with the chief justice seems almost
anti-climactic after the day's events. A roll call vote, all 100
senators voting ``aye'' on the proposal put forth by the Republican
and Democratic leaders. And then we stood in recess until next
week, when the first phases of the trial begin, perhaps with
motions on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After all of the media stories about confusion and partisanship,
I wonder how the media will play this bipartisan agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the many interviews in my office I observe that this
was not a ``win or loss'' for either side; but one side did give up
a partisan advantage it could have had. I give credit to Democrats
who could have forced partisan votes and made the Republican
majority look bad. That they did not is a good sign that the Senate
proceedings, at least for now, will be less partisan than the House
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   As I leave the office and reflect back on the week, I feel
better about the future of the country. But I am under no illusions
that anything will be easy about this trial. And, boy, do I have a
heavy briefcase of ``homework'' for the weekend. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
