<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DVD-BLAST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST DVD OFFERING A REAL BLAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The burgeoning digital versatile disc format has
reached another milestone, giving viewers a chance to feel as if
they're in midst of an atomic bomb test.
</P>
<P>
   Presuming they want to.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD version of ``Trinity and Beyond'' will go on sale next
month for $29.95, two years after the 95-minute video from Visual
Concept Engineering first hit store shelves. Goldhill Home Media
International, of Thousand Oaks in neighboring Ventura County, sold
a respectable 50,000 copies of the documentary; it will ship
between 2,500 and 5,000 copies of the DVD.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea of going to DVD was to make you feel as if you
were actually part of it and take it out of the realm of stock
footage,'' said Peter Kuran, producer and director of the
documentary on nuclear weapons development and testing that
occurred between 1945 and 1963.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one of the sequences, the shock wave goes by and knocks
over the trees,'' he said. ``They've made it feel like the wave
went past you by using all six speakers.''
</P>
<P>
   The DVD will carry a warning label about the ``extreme dynamic
range'' of some of the footage. That means playing ``Trinity and
Beyond'' at top volume could blow out speakers, an event that
occurred at AIX Media Group's Los Angeles studio during the
``authoring'' phase of production.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Kuran began collecting and restoring
declassified footage of U.S. nuclear tests, newsreels,
informational videos and rarely seen footage of Chinese and Russian
tests. The original video included narration by actor William
Shatner and music by the Moscow Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Kuran, whose Visual Concept Engineering, based in suburban
Slymar, also creates special effects, said he began working on the
DVD due to fan demand and his desire to make more material from the
days of the arms race available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been getting e-mail all along since `Trinity' came out
from people who wanted a laserdisc or DVD version,'' he said. ``We
went out to the Nevada test site and we found a lot of footage that
had been shot with two cameras together, so you get to see houses
blowing up in 3-D.''
</P>
<P>
   DVD, first introduced in March 1997, offers digital-quality
video and surround sound plus five hours of playback. Sales of DVD
players recently topped 1 million, and one analyst has forecast
that more than 19 million U.S. homes will own at least one DVD
player within five years.
</P>
<P>
   For the ``Trinity'' DVD, new features besides 3-D footage
include Dolby 5.1 surround sound, a slide show of photos from the
atomic testing era, Kuran's commentary, a database listing of U.S.
tests and motion graphics menus. The DVD version was made from a
new master print of the original.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Trinity' has done quite well considering there's no major
studio behind it,'' Kuran said. ``It's not going to be in the same
part of the store as `Titanic,' but at least it's in there. And the
DVD is a real improvement on the VHS because it maintains the
integrity of the original footage.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Goldman, president of Goldhill, said: `` `Trinity' is the
kind of project that we look for to differentiate ourselves in the
marketplace. What Peter Kuran and AIX have done is take very unique
historical footage, digitize and enhance it and take it to the next
level.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his next project, Kuran is working on ``Atomic
Journeys,'' focusing on tests where nearby residents weren't aware
of the effects of the explosions _ three of them in Alaska, two in
Mississippi and 900 in Nevada.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 0116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
