<HEADLINE>
CUNNINGHAM'S DUE FOR A PICK OR TWO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ They have one shot, a puncher's chance. And while
they're playing with house money now, their pockets are bulging
with the currency of belief.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, bless their optimism, are inhaling the
impossible, ignoring the scent of logic.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it smells like 45-20.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to test Aeneas (Williams), we're going to test the
rookie (Corey Chavous), we're going to test their safeties,`'
Minnesota Vikings receiver Cris Carter said. ``Because that's what
we do. We know we're going to score points.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Vikings didn't win 15 games by accident. They are
nearly unbeatable at home, an explosive team on turf, as nasty as
they are quick. They have nine Pro Bowlers, a fortress of an
offensive line, the most productive attack in the history of the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Reed is returning to the lineup, completing what could be
the best trio of receivers since the invention of goal posts. The
Metrodome is a noose of noise, a place where overmatched meets
overwhelmed. Add it all up, and you have what passes for bored
arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   A team and a town waiting to celebrate today's final score and
move on to a worthy opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember myself being a young Jake Plummer, where you just
go out, have fun and win games,'' Vikings quarterback Randall
Cunningham said. ``We're different. We have a rhythm, a basic style
that we stay with and don't change. We're kind of like a machine,
where you turn it on, it's got to go.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be as much of a veiled insult as you're going to find
entering this game. Not that the Vikings can't talk smack. They
just don't see the point.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, as the Cardinals arrived at their hotel, the lobby
was full of screaming fans, the kind that believe No. 16 can carry
a 16-point underdog into the winner's circle. In truth, the
Cardinals need an improbable trifecta: They need to dominate time
of possession, turn every opportunity into touchdowns and limit the
Vikings to field goals.
</P>
<P>
   A puncher's chance _ if they can stop the Vikings' offense
before it gets started. And it all starts with Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he was retired, cutting marble and granite for
kitchen counters. He is 35 years old, serene as a statue, convinced
that God really cares which team wins a football game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my selfish ways, I didn't want to play football anymore,''
Cunningham said. ``But I heard so many people ask when I was coming
back that I started thinking spiritually. I just went and prayed,
'God, if you're speaking through people to tell me to come back and
play football, I really need a clear sign. Have teams call me up.'
After I prayed that prayer, teams started calling. I took that as a
sign that God was answering my prayers. So that's what I did. I
accepted it.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk of reincarnation, Cunningham can be wildly
unpredictable. For all the MVP consideration, he is ultimately the
beneficiary of a stocked arsenal. He threw 14 touchdown passes
before his first pick. If the Cardinals' secondary can somehow
cloud his vision, keep red in the vicinity of purple, there is a
four-interception game lurking in his arm. He's due, and if it
happens today, the Cardinals have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   It would be wonderful if the Cardinals are game enough to make
it a game, unleashing the vacuum of pressure on the hosts. For as
sleek and skillful as the Vikings are, they are starting to get
bloated with self-infatuation.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they should. Maybe they are that good. And in all
probability, logic will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Mike Ditka's Chicago Bears upset the Redskins in
Washington. They caught the fever of belief, just like the
Cardinals. And when the San Francisco 49ers were listed as 20-point
favorites the following week, Ditka bristled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian army couldn't beat us by 20 points,'' Ditka said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Soviets couldn't, but the 49ers did. Twenty-three to
zip.
</P>
<P>
   The following season, the Bears won the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that. Because in the end, the most important thing
about today is where it leads tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bickley can be reache at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
