<HEADLINE>
BABY, IT'S COLD OUTSIDE, BUT THEY'LL PLAY INDOORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ What's the coldest you've ever been?
</P>
<P>
   For me, it had to be the Winter Olympics in Norway (holy fjords,
it was cjold) or any day in Minneapolis the week of Super Bowl
minus XXVI.
</P>
<P>
   As the plane descended on the eve of today's Cardinals-Vikings
game and the bleak winter scene appeared below, the memory of that
January week seven years ago came back to me with a shiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``How was your trip?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   I still can see his face.
</P>
<P>
   A robust-looking man with snowy hair and sparking blue eyes
identified himself as a member of the Super Bowl XXVI volunteer
task force. His task was to greet arriving visitors at the airport
and present them with a gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have a hand warmer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Winter smiled. ``Where you from?''
</P>
<P>
   When told it was Arizona, the greeter laughed. ``Here, have
another!'' He pressed a second mini-heater into my hand. ``Don't
mean to scare you,'' he said cheerfully.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals had to play outdoors today, they wouldn't stand
a chance. Most people think they don't anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesotans are hearty folk. They're accustomed to deep-freeze
weather. (Saturday's high hit one degree.) Their blood thick as
syrup, they can withstand temperatures most humans can't, and they
did, when the Vikings played their home games in old Metropolitan
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it wasn't cold,'' Carl Eller recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Eller played for the Vikings the last time the Cards came here
for a playoff game in 1974. The Cards lost, 30-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't cold because Bud Grant ``told'' me it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant was the Minnesota coach, and every season, as winter
approached, Bud told his team the dog story.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings, he said, were like a dog. As it gets colder, a
dog's coat grows longer. Grant told his players that by practicing
outdoors, regardless of how bitter the cold, their skin would
become thicker and their tolerance for the elements would increase.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota built the Metrodome in 1982. The Vikings scratched the
door, and barked with joy.
</P>
<P>
   The fact the Cardinals will play in a controlled climate (``I
hear they keep it pretty warm in there,'' Jake Plummer said) may be
the one positive going into the game they are expected to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Our lads don't have to play on a frozen field or worry whether
they brought the right type of shoes.
</P>
<P>
   They have to worry about Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
   Until kickoff, the Cardinals' primary objective will be to
survive. So far no one has suffered hypothermia or frostbite. As of
press time Jake had all his fingers. I counted.
</P>
<P>
   But it is c-c-old outside. The weather brought to mind another
Winter Olympics, in Calgary. The day of the opening ceremonies a
message flashed on the giant electronic board outside the stadium.
``Watch for frostbite warnings. White waxy skin, and a Smurf-like
appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometime between the singing of ``O Canada'' and the pigeon
release I felt myself shrinking and turning a bluish tint.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a stinger, eh?'' a bareheaded Canadian photographer said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a stinger, all right.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals would do well to follow the same routine Cotton
Fitzsimmons did when he coached the Suns and the team went to
Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   When the team plane landed, Cotton had a bus waiting on the
tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran from the plane to the bus,'' Fitzsimmons recalled. ``And
I always made sure the bus was heated.''
</P>
<P>
   When the bus arrived outside the hotel, Cotton placed his gloved
hands over his ears and sprinted to the lobby. ``About 15 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   When he got to his room, he turned up the thermostat. For dinner
he called room service. In the evening he watched TV. ``I saw every
movie the hotel had when I was there,'' Fitzsimmons said.
</P>
<P>
   When time came to go to the game, Cotton bundled up and raced
from the lobby to the bus, which drove directly into the Target
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there many times, but that's all I know about
Minnesota,'' Fitzsimmons said. ``It's a nice place, they tell
me.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
