<HEADLINE>
DITKA ISN'T A FAN OF THE METRODOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Chicago Bears Coach Mike Ditka used to refer to the
Metrodome in Minneapolis as the ``roller dome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So one year we get six boxes of in-line skates addressed to
Mike, and he's skating around our offices at Halas Hall,'' said
Cardinals defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis, who was linebackers
coach for the Bears before he joined Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin's
staff three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings got even. When the Bears took the field for pre-game
warm-ups, Vikings cheerleaders were wearing sunglasses, skates and
Jim McMahon headbands in honor of the Bears quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Ditka outdid himself before the game in Minnesota the next year
(1990). He called the place ``a barn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They got 40 huge plastic animals around the (Metrodome) field
and decorated the place with hay,'' McGinnis said. ``We come out of
our locker room and there's a plastic bull, sticking its (hind end)
in our face as we came out of the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ditka comes on the field and they're playing, Old MacDonald
Had a Farm. He gets into it. He's waving his finger over his head,
egging the fans on.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be calmer at the Metrodome today when the Cardinals
play the Vikings in an NFC second-round playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have played a playoff game in Minnesota once
before, in 1974 at frigid Metropolitan Stadium in Bloomington.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been much too cold for roller skating or farm
animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made sure we took everything,'' Cardinals trainer John
Omohundro said. ``We brought tennis shoes, Canadian broom ball
shoes and cleats.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quick turnaround &QL; 
 &QL; 
If the Cardinals lose today, they will have 24 hours to decide
which five players they will leave unprotected in next month's
expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the final four teams in the playoffs, each club has
to give its protected list to the Cleveland Browns by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals won't say who will be unprotected, but it's a good
bet that defensive tackle Jerry Drake, who is in jail because of
two driving-under-the-influence convictions, will be made
available.
</P>
<P>
   Other possibilities are cornerback Ty Howard and linebacker
Terry Irving.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, a native of Columbus, Ohio, hopes he's not on the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cardinals drafted me,'' said Howard, a 1997 third-round
pick. ``I would like nothing more than to play here. But I
understand it's a business. If it happens, I'll just make the best
of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a player from a team is picked, the team can pull back one
unprotected player. The most players any team can lose is two.
</P>
<P>
   Only one player of 10 or more years of experience can be exposed
and no kickers or punters can be left unprotected. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Food fest &QL; 
 &QL; 
Billionaire Paul Allen didn't just throw a lot of money at Coach
Mike Holmgren. He lured him away from the Green Bay Packers to the
Seattle Seahawks by serving him an extravagant feast last Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Allen served Holmgren, his wife, daughter and agent a
seven-course meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food was described in French, so I'm not sure what we had,
but it was good,'' Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   It helped when Allen, the third-richest man in America, offered
Holmgren an eight-year deal worth $40 million. He will make nearly
twice as much as as the next-highest paid coach in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the NBA lockout, I wasn't in midseason form with these
agents,'' said Seahawks President Bob Whitsitt, who also runs the
NBA's Portland Trail Blazers. ``I got worn down a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   They also gave Holmgren a lot of power and a fancy title _
executive vice president of football operations/general manager and
head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, my time and how I divide up my time is going to be
absolutely critical,'' Holmgren said. ``I think the key to that is
hiring good people around me. And we will do that. And then I have
to learn to delegate a little bit more because the time factor is
the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my No. 1 focus is and will always be coaching that
football team on Sunday. I think I'm pretty good at that, and the
other part, I will grow into.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Short memories &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the Packers replace Holmgren with former Philadelphia coach
Ray Rhodes, they will have to forget Rhodes' parting remarks from
Green Bay six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes resigned as the Packers' defensive coordinator because he
didn't think Green Bay was a good place for African-Americans to
live.
</P>
<P>
   Packers officials were furious with Rhodes' remarks. They were
trying to overcome that image in attracting free agents.
</P>
<P>
   If Rhodes doesn't get the job, Jacksonville defensive
coordinator Dick Jauron, another former Packers assistant, will be
a strong contender.
</P>
<P>
   Packers General Manager Ron Wolf said he would like to find
someone who's offense is compatible to the ``West Coast'' style
used by Holmgren, but he wouldn't rule out hiring a defensive
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``A defensive back coach has got to know offenses as much as
anybody,'' a Packers source said of Rhodes and Jauron.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren's offensive coordinator, Sherman Lewis, is not expected
to get much consideration. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Student of history &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carolina aggressively went after George Seifert and got him
before the other teams with coaching vacancies could make their
moves.
</P>
<P>
   The hiring has been endorsed by former Washington Redskins Coach
Joe Gibbs and Seifert's old boss in San Francisco, Bill Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really envy him,'' said Walsh, 67. ``I wish I was 10 years
younger. If I was, I'd try to out-interview George for the
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``George is one of the great coaches in the game today. His
won-loss record (108-35) is obviously superb. He's organized,
strong, demanding, fair, direct, honest and hard-working.''
</P>
<P>
   Seifert, who has the best winning percentage (.755) in NFL
history, is anxious to return to the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember the exact saying, but Teddy Roosevelt was
talking about competing and not competing and living in the gray
twilight that knows not victory or defeat,'' Seifert said. ``The
last couple of years, I've been living in a gray twilight. There's
an empty feeling.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jets quarterback Vinny Testaverde enters today's playoff game
against Jacksonville with an 0-6 record against the Jaguars.
``Unfortunately, no matter what happens in these playoffs, if Vinny
makes a mistake, that's all people are going to be talking about,''
former Giants quarterback Phil Simms said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the past 18 head-coaching hirings in the NFL, none has gone
to an African-American. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
