<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS_DIXON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIXON FINDS LIFE AT GUARD  
 EX-ASU DEFENDER BLOCKS FOR VIKINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not so much that it was surprising to hear Arizona
Cardinals defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis praising Minnesota
Vikings offensive right guard David Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   The shock was that McGinnis _ or any NFL coach, for that matter
_ even knows who David Dixon is today.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon is the former rugby player from New Zealand who showed up
at tiny Ricks College in Rexburg, Idaho, in 1988 and decided to
play football on a whim. He was so green, he says, teammates taught
him how to put the pads inside his pants.
</P>
<P>
   He transferred to Arizona State in 1990, started seven games as
a 6-foot-6, 296-pound defensive tackle for Cardinals secondary
coach Larry Marmie, then became a full-time starter as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   So what's this man doing starting at offensive guard for a team
that plays football at the highest level and owns the best 1998
record on the planet?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy who gets overlooked on that line,'' McGinnis said.
``Randall McDaniel and Todd Steussie (perennial All-Pros) get all
of the publicity, and rightly so, but David Dixon has been very,
very, very stable for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a load to move around in the middle. A load. I can say
nothing bad about David Dixon. You can't have an offense as good as
theirs is without a good line. It doesn't get a lot of credit
because they have so many big-name skilled players, but when you
sit down in a dark room and start cranking up the videotape, it's
very clear where it all starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercy, three ``verys'' and two ``loads.'' High praise for a man
who is as surprised to be where he is today as anyone. Dixon was
New England's ninth-round pick in the 1991 draft and was promptly
released in camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minnesota picked me up and put me on the other side of the
ball,'' said Dixon, now a svelte 352 pounds. ``Being new to the
game, it took me three years just to get everything down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get the playbook down and learn the system. I had to
learn how to use my feet properly, as well as all the techniques.
It's a totally different mind-set from playing defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, he's learned. Dixon made his first start against the
Cardinals last season in a 20-19 win at Sun Devil Stadium against
Eric Swann and since has started 28 consecutive games. Only ex-Sun
Devil McDaniel has a longer streak at 154 games. The Vikings are
31-10 (.756) in games that Dixon has started.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offense is harder to play than defense,'' Dixon said. ``You
have to maintain a sense of timing and direction to know where to
be at a certain time. On defense you react, and your assignment
moves and can change in a split second. You have to be much more
disciplined on offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I've become a starter, Randall has spent more time
helping me, showing me how and where to attack players. Of course
I'm surprised to be where I am now. I'm fortunate Minnesota had
patience and let me develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Marmie said he and his ASU staff gave brief thought to moving
Dixon to offense at ASU, but didn't because of his lack of football
background and brief period of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easier for him to learn defense than it was to learn
all the blocking schemes and such,'' Marmie said. ``But David
always ran well for a big man. He was big and powerful and we
played a gap-control, so it was easier for him to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   If Cardinals fans are banking on the Vikings to overlook the
upstart Cardinals, Dixon said they will be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the mind-set that we're going to have two hard games
to get where we want (Super Bowl),'' he said. ``Rashod Swinger is a
good, solid player. Their entire front four is solid all around.
They beat a good team to get to us, so why would we take them
lightly?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
