<HEADLINE>
DEFENDING THE STAGE  
 ASU TURNS NAIL BITER INTO ROUT AT WELLS FARGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona State found itself in a close, hard-fought basketball
game with Washington State at Wells Fargo Arena on Saturday, until
all sorts of things began to happen _ none of them good for the
visiting Cougars.
</P>
<P>
   A four-point ASU lead with 9:58 remaining ballooned to 16 over
the next six minutes. Then it really got crazy for Washington State
as the Sun Devils ended up winning, 91-63, to even their Pac-10
record at 2-2 heading into Thursday's home game against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   With 1:17 to go, Cougars guard Kab Kazadi was called for an
intentional foul against Bobby Lazor and was ejected. Washington
State Coach Kevin Eastman walked onto the court for an explanation
and got hit with technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after a timeout, Eastman said something else to the
officials, and was sent to the the principal _ literally. Official
Steve Wilson, the principal at Sahuaro High School in Tucson,
whistled Eastman for his second technical, which resulted in
Eastman's automatic ejection.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Eastman has been tossed as Cougars coach.
This is his fifth season.
</P>
<P>
   That much we know. As for anything else . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll talk about the game, because I guess the Pac-10 has a
rule about talking about the other stuff,'' Eastman said. ``And
believe me, I'd love to tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU (10-6) made 5 of the 6 free throws that resulted, and a
three-point basket by Alton Mason gave the Sun Devils essentially
an eight-point possession. That helped explain the lopsided result.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't the only reason. The Sun Devils overcame a
sluggish start _ ASU Coach Rob Evans had to call a 20-second
timeout four minutes into the game after the Cougars took an 8-2
lead _ and buckled down on defense. Washington State shot 34.5
percent for the game, the lowest by an ASU opponent in nearly three
years, making just 7 of 27 shots in the second half, and had 20
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cougars (7-7, 1-2) were without guard Jan-Michael
Thomas, who had eight three-point baskets and scored 34 points
Thursday against Arizona. Thomas became sick with a stomach virus
late Friday night and spent several hours at St. Luke's Hospital in
Tempe early Saturday morning. He was in no condition to play, and
watched the game from behind the bench, wearing warm-ups and a
hooded sweat shirt.
</P>
<P>
   That threw a hood over Washington State's outside game. Thomas
is one of the best long-range shooters in the league. He had three
three-pointers in a 19-second span against the Wildcats. Without
him, the Cougars were 1 of 13 from three-point range.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas also is a solid ballhandler, which would have helped
against ASU's pressure. Guard Blake Pengelly said his team missed
Thomas ``a lot, especially the way the game turned out. The guys on
the court were capable of shooting the ball, but tonight we weren't
hitting the open shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Eastman, who has one year remaining on his contract but is under
fire from fans and boosters, also lost forward Eddie Miller for a
key stretch in the second half. Miller, who finished with 12
points, apparently strained a groin muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ASU took advantage of all of the Cougars' problems, basically
with two big runs sparked by its defense. In the first half,
Washington State led, 22-15, but ASU scored 19 of the next 23
points to go up by eight. Then, in the second half, it was a 16-4
run.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said his team might have been cocky coming in, but that
didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our size kind of wore them down in the end, and I
think our pressure defense wore on them a little bit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lazy in the beginning of the game,'' said forward Mike
Batiste, who had 17 points and 14 rebounds. ``We weren't executing
or being patient.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time this year, ASU had five players score in
double figures. Lazor, whose torn jersey reflected how hard the
teams played, had 21 points. Guard Eddie House had 20, 18 in the
second half after shooting 1 for 7 in the first. Mason had 13
points, and freshman Kenny Crandall scored a season best 12. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
