r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ARIZONA_WASHINGTO     01-10 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA_WASHINGTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEFFERSON'S BASKET AT BUZZER SAVES WILDCATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON - If there someday is a Richard Jefferson highlight reel,
like the one run for Steve Kerr's jersey retirement ceremony on
Saturday, it can start with the basket that beat Washington at the
buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   There will be prettier ones for sure, but Jefferson again looked
like that third money guy the Wildcats need to support seniors
Jason Terry and A.J. Bramlett.
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied at 86, eighth-ranked Arizona (11-1, 3-1
Pac-10) went to the senior duo in the waning seconds with a high
give-and-go screen that backfired. Terry wound up taking a
desperate, off-balance three-point shot that fell a foot short.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson elevated for the ball, turned 180 degrees in the air
and released the winner with one-tenth of a second to go for an
88-86 victory that ran the McKale Center win streak to 24.
</P>
<P>
   This was heroics of a different variety for Jefferson. At Moon
Valley High School last year, he led his teammates in blowing teams
out or was the shooter by design in crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exciting, but anybody could've been there and taken
that shot,'' said Jefferson, who has been hounded to hit the
offensive glass because of his immense potential. ``I have taken a
few last-second shots, but nothing like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's pattern was familiar, though. The Wildcats have played
poorly in the first half of every Pac-10 game. This time, the
stumble was nearly too much as Washington (7-6, 0-3) took a 31-17
lead even though its go-to guy, 7-foot Todd MacCulloch, scored only
two points on a put back.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats flipped the energy switch and scrambled back to
trail, 47-45, at halftime, the third halftime deficit it has had in
four conference games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got young guys who don't know how to mentally
prepare to play,'' Arizona Coach Lute Olson said. ``Freshmen don't
understand how intense games are going to be. We have to shore up
what we're doing defensively. When we make it intense, we make it
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Bramlett never lacked defensive focus, asserting himself again
as a premier player guarding the post. MacCulloch, averaging 18
points a game, took five shots and two were follows. The last was a
bricked post shot with the game tied in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   Terry took care of the offensive end, dishing nine assists and
scoring a career-high 30 points with a McKale record 12 of 12 free
throw shooting. He got Arizona back into the game by hitting three
three-pointers to score 11 in the first half's final three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was Washington week for the Seattle native who
scored 27 Thursday against Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the game of my life every time I play against
them,'' Terry said.
</P>
<P>
   A 3{-minute dry spell still had Arizona trailing, 80-74, with
3:50 to play, but freshman Ruben Douglas hit a three-pointer and
Arizona hit nine of 10 free throws before Jefferson's game winner.
The Wildcats made 32 of 38 from the line on the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's unbelievable under the kind of pressure we were
facing,'' Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies got a team-high 19 points from freshman point guard
Senque Carey in his second start, but it was no moral victory for
Washington. Ranked 14th in the preseason, the Huskies are 0-3 in
the Pac-10, were swept in Arizona for the ninth time in 11 years
and still have not beaten a top-10 team in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're just tired of everything,'' said MacCulloch,
who played only 23 minutes because he was benched with two fouls in
the first half and three in the second. ``We're mostly tired of
being embarrassed. This weekend hurts a lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
