<HEADLINE>
KERR PROVIDES LAUGHS AT JERSEY RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Arizona's own ``Opie,'' fan favorite and star mid-1980s
guard Steve Kerr became the second Wildcats basketball player to
have his number (25) retired Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   So let's just get to the Kerr punch lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you would've told me my jersey would be hanging up here
when I first came, I would've been a little afraid,'' Kerr said in
a post-game ceremony at a packed McKale Center. ``I would've
thought the only way my jersey would be hanging from the rafters
was if I was still in it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Kerr, a guy remembered as much for rejuvenating the
program to a 1988 Final Four trip as he is for cracking that the
team was concerned about Coach Lute Olson's heroin problem at a
Final Four press teleconference.
</P>
<P>
   Olson gave the unrecruited kid his last scholarship in 1983.
Kerr said even Olson's wife, Bobbi, was the first to say he
couldn't play.
</P>
<P>
   But Kerr became a second-team All-America as a senior, when he
led the team to the Final Four averaging less than one turnover per
game in his first year at point guard. He was given the Most
Courageous Player national award for enduring reconstructive knee
surgery and the assassination of his father, Malcolm, an American
University president shot in the streets of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona waived a requirement that players had to be national
players of the year, like ceremony attendee Sean Elliott, to have
their number retired.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion even brought public address announcer Roger
Sedlmayr out of a two-year retirement for one last ``Steeeeeeeeeeve
Kerr.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The man has heart,'' Olson said of Kerr. ``It shows in
everything he did. He's one of the guys that epitomizes what
teamwork is about.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson tried jokes, but Kerr turned on the charm as always.
</P>
<P>
   On a highlight reel shown to the fans: ``After watching that, I
would've preferred my shorts be retired.''
</P>
<P>
   On his freshman year: ``I wasn't a very good basketball player.
. . . Please everybody don't disagree at once.''
</P>
<P>
   On Olson: ``I can call him Lute now. Me and Sean Elliott are the
only ones who can.''
</P>
<P>
   On a basketball career that now includes three NBA rings: ``I
feel like Forrest Gump.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 0225EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
