r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-L     01-10 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISET HELPS KINGS EARN 1-1 TIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ It was a night to commemorate Luc Robitaille's 500th
goal, but also a night for a different hero. This time, Stephane
Fiset was the key to the Kings' success, or at least to their
absence of failure.
</P>
<P>
   In goal for the first time in nearly a month after recovering
from his latest groin strain, Fiset made 32 saves, allowing the
Kings to steal a 1-1 tie with the Edmonton Oilers on Saturday night
before a Forum crowd of 14,936.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty good,'' Fiset said. ``I was surprised. I felt
like I didn't miss any games. The only thing I was nervous about
was my groin. It was on my mind the entire game.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Larry Robinson said: ``I thought he was steady. I
thought he really absorbed the puck well. He's worked hard and is
always prepared, so I didn't worry too much about him.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second overtime game of the week between the Oilers
and Kings, who had recorded a 4-3 victory four nights earlier in
Edmonton on a goal by Craig Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Blake scored for the Kings and Ryan Smyth scored for the
Oilers, who themselves got strong goaltending from Bob Essensa (29
saves). The strangest moment of the night came in the third period
when 5-foot-8 Kings winger Donald Audette fought 6-foot-2 Oilers
wing Bill Guerin to a draw. Both received fighting majors, and
Audette departed with an automatic game misconduct for not having
his jersey tied down.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (15-21-4) are 7-1-1 in their last nine games, extended
their unbeaten streak to six and were happy to escape with the tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost enough games we didn't deserve to lose,'' Robinson
said, ``so we'll take a point when we didn't deserve any better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings took an early lead on Blake's third goal this season,
20 fewer than he scored a year ago when he led NHL defensemen in
goal scoring and won the Norris Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Blake _ who missed 15 games earlier in the season with a broken
foot and another three when suspended for a slashing incident _
scored on an early power play, beating Essensa with a 35-foot
one-timer from the slot off a pass from Audette.
</P>
<P>
   But though the Kings held the lead, the Oilers (16-18-5)
controlled the flow of play. And 6:22 into the second period, the
Oilers got the opportunity they needed to even the score when Kings
center Jozef Stumpel received a double-minor penalty for
high-sticking Mike Grier.
</P>
<P>
   Less than one minute later, the Kings left Smyth alone in front
of their net, and Guerin passed him the puck. Fiset sprawled to
make the initial save, but Smyth slipped the rebound past him.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings escaped the second period without allowing another
goal, even surviving a shift in which the line of Ian Laperriere,
Matt Johnson and Eric Lacroix tried and failed several times to
clear the puck out of their zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' Robinson said. ``The guys out on that
shift are guys who want more ice time. We keep talking about
working on little things and those were little things. You have to
be able to work on all situations. You've got to be dependable, and
able to get the puck out of the zone. Otherwise, you don't get to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final moments of the second period, with the Kings
shorthanded, they got a scoring chance of their own, but a 20-foot
shot from the slot by Vladimir Tsyplakov deflected harmlessly off
the crossbar. The Oilers then created a similar chance, but Fiset
smothered Boris Mironov's 35-footer and didn't allow a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, it's like the puck sticks on you and doesn't come
out,'' Fiset said. ``Some other nights, the puck is all over the
place. I've been working on that in practice. When you work on
things in practice, good things happen in games.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiset made the best stop of the extra period, a glove save on
Todd Marchant with 1:16 to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
