<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS BENEFIT FROM EARLY TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fax machine starting humming at 2:55 p.m. Friday in the
Suns' offices, and by 3:01 p.m. General Manager Bryan Colangelo was
on the phone, where he'll spend much of his time for at least the
next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that surprised even its own team executives, the NBA
released clubs to begin contacting the agents for free-agent
players, negotiate contracts and talk about deals with other NBA
teams.
</P>
<P>
   There are some restrictions, including a ban on actually
contacting the players, but it cleared the way for teams to begin
putting their clubs together for the Jan. 18 start of training
camps.
</P>
<P>
   It's a huge break for the Suns, who have five players under
contract, hope to sign a major free agent and face a battle to keep
their key free agent, Antonio McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us a chance to do a lot of advance preparations, what
I would call a grace period, before the flood gates open,'' said
Colangelo, who would not comment on who he has contacted. ``It
allows us to get a feel for what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's especially beneficial to teams that are under the cap
(as the Suns are) and have a number of decisions to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the league &QL; 
 &QL; 
McDyess is one of the hottest properties on the free-agent market,
and rumors are running rampant about his intentions.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have expressed their desire to keep the 6-foot-9 power
forward, and they have the advantage of his Larry Bird exception to
give him a contract that begins at $9 million. The Suns can give
him a deal as long as seven years, while other clubs can give him
only six. And the Suns can give him larger raises than other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's definitely an advantage,'' said his agent, &UR; Tony Dutt.
</P>
<P>
   Houston reportedly has been the primary suitor for McDyess, and
the Rockets are much like the Suns in that they have some space
below the salary cap. The Rockets can clear about $10.5 million,
but to do it they would have to renounce the rights to Charles
Barkley or re-sign him to a minimum contract. &QL; 
 &QL; 
New direction? &QL; 
 &QL; 
There are indications around the league that the Rockets may go
hard for Chicago forward &UR; Scottie Pippen and hope that Pippen wants
out of the Bulls organization badly enough to take less from the
Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   There are also those in the Rockets organization that would
prefer the club pursue Wizards free-agent point guard Rod
Strickland.
</P>
<P>
   McDyess, who is close to Rockets forward &UR; Roy Rogers, who played
collegiately with him at Alabama, has indicated that Phoenix,
Houston, Denver and Chicago are the teams he will consider.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Chicago. If Michael Jordan returns, the Bulls won't have
money. If he doesn't, why go?
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the lowly Nuggets may wind up being the biggest
threat to the Suns' ability to keep McDyess, not Houston.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, McDyess played in Denver and liked living there.
His problems were with former coach/GM &UR; Allan Bristow, who has been
fired. He apparently has a good relationship with Dan Issel, who
left his job as a radio analyst to take the job of GM and coach.
</P>
<P>
   Second, McDyess fired his first agent, &UR; Arn Tellem, during the
off-season and hired Houston-based Dutt. That move fueled
speculation about Houston, but perhaps it should have added to the
Denver fire instead.
</P>
<P>
   One of Dutt's clients is guard Nick Van Exel of the Nuggets.
McDyess and Van Exel apparently have struck up a friendship this
off-season, and Van Exel joked to reporters in Houston that ``He's
going to Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   It may not be a joke, although Van Exel is in the final year of
his contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Nuggets also have plenty of money under the cap, and
LaPhonso Ellis is another friend of McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to get $9 million (the first year) wherever he
goes,'' Dutt said. ``The big things is that he's happy. He really
likes Phoenix. It's a tough process, no question.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
