<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_LAS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES BREAK TIES WITH VEGAS IN IHL 
</HEADLINE>
 VEGAS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Coyotes, winless in their past four games, have some serious
headaches in the minor leagues, too.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the team terminated its partial affiliation
agreement with the Las Vegas Thunder of the International Hockey
League with half the season still left to play.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, the Coyotes have been seething over the treatment and
public criticism that a few of their players and prospects have
been receiving from the Thunder coaching staff and management.
</P>
<P>
   Two players under contract with Phoenix, forwards Andrei
Vasilyev and J.F. Jomphe, recently were assigned elsewhere after
being vilified by Vegas Coach Bob Bourne and General Manager Bob
Strumm for supposed poor attitudes and lackluster work ethics.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past few weeks, we've worked to determine a route that
would work for both teams, and what we decided was that it was in
the best interest to terminate the affiliation for the year,'' said
Taylor Burke, the Coyotes assistant general manager.
</P>
<P>
   After signing a termination agreement Saturday morning, Burke
said two of the three remaining players in Las Vegas under contract
with the Coyotes were moved to other franchises in the IHL. Scott
Langkow, the No. 3 goalie in the organization, was loaned to the
Utah Grizzlies. Veteran Louie DeBrusk, a physical left wing, was
sent to the Long Beach Ice Dogs, where fellow Coyote Jocelyn
Lemieux resides.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran defenseman Michel Petit will also be moved elsewhere
once he recovers from a concussion and is cleared to play.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach Bourne and Strumm were unsuccessful Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said the unflattering comments were not the sole reason
the Coyotes decided to end their relationship with the IHL team
after 2{ seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not happy with the comments made (last week) by the
coach about J.F.,'' Burke said. ``But at the same time, it's not
like we're yanking all our players out of there because they came
out and said something about one of our players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at the overall picture here. We felt in order to
have an affiliation there, we needed our players part of a winning
environment and part of a healthy environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas is in last place in the IHL with a 9-23-5 record, 30
points behind first-place Chicago in the Western Conference. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
