<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-MCMANAMA-N-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBITAILLE REACHES MAGICAL 500 MARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congratulations to Luc Robitaille, who snared his 500th NHL goal
last week against Buffalo, thus becoming the 27th player to reach
the milestone, and just the sixth left winger to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a gangly kid whom everybody said probably wouldn't
make it in this league as the 171st overall pick in the 1984 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever didn't believe in me, well, screw them today,''
Robitaille said.
</P>
<P>
   The only left wingers with more goals than Lucky Luc: Bobby Hull
(610), John Bucyk (556), Michel Goulet (548), Frank Mahovlich (533)
and Dave Andreychuk (528).
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille, 32, already has 22 goals this season _ six more than
he finished with last year. He credits his turnaround to a
rededication to a fitness program this summer, in which he hauled
weight machines around with him and his family during a month-long
tour across the U.S. in a motor home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little embarrassing at some of the campgrounds,''
Robitaille said. ``People were coming in with their tents and they
were looking at me with this big motor home and my big squat rack
outside. A few people would come up to me. They thought it was some
kind of jack to lift the motor home. They didn't know what the heck
it was. It was kind of funny, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   His 500th goal wasn't funny. Not to rookie Pavel Rosa, who
assisted on the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my hero growing up,'' said Rosa, a native of the Czech
Republic. ``Sure, I was watching Wayne Gretzky and Jaromir Jagr,
but I had Luc's picture on the wall.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Conspiracy theory &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How bad is it in Chicago? So bad that now Blackhawks first-year
Coach Dirk Graham is pulling a Bobby Knight and charging that NHL
referees have it in for his team _ as if they were on the take.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be the same thing every game, either we're the
dirtiest team which ever has played the game or there's something
else going on,'' Graham said, among other things. ``I don't think
we're that dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, they are among the most-penalized teams in the league at
an average of about 24 minutes a game. Graham, though, barked
enough after recent losses that Bryan Lewis, the NHL's director of
officials, and Colin Campbell, the league's executive vice
president in charge of hockey operations, have personally checked
into the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are serious accusations,'' Campbell said. ``It's serious
to (the Blackhawks) and it's serious to the referees when they get
questioned. . . . I'm going to stand behind my officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, a former ref, seriously doubts Graham's speculation that
officials have something against Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for anyone who has that impression,'' he said.
``I can only address it as someone who wore a striped shirt for
over 10 years and did over 1,000 games on the ice. In all that
time, I've never heard any language from an official along the
lines of `Let's get them' or `Let's get any particular player.' '' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Stupid remark &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During a game last week against San Jose, New Jersey's Scott
Stevens allegedly told the Sharks' Brent Myhres, who recently
underwent treatment for alcohol abuse, to ``have another beer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit (Jeff) Friesen and I said, `Why don't you pick on
somebody bigger?' '' Myhres said. ``He came back with a comment on
alcohol. That's pretty classy when you've got your buddy two seats
down (Ken Daneyko) who has the same problem. But that's the
mentality of Scott Stevens. An idiot. What comes around goes
around. I think we play them one more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens didn't deny making the remark.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the heat of the battle, sometimes you say things you don't
want to,'' he said. ``Sometimes, you say things you regret.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Eight is enough &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Fred Brathwaite started in goal Friday night for the
Calgary Flames, he became the eighth different goalie to put on a
Flames jersey this season and the seventh one to actually dress for
a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody I've talked to in the past three or four days tells
me the same thing. Nobody's ever seen a situation like this,''
General Manager Al Coates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Flames, in order, have lost Ken Wregget (back injury), Tyler
Moss (groin), Jean-Sebastien Giguere (hamstring), and Andrei
Trefilov (hamstring).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you one thing,'' Coach Brian Sutter said. ``I've
stopped losing sleep over this.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a bright spot, though. Brathwaite pitched a 1-0
shutout over the league-leading Dallas Stars a day after being
signed off the Canadian national team.
</P>
<P>
   Any day now &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Expect the Vancouver Canucks to finally jettison themselves from
the Russian Rocket. Crybaby holdout Pavel Bure, sitting out despite
the guarantee of earning $8.5 million this season, will be dealt in
a major trade this week.
</P>
<P>
   Well, so says Canucks General Manager Brian Burke, who's lied
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not at any pull-the-trigger stage, but it's definitely
coming to a boil,'' Burke was quoted as saying Thursday. ``I don't
think it's unrealistic to think this might happen over the weekend
or early next week. There are concrete offers on the table for
players and draft picks.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Rangers, Los Angeles Kings and Florida Panthers
have all made offers to Burke for the former 76-goal scorer.
Chicago supposedly entered the talks late.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizard of Ozo &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, what do you know? The Colorado Avalanche wised up and
decided to end the nonsense involving unsigned defenseman Sandis
Ozolinsh. He agreed to a two-year deal worth $6.7 million _ $2.9
million this year and $3.8 million next year.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's pro-rated, Ozolinsh will earn $1.6 million this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem with that,'' Ozolinsh said. ``I didn't count
how much money I lost. I just thought this was the right thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozolinsh, who had been in Latvia since the summer, was looking
forward to making his debut this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in pretty good shape,'' he said. ``I played a lot of golf.
Hey, that's a sport. They show it on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can
be reached at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
