<HEADER>
A6674 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPT-TV-OLBERMANN-AZR &LR;      01-10 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPT-TV-OLBERMANN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIED PIPER OF PUNCH LINES  
 OLBERMANN LEADS SPORTSCASTING'S COMIC REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been almost 20 years since Keith Olbermann hit his head
on the subway _ insert your own punch line here _ and television
sports reporting hasn't been the same since.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a gag-filled ride from ESPN to MSNBC and now to Fox
Sports Net, where his presence could be the final piece of the
puzzle for the network in its bid to surpass ESPN in ratings and
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Olbermann, who started his Fox career with a three-day workweek,
which included a three-part series on the NBA lockout, begins his
regular Sunday-Thursday shift tonight. He will be seen from 11 p.m.
to midnight in the Phoenix market on Fox Sports Arizona, teamed
with Kevin Frazier. They follow Van Earl Wright and Chris Meyers,
another ESPN alum, giving Fox Sports Net a strong one-two punch.
</P>
<P>
   He came up with one of the best one-liners ever while at ESPN.
Talking about an injured player's status, he said, ``He's listed as
day to day _ but then, aren't we all?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's probably my most meaningful line,'' he said.
``It's both funny and meaningful. It's like when George Karl said
he never wanted to be on a non-stop plane.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he got tired of muttering another one of his signature
lines to himself: ``From way downtown . . . bang!''
</P>
<P>
   Olbermann played a big part in turning sportscasters nationwide
into would-be comics. A major difference is that Olbermann's humor
is not forced or corny. While at ESPN, he was one of America's
premier sports TV figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the style I have carries over well here, and I expect
it will,'' Olbermann said. ``Humor has become a staple with
everybody in the business now. What I will try to force are those
opportunities to be a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two elements here. With Dan Patrick (his partner on
ESPN's ``SportsCente''r), the humor sticks in your mind, and it was
replicated throughout ESPN, Fox and CNN/SI. But it can only be used
when it's there. You can reach about arm's length for a joke, and
if you go any further, you'll fall flat on your face. And I'm going
to try to do news analyses, story breaking and story chasing.''
</P>
<P>
   And with his three-part series, ```Who Shot the NBA?'' last
week, Olbermann proved adept in moving into other arenas.
</P>
<P>
   When Olbermann left ESPN in the summer of 1997, it was on good
terms. But when he MSNBC wanted to name his show ``The Big Show,''
which he and Patrick used, it caused some ripples.
</P>
<P>
   ``ESPN got very upset about it,'' Olbermann said. ``I thought it
was so small. They had actually tried to discourage Dan and I from
calling it that. All of a sudden, that hit me in a way I can't
rationally explain, and I made some negative comments, and that
didn't need to happen. But I did a radio commentary, and I
apologized for all the sour stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Olbermann found that the longer he stayed away from sports, the
more he missed it. It was Fox's aggressive style that lured
Olbermann back into sports. He said he sees a shift of power in the
industry, noting that when Fox says it wants to be competitive, it
means it wants to dominate an area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's evident they want to take this ballgame away from ESPN,''
he said. ``When I left ESPN, it was not an open question (on
dominant sports network) . . . It ain't that way anymore. My
responsibility is to make sure it stays that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Olbermann said the time came while he was at ESPN when he
realized the sports news shows on both networks were ``dead even.''
He said he realized that Fox's format of tying the sports reports
to a local event ``would eventually have to win.'' As an example,
he said when ``SportsCenter'' followed a Sunday night football
game, ratings would be five to six times higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
   The executive vice president for programming and production for
Fox Sports Net, Arthur Smith, called Olbermann ``the sports
television personality of the decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lewellan, vice president/media relations for Fox Sports
Net, said Olbermann had been on the Fox wish list for a long time.
He said Olbermann also would get the opportunity to work with some
of the other Fox talent as the network seeks the right chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Back to that subway thing. When Olbermann banged his head, it
affected his depth perception. As a result, he can't drive because,
while he's in motion, it takes him five to six seconds to realize
where other cars are, or where the curb is; which, he said, makes
him worse than only about 60 percent of the drivers out there. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
