<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6675 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOXTYSON-IMAGE-AZR &LR;      01-10 1922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOXTYSON-IMAGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON'S TOUGHEST FOE: HIS IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has passed out turkeys, kissed babies, signed autographs,
cracked jokes with Charles Barkley, played Santa Claus, talked
tough to juvenile inmates and marched from tent to cell alongside
Sheriff Joe Arpaio.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the parade always has included the media, an
electronic chain gang linked by cameras and computers.
</P>
<P>
   Heavyweight spin? Or the new Mike Tyson?
</P>
<P>
   It's anybody's guess. Tyson, himself, has always been tough to
figure. Humble one second, hostile the next. As a fighter by trade,
he has learned to rely on the feint as a fundamental, instinctive
skill. In the ring, the fake can set up a punch. Out of the ring,
the artful dodge is virtual reality. These days, perception is the
punch.
</P>
<P>
   Since the former heavyweight champion arrived in the Phoenix
area three months ago, there have been carefully orchestrated
``photo ops'' and repeated comments that suggest he is here to
resurrect himself in the mythical manner of the bird after which
the city is named.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona is where I'm starting over because this is where I
feel relaxed and under control,'' Tyson said Friday as he broke
camp at Phoenix's Madison Square Garden gym and left for Las Vegas,
where he will fight Frans Botha on Saturday in his first bout since
June 1997. ``Anymore, when I go back to New York, I feel like I'm
on another planet, or something.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngest heavyweight champion in this planet's history has
often behaved as though he were living in some other universe.
</P>
<P>
   By now, everybody knows the rap sheet. There was the infamous
incident in which he bit Evander Holyfield's ears during his last
fight 19 months ago. There was his obscene tirade in an abortive
attempt to get a boxing license in New Jersey. There was a prison
sentence for sexual assault. There's more. With Tyson, there always
is.
</P>
<P>
   Pound for pound, he might be the P.R. business' toughest
challenge. He even summed up the monumental task last week in a
flash of anger at the end of an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy with my credibility is shot,'' said Tyson, who won the
heavyweight title 12 years ago as a 20-year old. ``If the sleaziest
girl in the world says Mike Tyson grabbed her, society will believe
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy like Mitch Green, a known crackhead who uses heroin and
angel dust, is believed by a court of law. . . . He's still walking
the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, a former Tyson sparring partner who was awarded $45,000
after suing Tyson for injuries suffered during a 1988 street fight,
has had several brushes with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's angry remark was enough to send Tyson's new adviser,
Shelly Finkel, out into the Phoenix streets in search of more free
turkeys. Of course, Finkel has heard it before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, Mike is too honest,'' Finkel said during a rambling
Tyson interview last month. ``He doesn't know how to censor
himself.'' &QL;  &QL; 
 &UR; `Crisis P.R.' &QL;  &QL; 
Nevertheless, there's the suggestion that Tyson is learning how to
control the temper that always seems coiled and ready to strike.
That suggestion, at least, has been planted by a media campaign
since his move to the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turkeys, the toys . . . they are going down every avenue
they can,'' said Chris Ryan, whose Tempe firm, Ryan &AMP; Associates,
specializes in what he calls ``crisis P.R.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's clients have included people whose legal problems have
been the subject of media coverage. He tries to alter a perspective
cast in a negative light by the media. He recognizes the tactics
employed in the Tyson campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a strategy you normally take when you have somebody
with a damaged reputation,'' said Ryan, who has appeared on
national talk shows on several television networks. ``You
strategically plant ways to win people over. What are the ways we
can tug at the heartstrings? That sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign can work, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``With time,'' Ryan said. ``Time is the key. You're dealing with
the new reputation. Over time, the old reputation hopefully gets
lost in the memory banks.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Tyson can make that old reputation hard to forget.
After last week's outburst, respected boxing writer Michael Katz of
the ``New York Daily'' ``News'' wrote that good public relations do
not ``change the bully's stripes.'' &QL;  &QL; 
 &UR; Foreman was angry, too &QL;  &QL; 
But fighters have been known to change. And, in the Tyson case,
there is an intriguing, if not striking, precedent.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, George Foreman was not today's gentle,
wisecracking pitchman with a muffler for every car and a
cheeseburger for every meal. During the past 10 years, he's been
the genial warrior who made aging boomers feel good as he
reluctantly knocked out fighters half his age.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, Foreman was his generation's version of
Tyson. He was an angry, surly young man whose humiliation was
brought on by Muhammad Ali in the famous ``Rope-A-Dope,'' Ali's
victory at Zaire in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Foreman's hero was Sonny Liston, the star-crossed
and troubled heavyweight who was said to have had mob connections
before a mysterious death because of an alleged heroin overdose.
Tyson often speaks of his admiration for Liston. A question about
Liston precipitated his outburst last week.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Foreman grew out of his lousy reputation and on to
happy middle age. Foreman's transformation from lousy to lovable is
remarkable enough for even Tyson to take notice. At least, longtime
promoter, ring announcer and public relations man Bill Caplan sees
Tyson borrowing from the Foreman experience.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson appears to be have discovered a sense of humor. He's
cracking jokes at his own expense in a style that has the tone of
Foreman's self-deprecating remarks about his cheeseburger-built
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really taking a page out of George Foreman's book,'' said
Caplan, who began working as an adviser to Foreman the year before
he won a 1968 Olympic gold medal and danced around the Mexico City
ring with a tiny American flag stuck into a hand the size of a bear
claw. ``When George made his comeback in 1987, everybody starting
saying he was too fat. So George started making fat jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   Caplan noticed the Foreman parallel in Los Angeles last month at
a news conference during which the Tyson-Botha bout was announced.
Tyson cracked jokes about parole officers. He's still on parole
through March and could return to jail after he is sentenced Feb. 5
on a misdemeanor assault charge. That charge was filed following an
altercation after an auto accident in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   He also has been quick to mock himself for biting Holyfield's
ears. There's a widely published photo of him biting onto the
T-shirt of a crying child during an autograph session at the
downtown Phoenix gym. The shot was spontaneous, but, on second
glance, Tyson seemed to pose as though he had planned it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw Tyson in Los Angeles, I was thinking at the time:
`He's finally wising up,' '' said Caplan, who has worked as a
publicist for Top Rank promoter Bob Arum and Tyson's former
promoter, Don King. ``He was doing a little bit of what has made
George so successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, he's never going to be George Foreman. But he's on the
right trail. It seems to be working.'' &QL;  &QL; 
 &UR; Where's the money? &QL;  &QL; 
The re-working of Tyson's tattered image actually began last
spring, when he jettisoned King along with advisers John Horne and
Rory Holloway.
</P>
<P>
   Then Caplan signed on for a few months. It was Caplan's job to
tell the media how much was allegedly taken from Tyson, who has
earned $140 million since 1995 and yet has a tax debt of $13
million.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is suing King for $100 million. King has filed a
countersuit. Nevertheless, the numbers paint a stark picture and
plant an inevitable question: What happened to Tyson's money?
</P>
<P>
   In part, Tyson looks as though he was an unwitting victim
surrounded by a bad crowd. By mere reflection, that almost makes
him a sympathetic figure. The crowd has changed, and those changes
were one of the consistent themes throughout Tyson's Phoenix
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   But has ``he''?
</P>
<P>
   For the short term, there will be an answer Saturday at the MGM
Grand against Botha, a credible opponent. Botha is known for his
willingness to fight. If Botha can last beyond the initial moments
of a scheduled 10-rounder and land some telling blows in the
process, will Tyson revert to the wild man who went berserk against
Holyfield? If he does, all the well-intentioned P.R. will be
undone.
</P>
<P>
   For the long term, there's Tyson out of the ring. He has to stay
out of trouble, and there are plenty of people who are betting he
can't do it. He even hinted at it last week when a reporter,
identifying himself as a former prison inmate, asked whether it was
possible to steer clear of trouble for the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who's stayed out of trouble of any kind for 20
years,'' Tyson said.
</P>
<P>
   There's another, slightly cynical, side to this P.R. business.
In boxing, too much good can be very harmful. Tyson isn't the
game's biggest draw because he's Mother Teresa. He's big box-office
because he possesses a dark, destructive side. At his licensing
hearing in Las Vegas, he responded to questions about his
psychiatric report by saying he felt like Norman Bates, the slasher
in ``Psycho.'' The film wasn't popular because it was ``The Sound
Of'' ``Music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't want to turn the lion into a kitten,'' said
Valley public relations man David Hans Schmidt, who has represented
Tonya Harding.
</P>
<P>
   There doesn't seem to be much chance of that. Again, just listen
to Tyson, himself, when asked last week about the fascination that
people continue to have for him:
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they hate me more than anyone else. Maybe they want to
see my demise.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   But Tyson's demise would mark the end of boxing's biggest
moneymaker. He'll receive at least $20 million, not counting a
percentage of pay-per-view receipts, for the Botha bout, according
to sources within in his camp.
</P>
<P>
   P.R. people can count, too. There's plenty of incentive to keep
Tyson near the edge of a demise that few people ever see for
themselves. The dangerous balance between fame and infamy accounts
for the fascination. Even Tyson admits he had lost his balance. The
task now is to at least portray him as man attempting a comeback,
which is always the good fight.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his Phoenix training camp, there was a vigilant
effort to eliminate any potential that he might be nudged too close
to the edge of another fall. The parking lot near the rundown gym
on West Van Buren Street was surrounded by a chain-link fence that
was covered with tarps. Bodyguards checked the identity of those
allowed in and out of the gym.
</P>
<P>
   On the day Tyson was scheduled to play Santa, an expectant crowd
had gathered to watch his every move. There was one strange guy
with a movie camera. He wore a jacket that was spray-painted with
several obscene words directed at the police.
</P>
<P>
   Finkel couldn't miss him. Concerned, Finkel spoke to Tyson's
chief of security, James Anderson, a former New Jersey cop whose
son is Atlanta Falcons running back Jamal Anderson. The man in the
jacket soon vanished.
</P>
<P>
   If Tyson ever saw him, he didn't acknowledge it. Tyson just went
about his business. A line of kids, a tableful of toys and the
cameras were waiting for him.
</P>
<P>
   So was an old foe.
</P>
<P>
   His reputation might be his toughest opponent of all. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
