<SLUG> BC-SKI-ARIZONA_CONDITIONS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD SKI YEAR? IT JUST ISN'T SNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're hankering for a great skiing trip, you'd better look
at Colorado, where some slopes have 12 feet of snow or more.
</P>
<P>
   If that isn't an option, you can settle for skiing in Arizona.
Conditions aren't great for either downhill or cross-country this
season, and operators are worried they can't last long without
significant snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Snowbowl near Flagstaff opened Saturday on a limited
basis with a 26-inch base on the north runs. Manager John Murray
said his crews moved several thousand tons of snow to the north
slopes so that skiers could make it all the way to the chair lifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it's pretty good skiing,'' he said Saturday. ``We're
about 25 percent open. It's pretty cold up here, and the runs
facing north, out of the sun, have enough snow to keep us going.
Under current conditions, I think it'll last a week or more.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the worst start for Snowbowl. During the drought in
1995-96, the slopes opened on Feb. 6 and closed again in Feb. 9.
Thanks to a late-winter storm, they opened again Feb. 29 and stayed
open until March 20.
</P>
<P>
   The White Mountain Apache's Sunrise Ski Resort between Pinetop
and Springerville is closed, according to Robert Howard, director
of mountain operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been enough natural snowfall,'' Howard said. ``We
have limited snow-making equipment. This pretty much has me in a
state of panic. We're usually in operation for the rest of the
winter at about Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get a couple of inches of snow, then it'll get warm. We
can't get an accumulation of snow. We could move snow from other
areas, but we still wouldn't have enough to open.''
</P>
<P>
   An answering machine was the only contact with the skiing area
on Bill Williams Mountain near Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say when we'll open,'' the tape said. ``But we're
ready. We'll open as soon as Mother Nature provides.''
</P>
<P>
   A call to the skiing area on Mount Lemmon near Tucson received
no answer _ not even a message.
</P>
<P>
   At Snowbowl, the Mount Agassiz lift and lodge are the only
facilities open. As a result, there will be no children's or
beginners' ski areas. The slopes available on Agassiz are for
experienced skiers and snowboarders. Private lessons will be
available on a limited basis
</P>
<P>
   Lift tickets will be reduced to $25 for adults and $15 for
juniors (8 to 12).
</P>
<P>
   The number of lift tickets each day will be limited to 1,000,
according to Murray.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure we're not overcrowded,'' he said. ``We
want to have quality skiing, and we don't want all the snow skied
off.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that each skier, who spends the day, displaces a
ton of snow downhill. It happens when they make their turns. Each
night, crews groom the slopes by pushing the snow back up the
mountain. The sun, of course, has a lot to do with the demise of
snow on a slope.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said he didn't think Snowbowl would get 1,000 skiers on
Saturday. ``It doesn't look like it now,'' he said. ``People got
the news, and we'll probably be a little under 1,000.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to cross-country (Nordic) skiing, things are even
more bleak.
</P>
<P>
   There is skiing at Hannagan Meadows on the eastern side of the
state, but even the operators don't recommend it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not quality skiing,'' said Mike Baumann, who said he is a
cook at the lodge. ``It seems like it gets warmer and warmer every
day. During the day, the snow gets pretty slushy. What we really
need is a storm.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flagstaff Nordic Center and the Forest Lakes Touring Center
near Heber don't have enough snow to ski.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will be a late winter,'' said Tim Grier at Forest
Lakes. ``The jet stream just isn't in the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   For up-to-date information, Sunrise's toll-free number is (888)
617-6704. Snowbowl has a Phoenix number to get snow reports. It's
957-0404. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
