<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-IMPACT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA TERMS WILL AFFECT ALL PRO SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What really went on in that all-nighter that Commissioner David
Stern and Players Association Executive Director Billy Hunter
pulled to save the NBA season?
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny you should ask that question,'' said Gene Upshaw,
executive director of the NFL's players union. ``I was just talking
to (baseball's union executive director) Donald Fehr, and we were
having that same discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably only eight other people who understand what
it's like to be in that room _ the four commissioners and the four
executive directors from baseball, hockey, football and basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is, it doesn't matter how they got there,
they've got an agreement and now they all have to live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, so will other professional athletes and their
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Each time a labor agreement is reached in pro sports, the others
are watching closely to see how the new system works, whether the
same rules could help or hurt their own league or players, who
benefits and who doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it takes years to find out.
</P>
<P>
   And the agreement reached between the NBA and its players is
unprecedented. It includes, for the first time, a maximum amount
players can be paid for at least the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each sport is always looking to better itself,'' said Shawn
Hunter, Coyotes president, who worked in the NBA for seven years.
``I'm sure it will be studied closely by both the players and the
management sides in other sports, and if there are pieces of it
that make sense, I'm sure they'll be discussed by both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said he had not had an opportunity to see the agreement
and wouldn't comment on the specifics, but he said every league is
trying to find ways to contain costs and grow while keeping its
players happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to (control costs),'' Hunter said.
``Because the ultimate loser is the fans. Without the everyday fan,
we're dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm glad they reached an agreement. It's good for
professional sports in general when there is labor peace, and I
happen to be a basketball fan. I was surprised it went so long. I
worked in the NBA, and I never thought I would see even one game
missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks in Major League Baseball figure to be especially
interested in seeing the new agreement when it's put into writing.
The current labor agreement in baseball is up in 2000, but the
players have the option to extend it to 2001, which is likely.
</P>
<P>
   And baseball has some serious problems that must be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have the advantage of having a managing general
partner, Jerry Colangelo, who was involved in the NBA talks as
president of the Suns and a member of the NBA's Labor Relations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're busy now, but sometime soon I want to sit down
with Jerry and (Suns General Manager) Bryan (Colangelo) and go
through it,'' said Joe Garagiola Jr., general manager of the
Diamondbacks. ``There are some ground-breaking things that went
into that agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The maximum salary is something that's unprecedented in
professional sports, but it's too early to say what the
implications of that might be. We're fortunate to have somebody who
was involved in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior Colangelo has taken some heat for being part of a
league that was seeking ``cost certainty'' in a labor agreement, as
the NBA did, while at the same time spending millions to sign free
agents for his baseball club.
</P>
<P>
   But, Colangelo said it's a matter of working within the rules
that exist to put the best possible product on the court or
diamond. And just because he believes a system may have flaws
doesn't mean he isn't going to work within that system.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, Colangelo hopes, will learn from the NBA deal, which
he believes will close the gap between small-market teams and
large-market teams. That will create competitive and financial
parity, which restricts player movement, which lends itself to
continuity and fan loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to speak to (Baseball Commissioner) Bud Selig,
he'd tell you there is nothing more important on his plate than
this whole area of creating parity,'' Colangelo said. ``There are
only two ways to close the gap: On the expense side, you put a lid
on of some type. And on the revenue side, you share as much as
feasible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not socialism because there are quite a few variables.
But it's easier said than done. Any economic system that does not
have some kind of limitation at the top, and does not have
substantial revenue sharing, is going to have more than its share
of problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This closes the gap in our league. What it will do is
absolutely stabilize the league, and if you buy into the theory
that  stable league is good for the players and owners, then it's
in everybody's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``In baseball, there is a real division from the haves and
have-nots, just tremendous disparity on the revenue side from those
at the bottom and those at the top. You want every team to at least
have a shot at being competitive. There's something wrong when
teams can only break even by cutting salaries to the minimum, then
waiting for a big check in revenue sharing from the haves. It's not
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Selig and executive vice president Sandy Alderson were
not returned late last week, and many people involved in the
different league management and union teams were not willing to
discuss the deal until they had time to study it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our collective bargaining agreement is in place until 2004,''
said Frank Brown, a spokesman for the NHL. ``We're locked in. We'll
certainly study it when pen is actually put to paper, but it really
has no importance to us until our negotiations come up in the next
millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe that for a minute. NHL owners will be studying it
closely by next week, and so will the league's players union.
</P>
<P>
   Upshaw said he already has seen a rough version of the
agreement, and apparently so has NFL management.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears the NBA has taken some steps to maintain and
strengthen the competitive balance of their league,'' said Greg
Aiello, a spokesman for the NFL, who returned a call left for the
league's senior vice president for labor relations, Peter Ruocco.
</P>
<P>
   ``They appear to have a system that will promote equality.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did some things that we did in our most recent contract
extension, which was increasing minimums for veteran players to
help the middle class, and some of the things they did with their
drug program. It appears they've got a very good, balanced
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   One might expect a different viewpoint from the players. After
all, many pundits have declared a major victory for the NBA's
owners.
</P>
<P>
   But Upshaw isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've looked at the preliminary agreement, and it's amazing to
me the players were able to get as much as they did with virtually
no leverage,'' Upshaw said. ``Everybody is saying the owners won,
but I think they ended up with a compromise that's not bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there are some limits, but there also were some
significant increases in the minimums for the players. And many of
the NBA's stars are grandfathered into the agreement. I think
Michael Jordan can survive on a 5 percent raise from his $30
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when we made our deal in 1993, everybody said it
was the worst deal in sports, and the owners would laugh all the
way to the bank. But we've negotiated two extensions already, and
it worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got labor peace until 2004, the players are happy, the
owners are happy and the Arizona Cardinals are in the playoffs.
Something must be working right.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
