</P>
<P>
   IN WASHINGTON: Art Dalglish, 301 460-6176.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TALK _ WASHINGTON _ The rosy bipartisan glow surrounding
the Senate's bipartisan agreement on rules for an impeachment trial
faded a bit Sunday. Sharp differences emerged as Democratic and
Republican senators appearing on TV interview shows wrestled with
controversial subjects their agreement had deferred, such as
whether there should be witnesses. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   GALEGIS-PREVIEW _ ATLANTA _ It's the first day of the 1999
legislative session. A new governor and lieutenant governor will be
sworn in, as will several constitutional officers and the entire
Legislature. The day's festivities start with a 7:45 a.m. church
service and conclude with the governor's ball. (Pruitt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   PEACE-CORPS _ ATLANTA _ Who are the people attracted to the
Peace Corps, and what does it take to be accepted? We attend the
first in a series of metro Atlanta recruitment drives, this one at
the Auburn Avenue Library. Two interesting angles: Why would people
want to work hard for almost no pay in the middle of the best
economy in world history, and is there concern about safety in the
wake of the murder last month of an Atlanta Peace Corps worker in
Gabon, West Africa? (Smith, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   This budget will be updated at 6 p.m. EDT and afterwards as
necessary based on news developments.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS and GRAPHICS All times are Eastern unless otherwise
noted. If stories will move after 8 p.m. Eastern, an ETA will be
given.
</P>
<P>
   If stories, photos, graphics or layouts will not move or will
move late, we'll send an advisory on the wire.
</P>
