<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6789 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     01-10 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 17)  
(lb) 
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; VIRGIL THOMSON: COMPOSER ON THE AISLE &LR;  By Anthony Tommasini.
Norton, $18. A music critic for The New York Times portrays Thomson
as both a vivacious Midwesterner affected by the hymns and band
concerts of his childhood, and a man capable of baffling cruelty.
In 1997 the Times reviewer Nicholas Fox Weber said this biography
``evokes the composer's critical ear and describes his music with
words that bring us right into the concert hall.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHARMING BILLY &LR;  By Alice McDermott. Delta, $12.95. In a New
York bar where the friends and family of a dreamy, hard-drinking
Irish-American named Billy Lynch gather after his funeral, a
corrosive 40-year-old lie about a woman tragically lost and
presumed dead is gradually unraveled. This novel, which won a
National Book Award in 1998, is about the power of romantic
mythmaking and the way a person's life can be shaped by the
expectations of others. Last year in The New York Times Book
Review, Alida Becker called it an ``eloquent and unsettling'' tale
that ``like its title character ... works on our sympathies with an
insistent sadness and an ingratiating charm.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued McDermott's earlier novels,
including  &UR; THAT NIGHT &LR;  ($12.95), which centers on a battle that
breaks out in a New York suburb when the parents of a pregnant
teen-ager try to keep her from her hoodlum boyfriend. In 1987 the
reviewer David Leavitt admired the ``almost baroque richness of
McDermott's sentences, the intellectual complexity of her moral
vision and the explicit emotion of her voice.''
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; A BIGAMIST'S DAUGHTER &LR;  ($12.95), a young woman working at a
vanity press becomes involved with a novelist whose
work-in-progress about a bigamist stirs troubling memories of her
own elusive father. In 1982 Anne Tyler wrote, ``McDermott ...
writes with assurance and skill, and she has created a
fascinatingly prismatic story.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A HISTORY OF DOGS IN THE EARLY AMERICAS &LR;  By Marion Schwartz.
Selected drawings by Susan Hochgraf. Yale University, $15. A
physical anthropologist reveals how man's best friend was many
things to many peoples before the Europeans arrived in the Americas
in the 1500s. In some places dogs were revered as deities, in
others eaten as dinner. In 1997 the reviewer Timothy Foote called
this ``a fascinating, scholarly mishmash, with extraordinary
drawings.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EMINENT DOGS, DANGEROUS MEN &LR;  By Donald McCaig. Lyons, $14.95. A
chronicle of the author's difficult search through Scotland for the
perfect border collie to herd sheep on his Virginia farm. This
``lively travelogue-history'' is ``rich in dog lore and by no means
poor as a study of human behavior,'' Christopher Lehmann-Haupt
wrote in The New York Times in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BURDEN OF DESIRE &LR;  By Robert MacNeil. Harvest/Harcourt Brace,
$14. After a French freighter explodes and destroys part of
Halifax, Nova Scotia, in 1917, a clergyman stumbles onto a woman's
passionate diary, falls in love with its author and enlists a
friend to help track her down. In 1992 the reviewer Susan Fromberg
Schaeffer called this ``a novel filled with riches and alight with
understanding of the small events that lead to the huge upheavals
in life.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAPPED IN THE NET: THE UNANTICIPATED CONSEQUENCES OF
COMPUTERIZATION &LR;  By Gene I. Rochlin. Princeton University, $17.95.
Focusing on the current and expected effects of computers and
networking on everything from air travel to the financial markets,
the author argues that automation is making it nearly impossible
for people to make modest mistakes and learn from them. In 1997,
Lawrence Hunter called this ``an insightful and painstakingly
documented book.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CRYSTAL FIRE: THE INVENTION OF THE TRANSISTOR AND THE BIRTH OF
THE INFORMATION AGE &LR;  By Michael Riordan and Lillian Hoddeson.
Norton, $15. This traces the careers of three American physicists
whose work paved the way for today's microprocessor chips.
``Riordan and Hoddeson reconstruct the birth of the transistor with
considerable aplomb,'' John Durant wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FELIX IN THE UNDERWORLD &LR;  By John Mortimer. Penguin, $12.95.
This British author's 27th book is a comic romp about a feckless
novelist who gets caught up in paternity-suit blackmail and murder
during a nightmarish book tour. In 1997 Christopher Buckley called
this a ``witty work, reminiscent of other late-period novels like
Kingsley Amis' `Russian Girl' and Peter De Vries' `Peckham's
Marbles.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DREAM STATE: STORIES &LR;  By Moira Crone. University Press of
Mississippi, $14.95. Many of the vaguely confused characters in
these tales are transplanted Northerners adrift in New Orleans and
southern Louisiana but unable to move on. ```Dream State'
successfully presents a fresh version of the Deep South, one that
is exotic without being either grotesque or romanticized,'' Gary
Krist wrote in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WITH CHATWIN: PORTRAIT OF A WRITER &LR;  By Susannah Clapp. Penguin,
$12.95. The enigmatic Bruce Chatwin, who died of AIDS at the age of
48, is portrayed by his first editor as a brilliant travel writer
and novelist, and an immensely talented art dealer. This is an
``adoring memoir'' by an observer ``graced with a special vantage
on his life and work,'' William Ferguson wrote in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
