<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, Jan. 11:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ECON (Havana) _How people are managing in an embargoed
economy. 1800 words. By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   GULF-OIL-PRICES (Kuwait City) _ A sustained decline in world oil
prices has left the gulf states with a growing sense of
vulnerability. 1400 words. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-VILLAGE (San Vicente Del Caguan) _ In the streets, the
campesinos of San Vicente del Caguan dared a quiet pride and even
hope, seeing luminaries from the nation's capital and around Latin
America descend on their town for a giant party to begin talks with
leftist rebels this week. ``Laboratory for peace,'' said banners
strung across the airport and around the square, where the
government and leftist rebels have opened talks toward peace. The
signs did not refer so much to the national feelers to end the
fighting that has claimed 35,000 lives over the last decade, as to
this town's novel attempts to find a peace of its won with the
rebels in recent months. 1300 words. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-RDP (Cairo, Egypt) _ After more than a month of rising
defiance, the Iraqi government on Sunday inexplicably postponed a
vote in which its Parliament had appeared ready to take further
steps along a collision course with its Western foes. Instead, the
Parliament issued only a mild statement critical of last month's
American-led air strikes against Iraq; on Saturday, there had been
calls from some members of Parliament for measures that would have
been a direct challenge to the United Nations. 1000 words. By
Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-POLITICS (Hong Kong) _ Eight months after it scored a
resounding victory in legislative elections here, Hong Kong's
pro-democracy movement is divided over whether the Democratic Party
should abandon elective politics and take its cause to the streets.
1000 words. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-VOTE (Lagos) _ Officials monitoring Nigeria's statewide
elections said on Sunday that they had been generally peaceful and
well-organized, describing them as an improvement over last month's
local elections and another positive step toward next month's
presidential contest. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   KAZAKHSTAN-VOTE (Almaty) _ President Nursultan Nazarbayev ran
for a fresh seven-year term on Sunday against three virtual
unknowns. The official turnout in this Central Asian nation, which
has been courted by the west because of its large energy reserves,
was 86 percent. Official vote results were expected Monday. By
Steve LeVine.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-VATICAN (Ottawa) _ The second-ranking Vatican diplomat in
Canada is accused of stalking a former employee. 600 words. By
Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-MURAL (Johannesburg) _ A mural in the center of
Johannesburg honoring the apartheid struggle contains not the faces
of Mandela or Tutu or Biko, but those of actors from the afternoon
soaps. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w' code)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ Lede-all on the impeachment issue. By
Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-POLITICS (Washington) _ The question now is whether
Congress and the Clinton administration can work together to deal
with the full plate of issues facing the country. Both parties have
powerful motivations to prove that they have not been consumed by
impeachment. But the challenge of getting on with the people's
business will be complicated not just by impeachment-induced
bitterness and distrust, but by the host of differing agendas in
play, from Gephardt and Gore to the conservative right. By Richard
W. Stevenson and John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SENATE (Washington) _ In setting a detailed schedule to
resume the Clinton impeachment trial but putting off the vexing
issue of whether witnesses will be heard, the Senate demonstrated
to many lawyers and others just how different an impeachment trial
is from any other legal proceeding. By Neil Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-HISTORY (Washington) _ With a contemporary
constitutional drama going on just a few miles away, historians
flocked to the nation's capital last week to discuss topics like
the dilemma of the South Asian intellectual and acoustics in early
America. And maybe something else, too. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   RENO-RECORD (Washington) _ On Monday, Janet Reno becomes the
longest serving attorney general of this century, breaking a record
held by Homer Cummings, an attorney general in the Roosevelt
administration who held the post from March 4, 1933, to Jan. 2,
1939. Reno, who took over in 1993, is highly unlikely to break the
all-time service record held by William Wirt, who served for 11
years from November 1817 to March 1829. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-POLITICS (Undated) _ The vice president prepares for a big
week on the road, as the impeachment trial begins in earnest in
Washington. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-STUDY (Undated) _ The recent wave of get-tough-on-crime
sentencing laws has succeeded in making criminals serve longer
prison sentences and slowed the release of prison inmates; but it
has also helped increase the nation's record prison population even
as crime has dropped in the 1990s, according to the first
comprehensive study of the new laws released by the Justice
Department. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
