<DOCNO> NYT19990110.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6795 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROSPECTUS-COLUMN-NYT     01-10 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSPECTUS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO WIN RESPECT FOR NEW YORK'S SOFTWARE INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Calif., Mass.) 
(mk) 
 By JANET STITES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bruce Bernstein is a frustrated man. The proprietor
of Main Street Partners, a database application developer based in
New York, he is also a tireless promoter of the city's software
developers as president of the New York Software Industry
Association.
</P>
<P>
   What frustrates Bernstein is that New York's software industry
is almost entirely overlooked except when it is related to new
media, the industry that has grown up around the Internet. The
problem with fusing the identities of the two industries, he says,
is that excitement over the evolution of the Internet into a mass
medium eclipses his industry and undermines its value. In short,
New York City is known for its content, not its code.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the software industry is lumped into new media, it hurts,''
Bernstein said. ``It hurts when people want to make investments
here or locate their company here. It hurts when the best
programmers don't want to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, New York City, unlike Silicon Valley or Boston's Route
128, is not recognized as a center for software development. It is
not the first place venture capitalists look to invest in
technology or programmers look for jobs. Citing perhaps the most
obvious flaw in the common perception, Bernstein said, ``People
forget that New York City was the home of IBM.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Fish, a partner in the New York City office of the venture
capital arm of PricewaterhouseCoopers, agrees that the popular
perception is a problem. ``Traditionally, venture capitalists have
invested in proprietary technology, something which will have an
ongoing life,'' he said. ``They need to know that the software
industry is here and thriving.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Fish said, ``the software industry has played
second fiddle to the hype of new media.'' But software development,
he added, is a true technology industry, ``while new media falls
more along the lines of entertainment and publishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, part of the identity problem is that the edges of the two
industries blur on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Software may not be the best term now for our industry, with
all the issues of convergence,'' Bernstein said. ``We like to think
of it as software and information technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein also contends that many new-media companies are really
software developers in disguise. For example, in his mind,
Doubleclick, an online advertising agency that places clients'
banners across the Internet and is one of the most successful
companies in Silicon Alley, is a software developer. ``The engine
of its success is software technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion is understandable. Historically, software came in
a box and was purchased at computer stores. It was easy to
recognize. ``Packaged software is not delivered in a package
anymore,'' Bernstein said. ``It's delivered over the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Or it may be software developed for use on the Internet. Comet
Systems, for instance, has developed a software tool for creating
customized cursors at Web sites. While a user is visiting a Disney
site, the cursor might be mouse ears, while at the NFL site it
might be a football. Software? New media? New-media software?
</P>
<P>
   According to the association's definition, software companies
fall into four categories, divided by product or service: packaged
software, custom software, systems integrators or
information-technology management consulting. In addition, the
association recognizes in-house software groups, academic computer
science centers and freelance programmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, if a primary part of a company's revenue comes
from writing code, we consider it a software company,'' Bernstein
said. ``Of course, the holy grail is to design your own package.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's software industry has had very little in the way of
hard numbers to promote itself. And despite Fish's concerns, even
PricewaterhouseCoopers' own research categorizes software and new
media together. When Coopers &AMP; Lybrand, now merged into
PricewaterhouseCoopers, published its much-cited survey of
new-media companies in New York City in the fall of 1996, it did
not distinguish software companies from more media-oriented
companies.
</P>
<P>
   And at the Web site of the PricewaterhouseCoopers venture
capital survey, figures on financing for Internet companies and
software companies are listed together. A quick glance at the
survey's findings for the last three years, however, shows that
nearly half the companies in the New York metropolitan area that
won financing were software developers.
</P>
<P>
   The association will soon have a better set of numbers to fall
back on. The New York City comptroller's office is nearing the end
of a study on the software industry, and its report will be
released Jan. 21 at the New York Software Summit and East Coast
Summit for Java Technology at the Fashion Institute of Technology.
The New York City Comptroller, Alan Hevesi, will present it when he
delivers the event's keynote address.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to have good data,'' David Neustadt, a
spokesman for Hevesi's office, said. ``If you want to help an
industry, you have to know what they have and what they need. We
want to help get people to take the industry more seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   In a city that brims with industrial variety and that is the
world center of several businesses, including broadcasting,
finance, publishing and fashion, Bernstein's battle for identity
may be a tough one, and it may be that the software industry will
never attract the recognition and influence it deserves. But it
will probably be distinguishable from new media in one major way
for a long time to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the software companies are financing themselves out of
revenue,'' Bernstein said. ``They make money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
