<HEADLINE>
FALLOWS JOINS MICROSOFT  
 GOLDEN BOOKS HORROR STORY  
 MEHTA INDIGNANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Fallows, former editor of U.S. News and World Report and
author of ``Breaking the News: How the Media Undermine American
Democracy,'' is well known as a critic of what journalists write.
But he has also been an armchair critic of the computer software
that they use to write with.
</P>
<P>
   Now Fallows, 49, who was replaced last June as editor of U.S.
News, has an opportunity to influence the software. He joined
Microsoft Corp. last week as a member of the product development
team for Word, the leading word-processing program.
</P>
<P>
   When Fallows was a writer for The Atlantic Monthly, his editors
indulged his nerdish inclinations by allowing him to write
occasional computer columns. He was an outspoken member of that
quixotic minority that tried to resist the Microsoft tide, writing
articles that extolled the virtues of IBM's OS/2 operating system
over Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Talking last fall with Steven Ballmer, a fellow alumnus of the
Harvard Crimson and the president of Microsoft, about going to work
for the software industry's standard setter, Fallows said he felt
``like some French diplomat finally admitting that most of the
world speaks English.''
</P>
<P>
   As a journalist, Fallows has had a penchant for public policy.
But as a new Microsoft employee, he is reticent when the
conversation turns to the company's confrontation with the Justice
Department. ``On the antitrust issue,'' he said, ``reasonable
people can come to different conclusions.''
</P>
<P>
   Fallows says he wants to make Word more helpful and less
irritating to use for people who do in-depth research and writing,
like academics, journalists and authors. His boss, Jon DeVaan, a
Microsoft vice president, said Fallows brought an author's
perspective, creativity and a genuine enthusiasm for technology to
the software design team.
</P>
<P>
   Fallows says he intends to work at Microsoft for six months or
so and then return to writing magazine articles and books.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVE LOHR &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Golden Books Misses Out on Happily Ever After
</P>
<P>
   If Golden Books Family Entertainment ever chose to publish its
own recent history, it would belong in the category of horror
stories. Stock in the troubled children's publisher closed at a
mere 34.375 cents a share on Friday, after trading as high as
$11.875 a share on Feb. 2, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Though figures for the fourth quarter _ traditionally the year's
best _ are not out yet, there seems to be so little hope for a
turnaround that Ariel Capital Management, an investment firm that
once owned 20 percent of Golden Books stock, dumped its entire
holding last fall. Though Richard Snyder, the chairman of Golden
Books, has continually promised improvement, the company's
performance has deteriorated so badly that John Miller of Ariel
said in an interview last week, ``We kept hearing that fundamentals
were improving, but it turned out they were deteriorating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Deteriorating'' is an understatement. In the first nine months
of 1998, current liabilities ballooned to $267 million because the
company failed to meet interest payments on $149 million in senior
preferred notes that had been carried as long-term debt. Those
notes immediately became current liabilities, dwarfing current
assets of $144.6 million. The company is trying to renegotiate with
bondholders.
</P>
<P>
   Cash flow, meanwhile, was a negative $70 million, nearly twice
the $38 million loss a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter of 1998, the company lost $18.9 million, or
71 cents a share, compared with $17.9 million, or 76 cents a share,
in the corresponding quarter a year earlier. Golden Books said
higher sales of its children's books were offset by a drop in its
adult book business.
</P>
<P>
   Two board members, Barry Diller, chairman of USA Networks, and
Linda Janklow, wife of the publishing agent Morton Janklow, have
resigned. Last week, John Ferrara, the chief financial officer,
left, and the company could be dropped from listing on the Nasdaq
stock exchange, Golden Books acknowledged in its most recent
quarterly statement.
</P>
<P>
   Because the stock has been trading below $5 a share, it has
failed to meet some Nasdaq requirements. A Golden Books spokesman
said the company was negotiating with Nasdaq, and that a rule that
would require the stock to trade at more than $1 a share for 10
business days out of the next 90 calendar days or lose its listing
was not yet applicable.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder's current strategy for solving Golden Books' problems
remains unclear. But as each month passes, it seems the strategy
will have to be ever more imaginative.
</P>
<P>
   _ GERALDINE FABRIKANT &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Writer Finds No Room at the Library
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New Yorker's move to the Conde Nast building in
Times Square, planned for the summer, has ignited a feud between
unlikely opponents: a prolific author and the New York Public
Library.
</P>
<P>
   Ved Mehta, the author of 22 books and a staff writer at The New
Yorker from 1961 to 1994, has long used the library as a research
site, despite his blindness; he has assistants who read to him in
his private office at The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   He was allowed to keep the office even though he was no longer
an employee of the magazine (he likes to say he was ``terminated''
by Tina Brown in 1994). But he will not get office space in The New
Yorker's new, smaller quarters in the Times Square building. A
spokeswoman for the magazine, Perri Dorset, said there would be
room only for regular contributors to the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   When Mehta heard that the library, as part of its renovation,
was creating 15 private rooms for scholars, he was curious about
the new spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to apply for an office, and the answer came back no,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Oyama, manager of public relations for the library,
said the private rooms were apportioned out by the Center for
Scholars and Writers, a new program that has been endowed by a $15
million grant from Dorothy and Lewis Cullman. The space is open
only to scholars who apply for specific study projects and is
available during the course of an academic year, Ms. Oyama said.
</P>
<P>
   Mehta, who is the recipient of a MacArthur grant and two
Guggenheim fellowships, said last week that he had met with Paul
LeClerc, president of the New York Public Library. LeClerc, he
said, was ``sympathetic,'' but the meeting had little result. Mehta
said he believed that other writers of his stature had received
adequate work space when they asked for it, and he had not.
</P>
<P>
   Mehta said he would sue the library _ if it did not provide him
with ``proper facilities'' _ for discriminating against him as a
blind person.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oyama said the library was not acting illegally by denying
Mehta a private office.
</P>
<P>
   LeClerc said there were semiprivate accommodations for writers
who had pending book contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as we go through the rest of the renovation process, we
will be sure to accommodate visually impaired writers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mehta is unswayed in his mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've written 22 books, I was a staff writer at the New Yorker
from 1961 to 1994, I've never had a sabbatical and I've worked
seven days a week,'' he said. ``I don't understand the priorities
of this civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
</TEXT>
