<HEADER>
A6801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEACE-CORPS11-COX     01-10 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEACE-CORPS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peace Corps recruting campaign comes to Atlanta
 &HT;    By Gita M. Smith
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A stint in the Peace Corps has been called, ``the
toughest job you'll ever love,'' and current recruiting materials
ask,''How far will you go to make a difference?''
</P>
<P>
   To some on the outside, the organization that John F. Kennedy
founded in 1961, with its altruistic, wide-eyed image, is something
of an anachromism. Why, in the best U.S. economy in memory, would
someone sweat for 27 months for grunt wages ($6,075 paid in a lump
sum at the end), in places with no running water or modern
amenities?
</P>
<P>
   Why risk one's life, especially when war or revolution can break
out _ and often does _ in developing nations where the Peace Corps
typically places its people?
</P>
<P>
   To answer these and myriad other questions, the Peace Corps is
making a recruiting push in Georgia this month. As part of its plan
to add 4,000 new volunteers nationwide by the year 2000, three
get-to-know-us sessions have been scheduled in Atlanta, and one in
Athens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to an 8 percent budget increase, we will be adding a
ton of volunteers to teach English as a second language,''
recruiter Stephanie Greene said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Among those present and hoping to probe behind the Peace Corps
image was Bob Zwald, 70, of Cumming, who has spent the past two
summers in China with the Amity Foundation, teaching English to
middle-school teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in giving something back to the world,'' said Zwald,
who hopes his grandchildren will grow beyond ``this basically
selfish society we live in.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``giving back'' sometimes comes at a price. The murder of
Atlanta Peace Corps worker Karen Phillips in Gabon last month
saddened several returning volunteers who attended the session.
Still, they said, the dangers abroad are really no greater than
those faced every day in big U.S. cities, and for most volunteers
who live with a foreign host family in a close-knit village, the
dangers are few.
</P>
<P>
   ``Security measures are a major part of the training, and we
have escape plans for our people, as well as radios and beepers for
them to wear in areas where there are no phones,'' said Greene.
</P>
<P>
   ``If war or civil unrest could endanger our people, we send out
the message 'Susie is having a baby,' which means 'Get out of the
country NOW,' `` she said.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Lea Clinton, who served in Honduras, and Latanya Mapp, who
served in Lesotoh, said they were trained to handle a variety of
situations. Mapp learned, and subsequently taught others, how to
walk safely in the streets at night. Now, she says, she sees how
careless American children are in traffic, and it bothers her
``that they wear black at night, and get run over.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said, ``My village had a self-defense training course,
which was good because many Third-World countries are
male-dominated, and women are considered fair prey. But in the end,
it's the volunteer's responsibility to take care of herself and be
aware of what is going on around her, just like it is here at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Making a positive contribution eventually eclipsed daily safety
and comfort concerns, the volunteers agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn patience, despite yourself, and you come back a
better person for it,'' said Clark Efaw, who taught small business
development in Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to draw your water from a well and boil it. There's
no phone, so you take a day to go to another village to talk to
someone, and if he's not there, you have to come back home and try
again tomorrow,'' Efaw said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My metabolic rate is half what it was before I went into the
Peace Corps,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   New volunteer Kevin Robinson, scheduled to leave Atlanta on Jan.
19, listened closely at Thursday's session. He was a Georgia State
University grad when he found himself tending bar at age 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized one day, this is not at all what I had planned for
my life,'' Robinson said. ``I'd rather spend the next 27 months
building schools in Gabon than mixing cocktails, while I think
about the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   And he promised to write ``a long letter'' when he gets there.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
