u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-JORDAN-RETIRE-N     01-10 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-JORDAN-RETIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLISHERS ROOT FOR MICHAEL JORDAN'S RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Ill.) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Michael Jordan retires from basketball sometime before the
lockout-shortened season begins, the fans will weep and the
networks will gnash their teeth in despair.
</P>
<P>
   But one sector of the population will cheer: Book publishers
will roll up their tweedy sleeves and shout with joy. Because while
the TNT and TBS networks, owned by Time Warner, sank $890 million
into a four-year contract to broadcast the National Basketball
Association's games and General Electric's NBC paid $1.75 billion,
and the fans waited patiently for the doors of Madison Square
Garden in New York to swing open, and the vendors and concession
workers and radio announcers stood by across the country, the book
publishing industry was waiting like an eager undertaker.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations are especially high at the Random House unit of
Bertelsmann AG, which has invested heavily in two books: Jordan's
own book, ``For the Love of the Game: My Story,'' a lavish
coffee-table volume published by the Crown Books division last
fall, and David Halberstam's ``Playing for Keeps,'' which Random
House will publish on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Martin, associate publisher of Crown Books, said that if
Jordan retired, it would be the book-publishing equivalent of the
most thrilling buzzer-beater ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``His retirement will bump up sales,'' Martin said, ``and
combined with the season coming back, well, there's this great
second hit coming. There's a whole new selling picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin pointed out several places in ``For the Love of the
Game'' where Jordan discusses the possibility of retirement. The
book, Martin added, is ``his final word about his pleasure and love
for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Vancil, the outside editor of the book and the president of
Rare Air Inc., a Chicago publishing company described on the jacket
of ``For the Love of the Game'' as ``the exclusive provider of
Michael Jordan publishing properties,'' said there was no doubt
that Jordan's retirement was a factor the publishers had considered
and, in fact, counted on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea from early on was that we were not going to release
this book until he was retiring,'' Vancil said. ``When we sat down
and decided whether or not to make this a fall book, I sat down
with Michael and explained the reality of it to him. I said, `This
is the situation. This is your career retrospective.' And he said,
`Go ahead.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's retirement and any subsequent sales jump would be
important news for Crown, which printed 700,000 copies of the book,
which sells for $50. Despite the book's short-lived best-seller
status, Barnes &AMP; Noble has reported that ``For the Love of the
Game'' has still not sold according to Crown's high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was the six-month NBA lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all expecting their season to go ahead, and there was
this lockout, this strike,'' Martin said. ``At first, we weren't as
concerned because the book was larger than life. Then, as things
waned and we got into December, everybody was thinking, `Darn.'''
</P>
<P>
   There was the nagging problem of publicity. During the lockout,
Jordan did not promote the book, or as Martin put it, ``He hasn't
said boo.''
</P>
<P>
   Another financial drain for Crown is the cost of producing the
book: It was printed on specially created paper (``100(NU) rare air
gloss text'') and manufactured in the United States by the same
printers who print brochures for Rolls-Royce. (Shipping finished
books from overseas, where glossy American books are usually
printed because of cheaper prices, would have meant transporting
them by freighter, so they would not have been available for the
start of the season.)
</P>
<P>
   But expectations are also high at Random House for Halberstam's
``Playing for Keeps: Michael Jordan and the World He Made.''
Halberstam finished work on the manuscript in December. His editor,
Scott Moyers, said Random House wanted to publish the book ``sooner
than later.'' In fact, there was not even time to print the
traditional bound galleys for reviewers; they received bound
manuscripts instead.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Perry, director of publicity for the Random House imprint,
said Random House chose to publish quickly, ``knowing that Jordan
would likely have this decision to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam's books about sports _ ``The Summer of '49,''
``October 1964,'' ``The Breaks of the Game'' and ``The Amateurs'' _
have all been best sellers and have outsold his other books, like
``The Powers That Be,'' with which he made his reputation as an
author.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said he had thought carefully about the timing of the book
and Jordan's possible retirement. ``If he plays, it's only because
it's a short season,'' Perry said. ``It's not like he's going to
keep going. It's almost happenstance. The career, as wonderful as
it is, is pretty much done.''
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam _ who will tour the country for a month promoting the
book, starting with an appearance on ``The Today Show'' _ said he
would personally prefer to see Jordan play another season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael is an industry in his own, and he coins side
industries, and book publishing is certainly one of them,''
Halberstam said, adding that Jordan's retirement was not the reason
he wrote the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young, in my early teens, there was no NBA,'' he
said. ``The significant heroes in sports were white baseball
players. The idea that later in my life, the single most celebrated
athlete in America, a man who went to a college that he could not
have gone to when I was a reporter in Vietnam, who is the best
salesman in this country and in the world _ that's the equation you
would want to answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the retirement I am utterly immune to. You really can't
worry. What will the strike do? What will retirement do? Does it
help, or hurt? I just can't care.''
</P>
</TEXT>
