<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HDTV-PRICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HDTV SET PRICES ARE FALLING, BUT CONSUMERS REMAIN SCARCE
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Nev.) 
(ms) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ If the consumer electronics industry can be counted
on for one thing, it is that the prices of their products will
plummet, even when that may not be in the best interests of the
companies involved.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with high-definition television. Just two months after
the transition to digital broadcasting began, one company
exhibiting new products here at the annual Consumer Electronics
Show is offering an HDTV for $2,999, less than half the cost of the
cheapest set the industry was selling in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Several other companies announced plans to sell HDTV's in that
price range by the end of the year, leaving some executives worried
that the industry, among the least profitable in the United States,
is once again digging a hole for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a question of how much we want prices to come down,''
said Howard Stringer, the chief executive of the Sony Corp. of
America. ``We still have to sell'' conventional, analog television
sets.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Shapiro, head of the Consumer Electronics Manufacturers
Association, which sponsors the show, announced Friday that his
member companies sold 13,176 HDTV's to dealers in the last months
of 1998, and retailers said the companies had not been able to
produce enough sets to meet demand. The figure surprised most
people at the show. Before the announcement, Saul Shapiro, a vice
president for ABC, had said he thought ``a few hundred people
across the country'' were watching his network's high-definition
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising or not, 13,176 is a tiny fraction of the nation's
television business. Last year, Americans bought more than 27
million conventional television sets. And Stephen Nickerson, a vice
president with Toshiba America Consumer Products, noted, ``No
matter how many digital televisions are sold, analog set sales
cannot go down'' because ``digital sales are not going to pay the
bills.''
</P>
<P>
   From every corner of the television industry, company executives
and government officials have been urging the manufacturers to drop
their prices _ and fast, so the transition to digital broadcasting
can pick up speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digital television must be affordable if consumers are going
to embrace it,'' Susan Ness, a member of the Federal Communications
Commission, said at the convention. And Peter Smith, a vice
president for NBC, echoed that, saying his network needed ``a clear
expectation and confidence that someday everyone will be able to
afford an HDTV.''
</P>
<P>
   Those comments, and others like them, resulted from the product
announcements that had been made in the months before the show.
Every mainstream manufacturer but one was offering giant,
rear-projection high-definition television sets that cost $7,000 to
$12,000. The holdout was Sony, which is selling a table-top HDTV
with a picture tube for $9,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies showing their wares indicated that the
landscape would change drastically later this year. By the
Christmas shopping season, when most televisions are sold, several
manufacturers will be selling ``direct-view'' HDTV sets, the ones
with picture tubes, for $3,000 to $5,000, executives with the
companies say. These table-top sets will not be able to offer a
picture as a clear and sharp as the big ones, but they will still
look far better than conventional analog televisions.
</P>
<P>
   One company, Hitachi, is already selling an HDTV of sorts for
$2,999, although to receive HDTV, a buyer would also need a digital
tuner box, which by midyear will be on sale for about $700. The
company says the 36-inch, direct-view model offers sufficient
resolution to qualify as an HDTV. But Hitachi's model has a
traditional, square picture tube. To qualify officially as an HDTV
under the industry's guidelines, a set must have a wide screen.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, by the end of this year, many other companies say
they will be offering wide-screen table-top HDTV's at lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the rub. While $3,000 is notably more appealing than
$7,000 or more _ the industry already sells hundreds of thousands
of conventional sets for about $3,000 _ it is still far more than
most people are willing to spend for a television set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the price needs to be about 1.5 times the cost of an
analog set'' for mass sales to begin, said John W. Strobel, the
vice president for digital television marketing at Philips
Electronics N.V., the nation's second-largest seller of
televisions. And right now, most analog sets sell for $250 to
$1,500.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, some manufacturers say they fear that many
consumers will view a $3,000 high-definition television as simply
an over-priced set, not an irrelevant piece of esoterica, as the
$8,000 HDTV's are generally regarded now. And, the manufacturers
add, American consumers are well trained by decades of experience
to understand that a consumer-electronic product costing $3,000
this year will almost certainly cost $1,500 next year. So they will
wait.
</P>
<P>
   That leads to the fear pervading the industry. Once the new,
lower-priced HDTV's reach the showrooms later this year, American
consumers will begin taking notice. They will decide to buy an
HDTV, but after the price falls even further. And in the meantime,
they will not buy anything else _ analog or digital _ giving the
industry a disastrous year.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives have been hoping for a seamless transition
that when graphed, looks like an X as the sale of digital sets
climbs at the same rate as the sale of analog sets falls. But some
companies, hoping to use the transition to gain a greater market
share, are cutting prices faster than the others had bargained for,
threatening that development.
</P>
<P>
   Some executives had worried that they would have faced this
situation already. But the industry actually sold 6 percent more
television sets in 1998 than the year before _ the largest number
of them at the end of the year, after the first high-definition
sets had gone on sale. This suggests that most consumers have not
yet taken serious notice of high-definition television.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
