<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Jan. 11, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bitterly cold air will arrive across the Great Lakes and
Northeast on Monday in the wake of a cold front departing the
Atlantic seaboard. Residual moisture behind the front will cause
snow flurries to linger across the mountains of New England.
Farther east, gusty winds from the northwest drying on descent from
the Appalachians will squelch clouds, causing abundant sunshine
along the northeast coast.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as cold air gathers heat and moisture on transit over
the unfrozen Great Lakes, snow squalls will affect areas downwind
of the lakes. Over 6 inches of fresh snow could accumulate in
Michigan's upper peninsula and the snow belts east of Lake Erie and
Lake Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   After a clear and cold start, sinking air currents associated
with high pressure will promote sunny conditions over the Southeast
on Monday, including northern Florida. A jet-stream disturbance
crossing the tepid waters off south Florida could spawn a few
showers near the southeast coast.
</P>
<P>
   An ``Alberta clipper'' low, which is a fast-moving low-pressure
system originating in the province of Alberta, will cross the
northern Plains on Monday. The low will bring a swath of snow from
North Dakota to Illinois, though a modicum of moisture and the
system's rapid movement will preclude heavy snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   Gusty winds from the west will direct warm air to the front
range of the Rockies on Monday with noticeably milder conditions
streaming into the southern Plains and Texas. Onshore breezes will
promote showers near the northwest coast Monday. Fog will still
plague much of the Central Valley, with cirrus clouds dimming the
sun at times elsewhere in California.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: California Contrasts
</P>
<P>
   Paso Robles, Calif., experienced record extremes in temperature
on Saturday without a cloud in the sky. The day dawned calm with a
record minimum of 21 degrees, breaking a 50-year-old record by 1
degree. An active breeze from the east developed at midday and this
helped to raise the afternoon temperature to a record 74 degrees,
eclipsing a record set in 1962. The 53-degree change in one day at
Paso Robles is more than some sections of the California coast see
in six months and is also indicative of the dry air mass that has
migrated to the central California shores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
