<HEADER>
A6829 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEYBOARD-CONVERSATION     01-10 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEYBOARD-CONVERSATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSION AND MOONLIGHT, WITH FOOTNOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In classical music, it often seems, all roads lead to
Beethoven. Two such paths converged last week when Jeffrey Siegel
and Ruth Laredo, pianists and commentators, turned their efforts to
that German master.
</P>
<P>
   Talk from the stage has become commonplace in recent years, if
not during concerts themselves then in the form of preconcert
lectures, as musical institutions strive to sustain or build on
current audiences. Commentary is increasingly seen as a way to
bridge the gap between listener and performer, and to compensate
for cutbacks in educational resources among the public. But the
pianists at hand began supplementing their performances with chat
long before it became fashionable to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel, who is in his 12th season of Keyboard Conversations at
the 92nd Street Y, gave a rationale for the practice at the start
of his program, ``Beethoven Forever,'' on Wednesday evening. The
conversation is intended to make the listening experience more
meaningful, he said, ``something more enriching than a mere wash of
sound.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time of ``musical too much,'' he added, with masterpieces
often taken for granted, ``one needs to learn to listen to that
which one hears.'' Accordingly, he provides a brief analysis of a
composition, complete with musical examples, before playing it
whole.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Laredo, who is in her 11th season of Concerts With
Commentary at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, seemed less
interested in providing detailed musical insight on Friday evening
than in creating an atmosphere. Her commentary consisted of a
reading of biographical information that might just as well have
been printed in the program, except on the theory, perhaps, that
the material sinks in better when administered aurally and that the
process enhances the connection between performer and listener.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Laredo's little lectures and performances, one as formal as
the other, remained distinct. Siegel, despite a certain stiffness
of manner, established a more relaxed setting for the listener
while making greater demands on himself.
</P>
<P>
   Public speaking, performance and analysis all demand different
types of concentration, which don't mix easily. Every longtime
listener has undoubtedly seen performers who, having delivered
detailed explanations of what they were about to play, proved
unable to play it, as if stumbling over feet watched too closely in
the act of walking.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel did remarkably well at all this, not only speaking but
also playing from memory, even as he extracted a voice from the
texture or showed how a particular turn or cadence might have
progressed differently. The demonstrations were illuminating,
although they tended to continue into the performances, with Siegel
making many of the same points again in exaggerated fashion, mildly
distorting the flow of the music and occasionally tripping
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   For all of that, he gave interesting expositions and reasonably
persuasive performances of three Beethoven bagatelles as well as
two sonatas: the ``Pathetique'' and the late E major (Op. 109).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Laredo was less compelling on both counts. She opened with
the ``Moonlight'' Sonata (the famous first movement only),
presumably trying to set a mood but instead establishing a tone:
one of perfunctoriness, which was furthered by a late program
change, with the lofty Opus 101 Sonata dropped from the end.
</P>
<P>
   Her survey of Beethoven's life thus seemed oddly inconclusive,
trailing off with the ``Appassionata'' Sonata (Op. 57). The
performances of that work and of the early C major Sonata (Op. 2,
No. 3), though unmingled with significant analysis, suffered
occasional slips of hand or memory but were basically sound and
shapely.
</P>
<P>
   To judge from audience turnout and response, it is clear that
these series, seemingly similar but in fact quite disparate, have
developed loyal and appreciative followings. Whether they serve any
larger function in building audiences for classical music is an
open question but one that need not concern these performers. In
carving out valued niches for themselves, they have done enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
