<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6831 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOMA-PROFILE-MEDIA-AR     01-10 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOMA-PROFILE-MEDIA-ART-950&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KAY GRAHAM OF JAPAN'S MEDIA INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By SUZANNE CHARLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In a wood-paneled room rich with Persian carpets in the
sedate Bunkyo-ku district, Sawako Noma, 55, sat forward as she
offered a visitor coffee. Wearing a neat gray suit with knee-length
skirt, her short hair neatly coiffured, her crossed ankles leading
to sensible low heels, Mrs. Noma looked to be the prototypical
Japanese housewife: demure, gracious, unprepossessing.
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what Mrs. Noma was until 1987, when her husband
died and she took over the reins of Kodansha Ltd., Japan's largest
publishing company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no editorial experience, no schooling in business,'' she
said. Her resume bears out her words. The first entry, after higher
education (Seisen Women's University) reads: June 1987 _ President
and CEO, Kodansha Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   She is, some say, the Katharine Graham of Japan's media
industry. The busts &UR;  &LR;  guarding the fireplace in the guest room of
the corporate headquarters are those of her grandfather, Seiji
Noma, who started the company in 1909, and her grandmother who ran
the company for a time. But to make the analogy complete, one might
have to throw in Random House for good measure. As head of
Kodansha, Mrs. Noma reigns over an empire of 1,173 employees, 54
magazines, a newspaper, and book companies in Japan, the United
States and Europe that published 2,576 new titles in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Like her counterpart at The Washington Post, Mrs. Noma met with
some resistance when she assumed power. ``Kodansha tends to attract
some very smart, very arrogant, very hidebound people _ extremely
well-paid men who see themselves as creme de la creme,'' said a
publishing executive who insisted on not being identified. ``There
was a tremendous war _ rather like the Heike-Genji war,'' he said,
referring to Japan's 12th-century civil war. ``The Nomas had become
weak, because there was no male heir ready to assume power.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Noma graciously but firmly skirted any suggestion of
rebellion, saying only, ``I think everybody thought the president
had to be a man.'' But she said her son, Yoshinibu, was only 18
years old at the time, a university freshman. ``I didn't want to
sacrifice his youth,'' she said, adding that she wanted him and her
three daughters to be able to experience life and make their own
mistakes. At the same time, she felt a sense of duty to the family.
``It was my obligation to become president,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to her speak, it is clear that she also relished the
chance to break out of her sheltered existence. ``My curiosity was
stronger than any fear,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't say anything,'' Mrs. Noma recalled of her first year
on the job. ``I just watched and found out how things were run.
Then I started making suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   Her suggestions have won her respect inside and outside her
company, and business analysts credit her with Kodansha's success.
(In 1996, World Business, an Asian business magazine, selected her
as one of the world's 50 most prominent businesswomen). In the
decade since she has taken over, Kodansha has solidified its
position as the No. 1 publishing company in Japan. Corporate sales
in 1997 topped 200 billion yen ($1.8 billion) _ a 32 percent
increase over 1987, and a quite respectable figure considering that
Japan has been in recession for the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   One of her first acts as president was to dump Penthouse Japan
from the company's magazine roster. She approved the addition of a
number of women's magazines to an already successful group. The new
ones are Voce (which concentrates on beauty with a clever ad
campaign featuring some of Japan's most unattractive personalities,
all made up), Vivi (aimed at women in their teens and 20s) and Mine
(for independent young women, single or just married).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese magazine business has been horrible since the
bubble burst,'' said Robert Kirschenbaum, president of Pacific
Press Service, a Tokyo photographers' agency. ``But the women's
magazines continue to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine stable _ which accounts for 64 percent of
Kodansha's sales _ is broad, ranging from the respected literary
magazine Gunzo, with a circulation of 20,000, to the comic magazine
Shonen, 400 pages of tales of wild-eyed sushi chefs and crazed
ninjas. Shonen is bought by 4.2 million preteen and teen-age boys
and girls each week.
</P>
<P>
   The book list is similarly varied, ranging from works by
literary luminaries like the Nobel laureates Yasunari Kawabata and
Kenzaburo Oe to children's books, including ``Totto-chan: The
Little Girl at the Window,'' which has sold 6.8 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Noma has also continued to expand Kodansha's global reach
by financing several literary awards _ including one for
translations of Japanese literature _ and by publishing works of
Japanese literature through Kodansha International and its
subsidiary, Kodansha America.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Noma's eldest daughter, Chikako Noma, who works as a senior
editor for Kodansha America in New York, noted that the
international division was more of a mission than a profit center.
The mission has met with considerable success. The division has
introduced English translations of the works of the Nobel laureates
as well as those by a younger writers, including ``Norwegian
Wood,'' by Haruki Murakami.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most surprising, under Sawako Noma, the editors at
Kodansha America have published original titles on American life,
several of which have made it to best-seller lists. ``Having Our
Say,'' the stories of Sarah and A. Elizabeth Delany, two black
sisters, sold 1.5 million copies and was on The New York Times
best-seller list for 35 weeks (hardcover) and 63 weeks (paperback,
published by Dell).
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   No Western publishers have achieved such bicultural success,
although the Japanese public has a voracious appetite for foreign
books.
</P>
<P>
   Sawako Noma and others point out that publishing is very
different in Japan from what it is in the rest of the world, and
the language barrier has proved to be a mighty fortress against
foreign incursion, as would-be interlopers like Rupert Murdoch have
learned.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese publishers are also blessed with a public that is
almost 100 percent literate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America, there are a limited number of people who can be
called readers,'' said Tetsu Shirai, deputy executive director of
Kodansha International who headed Kodansha America in the 1980s.
``In Japan, the ordinary citizen likes to read _ reading is seen as
entertainment and has been since the 16th and 17th centuries. In
America, there seems to be a psychological barrier for people to go
to a bookstore. Here, it isn't uncommon, even in the smallest of
towns, for people to set a date to meet at a bookstore.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Japanese publishers are worried. Sales show that
instead of buying books and magazines, young people are spending
their money on cellular phones and computer games. Kodansha and
other publishers are starting a campaign this spring to combat this
trend.
</P>
<P>
   And Sawako Noma signed off on the company's expansion into
animated movie and video productions, based on its cartoon
characters. ``Akira,'' which stars a big-eyed character by the same
name, became an instant classic, and ``Ghost in the Shell'' hit No.
1 in sales in its seventh week on the U.S. video charts in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 1732EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
