<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WB-TIME-WARNER-1000(2     01-10 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WB-TIME-WARNER-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WB SUCCEEDS BY SERVING YOUTH ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Along with much of the audience and most of
the profit, the confidence bordering on arrogance that once
characterized the network television business has faded away this
season.
</P>
<P>
   But it is alive and well in at least one place, TV's youngest,
hippest and increasingly only upwardly mobile address: the upstart
would-be network known as WB &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to figures that make WB the only broadcast network to
demonstrate ratings growth this season, company executives view
themselves as already securely established as a legitimate fifth
network, on track to turning a profit within two years, and in
position to assume complete leadership among the youngest segment
of adult TV viewers within five years.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe, the two top WB executives said, the network might
just even start scheduling more shows from Warner Brothers, the
studio owned by its parent company, Time Warner &UR;  &LR; _ if only the
studio starts making shows good enough and hip enough to squeeze
their way onto the roster that now includes such youth-oriented
hits as ``Buffy, the Vampire Slayer,'' ``Dawson's Creek'' and
``Seventh Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Warner Brothers just has to do a better job'' developing shows
with the youthful skew that WB requires, said Jamie Kellner, the
chief executive of WB. Kellner and Susanne Daniels, the new
president of WB's entertainment division, spoke at a session of the
Television Critics' Association meeting here last week and in
separate interviews later.
</P>
<P>
   For WB, ``broadcasting'' is increasingly a misnomer because the
network is unflinchingly dedicated to never becoming too broad for
its own good. The model, as Kellner put it, is not what NBC &UR;  &LR; has
been for the last five years, the dominant network with a wide
range of viewers, nor even what Fox &UR;  &LR; would like to become, the
leader with a large adult group of viewers up to the age of 49.
</P>
<P>
   Radio is attractive as the new model, Kellner said, because
radio companies have done increasingly well on Wall Street despite
being highly fragmented and controlling extremely small slices of
audience.
</P>
<P>
   That looks to be the future of television networks as well, he
said, adding, ``If it's going to be a fragmented marketplace, make
sure the one you're hanging onto is the most valuable one in terms
of advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   As WB sees it, what advertisers want is youth, more youth and
nothing but youth, and the network is searingly focused on giving
them exactly that. Far from looking to expand its reach, to compete
for wider segments of viewers, Kellner said, WB would stick to its
youth orientation. ``Our goal is to remain with a median age under
30 years of age,'' he said. ``That is the long-term, set-in-stone
goal for this network.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least one other goal when the network was established
four years ago by the Warner television studio was that it would
serve as the fallback distribution outlet for the programs the
studio makes. Warner Brothers was concerned about the increasing
effort by the networks that carried its programs, mostly NBC, owned
by General Electric Co., and ABC, &UR;  &LR; a unit of Walt Disney Co., to
fill their schedules with shows they themselves owned. Subsequent
schedules from those networks have begun to validate those
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Kellner conceded that ``vertical integration is going to happen
in television,'' with networks relying more on shows delivered by
the studios with which they are aligned.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean Warner Brothers will soon be restricted to
producing shows exclusively filled with characters in their teens
and early 20s?
</P>
<P>
   Barry M. Meyer, the executive vice president of Warner Brothers,
said he did not think so, because he could not envision a time when
a network would be totally vertically integrated, locking out shows
from any other studio. He conceded that the ``landscape has changed
a bit,'' with networks like NBC trying to compel studios to cede
ownership to them on every show scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are still producing older shows for CBS &UR;  &LR; and a lot of
shows for NBC,'' Meyer said. ``If there is a major shift in the
policies at these networks, then the whole industry is going to
have to be re-evaluated.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Warner Brothers is more than happy with the
success being built by WB, Meyer said. ``How could we not be
pleased?'' he asked. ``I don't think it's too strong a statement
that the WB is redefining the business in a way, both in its
economic model and the way they have niched themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, for the moment at least, WB is hardly a conduit for
Warner Brothers programs; only a few of its shows, and none of its
high-profile hits, are provided by the Warner's studio. Instead,
WB's schedule is dotted with shows supplied by the Warner Brothers
studio's main rivals, like Fox (``Buffy''), Disney &UR;  &LR; (``Felicity''),
Sony's Columbia unit (``Dawson's Creek'') and Aaron Spelling's
Spelling Entertainment Group (``Seventh Heaven'').
</P>
<P>
   The WB connection has proved to be a windfall for these studios
because in recent years shows on WB have sold re-run rights in
syndication for very high prices. Ms. Daniels noted that after its
first year, ``Buffy'' sold to the FX network for more than $1
million an episode.
</P>
<P>
   Kellner said WB was under no obligation to favor Warner Brothers
shows. The network is a partnership of Time Warner, the Tribune Co.
television stations group and his own company, Acme Broadcasting.
``We're in this together,'' Kellner said, adding that if Time
Warner and Tribune are unhappy with WB's executives, ``they can
fire us if they want to,'' but that while they're in place ``we
operate the business.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that ``in our first two years we got no cooperation from
the studio.'' Very few of the studio's producers generated programs
for WB. Since then, he said, ``more effort has been made.'' But he
said, ``Maybe there's a hex on us or something like that, but we've
not been able to break through yet with Warner Brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellner added: ``We always said we were going to put on the best
shows. It's their job to get some of their shows to be the best
shows.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Daniels said she expected more Warner shows to start
filtering to WB soon, after existing deals tying some of the best
Warner Brothers producers to NBC and ABC run their course. She
mentioned the team of Marta Kaufman, Kevin Bright and David Crane,
the creators of ``Friends''; Bruce Helford of ``The Drew Carey
Show'' and John Wells of ``E.R.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The object of the business is to make money,'' Kellner said,
describing the approach he believed Warner Brothers executives
should apply to WB. ``The younger you are in terms of the appeal of
your programs, the higher the value in syndication.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellner contrasted WB's strategy for building a new network with
that of Fox, where Kellner worked during its ascension in the late
1980s and early 1990s. The mistake Fox eventually made, both he and
Ms. Daniels said, was to abandon its one-time identity as ``the
bad-boy network,'' as Ms. Daniels put it, in a quest to overtake
NBC for command of the broader age group favored by many
advertisers, viewers between the ages of 18 and 49.
</P>
<P>
   Kellner said the push by Fox, a unit of News Corp., to acquire
rights to the National Football League was a mistake because it
signaled the end of a programming approach characterized by the
philosophy ``If you can see it somewhere else, it doesn't belong
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, football became hugely costly. ``The Fox network is not
profitable now,'' Kellner said,
</P>
<P>
   For Fox, of course, this analysis flies in the face of the
growth that acquiring football helped fuel, both in adding stronger
affiliated stations and in gaining wider credibility for Fox as a
full-fledged network.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kellner has a growing body of ratings results to back up
his arguments. Of the six networks now competing in prime time,
only WB has shown increases in viewing this year, about 10 percent
for the season. More important for WB, whose early success came
largely as a result of enormous viewing by teen-age girls, some of
the most significant increases have been among viewers who qualify
as young adults, those between the ages of 18 and 34.
</P>
<P>
   Kellner said WB took in about $300 million in advance
commitments from advertisers last spring, and he predicted the
comparable figure will reach $450 million this year. Movie
advertisers, particularly, have flocked to WB shows, looking for
the young viewers that form the base audience for so many
contemporary films.
</P>
<P>
   So confidence _ yes, even arrogance _ is brimming over at WB.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we are the No. 1 network 18 to 34, we'll probably be the
most profitable network in America,'' Kellner said. ``That's our
goal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
