<HEADER>
A6842 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SUPERBOMB-REVIEW-N     01-10 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SUPERBOMB-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RACE FOR THE SUPERBOMB': THE MERRY, SCARY OLD DAYS OF RACING FOR
THE BOMB 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS.: Broadcast notes are at end of review.) 
(EDS.: Time, channel are for the New York metropolitan area. Check
local listings.) (js) By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a decade after the end of World War II, the United States
and the Soviet Union waged a secret war to be the first to create
the ultimate weapon. Few people in either country knew of it, and
even the scientists and officials entrusted with the work could not
grasp the full import of what they were up to. Their efforts and
concerns are the stuff of ``Race for the Superbomb,'' Monday
nights' absorbing two-hour ``American Experience'' chronicle of the
building of the hydrogen bomb.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, mistrust of Soviet intentions combined
with what scientists had learned in making an atom bomb gave
impetus to research, championed by Edward Teller, into a weapon of
practically unlimited destructive power. In the Soviet Union,
Stalin ordered a crash program for a Soviet bomb by a team of
physicists that included, famously, the young Andrei Sakharov.
</P>
<P>
   International tensions in Berlin and Korea added to the urgency.
Although most of the U.S. physicists who had worked on the atom
bomb warned against what became known as ``the super'' (Isidor Rabi
and Enrico Fermi called it ``an evil thing''), President Harry S.
Truman, fearing lest the Soviets get there first, gave the
go-ahead, and both countries went on crash programs.
</P>
<P>
   The differences among U.S. physicists both in their attitudes
toward the idea of a hydrogen bomb and in approaches to its
creation are described Monday evening in remarkably clear fashion.
When a test of the first hydrogen device was exploded with 800
times the power of the atom bomb that destroyed Hiroshima, it was
at once evidence of the scientists' success and a confirmation for
opponents that the weapon was too powerful ever to use.
</P>
<P>
   Sakharov, who was playing catch-up with his own weaker version
of an H-bomb, said that thoughts of potential casualties turned him
old and gray. But warnings by Soviet scientists of an end to life
on earth were shelved by the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States careers were destroyed along with
friendships. The nation was alerted to the clash among the band of
physicists who had built the A-bomb when J. Robert Oppenheimer, who
condemned the idea of aiming hydrogen bombs at enemy cities, was
deprived of his security clearance, ending his role as a government
adviser. Teller, who testified against him, was ostracized by his
former colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   By 1955, the narrator says, ``The H-bomb had become a symbol of
doom.'' U.S. planes, some equipped with the bombs, were on constant
alert, requiring a huge peacetime military establishment. Richard
Rhodes, the H-bomb historian who contributes significantly to ``The
Race for the Superbomb,'' says the effort ``essentially militarized
a very peaceful democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   An epilogue notes that years after the collapse of the Soviet
Union, several thousand nuclear warheads of both Russia and the
United States remain poised for action, even though everyone now
recognizes they are too dangerous to launch. Getting rid of the
super, this thoughtful documentary concludes, has proved even
harder than building it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `RACE FOR THE SUPERBOMB'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Monday, 9 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Ott, producer; Sharon Grimberg, associate producer; Peter
Rhodes, editor; Michael Whalen, music; David Ogden Stiers,
narrator. For `The American Experience': Margaret Drain, executive
producer; Mark Samels, senior producer; David McCullough, series
host. Produced by WGBH/Boston.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
