<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6843 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TALK11-COX     01-10 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TALK11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE BIPARTISANSHIP FRAYS AS TOUGH DECISIONS LOOM
 &HT;    440&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The warmth of bipartisan accord chilled slightly
Sunday as U.S. senators clashed over witnesses and other issues in
the impeachment trial for President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Although both sides continued to praise Friday's 100-0 vote that
set procedures for opening the trial next Thursday, the decision of
whether the Senate should hear witnesses was put off. But it flared
up again as the Senate jurors fanned out to the Sunday television
talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans gave strong indications that they want to hear from
at least a handful of witnesses on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe some will have to be called,'' said Sen. John
Chafee, R-R.I.. While some Democrats considered Chafee a possible
ally in any move to cut the trial short, the senator said he would
not go along with an early dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me it is hard to have a trial without witnesses,''
Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said. If
House prosecutors say they need such testimony, ``It's going to be
pretty hard for senators to vote against it.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats doubted the need to go beyond the written record to
reach a verdict on the perjury and obstruction of justice charges
against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said on CBS-TV's
``Face the Nation'' that he opposed the idea because ``we have a
body of evidence which is just phenomenal, 60,000 pages, five
volumes, an amazing array of data. We are ready now to present the
evidence and make the decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Republican House ``managers'' who will lay out
the impeachment case to the Senate continued to lobby hard for
admission of witnesses to bring their case to life. The rules now
require a full presentation of the case followed by a vote whether
to invite witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a trial if you don't have witnesses,'' said Rep. Bill
McCollum, R-Fla. on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsay Graham, R-S.C., echoed the sentiment and proposed
6-10 witnesses. ``We're alleging that the president turned the
judicial system upside down, and you need witnesses to tell that
story,'' he said on NBC. Otherwise, ``it's easy to write it off as
a bunch of lawyers telling tales.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid this disagreement, Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, denounced the
charges against Clinton in the harshest rhetoric since the senators
were sworn in as ``impartial'' jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unanimous vote taken in the Senate the other day, I think
in no way legitimizes the sham, partisan action taken by the
House,'' Harkin told Fox News. ``All we can do is hope to cloak
ourselves ... with some dignity in handling this pile of dung.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H. shot back, asking ``Well, is your
position, Tom, that if the president committed perjury, he should
not be removed from office?''
</P>
<P>
   Harkin said that it ``depends'' on the case, and repeated that
the House had been ``reckless'' in the way it built its case.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats voiced open skepticism about the case they will
soon hear. On NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' Sen. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif., echoed White House complaints that the impeachment was a
partisan move by a lame-duck House.
</P>
<P>
   Another Californian, Democratic Sen. Dianne Feinstein, said that
although Clinton's conduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair was
reprehensible, she goes into the trial with a view ``jaundiced'' by
four years of investigations of Clinton. ``I kind of developed a
view that there are people who want to, quote, 'get this
president,' `` she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, told her that ``as jurors we have to
put that behind us'' and added, ``it isn't a question of how this
matter got to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the emergence of strife, some in this unique jury tried
to keep alive the mood established last Friday when the 100
senators met privately in the historic and intimate old Senate
chamber, where Henry Clay once forged compromises.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., said that meeting without the glare
of TV cameras had made a difference and would aid in the Senate
trial, where the current rules call for deliberations on motions
and the verdict to be conducted in secret.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., speaking on ABC's ``This Week,''
concurred. ``Our motivation ought to be to have whatever possible
being made public,'' he said, but added that he would oppose an
effort to open the entire process to cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Assessing the bipartisan cooperation so far, Sen. John Breaux,
D-La., said he has urged the White House to avoid a ``scorched
earth'' defense such as was used in the bitter House debate.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux said, the process is ``bipartisan at the kickoff,'' ``the
half-time is questionable,'' and ``if there is overtime, all bets
are off.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
