<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILICON-VALLEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN IN THE VALLEY, A SURGING ECONOMY COOLS JUST A BIT
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Silicon Valley's surging economy slowed during
1998, stung in part by the Asian economic crisis, according to an
annual report that tracks the health of the nation's leading
high-technology center.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley added 19,400 jobs last year, compared with 62,000
in 1997, and exports from the region declined for the first time in
eight years, according to the 1999 Index of Silicon Valley, which
was released Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which is compiled by Joint Venture: Silicon Valley
Network Inc., a coalition of corporate and civic organizations,
shows that the region has continued to grow but that some of the
remarkable start-up fever, a trademark of the area, has ratcheted
back. Initial public offerings, which peaked at 73 in 1996, fell to
32 in 1998, and commercial vacancies, which have been at historic
lows, inched up slightly, by more than a percentage point, from the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some signs of slowdown and a long recession that has
gripped the semiconductor equipment industry, which is centered in
the valley, there were still signs indicating that the area remains
a remarkably robust economic region.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the real average wage in the area rose 2 percent
last year, to $49,060, and real per-capita income continued to rise
at a rate faster than that of the nation as a whole. Quick-growing
companies, or ``gazelles,'' increased to 92 from 64, largely on the
strength of the explosion in Internet commerce. And the amount of
venture capital invested in Silicon Valley grew 14 percent, to $3.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The slowing of the growth rate in the area was not viewed as
entirely bad by the researchers who track the region's economic and
quality-of-life trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say we've gone back to a more normal growth rate,''
said Douglas Henton, president of Collaborative Economics in Palo
Alto, Calif., which prepared the report for Joint Venture. ``The
valley's long boom has put incredible pressure on the environment
and on housing and transportation.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the report included data that compare the
region's productivity in specific industries with the rest of the
country. Measured in terms of value added per employee, Silicon
Valley workers in the computer and communications industries
generated $250,000 for each employee, compared with slightly less
than $100,000 for the average U.S. &UR;  &LR; worker. Valley workers also
sharply outpaced average rates in the semiconductor industry and in
software.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a tremendous amount of productivity,'' Henton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the continued strong growth of the valley economy, Joint
Venture officials noted some signs of inequality and a failure to
meet future educational needs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, from 1991 to 1997, the report shows that real
income fell 8 percent for households in the bottom fifth of income
distribution. At the same time, real income rose 19 percent for
households in the top fifth of the income pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the high school graduation rate, which is now at 70
percent, has been slipping in the last five years; the graduation
rate for Hispanic students stands at 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new economy, which is more and more diverse, and the new
demographics are not intersecting,'' said Ruben Barrales, president
and chief executive of Joint Venture. ``You have Hispanic and black
kids who are not participating, and we're looking at an
unsustainable scenario right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Transportation and housing also continue to be issues that
plague the area. Last year, 31 percent of the freeway miles in
Santa Clara County received the worst possible congestion rate, up
from 26 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that Silicon Valley is considered to be the
most wired region of the country, only 52 percent of its residents
have access to e-mail. That falls to less than 30 percent for those
households with incomes of less than $40,000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
