<SLUG> BC-GIOBBI-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE REVIEW: AN EMBRACE IN MIDAIR AND OTHER ENCOUNTERS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Art is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dance and the circus were happily united when the
Lisa Giobbi Movement Theater performed on Saturday night as part of
the Altogether Different series at the Joyce Theater. The
offerings, most of them created by Ms. Giobbi, made the cast both
dance across the floor and hang above the stage from various kinds
of trapezes, cords, wires and rigging.
</P>
<P>
   Two new pieces showed off Ms. Giobbi's ingenuity.
``Temptation,'' a New York premiere to a taped score by Hayley Moss
and a group called Nomad, began with Ms. Giobbi's moving languidly
on the floor. She was tempted in an unusual fashion by Timothy
Harling, who descended head downward on a wire and pulled her up
into his arms. After entwining in midair, he returned her to the
floor looking astonished. Anyone would be astonished after an
encounter like that.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Babylon,'' a world premiere to music by Ms. Moss, Ms.
Giobbi remained high above the stage, wiggling seductively in a
scarlet costume by David Robinson that made one recall that in
ancient times Babylon was celebrated for its opulence and vice.
</P>
<P>
   Other works made artful use of earth and air. Ms. Giobbi
remained rooted to the floor in ``Hormonal Tempest.'' But the
lighting by Donalee Katz and Mitch Levine caused her arms to cast
enormous, grotesque shadows on the backdrop. Ms. Giobbi floated in
midair throughout ``Falling Angel,'' in which she resembled an
angel at times and a sylph from a 19th-century Romantic ballet at
other times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fear of Flying,'' for Jennifer Binford, Rebecca Jung,
John-Mario Sevilla and Terry Pexton, contrasted rolling movements
on the floor with aerial swayings. In ``Give Me a Sign,'' Ms.
Giobbi and Harling seemed involved in a gauche courtship.
</P>
<P>
   Harling was dragged about by bands of material attached to his
body in ``Sabastian,'' a solo he choreographed. He and Ms. Giobbi
dangled precariously from a trapeze in ``Fall From Grace,'' which
she choreographed with Sasha Pavlata. Despite the title, no one
fell. In their collaboratively devised ``Polymorphously Perverse,''
Ms. Giobbi resembled an inert rag doll as Harling partnered her.
Then he appeared to rape her. This duet certainly involved more
than clever stunts.
</P>
<P>
   The Altogether Different series features five companies at the
Joyce Theater, 175 Eighth Avenue, at 19th Street in Manhattan's
Chelsea section. Ms. Giobbi's group performs again on Thursday and
Sunday nights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 1805EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990110.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONK-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT     01-10 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONK-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC REVIEW: WALLOWING IN MELODIOUS HAPPINESS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anyone who has seen the new ``Star Trek'' movie will
have no trouble recognizing Meredith Monk and her fellow performers
as they appear in her ``Celebration Service'' at St. Mark's Church
in the East Village. They clearly are the Ba'ku, a peace-loving
people who have gained the secret of eternal youth and rejected
technology, even though their earth-tone clothing looks
suspiciously machine woven.
</P>
<P>
   The religion of the Ba'ku is unstated in ``Star Trek:
Insurrection,'' but it must surely be much as Ms. Monk imagines it
in her hourlong ceremony of song, recitation and gentle
calisthenics. Happiness is all. Happy texts come from everywhere: a
20th-century Osage woman, Martin Buber, poets of ancient India,
Afghanistan, Japan and China, the ubiquitous Hildegard von Bingen.
Happy music comes from the throats of the performers in Ms. Monk's
habitual style, which abstracts from Appalachian folk song and
Gregorian chant the lowest common denominator. Happy people sing
and smile.
</P>
<P>
   Their happiness is engaging, but disquieting. For a long time
Ms. Monk has calmly gone about breaking the normal contract of
performance, whereby performers do something excellent. She is not
in the business of excellence. She prefers pleasantness. There are
some nice moments in ``A Celebration Service,'' including a bit of
organum near the start and a twelve-part canon excerpted from
``Atlas.'' (Several additional numbers, too, come from other works
by Ms. Monk.) But the most complicated melody is one the audience
is invited to sing, ``Processional.''
</P>
<P>
   With nothing happening Friday that demanded expertise (happiness
being the most undemanding emotional state), one felt present at
something like a grade-school show. The point was not to be moved,
stirred or struck, but to condone, and perhaps this is asking too
much when the show is being put on by grown-ups. So sweet, so
tender and so unassuming, ``A Celebration Service'' was distinctly
aggressive in its demands for a sympathy it refused to earn.
</P>
<P>
   There are further performances next weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 1805EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990110.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6856 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMAZON-STOCK-ART-NYT     01-10 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-STOCK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFILING TO ADD ART NOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  AMAZON SURGE MAY REFLECT THE NEW MATH Of THE INTERNET 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ATTN: Calif., Ga.) 
(ms) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Amazon.com, the best seller that really mattered last week
was not a book title, but the company's stock. Whether it was
simply more Internet frenzy, or a further sign that online commerce
may require its own investment calculus, the company's shares had a
remarkable run last week.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, an Internet bookseller which has yet to report a
profitable quarter since going public in May 1997, saw its share
price soar by nearly 50 percent in the first trading week of the
new year. Since the beginning of December, the stock price has
climbed about 150 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some of last week's run-up came in response to news _ a stock
split, word of robust holiday sales of the company's books and
compact disks, and a deal to acquire a new warehouse. But mainly,
optimistic investors seemed willing to buy Amazon.com shares at any
price.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Friday, Amazon.com's total stock market value
surged past $30 billion, making it worth more than a major
industrial company like Texaco Inc. And even after some investors
had second thoughts, and the stock retreated sharply from its high
point, Amazon.com, with a market value of $25.4 billion, was still
worth more than the combined value of two leading retailers, J.C.
Penney and Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Amazon.com closed Friday at $160.25, up just $1.375
for the day, after trading as high as $199.125 earlier in the
session.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say this unrestrained enthusiasm despite the
company's lack of profit may reflect investors' appreciation for
Amazon.com's sales momentum and the value of its dominant position
as the leading electronic bookseller. Moreover, it comes as many
investors seem to be finding the shares of a variety of Internet
companies irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, for example, Broadcast.com Inc., which provides video
and audio programs on the Internet, saw its shares soar $65.50, or
49.6 percent, to close at $197.50, after trading as high as $230.
In the absence of news that would justify such a surge, Nasdaq
officials asked the company to offer an explanation, but
Broadcast.com declined to provide one.
</P>
<P>
   In such a context, some Internet bears see more greed than logic
in the meteoric rise of Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you explain this behavior?'' said Rick Berry, an
analyst in Atlanta with J.P. Turner &AMP; Co., who is advising
investors to sell Amazon.com's stock. ``It is avarice in its most
pure form. It's the greater fool theory, which is that someone buys
stock in the hope that someone is going to come from behind and buy
it for even more.''
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns may be expressed in a meeting expected Monday in
New York, where officials of the National Association of Securities
Dealers are to meet with securities industry executives to discuss
the recent volatility of many Nasdaq stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Berry predicted that last week's market surge in Amazon would
probably represent a buying climax, and he said he expected the
stock to start falling 30 to 50 percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts see an underlying logic, even if it does not
conform to conventional investing theory.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com's stock began booming in the first week of 1999
trading as investors anticipated the 3-for-1 stock split last
Tuesday. That same day, the Seattle-based company announced that
its fourth-quarter sales had quadrupled, to $250 million. The
company's electronic store drew more than a million new customers
in the peak holiday season when it started expanding its product
lines to include stuffed toys and personal electronics.
</P>
<P>
   That expansion impresses Derek Brown, a senior analyst with
Volpe Brown Whelan in San Francisco, who said investors were
speculating on the prospects for the company's movement into the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon sale's have gone from nowhere to $250 million,'' said
Brown, who noted that their fourth-quarter sales exceeded his
expectations by 30 to 40 percent. ``They're on a run rate for a
billion dollars a year. That revenue used to be going to
traditional booksellers. I think Amazon is taking market share and
expanding the market, and the question is who are they taking
market share from?''
</P>
<P>
   The third-place Internet bookseller, the Borders Group, has
suffered from the view that the bookstore chain has not invested
aggressively enough in the Internet. Its new chief executive,
Philip M. Pfeffer, said in late December that the company needed to
start doing more to promote its activities on the Internet even as
it continued a rapid international expansion of superstores. Last
week, Borders said its online commerce effort is projected to post
a loss of 12 to 14 cents for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble has seen its own electronic store remain lodged
in the No. 2 spot and is also losing money. But the rich German
media conglomerate Bertelsmann A.G. is its new partner in the
venture, and Bertelsmann's new chief executive, Thomas Middelhoff,
predicts that barnesandnoble.com will overtake Amazon sometime next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Barnes &AMP; Noble announced that its online sales in the
critical seven-week holiday period ending Jan. 2 rose to $17.8
million, nearly quadrupling 1997 sales in the similar period.
</P>
<P>
   But can the more traditional booksellers beat the upstart
Amazon.com in the publicity wars?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the biggest reasons behind Amazon's success is
the fact that they do have brand momentum _ Amazon gets a
tremendous amount of free publicity,'' Brown said. ``Investors
could lose interest in them, but right now they are the dominant
E-commerce player and there is little to suggest that they won't be
dominant in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly last week, there seemed to be no limit to investor
enthusiasm for the future of Amazon.com. As of Sunday afternoon,
even its No. 3 and No. 5 best sellers seemed particularly apt:
``The Motley Fool's Rule Breakers, Rule Makers: A Foolish Guide to
Picking Stocks'' and ``How to Get Started in Electronic Day
Trading: Everything You Need to Know to Win in Wall Street's
Hottest Game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 1809EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
