<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: MEASURING JUMPING TALENT; POOL CUE WITH FEEDBACK; IBM TOPS
THE LIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., Ariz., Japan)  (lb) 
 By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What makes a basketball player worth millions of dollars?
Although many factors can be involved, jumping ability doesn't
hurt. Coaches have tried to measure such talent using a system of
tall poles. Now two University of Tulsa students and a professor of
mechanical engineering have designed a method of measuring how high
someone can jump that adds a computer microprocessor and
mathematical formulas to the calculation.
</P>
<P>
   A patent for the device was issued to the professor, Steven
Tipton, and two mechanical engineering graduate students, Matt
Hackworth and Kelly Willson.
</P>
<P>
   One common technique relies on a framework of poles that looks
like ``a big clunky hat rack with rulers sticking out of it,''
Tipton explained. An athlete first reaches up and touches the
highest tag he can reach. Then he or she jumps and swats at even
higher tags. Another testing method involves putting chalk on an
athlete's hands and having him or her jump and touch a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Dissatisfaction with these methods prompted the search for a
better device. The students came up with a 9-pound, briefcase-size,
computer-controlled jumping meter. The device consists of
electrical switches attached to a timer, which is in turn attached
to a microprocessor and a display screen.
</P>
<P>
   An athlete stands upright on a slim, battery-operated pad
embedded with a series of pressure-sensitive switches. His weight
shuts down power to the mat. Then he jumps, instantly reactivating
the switches and triggering a timer. When the athlete lands again
on the pad, the switches are flipped off once again.
</P>
<P>
   The timer registers the seconds that the athlete is airborne,
and the inventors say they can use a mathematical calculation to
translate that time into a height measurement.
</P>
<P>
   Though the invention belongs to the University of Tulsa, Tipton,
Hackworth and Ms. Willson received patent 5,838,638.
</P>
<P>
   Pool Cue Offering Two Kinds of Feedback
</P>
<P>
   Playing pool may not require strength or speed, but it certainly
depends on pinpoint accuracy. Hand-eye coordination is essential to
billiards, snooker and pocket pool, as is the ability to visualize
where a ball will go. Paul Petrusek, an inventor from Phoenix,
believes mastering that technique may be the hardest part of
learning to play pool well. So he has patented a cue stick with a
guide rib embedded along its shaft.
</P>
<P>
   Beginners often miss shots in pool when the cue twists or
rotates, putting too much English on the ball and sending it off
its intended path. With difficult shots, like those reached from
the far side of a pool table, an open bridge is often used. But
Petrusek believes a bridge reduces accuracy even more.
</P>
<P>
   He believes his ribbed cue will provide beginners with the
visual and tactile feedback necessary to eliminate poor cue
handling and teach players how to continuously reproduce accurate
shots.
</P>
<P>
   His cue looks like an ordinary pool stick with a tip, a shaft
and a butt. The guide rib attaches along the length of the shaft
section in two possible ways, either slid into a dovetail joint or
snapped into clips arrayed in a groove. The rib, protruding from
the shaft, can be round, square or pointed like the tip of a
triangle.
</P>
<P>
   A player would aim the cue with the rib facing downward toward
the playing table and sliding between his or her fingers as a
guide. It could also be used with an open bridge. Petrusek received
patent 5,704,842.
</P>
<P>
   IBM Leads List of Most '98 Patents
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Patent and Trademark Office issued its annual list of
top 10 patent recipients last week, and for the sixth consecutive
year, IBM led the pack _ this time with 1,724. Otherwise, the list
was dominated by Japanese companies. The other nine, in descending
order of most patents received, were Canon, NEC, Motorola, Sony,
Samsung, Fujitsu, Toshiba, Eastman Kodak and Hitachi. Together, the
10 companies won nearly 50 percent more patents than the number
granted to the 1997 top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, DC 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
