<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6881 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRISON-STUDY-ART-1100     01-10 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-STUDY-ART-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE PRISONS SWELL AS RELEASE OF INMATES SLOWS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent wave of tougher sentencing laws has succeeded in
making criminals serve longer prison sentences and slowed the
release of inmates, helping to increase the nation's record prison
population even as crime has dropped in the 1990s, according to the
first comprehensive study of the new laws released Sunday by the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   The report, by the Bureau of Justice Statistics, found that the
average time served in state prison by violent criminals rose to 49
months in 1997 from 43 months in 1993. Measured another way, the
proportion of their sentences that these offenders had to serve
before release increased to 54 percent in 1997 from 47 percent in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the number of all types of criminals who were
eligible for release from state prison who were actually let out
fell to 31 percent in 1996 from 37 percent in 1990, the Justice
Department report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental thing the report shows is that the changes in
the American prison population are the result of a shift in policy,
rather than any basic change in the nature of criminals or the
crime rate,'' said Franklin Zimring, director of the Earl Warren
Legal Institute at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   As another indication of how public anger at criminals affected
the justice system, the report said that while most crime rates
fell beginning in 1991, the proportion of criminals arrested for
violent crimes who were sentenced to state prisons jumped sharply.
The number of arrests for murder, for example, declined to 16,100
in 1996 from 19,800 in 1990, but the rate at which offenders were
sent to prison for murder rose to 613 per 1,000 arrests in 1996
from only 460 per 1,000 arrests in 1990. Although the report did
not say so, this increase appeared to reflect harsher treatment of
criminals by prosecutors, judges and juries.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of tougher sentencing laws and public attitudes
toward crime helps explain a seeming anomaly, the report concluded.
The number of inmates incarcerated in state prisons climbed 60
percent from 1990 to 1997, but the number of people sent to prison
grew only 17 percent during those years.
</P>
<P>
   There are now 1.8 million Americans behind bars _ in jails and
state or federal prisons _ and the state prison population has been
growing at 7 percent annually since 1990, though the crime rate has
fallen for seven straight years. The Justice Department report
covered only state prison populations, which total about 1.1
million inmates.
</P>
<P>
   While the report clearly demonstrates that the new laws have
achieved the public's goal of making criminals serve longer prison
sentences, there is still widespread debate among criminologists,
law-enforcement officials and politicians over how much this has
contributed to the drop in crime.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing they agree on is that incarcerating more
criminals averts some crimes. But precisely how many is virtually
impossible to measure, given the disparity in incarceration rates
between the 50 states and the difference in motivation for and
frequency of crimes like murder and theft.
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians now claim the increase in the number of people
behind bars is responsible for the decline in crime, but Alfred
Blumstein, a criminologist at Carnegie-Mellon University in
Pittsburgh, said this was ``too simplistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It ignores the fact that throughout the 1980s crime rates were
going up when the prison population was rising just as fast as it
has in the 1990s,'' Blumstein said.
</P>
<P>
   To gauge how much impact prison has had on crime, Blumstein
suggested, it is important to separate older and younger criminals.
Since 1980, the homicide rate for adults ages 24 and older has
declined by half, and it is likely that the incarceration of many
older people convicted of murder has affected the adult homicide
rate.
</P>
<P>
   But prison has much less impact on younger people, who are
generally more impulsive and less likely to be sent to prison, and
it was an explosion of homicide by juveniles and young people that
drove violent crime rates skyward in the late 1980s, Blumstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many law-enforcement authorities have insisted that it is really
the improved and more aggressive police work that has reduced
crime, especially in New York City. But Blumstein said he has found
that police arrests per crime from 1980 to 1996 ``were remarkably
flat'' in the nation as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means there has been no demonstrable change in police
effectiveness in solving crime,'' he said, and therefore changes in
police practice ``have not been contributing to the growth in
prison population.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Justice Department report suggests that the movement by
the states and the federal government, beginning in 1984, to pass
so-called ``truth in sentencing'' laws has been instrumental in
increasing the length of time served by inmates. These laws were
designed to meet the public's frustration with sentencing practices
that allowed judges to give criminals so-called indeterminate
sentences _ a term of five to 10 years, for example. Inmates were
often released after only a fraction of the time had been served.
</P>
<P>
   The rush to pass tougher laws, which require inmates to serve
substantial portions of their sentences, speeded up after the
federal government passed its own law in 1994 providing grants for
prison construction to states that force inmates to serve 85
percent of their terms. Forty states now have a version of such
laws.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the changes in laws under which inmates now must
serve longer sentences, the Justice Department found other factors
that have also resulted in longer time served for prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen states have eliminated their parole boards, reacting to
the public's feeling that the boards were too lenient on inmates.
But even in those states where parole boards retain authority over
prison releases, the report said, the average time served by
inmates has increased to 25 months in 1996, up from 23 months in
1990, as the boards themselves have followed the trend toward
tougher punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Overall release rates from state prisons, for those inmates
eligible for release, have dropped to 31 percent in 1996 from 37
percent in 1990, the report found. The release rate for murderers
has fallen fastest, to 5.2 percent in 1996, down from 9.7 percent
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that black prison inmates generally serve
longer time for the same crime than white inmates _ 26 months for
blacks for all types of crimes compared with 24 months for whites.
The difference is most pronounced for rape, with black inmates
serving an average of 70 months while whites serve 56 months.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For drug offenses, blacks serve 20 months and whites, 18 months,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   But for murder the situation is reversed. Blacks serve an
average of 86 months, while whites serve 90 months. Since most
murders occur within a race _ with most whites killing other whites
and most blacks killing other blacks _ these statistics suggest
that the key factor in sentencing for murder may be the race of the
victim, not the race of the killer, with a lesser value being
placed on the life of black victims.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the report's most surprising finding was the slowness in
the growth in the number of new inmates sent to prison each year,
compared with the rapid increase in the prison population. The
number of new prisoners reached 540,748 in 1996, up 17 percent from
460,739 in 1990. But the total state prison population climbed to
1,100,850, up 60 percent from 689,577 in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
