<SLUG> BC-GALEGIS-PREVIEW11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barnes' inauguration signals start of challenging governorship
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For weeks after his November victory, Roy Barnes
studied inaugural addresses and pored over the utterances of other
governors taking office near the dawn of a new century.
</P>
<P>
   During an annual family holiday outing to New York, he stayed
behind in the hotel room to work on a draft of his own speech while
the rest of the family took in the post-Christmas sights of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, with the state Capitol as a backdrop, Barnes today will
deliver his carefully polished inaugural address to an anticipated
crowd of about 5,000 _ a 10-minute oratory that many associates say
Barnes has prepared for his whole life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a personal address,'' was all press secretary Gary
Horlacher would reveal about what Georgia's 80th governor will say
as he takes the oath of office. ``It's not a policy wonk speech.
It's an address from the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanked on the stage by seven of the state's eight living
ex-governors, Barnes will set the tone for his administration,
mindful that it has to follow Zell Miller, the state's most popular
and most heralded governor in recent history.
</P>
<P>
   For Barnes, a folksy Mableton attorney, the traditional outdoor
inauguration under what organizers are praying will be sunny,
albeit brisk, conditions, is a moment that seemed unlikely after
his first bid for governor in 1990 fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   But lest Barnes gets caught up in the loftiness of the moment _
a prospect aides say is unlikely for the man who's spent more than
two decades immersed in the day-to-day minutiae of policy-making in
the Legislature _ the inauguration also signals the start of the
year's legislative session. That's where he'll have to make good on
the campaign promises that put him on the flag-draped stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work ahead is what's going to be tough,'' said Sen. Steve
Thompson (D-Powder Springs), Barnes' floor leader in the Senate,
``because we have the issues of air, water and transportation that
have to be dealt with.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes won the governorship on promises to implement regional
approaches to combat water pollution, reform managed health care
and come up with new ways to untangle metro Atlanta's traffic
gridlock and clean up smog-laden air that prompted a federal
highway funding cutoff.
</P>
<P>
   After midnight chimes the end of the inaugural ball and a
weekend of festivities, Barnes will face lawmakers likely to battle
his administration over details of his proposals.
</P>
<P>
   But for today, the hard work of the next four years will be set
aside as Barnes and Lt. Gov.-elect Mark Taylor start the day with
an ecumenical service at Providence Missionary Baptist Church,
where more than a dozen religious leaders are to offer prayers for
the success of the new administration.
</P>
<P>
   About five miles away and minutes after the final benediction,
all 236 members of the Georgia Legislature will be sworn in for a
two-year term. Then lawmakers will file outside to watch Barnes and
Taylor take their oaths of office.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no parade, but local bands and choral groups will
be positioned to entertain attendees along the trek from the
Georgia State MARTA station to Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Offering the invocation will be the Rev. Frank Harrington, the
lieutenant governor's pastor in Atlanta _ and minister to the man
Barnes outpolled to win the governor's job, Republican Guy Millner.
</P>
<P>
   The full House and Senate will be able to look on from their
guest-of-honor positions around the stage erected at the foot of
the West Capitol steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy's trying to put his own stamp on (the ceremony),'' said
Senate Minority Leader Eric Johnson (R-Savannah). ``His life is the
Capitol and the General Assembly. This is a way of him
acknowledging those roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
