<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOCK-FULL OF CHOCOLATE RECIPES TO DIE FOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Death by chocolate?
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. I don't think it's going to work, in no fault due to one
recent medical dispatch indicating that people who eat chocolate
live longer than those who abstain.
</P>
<P>
   So let that be your resolution for the new year. Start each day
with capsules of vitamin E, vitamin C, a multivitamin, half an
aspirin and then hit yourself in the kisser with a few Hershey
kisses.
</P>
<P>
   Now, don't get that wild look in your eye. The study did not
indicate that you'll live to be 108 if you brush your teeth with a
Snickers bar after a breakfast of Coco-Puffs with double-fudge
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Moderation is the watch word.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, that does not seem to be the sermon preached by Marcel
Desaulniers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chocolate is not just the most deliciously intoxicating
substance in the cosmos, it might be the key to universal peace,''
he has written.
</P>
<P>
   The Williamsburg, Va., chef also wrote ``Death by Chocolate''
and, most recently, ``Death by Chocolate Cookies.''
</P>
<P>
   And he may be right about the soothing properties of chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   If everybody in Congress were forced to consume a Chocolate
Boulder before delivering a speech on the floor of the House or
Senate, back-slapping would replace back-stabbing and Henry Hyde
would make a motion to adjourn so he could join Bill Clinton for a
game of croquet on the White House lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Marcel's Chocolate Boulders
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half cups pecan pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 pound semisweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   One-half pound butter, cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 cup tightly packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon pure vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Toast the pecans on a baking sheet in a 350-degree oven. Remove
after 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Chop half the semisweet chocolate into quarter-inch pieces. Chop
the rest into eighth-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Heat an inch of water in the bottom half of a double boiler over
medium heat. Place the quarter-inch pieces in the top half of the
boiler. Heat until completely melted, stirring with a rubber
spatula. (Alice used chocolate chips and melted them in the
microwave.) Transfer the chocolate to a one-quart bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Place the softened butter in the bowl of an electric mixer. Add
the brown sugar and beat three minutes on medium speed. Scrape down
the sides with a spatula, add the eggs and vanilla then beat again,
three minutes on medium speed. Scrape down the sides then beat
again on high speed for two minutes, until smooth. Add the melted
chocolate and beat another minute on medium until incorporated.
</P>
<P>
   With the mixer on slow speed, gradually add the flour, baking
powder, salt and mix for 30 seconds. Stop the mixer motor. Add the
remaining chocolate bits and pecans. Mix on slow speed 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Remove bowl from mixer and stir with the rubber spatula to make
sure everything is thoroughly combined.
</P>
<P>
   On two cookie sheets, form cookies from heaping tablespoons of
the batter.
</P>
<P>
   Bake the sheets on the top and middle shelves of the 350-degree
oven for 12 to 14 minutes. Halfway through the baking process,
reverse places of the cookie sheets on the shelves, and turn each
sheet 180 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   When cookies are done, remove from oven, let cool on the sheets.
This recipe should make three dozen cookies. The chef recommends
they be consumed within two days, sooner if possible.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe for Chocolate Boulders is contained in the book
``Best of the Best,'' published by the editors of Food and Wine
Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Alice the Artist recently cooked up a batch of Boulders, which
were terrific, then from the same book found this recipe for
chocolate bread pudding, which is sensational. It is from
``Emeril's Creole Christmas'' but would also be terrific as a
dessert at Easter, the Fourth of July or Ground Hog Day.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Bread Pudding
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup firmly packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   One-eighth teaspoon freshly ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon pure vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 cup semisweet chocolate chips, melted
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup Grand Marnier
</P>
<P>
   2 cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   8 slices day-old white bread
</P>
<P>
   2 more cups semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   Spiced cream
</P>
<P>
   The chef advises that you can substitute any orange-flavored
liqueur for Grand Marnier. If you use liqueurs only for cooking,
buy those tiny, airline-style bottles for sale at the liquor store.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the crusts from the bread and cut the slices into
half-inch cubes. You should have about four cups.
</P>
<P>
   Grease a six-cup loaf pan with butter.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the eggs, sugar, cinnamon, nutmeg, vanilla, melted
chocolate and Grand Marnier together in a large mixing bowl until
very smooth. Add the half-and-half and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Add the bread and let mixture sit for 30 minutes, stirring
occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Pour half the mixture into the prepared pan. Sprinkle the top
with the unmelted chocolate chips. Pour the remaining bread mixture
over the chocolate chips. Bake until the pudding is set in the
center, about 55 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Let cool for five minutes. In 20 minutes Alice's pudding looked
like a punctured football. Not to worry. Because you cut the
pudding into 1-inch-thick slices and cover up all the sins with:
</P>
<P>
   Spiced Cream
</P>
<P>
   1 quart heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Beat the cream with an electric mixer on high speed in a large
mixing bowl for about two minutes. Add the sugar, cinnamon and
nutmeg and beat again until the mixture thickens and forms stiff
peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Alice cut this spiced cream recipe in half and had more than
enough to cover the pudding slices.
</P>
<P>
   There. We have done enough for the mental and physical health of
readers for this week.
</P>
<P>
   We are now trying to determine if any health studies have
indicated beneficial results from a diet of pork cracklings,
pepperoni pizza and maple bars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
