<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6895 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUBWAY-DEATH-ART-3TAK     01-10 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBWAY-DEATH-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCUSED SUBWAY KILLER LIVED A LONELY LIFE SHAPED BY MENTAL
ILLNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Goldstein is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By N.R. KLEINFIELD with KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As far back as when he was 16 and first had an
inkling that something was wrong with him, his life appeared to
turn inward and downward. Until the police took him away, he lived
in a basement shoebox of a room in Queens. He watched ``The
Simpsons'' and listened to Pink Floyd and ceaselessly paced the
linoleum floor.
</P>
<P>
   He would prattle on about becoming a business executive, though
he never progressed beyond landing a job at a Dunkin' Donuts that
lasted one day. He yearned to have an adoring wife and family, but
he had no real friends. Adrift in his thoughts, he would wander
through a graveyard and circle the streets of Queens in the dim
hours before dawn. Acquaintances said he could not seem to grasp a
future because he barely had a present.
</P>
<P>
   From the recollections of those who knew him, Andrew Goldstein,
the 29-year-old man accused of pushing Kendra Webdale to her death
under a subway train on Jan. 3, felt forlorn and rootless, an
uncomfortable and frustrated man in the grip of schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   When someone with a mental illness kills, images are evoked of a
crazed and wicked population that should be separated from the rest
of society, even though research confirms that the mentally ill are
generally no more dangerous than anyone else. But many of them need
more care than they get. Advocates who work with the mentally ill
have been quick to conclude that Andrew Goldstein was one more
person neglected by the system, that this tragedy reinforces the
notion that there is too little money and too few programs to serve
a needy population that is no longer kept in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, with Goldstein arraigned on a charge of
second-degree murder and under observation at Bellevue Hospital,
and with his past care under investigation by state and city
officials, it is unclear how well or poorly he was served by the
fragmented mental health system and by society. Nor is it clear
whether the death on those subway tracks could have been prevented.
There is always ambiguity and nuance in such stories. Mental
illness defies a tidy narrative.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein's life, as pieced together from interviews with people
who knew him and with state and city officials, is indeed untidy.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Queens on Sept. 26, 1969, and grew up on Long
Island. His parents divorced and his father moved to Delaware.
Kevin Canfield, Goldstein's court-appointed lawyer, said that
Goldstein had told him that his father is an anesthesiologist and
his mother a secretary, and that he has two brothers. Canfield said
that Goldstein's parents refused to talk about their son.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein went to the Bronx High School of Science, a top public
high school that admits students through a citywide entrance exam.
``For the most part, he was always alone,'' said Carl Aridas, 29, a
risk management officer who went to high school with him. ``He
played chess but was not particularly good. He also came out to
play softball but he wasn't too athletic.'' He said Goldstein was
focused on his grades and intent on going to medical school.
</P>
<P>
   Without warning, something scary happened when he was 16.
According to Canfield, Goldstein told him that he was riding the
bus to school and reading a book when he could no longer make sense
of the sentences before him. He began getting medical and
psychiatric care.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he graduated from Bronx Science in 1987 and enrolled at
the State University of New York at Stony Brook (where he took
courses on and off until as recently as the fall of 1997). While at
college, his schizophrenia intensified (the disease tends to
manifest itself during the college years) and in August 1989 he was
committed to Creedmoor Psychiatric Center, a state-run hospital in
Queens, the first of three commitments there. He was discharged in
September and remained an outpatient. In August 1992, he was
committed a second time and again was discharged the following
month.
</P>
<P>
   Under his disability, he received a monthly Supplemental
Security Income check of about $550. For several months, he shared
an apartment in Kew Garden Hills with Larry Termo, now 51, a
counselor at Incube Inc., a New York organization that helps people
with psychiatric histories get jobs. Goldstein was going to
Vocational Rehabilitation Service in Queens for treatment, though
someone who knew him there said he was flippant and not truly
engaged in the group sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Termo said Goldstein was unreliable about taking his medication.
He took Haldol, an anti-psychotic, and Cogentin, which treats the
trembling side-effects that often accompany Haldol. Termo said
Goldstein complained that the pills made him sleepy.
</P>
<P>
   Termo said he also felt Goldstein was in some denial about his
illness. Termo urged him to find work. Goldstein reported to his a
job at Dunkin' Donuts for only one day, Termo said. He insisted he
wanted to start at the top. ``I would talk to him, his eyes would
get wide, he wouldn't quite understand,'' Termo said.
</P>
<P>
   Termo said Goldstein affected a joking manner, but seemed to
derive little pleasure out of life. One of the few times Termo saw
him truly happy was when they watched the sun rise in a Queens
park. This simple exercise put Goldstein in a buoyant mood. While
he was out, he phoned his mother to tell her about how he was
having such fun.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   When Termo would wake up at 7:30 a.m. to get ready for work, he
would often find Goldstein shuffling in the front door after
walking the neighborhood all night. Goldstein told Termo he was
making phone calls to a high school friend in Japan in the middle
of the night. The bills mounted and Termo had to pay some of them.
Once, Termo said, Goldstein ordered a $5,000 stereo that he put on
his mother's charge card. She made him return it.
</P>
<P>
   Although Termo did not feel Goldstein was dangerous, he felt he
was too much for him to handle. He thought he needed close
supervision. ``I couldn't take care of him,'' he said. ``He wasn't
doing anything with his time. I didn't feel it was healthy for him
to be just collecting his checks.'' He asked him to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Goldstein was admitted to Creedmoor's
``crisis unit,'' which gives short-term help to recently discharged
patients who are having serious trouble. While there, he assaulted
a nurse. She was not seriously injured. The assault caused
Goldstein to be committed to Creedmoor for a third time, in
December 1992. This time, he remained until August 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Termo said he visited Goldstein once at Creedmoor. Goldstein
told him that someone had a knife and wanted to hurt him. He also
said, ``Look, all of this because of a housing problem.''
</P>
<P>
   When Creedmoor discharged him, his doctors did not feel he was
ready to rejoin the community. So he was assigned to Creedmoor's
12-bed community residence that afforded supervised care. In
November 1994, he was discharged. The State Office of Mental Health
said that it has reviewed his Creedmoor discharge and deemed it
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein went to live at the Leben Home for Adults, a boarding
house containing 371 beds in Elmhurst, Queens. It offers room and
board but no counseling or supervision for someone who is mentally
ill. He lived there for most of four years.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his discharge plan, Goldstein was required to
continue counseling and medication, and he received treatment at
the New York Psychotherapy and Counseling Center and, most
recently, at the Bleuler Psychotherapy Center. Officials from both
centers did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   According to Canfield, Goldstein told him he would have periodic
hallucinatory episodes. A sense of overwhelming dread would
overtake him. He would see squares moving from the back of his head
to the front. Then his mind would go blank and he could not
remember what happened next.
</P>
<P>
   There were sundry other hospitalizations. He was treated at
Bellevue Hospital Center last May and in August went to Hillside
Hospital in Glen Oaks, Queens, to seek help. He was given a
prescription for 10 days. When the hospital called to see if he was
taking the medication, a hospital spokeswoman said, they learned he
had given them a wrong number.
</P>
<P>
   His only brush with the police was on Dec. 17, 1997. Law
enforcement officials said several youths at a Barnes and Noble in
Forest Hills, Queens, harassed him, and as he left he knocked a
woman into a bookshelf. Her eye and face were injured. He was
arrested on misdemeanor assault charges, though the woman did not
proceed with the case. The police took him to Elmhurst Hospital
Center for evaluation, where he was kept for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After he was arrested last Sunday, police officials said
Goldstein told them that less than a year ago he had tried to push
another woman in front of a subway train in Brooklyn. But the
police could find no record of the event, and his lawyer said that
Goldstein told him that the incident actually involved shoving a
woman while they were on board a subway train.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three months, Goldstein occupied a $300-a-month
basement room in a three-story brick house in Howard Beach, Queens.
He had lived there for six months several years ago, but Sarita
Gonzalez, his landlady, said she made him leave because of slovenly
habits and for nearly causing a fire while cooking. He begged to
come back, and she relented three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Three other men rented companion rooms: John Olson, 20, and
Bernard Nuza, 23, brothers who work at a local bagel shop, and
Isaac Vega, 38, a messenger. They said Goldstein was often
outwardly in a good mood _ they would even call him ``Happy'' _ but
he was desperately lonely and spoke in a disjointed fashion. Late
at night, he would drift past Nuza's room and try to strike up a
conversation. ``I think he just wanted some attention and no one
was willing to give it to him,'' Nuza said. ``He wanted to go out
with us, but he was too weird to go out with.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein noticed that two of them smoked. He began smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The other renters said he had a strained relationship with his
parents. His father would send him $50 a month, his landlady said.
Olson said he recently had a squabble with his mother over money.
He said that Goldstein would go to her for a few dollars and she
would tell him that was the last time he could see her that month.
``Everything was a negative about mom,'' said Vega.
</P>
<P>
   He never seemed to work. He had resumes in his room that listed
one-month stints as a receptionist at a leasing company, a grillman
at McDonald's and a telemarketer. He had a blank application for a
job at a CVS Pharmacy and financial aid applications to SUNY and
York College.
</P>
<P>
   To pass time, the others said, Goldstein would visit a nearby
cemetery and wander around inspecting the gravestones. Sometimes he
took long walks at night. Mostly, he stayed in his room, watching
TV and listening to music. He especially liked Pink Floyd's ``The
Wall'' which, among other things, is about mental illness and drug
use.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just a weird guy,'' Olson said. ``Sometimes he would
just laugh out loud for no reason. He would wear the same clothes
for three or four days.''
</P>
<P>
   And he would pace, back and forth across the short parameters of
his room, a dozen times, before pausing and then resuming the
pattern. Nuza said that Goldstein frequently told him he wanted to
be hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, Goldstein went unannounced to see his old
roommate, Larry Termo. They went to a Wendy's restaurant. Goldstein
had a Coke and Termo a coffee. Goldstein was broke, so Termo paid.
</P>
<P>
   Termo thought Goldstein seemed more together and, needing the
money, he mentioned that maybe he should move back in with him.
Goldstein quickly warmed to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Termo told him, ``Listen Andy, you're not going to become an
executive right away. You're going to have to take your medication
and see a counselor and acquire some skills.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Goldstein replied, ``Larry, you're really helping me.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not see him again. Two weeks ago, he left a message on
Termo's answering machine. He said he would like to get together
again. He said maybe they could go to Wendy's. He did not leave a
number, and Termo was unable to return the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy was an immature young kid who wasn't following his
therapy and was in denial that he needed therapy,'' Termo said. ``I
always felt he would learn the hard way, but not like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The other renters in the Queens basement said that recently he
had stopped taking his medication. Canfield said Goldstein told him
that his medication left him disassociated and lethargic and his
muscles stiff. Newer anti-psychotic drugs don't have the severe
side-effects of the older generations, but they are more costly.
``Andy wanted to be institutionalized,'' Canfield said. ``He knew
his life was terribly painful for himself and his family. The
tragedy is that Andrew was on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Vega said Goldstein felt particularly unwanted during the
holidays. He said that the day before he was arrested he went to
the hospital to have his ankle looked at, though there was nothing
wrong with it.
</P>
<P>
   Those who work with the mentally ill said that Goldstein seemed
poorly served by the system. ``We're really concerned that there
are huge gaps in the mental health system,'' said Jody Silver,
director of advocacy for Community Access Inc., a Manhattan program
that provides supported housing for people with psychiatric
disabilities. ``He had a place to live but he didn't have support.
It sounds like he needed a program with an intensive support
service, where he would be visited daily by a case worker who would
monitor his medication and help him with his life. He was totally
alone in the community. This person was grossly underserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Schwartz, the assistant executive director at Venture House,
a so-called clubhouse for the severely mentally ill in Queens where
people can come to socialize and get peer support, said, ``It
doesn't seem like anyone was going out of their way to help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he has not reviewed Goldstein's records, Neal Cohen, the
city's mental health commissioner, said he could not gauge how well
the system served him. He agreed that there remain funding issues.
``We have by no means completed the construction of the community
mental health system,'' he said. But he felt coordination among a
fragmented system was more vital.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, I think it's less an issue of more services
than it is an issue of coordination among the services we have,''
he said. ``When someone drops out with a history of serious mental
illness, we want the community program to make a serious effort to
return the person to the program. That's something that doesn't
just come with funding. It comes with a culture of how you care for
people with serious mental illness.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the city plans to start a pilot program called the
``Alert Program'' in the next few months. Five Manhattan hospitals
will be linked to a central data base containing treatment
information about anyone who is mentally ill and appears at the
emergency rooms of those hospitals. The hope, he said, is
eventually to expand the database citywide.
</P>
<P>
   At around 10 o'clock on Jan. 3, police officials said, Andrew
Goldstein went into Manhattan. As usual, he ate fast food. At a
Virgin Megastore near 14th Street he listened to some compact disks
at the free listening stations.
</P>
<P>
   By 5 p.m., he had made his way to the northbound platform of the
N and R station at 23rd Street and Broadway. He saw a woman at the
south end of the station. He asked her the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
