<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6910 &Cx1f; tta-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINCOLNCENTER-ARTSALE     01-10 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLNCENTER-ARTSALE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINCOLN CENTER MAY SELL A JASPER JOHNS ARTWORK  
 (EXCLUSIVE) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts is considering
selling Jasper Johns' only public artwork, the monumental
``Numbers, 1964,'' in hopes of raising what some people estimate
could be as much as $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   It would be the first time Lincoln Center had parted with work
from its impressive holdings, and opponents of the sale are worried
about the implications of a sale.
</P>
<P>
   The complex is faced with increasingly heavy production and
maintenance costs, and some fear that if it sells ``Numbers,'' it
might also sell other works on its central plaza and in the lobbies
of its buildings. The art, which thousands of music, theater and
ballet devotees see year-round, includes pieces by Henry Moore,
Elie Nadelman, Marc Chagall and David Smith.
</P>
<P>
   For 35 years ``Numbers'' has graced the lobby of the New York
State Theater. It was commissioned by one of the building's
architects, Philip Johnson, and has always hung in the spot
selected by Johnson and Johns.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the possible sale of ``Numbers,'' an imposing
9-foot-by-7-foot painting of Johns' signature gridded numbers, has
been circulating around the art world for months.
</P>
<P>
   In October Beverly Sills, Lincoln Center's chairwoman, and
Nathan Leventhal, its president, wrote to the artist: ``Word has
reached us you are upset as a result of hearing rumors that Lincoln
Center was about to sell your magnificent work `Numbers' which is
proudly displayed in the New York State Theater. This is not the
case.'' The letter said that Lincoln Center had been approached by
``several individuals,'' but that the board had ``no intention of
considering these offers or seeking others.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, however, Leventhal and Ms. Sills wrote Johns
again, saying that ``because the pressure continued to increase
from several would-be buyers we felt we had a fiduciary obligation
to inform the full Lincoln Center board of directors of these
expressions of interest. At a Dec. 14 meeting the board unanimously
decided to consider selling the painting.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, Leventhal said no firm offer had been made.
But whatever the status of a possible deal, opposition has been
mounting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's appalling,'' said Johnson, adding that he did not
know the details of a possible sale, only that Ms. Sills and
Leventhal had scheduled four different dates to meet with him, but
that ``the meeting was put off all four times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The sale of this painting is a disservice to artists, to art,
to architecture, to the architectural profession and to the
public,'' Johnson added. ``It was commissioned for the building and
is by the greatest American artist of our time.''
</P>
<P>
   Johns, in a letter he faxed on Saturday to Ms. Sills and
Leventhal, wrote: ``I realize that I am not a disinterested
observer of these maneuvers, but I do feel obliged to state my
conviction that stripping our public spaces of their salable
features would seem shortsighted and even irresponsible. I do not
think that `pressure ... from ... would-be buyers' has any
relevance to that idea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Numbers'' is historically significant because it is the
largest work in his numbers motif, and the only one in which each
number is a separate unit, on an individual stretcher, fashioned
from a material called Sculpmetal and then bolted to other units.
Because the painting was made specifically for the New York State
Theater, home to the New York City Ballet and the New York City
Opera, Johns derived the measure for the numbered grids from the
foot length of the dancer and choreographer Merce Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Johns said he could not remember what he
was paid for the painting. But he clearly remembers wearing a hard
hat when he visited the site while the building was still under
construction, to see where his piece would hang. ``I made the work
based on the site,'' he said. ``Since it's my only public
commission, it is of great importance to me. I would like it to
stay where it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the prospect of raising more than $15 million is alluring
to the board of Lincoln Center. The center has mounting expenses
because of the rising costs of its productions and festivals as
well as the maintenance of its aging buildings. But Leventhal said
it was too early to discuss the specifics of the proceeds of a
sale, because ``if there is an offer, I don't know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to say what the money could be used for other than
to ensure that ``we will continue to do what's necessary to promote
Lincoln Center.'' He did, however, say that money from a sale would
not go toward the rising cost of operating the theater.
</P>
<P>
   The New York State Theater is owned by the city and leased to
Lincoln Center, which in turn leases it to the City Center of Music
and Drama Inc., the original parent of the City Ballet and City
Opera. But Leventhal said the artwork within the theater belongs to
Lincoln Center and is the center's to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Numbers'' was bought through a fund set up by the Albert A.
List Foundation, an organization that supports the arts. Leventhal
said he had letters from Vera List, Albert's widow, endorsing the
sale. On Saturday, Mrs. List said she understood Lincoln Center's
reasons for wanting to part with ``Numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Johns is a museum piece,'' she said. ``But I still hope
they use the returns to buy contemporary art, because it enhances
the environment.'' While she said she had no idea who was
interested in buying the painting or how much it would bring, she
added, ``I assume it is worth a goodly sum of money and Lincoln
Center certainly needs money.''
</P>
<P>
   But many other people associated with Lincoln Center are
strongly against a sale. ``We at the New York City Ballet oppose
the sale of the painting,'' said Christopher Ramsey, the company's
director of external affairs. ``Eugene P. Grisanti, a member of the
ballet's board, spoke out forcefully against it at the most recent
board meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people in the museum world, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, expressed concerns over the safety of the painting,
which hangs on the lobby's north wall with a protective cordon of
red velvet ropes. Security isn't tight enough, some say. Others
believe that despite the ropes, people in the crowded lobby might
bump into the work.
</P>
<P>
   But those who believe it should stay where it is point out that
the artist chose to work with Sculpmetal because of its durability,
rather than using oil paint and encaustic, an ancient technique
involving pigment suspended in melted wax, which Johns is credited
with reviving.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a draft letter to Leventhal and Richard Schwartz, vice
chairman of the New York State Council on the Arts, Kirk Varnedoe,
the chief curator of painting and sculpture at the Museum of Modern
Art and a member of an advisory committee to Lincoln Center, wrote:
``One of the joys of any culture, and particularly of any
metropolitan area, is the possibility of encountering art outside
the museum, in a civic space. This ideal was the motivating
principle behind the series of commissions initiated as part of the
Lincoln Center project.''
</P>
<P>
   To sell this artwork for profit, Varnedoe continued, would be
``betraying'' the understanding under which the artist made the
work. ``The violation of trust would be bad enough were the piece
transferred to a museum; but 10 times worse if it were sold into
private hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Few museums would have the money to buy a painting as expensive
as this without the help of a patron. Leventhal declined to say how
much he believed the painting was worth, and said no value had been
determined. Officials at Christie's and Sotheby's auction houses
said that they had been approached by Lincoln Center recently to
appraise the work.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the painting's large size and the recent market for
Johns' work, some of the auction experts said ``Numbers'' was worth
about $10 million. Several people who have had reports from Lincoln
Center board members, though, said the price being offered was much
higher: $15 million, after a previous offer of $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation in the art world about a buyer has included David
Geffen, the Hollywood entertainment executive, who has paid
exceptionally high prices for contemporary artworks and who might
ultimately give ``Numbers'' to the Los Angeles Museum of
Contemporary Art, where he is a trustee and a building is named
after him. (Reached by phone at the weekend, Geffen denied any
interest in buying the painting.)
</P>
<P>
   Another theory is that Lincoln Center has approached the
Metropolitan Museum of Art and the Museum of Modern Art in
Manhattan, though no one wanted to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   Johns' work has long been coveted by museums around the world.
Three years ago the Museum of Modern Art held a much acclaimed
Johns retrospective. And in October the Metropolitan Museum
acquired its first Johns, ``White Flag,'' from 1955, the second in
a series that he based on the American flag. The painting came
directly from the artist's collection.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the fate of ``Numbers,'' the loudest protesters firmly
believe Lincoln Center has no business moving it, no matter what
the offers. ``It was created for the theater,'' Ramsey said. ``And
that dictates where it should stay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
