</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS WEEK WILL HAVE A THEME FOR A PROBABLE GORE CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While still months from officially declaring
himself a presidential candidate, Vice President Al Gore is
scheduled to announce a series of initiatives this week that his
aides say will be major themes of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Gore will unveil the administration's budget request for
community planning programs. Tuesday, he will propose tax
incentives for education and job training programs. Wednesday, he
will award Empowerment Zone grants and speak to a Jewish group in
New York in support of the Israeli peace process. Thursday and
Friday, he will be the host for officials from 45 countries at a
conference to promote open trade.
</P>
<P>
   These issues may sound familiar, as they have been hallmarks of
the Clinton administration. But as the backbone of Gore's campaign,
they clearly define him as an extension of Clinton, a calculation
that suggests the vice president is confident voters will reward
him for the administration's successes but not blame him for the
president's personal failings.
</P>
<P>
   But by offering only mild criticism of the behavior threatening
to drive Clinton from office, Gore seems willing to endure some
criticism. Already, two Republican presidential hopefuls, Lamar
Alexander, the former governor of Tennessee, and Sen.r John McCain
of Arizona, have denounced Gore as an apologist for the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the electoral clock is ticking, we are still more
than two years away from the term of the next president,'' Gore
said Sunday in an interview. ``So while political speculation is
understandable and omnipresent, for my part, I'm going to continue
to focus on my work as vice president and put off for quite some
time into the future a formal announcement of my candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides say he is betting that with the stars aligned as
they are _ a robust national economy, an enormously popular
president and a Clinton-Gore fund-raising apparatus already tapping
Democratic donors for the $20 million Gore expects to raise by
December _ the vice president risks nothing by not stepping out
from behind Clinton, even with the impeachment trial set to begin
this week.
</P>
<P>
   That means that people waiting to learn more about Al Gore, the
presidential aspirant, had better settle in for Al Gore, the vice
president, for many months to come. For now, he is not willing to
articulate so much as a sentence about his own personal values or
priorities, beyond the work at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, how I define my campaign and myself as a
candidate,'' Gore said. ``With all due respect, I would like to
defer a discussion of my candidacy until I have formally announced
as a candidate. I am well aware that the work which the president
and I do has all manner of political resonance, and that's as it
should be in this system. But I'm going to focus on the substance
of that work and on the impact it has on the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's unwillingness to begin defining himself as a candidate
may have had an impact at least on potential opponents. Two
potential Democratic contenders, Sens. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska and
Paul Wellstone of Minnesota, have decided not to run, and aides to
Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the House Democratic leader, said
he was unlikely to try.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, the former senator from New Jersey, has formed an
exploratory committee. And Sen.r John Kerry of Massachusetts and
the Rev. Jesse L. Jackson said they were considering a run.
</P>
<P>
   But none seems to have the fund-raising power or grass-roots
organization that Gore has built in recent years as an active
campaigner for other Democrats. He has built especially strong
contacts in the four states that will have a large influence in
producing the party nominees by virtue of their early caucuses and
primaries _ Iowa, New Hampshire, New York and California.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment trial, to be sure, remains an uncertainty. Even
so, Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic leader, said
Sunday in an interview that he did not believe that anything that
happened to Clinton ``would have any effect at all on the vice
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are not entirely sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that he would not much be affected,'' Sen. Joseph
I. Lieberman of Connecticut, one of the first Democrats to
criticize the president's moral judgment, said in an interview.
``But I'm only guessing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
