<HEADLINE>
UNDER HEAVY CLOUD, KAZAKHSTAN VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALMATY, Kazakhstan _ In an election condemned by the United
States and Europe before it was even held, President Nursultan
Nazarbayev, who has led Kazakhstan since Soviet times, ran for a
fresh seven-year term Sunday against three virtual unknowns.
</P>
<P>
   The official turnout in this Central Asian nation, which has
been courted by the West because of its large energy reserves, was
86 percent. Official results were expected on Monday, and
presidential aides said they hoped Nazarbayev would win by an 80
percent margin. Nazarbayev's chief rival, former Prime Minister
Akezhan Kazhegeldin, was disqualified from running.
</P>
<P>
   In the capital, Astana, Nazarbayev rejected vote-rigging
charges.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the U.S. State Department declared the election
unfair. The Organization of Security and Cooperation in Europe, the
West's main election-monitoring agency in the region, said it would
not recognize the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the turnout figure and the tallies for all the candidates
have clearly been determined way in advance, and the only thing
interesting in this campaign is whether Nazarbayev receives 90
percent or below,'' said a Western diplomat.
</P>
</TEXT>
