<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Monday, Jan. 11, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact David Brady at the Daily News, (818) 713-3470.
</P>
<P>
   QUAKE-SCIENCE (Los Angeles) _ When the Northridge Earthquake
erupted along a previously unknown fault on Jan. 17, 1994, it
demolished scientists' longtime hopes of predicting the Big One.
Yet on the eve of the quake's five-year anniversary, seismologists
report there is good news. Information gleaned from the quake is
helping shape crude forecasts of impending trouble, useful in
preparing structures for an eventual strike. By Phil Davis. (Will
move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   GREASE-THEFTS (Los Angeles) _ It's on your french fries, it's on
your burgers. It's grease, but to thieves, the goo is liquid gold.
So significant is the crime that on Jan. 1, a new law took effect
giving the California Highway Patrol the right to search trucks
without probable cause if they believe inedible kitchen grease is
being illegally transported. By Lisa Van Proyen.(Will move in the
``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   BOX-OFFICE (Los Angeles) _ ``A Civil Action'' scored a winning
verdict at the nation's multiplexes with an estimated $14.5 million
at 1,802 theaters during the Friday-Sunday period, studio sources
said Sunday. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``a'' national and
``n'' California news files.)
