<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-VOTE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTING IN NIGERIA GETS HIGH MARKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ Officials monitoring Nigeria's countrywide
elections said Sunday that the voting had been generally peaceful,
well organized and represented an improvement over last month's
local elections and another positive step toward the presidential
contest next month.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary results in the races for governors and legislators
in 35 of 36 states on Saturday showed that Nigeria's three
political parties scored victories in their ethnic and geographic
bases. Monitors said that the turnout was lower than in last
month's local elections, particularly in the Muslim-dominated,
Hausa-speaking north.
</P>
<P>
   The leading party, the People's Democratic Party, continued to
solidify its national standing by winning the governor's race in
more than half the states. The results further strengthened the
likelihood that Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo, the party's most prominent
member, would become the next president of Nigeria, Africa's most
populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   It was a measure of how dramatically Nigeria's political climate
has changed in the six months since the sudden death of the
dictator Gen. Sani Abacha that the governor-elect in Lagos state,
Bola Tinubu, is a former exile who spent the last four years in
London.
</P>
<P>
   ``The journey to today's triumph has been rough and difficult,''
said Tinubu, dressed in a navy blue aso oke, the traditional garb
of Nigeria's southern Yoruba people, in his victory speech.
</P>
<P>
   Tinubu, a former senator, returned to Nigeria after Abacha's
successor, Gen. Abdulsalami Abubakar, began a series of political
reforms scheduled to culminate in a handover to a civilian
government in May. His return came just after the sudden death in
July in prison of Moshood Abiola, the billionaire Yoruba and Muslim
businessman who succeeded in unifying this ethnically and
religiously divided country of 108 million, but whose victory in
the 1993 presidential elections was annulled by the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a victory for pro-democracy forces,'' said Tokunbo
Afikuyomi, another former exile who was among hundreds dancing to
Kool and the Gang's ``Celebration'' in Tinubu's house. ``It shows
that Abiola lives on.''
</P>
<P>
   Their great hope mixed with great skepticism, Nigerians cast
ballots last month in elections that domestic and foreign monitors
judged free and fair, though marked by widespread logistical
problems and at least 10 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   During the weekend, about 100 officials from embassies and
American and British election-monitoring organizations, as well as
hundreds of Nigerians, fanned out across the country to observe
ballots that were cast in the open, on sidewalks and under trees,
at simple wooden tables on which two rocks typically held down
posters that read ``polling station.''
</P>
<P>
   Monitors said the voting was more orderly than last month's.
Election officials were better trained and more responsive to
complaints, security around polling stations had improved, and
voting areas were more clearly defined. Elections have been held in
the past, but they were often rigged by the military, which has
ruled Nigeria for all but 10 years since independence from Britain
in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a better conduct of the polling,'' said K.
Srinivasan, leader of a monitoring team for the Commonwealth of
Britain and its former colonies. ``In many places a considerable
improvement. Orderly, well-organized and some lessons had been
learned. It's another step toward the road to democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Elections were held in all but one of the 36 states; they were
canceled in Bayelsa, in the Niger Delta region, where at least 20
people have been killed recently in protests over the distribution
of oil wealth.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The People's Democratic Party, a centrist party that won 60
percent of the races last month, is composed of many former
opponents of Abacha. Obasanjo, president from 1976 to 1979 and the
only military ruler to have given up power to a civilian
government, is considered such a formidable front-runner that the
two other parties have said they will present a common challenger.
</P>
<P>
   While the Alliance for Democracy and the All People's Party are
ideologically opposed, they complement each other geographically.
The Yoruba-dominated Alliance for Democracy, which is made up of
many former supporters of Abiola, won the governor's seat in six
states in its southwest base. By contrast, many former allies of
Abacha belong to the All People's Party, which won a handful of
gubernatorial positions in northern and central Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   Monitors said that the turnout appeared low in Saturday's
elections, especially in the central and northern states, where at
some stations only 5 percent of registered voters cast ballots.
They attributed the decrease from last month in part to the Muslim
holy month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   About 800 agents with the Transition Monitoring Group, an
umbrella organization of 45 Nigerian organizations observing the
elections, issued generally positive reports, said Clement Nwankwo,
the group's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there were still isolated cases of violence and some
reports of ballot boxes being stolen by party supporters,'' Nwankwo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Observers also warned that there were inconsistent practices at
polling stations, a fact that could open the door to abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``One uses ink, the other doesn't,'' Srinivasan said. ``One
folds the paper before giving it to the voter, and another
doesn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 1942EST &QL; 
