<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-SIDE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A brutal game for Brunell
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ With his left ankle swollen and his
psyche scarred, Jacksonville Jaguars quarterback Mark Brunell
limped away from Sunday's divisional-round playoff defeat here
Sunday looking like a worthy candidate for the red badge of
courage.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, for much of the four hours that preceded
Brunell's depature from Giants Stadium, the six-year veteran played
as if he was trying to win the booby prize instead of a spot in the
AFC championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had chances to get points on the board, and we had some big
plays, but we also had some costly turnovers that really hurt us,''
Brunell said following the 34-24 loss.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other player on the Jacksonville offense, Brunell
was in the middle of all three _ the chances, the cheers and the
choking.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on a balky ankle that had hobbled him the final month of
the regular season, and which required a painkiller injection for a
second consecutive week in the playoffs, he completed only 12 of 31
passes for 156 yards. Offsetting his three touchdown passes were a
like number of interceptions. His passer rating for the game was a
miniscule 46.0 and, to anyone who witnessed his performance, that
number doesn't lie.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it was a day when Brunell was alternately brilliant
and boneheaded.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that Brunell's ankle injury precluded him from
scrambling or using his feet to buy time in the pocket, Jets
defensive coordinator Bill Belichick primarily relied on a scheme
that placed more emphasis on covering than rushing. In the New York
``nickel'' packages, there often were only two defensive linemen on
the field. One neat wrinkle installed by Belichick featured five
linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell there were times he was confused and other
instances where he simply had nowhere to go with the ball,'' said
Jets strongside linebacker Mo Lewis, the former University of
Georgia standout. ``We just wanted to drop people and force him to
sit in the pocket. Going in, we figured his running wouldn't be too
much of a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Brunell ran only twice, for nine yards.
</P>
<P>
   More shocking was Brunell's lack of accuracy. A 52-yard bomb to
wide receiver Jimmy Smith on the final play of the first half was a
superb touch pass, perfectly placed over Jets cornerback Otis Smith
and free safety Jerome Henderson. A 19-yarder to Keenan McCardell
for a touchdown on third-and-15 showed nice arm strength. But
Brunell had consecutive completions only three times, was
scatterarmed much of the afternoon and had five throwaways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was,'' he acknowledged, ``a long day.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
