</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGS-JETS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jets shoot down Jaguars
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Long before it was a buzz phrase among
those harkening to a purer time in sports, Bill Parcells was old
school. The New York Jets coach embraced a time-honored football
theory that if you've got a big gun in a big game, you shoot it as
often as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In his team's 34-24 victory over Jacksonville on Sunday
afternoon, Parcells took that adage one step further, blasting away
at an overmatched Jaguars defense with a relentless double-barreled
attack that produced big plays and a berth in the AFC championship
game against the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   If Parcells was the precision marksman, his bullets were Jets
tailback Curtis Martin and wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parcells just kept loading and reloading those guys,'' said
Jaguars linebacker Kevin Hardy. ``Those two were shooting holes in
us all day.''
</P>
<P>
   On the game's first play, Martin caught a 17-yard screen pass
from Vinny Testaverde. On the second snap, the quarterback fired a
7-yard sideline pass to Johnson. Those two plays were simply an
auguring of what was to come.
</P>
<P>
   _ The pair combined to touch the ball on 53 of New York's 77
snaps, accounted for 331 of 429 yards and 21 of 29 first downs, and
scored all four Jets touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Martin had 42 ''touches'' for 182 yards. He rushed 36 times
for 124 yards, caught six passes for 58 yards and produced 13 first
downs. Twice he scored in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   _ The loquacious Johnson generated 149 yards on 11 ''touches,''
including nine catches for 121 yards. He scored the game's first
touchdown on a 21-yard reception. With less than a minute to play
in the second quarter, he sprinted to an 11-yard touchdown on a
clever end-around play. The same running play netted the Jets a key
first down in the fourth quarter and came on the same drive when
Johnson moved the chains with a 20-yard catch on third-and-14.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I'm proud of some of the little things I contributed,
too,'' said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The first overall player selected in the '96 draft finished the
game off with a flourish, intercepting Mark Brunell's desperation
last-second heave after Parcells inserted him as an extra defensive
back. He also made the key recovery of a second-quarter fumble and
veterans from both clubs suggested the unusual play was the game's
biggest.
</P>
<P>
   So versatile was his offense that Parcells, the first coach in
NFL history to lead three different teams to a conference
championship game, even offered rare praise. That the Jets were
unable to close out the Jaguars could be attributed to a defense
that became too comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Leading 17-0, the Jets were stunned by Jimmy Smith's 52-yard
touchdown catch on the final play of the first half. They also
surrendered an 88-yard kickoff return to Reggie Barlow, a play that
led to a Jaguars touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells' exuberance over his offense wasn't quite overshadowed
by those defensive lapses, but he wasn't happy with them and
acknowledged the Jets will have to improve by next Sunday to have
any chance of upsetting the Broncos. Still, the man many feel is
the best big-game coach in recent league history, has been around
long enough to know you allow yourself at least a few hours to
enjoy a playoff victory.
</P>
<P>
   Especially if you're coaching a team that hadn't posted one
since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ''Look, it wasn't aesthetically perfect in a lot of areas,''
Parcells said. ''But let's face it, that is a pretty good win for
this franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
