</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS' HAUNTING OPPORTUNITY IN DENVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Subs for story slugged FBN-JETS-BRONCOS on sports digest.) 
 (ms) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It didn't take long. The third or fourth
question for Bill Parcells after the Jets' 34-24 victory over the
Jaguars on Sunday involved his thoughts on the American Conference
championship game next Sunday in Denver, where on Saturday the
Broncos, with Terrell Davis galloping for 199 yards, stomped the
Dolphins by 38-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they play like they did against Miami, it'll be hard for
anybody to beat 'em,'' Parcells said. ``We're going to prepare and
do the best we can, but we have to improve to beat 'em. They're the
world champions, so we'll be hard pressed to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Those diplomatic words are about all anybody would expect
Parcells to say about how the Jets will try to rope, brand and
break the Broncos, especially in Mile High Stadium, where the
Broncos are 18-0 since losing to the Jaguars in the 1997 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But the Broncos are beatable; The Giants showed that.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a haunting opportunity for Parcells and these Jets
to do in Denver what Parcells and his 1990 Giants did in San
Francisco by dethroning the 49ers, who were then going for record
Super Bowl three-peat, in that season's National Conference title
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't thought about that,'' Parcells said, ``but what
happened with the Giants eight years ago is irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Not really. Not when the same coach is planning how a similar
underdog team with a similar ball-control offense will be trying to
dominate the time of possession in order to keep the ball away from
the reigning Super Bowl champions, who have a similar classic
quarterback: John Elway now, Joe Montana then.
</P>
<P>
   Time of possession made the difference Sunday _ nearly 40
minutes for the Jets, slightly more than 20 for the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   And after those 1990 Giants upset the 49ers, 15-13, on Matt
Bahr's five field goals, time of possession is why those Giants
edged the Buffalo Bills, 20-19, in Super Bowl XXV _ roughly 40
minutes for the Giants, roughly 20 for the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   In another similarity to 1990, those Giants had to cope with a
Bills team that had routed the Raiders, 51-3, in the American
Conference championship game, just as the Jets must now cope with
the Broncos coming off their rout of the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   In the National Football League's theory of relativity, a team's
next game seldom has anything to do with its previous game. The
teams and the matchups are different. But the concepts can be the
same. So look for the Jets' offense to be as aggressive in Denver
as it was Sunday against the Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   As good as the Jets' defense is, its defensive coaches (Bill
Belichick, Al Groh and Romeo Crennel, ordained by Parcells as
``Wizards'') know they can't shut down Elway and Davis completely,
any more than they shut down the Jaguars' offense with Mark Brunell
and running back Fred Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' defense isn't the 1990 Giants defense (Lawrence
Taylor, Carl Banks, Leonard Marshall, Erik Howard and Mark Collins)
that limited Montana's offense to one touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   To get to Super Bowl XXXIII in Miami on Jan. 31, the Jets must
outscore the Broncos. And the best way to do that is with long,
time-consuming drives that will depend on running back Curtis
Martin's durability and Vinny Testaverde's passes to Keyshawn
Johnson, Wayne Chrebet and Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curtis felt so light on his feet, he told me, `I've got to
have the ball today,''' fullback Keith Byars said. ``After the bye
week, he was running with fresh legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin gained a total of 182 yards _ 124 on 36 rushes (one for
every million dollars in his five-year, $36 million contract), 58
on 6 receptions of screen passes. And if the Jets are to upset the
Broncos, Martin must find a way to put those numbers together next
Sunday in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Denver defense didn't let Miami establish a running
game,'' Byars said. ``They turned Miami into a must-pass offense.
They took away Miami's will.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Bronco defense was capable of taking away the Jets'
will, Byars said: ``No, not a divisional champion. Just like we
didn't take the will away from Jacksonville.'' And after watching
how the Jaguars didn't fold against the Jets after trailing by 17
points on three different occasions, the Broncos might be
susceptible to just a bit of overconfidence next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Sharpe, their talkative tight end, reminded the Dolphins
``to have Jimmy Johnson's office ready because we're going to need
to break down film'' at the Super Bowl, as if the Broncos were
already the AFC champions.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Broncos were talking about going undefeated this
season, they lost to the Giants, 20-16, and then lost to the
Dolphins, 31-21. So they're beatable. Not that the Jets think they
can sneak up on the Broncos as the Giants did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Broncos didn't have any respect for the Giants,'' Pepper
Johnson said. ``We might not have that type of advantage that the
Giants did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' advantage is Bill Parcells, along with his defensive
Wizards and his other assistant coaches _ the same coaches that
were on Parcells' staff when the 1990 Giants upset the 49ers and
then the Bills. And on Friday the Jets will be going to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get us a big plane,'' Parcells told the Jets' president, Steve
Gutman.
</P>
<P>
   The coach meant a chartered jet with a big enough fuel tank so
that it can get to Denver non-stop. To go with what Bill Parcells
hopes will be a non-stop ball-control offense. Just like the 1990
Giants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
