<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH RIGHT BICKERS AFTER A POLITICAL DEAL WITH LEFT IN LYONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Leaders of the French conservative political parties
that lost the last national elections in 1997 were at each other's
throats again this weekend, this time over a victory.
</P>
<P>
   After three days of political back-stabbing and maneuvering amid
furious charges of betrayal, a centrist conservative was finally
elected head of the Rhone-Alpes regional parliament in Lyons early
Saturday morning, but only with leftist support from Socialist
members. The vote plunged the right _ still smarting from its 1997
national loss to the leftist coalition that put the Socialist Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin in power _ yet further into disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Anne-Marie Comparini, a member of the Union for French Democracy
party, won the regional office in post-midnight balloting after a
37-hour marathon of shady bartering that even her party colleague,
Mayor Raymond Barre of Lyons, had described as ``a disgusting
spectacle.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Comparini's triumph was a blow to former Defense Minister
Charles Millon, who had been head of the Lyons regional parliament
since 1988. Millon has been losing ground since last spring, when
he accepted support from the extreme-right National Front. The
National Front, led by Jean-Marie Le Pen, was anathema to moderate
rightists until last March, when the Socialists and other leftists
whittled down the conservative vote in elections for the powerful
regional assemblies, which control millions in spending on schools
and public works and often lure national leaders as members.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Millon, three other mainstream conservative regional
assembly leaders accepted support from the National Front, which
President Jacques Chirac denounced as racist and xenophobic for
policies that call for expulsion of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative leaders in Paris purged the apostates and formed a
new umbrella campaign organization called the Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, it was a pretty shaky grouping. Its leader, Philippe
Seguin, of the Rally for the Republic movement founded by Chirac,
was furious at the deal with the left that brought Mrs. Comparini
to power in Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the Alliance has not broken up _ let's say it's in
seriously bad shape,'' a spokesman for Seguin, Francois Fillon,
said in an interview with the conservative weekly Journal du
Dimanche. His party and its leaders, he said, expected their
partners to explain why they had accepted leftist support to win.
</P>
<P>
   Francois Bayrou, head of the Union of French Democracy,
congratulated his party colleague Mrs. Comparini on her victory and
said that while left and right would mostly keep going their
separate ways, Saturday's vote had shown that they could meet to
defend essential French republican values against extremism if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Millon, who has started a party of his own called ``The Right,''
demanded new regional elections Sunday and said that he was sure
the right could win them. ``The Alliance has blown up in mid-air,''
he told French radio.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance has been hoping to agree on a single ticket, led by
Seguin, for elections to the European Parliament in June, counting
on a strong showing then to bolster the conservatives in the next
presidential elections three years from now.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying problem for the conservatives has been that the
National Front consistently draws off 15 percent of the rightist
vote, depriving the mainstream parties of enough support to defeat
the leftist opposition in many constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
