<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENO-RECORD-ART-NYT &LR;      01-10 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-RECORD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO'S TENURE SETS A RECORD THIS CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno is set on Monday to
become the longest-serving attorney general of this century,
surpassing the record set 60 years ago by Homer Cummings, an
attorney general in the administration of Franklin Delano
Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's longevity at the Justice Department is notable because
she got the job in March 1993 almost by accident when President
Clinton hurriedly plucked her from her job as the elected
prosecutor in Dade County, Fla., after his first two nominations
for attorney general collapsed in embarrassing controversies over
household workers.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, 60, is unlikely to break the record for longest time in
the post. That is held by William Wirt, who served for 11 years
over the administrations of James Monroe and John Quincy Adams,
from Nov. 13, 1817, to March 3, 1829.
</P>
<P>
   Cummings held the post from March 4, 1933, to Jan. 2, 1939,
serving as one of Roosevelt's chief legal advisers during the
Depression banking crisis, and helping create the New Deal recovery
program.
</P>
<P>
   Cummings' insider role at the White House serves as a sharp
contrast to the chilly gulf that has often separated Reno and
Clinton, whose aides have complained about Reno's crusty
independence each time (five so far) that she has referred cases
involving Cabinet officials to independent prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   But the independent-counsel statute has also indirectly helped
Reno keep her job. Largely because removing her would seem
blatantly motivated by political pique, Clinton has never dared to
try.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's tenure got off to a potentially disastrous start when she
approved a tear-gas assault in April 1993 by the FBI on an armed
religious cult barricaded at a compound near Waco, Texas. More than
80 people died in a resulting fire. Reno accepted responsibility
for the tear-gas assault, but said the deaths were caused solely by
David Koresh, the Branch Davidian leader, who died.
</P>
<P>
   In legal circles, Reno has never been regarded as one of the
giants of the office. Nor has she compiled a record of aggressive
initiatives like Robert F. Kennedy's efforts on civil rights or
organized crime. Still, in a period when crime rates have been
falling, Reno has been an advocate for law enforcement and for
measures against youth violence and violence against women.
</P>
<P>
   In the Justice Department her stewardship has elicited criticism
and praise. Her wooden manner, lack of command of some issues and
inability to set priorities have infuriated subordinates and
threatened to erode her authority over a department of more than
100,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno remains a solitary figure of propriety in the
frequently troubled Clinton administration. She has many admirers
within the Justice Department, particularly among lower-level
employees. They regard her as a relentlessly honest and rigorously
fair public official who has softened the aloof image of the
office.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a joke going around the department suggested that some
aides are ambivalent about Reno's tenure. As the joke goes, one
employee says to another, ``Did you know that Janet Reno has just
broken the record for the longest-serving attorney general in the
last 150 years?''
</P>
<P>
   His colleague replies, ``I thought she'd been here longer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
