A6945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-DEFENSE-NYT     01-10 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS NOTEBOOK: OTIS SMITH, JOHNSON, TESTAVERDE AND BIG PLAYS
</HEADLINE>
 By FRANK LITSKY  
 (ms) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In his nine seasons in the National
Football League, Otis Smith has been a heartbreaker. The New York
Jets' 33-year-old starting cornerback makes big plays, but some of
them help the other team and not his.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's ups and downs in the Jets' 34-24 playoff victory over
the Jacksonville Jaguars Sunday were typical. On the plus side, he
made an interception and knocked down three Jaguar passes (as a
team, the Jaguars broke up only three passes). On the minus side,
he allowed two touchdown catches by Jimmy Smith, and his
pass-interference penalty on fourth-and-9 midway through the fourth
quarter let the Jaguars keep the ball and kick a field goal that
closed their deficit to 31-24.
</P>
<P>
   On Jimmy Smith's second touchdown, five minutes into the final
quarter, he came back on an underthrown pass; it was a good play by
him rather than a bad play by Otis Smith. On his first touchdown, a
52-yard desperation throw as time expired in the first half, Otis
Smith had outside coverage and Jerome Henderson, playing safety,
was supposed to cut over and protect the inside. Henderson got
there too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just miscommunication between the safety and myself,''
Otis Smith said. ``He thought I was going to be there. I thought he
was going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jets Coach Bill Parcells thought Henderson would be there, too.
When he was asked about that play, he said of Henderson: ``There's
no excuse for that. He got over too late.''
</P>
<P>
   What did Parcells say to Henderson?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can repeat it,'' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   The interference penalty against Otis Smith also came on a pass
from Mark Brunell to Jimmy Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Jimmy even saw the ball,'' Otis Smith said. ``I
broke on it, and I told the official that. He said I pushed. If he
could have looked at a replay, he may have called it differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Otis Smith's day appeared bittersweet. Not so, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way the game goes,'' he said. ``They make plays.
You make plays. I don't take any plays personally.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IT'S HARD TO MAKE HIM HAPPY
</P>
<P>
   Pepper Johnson, the Jets' middle linebacker, and Jumbo Elliott,
one of their offensive tackles, won Super Bowl rings while playing
for Parcells and the New York Giants. They did not need words to
know that the coach was hardly pleased with the way the Jets, after
taking a 17-0 lead, let the Jaguars back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing for Bill a long time,'' Johnson said. ``I'm
not happy and I know he isn't happy. He didn't say that in so many
words, but he wouldn't say you played a great game unless he
thought that. He wasn't happy with the score. We had these guys
down and they came back. He's not coaching just for a victory. With
him, a win isn't just a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, like Johnson, understands Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the game,'' Elliott said, ``he didn't tell us anything
except that we have tomorrow off. But I think he was happy that the
game plan worked extremely well. He knows how to handle things.''
</P>
<P>
   But like almost every other pro football coach, Parcells is a
prisoner of the more-work-is-better mentality. What were his
post-game plans?
</P>
<P>
   ``Get to bed early,'' he said, ``and get in the office early
tomorrow to start getting ready for Denver.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TESTAVERDE NOT THERE YET
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Testaverde did more than his share in helping the Jets
win. He completed 24 of 36 passes. In the second quarter, when
Curtis Martin fumbled, Testaverde ran down Chris Hudson, who had
picked up the fumble, and caused him to fumble away the ball on
what appeared to be an attempted lateral.
</P>
<P>
   But after the game, the Jets' quarterback seemed more interested
in handing out praise. He had kind words for Curtis Martin (``he
ran the ball fantastically''). He spoke highly of his offensive
line (``that one sack was my fault because I held on to the ball
too long''). He commended the Jaguars (``every time we scored a
touchdown, Jacksonville came back with a big play'').
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest game I've won as a pro,'' the 12-year
professional said. ``Next week against Denver will be bigger. I'm
excited, but I'm not satisfied yet. It's not a matter of money.
It's not a matter of fame. I just want to play for a Super Bowl
ring.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 2009EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
