<DOCNO> NYT19990110.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6946 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GEORGE-COLUMN-NYT     01-10 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GEORGE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: ADVERSITY MAKES JETS MORE AGGRESSIVE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Bill Parcells stormed toward Keyshawn
Johnson one day in practice last week and screamed that he had
ruined a play. Johnson yelled back that he had not. Johnson
explained why. Oh, Parcells said. Sorry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a little nervous,'' Parcells confided in Johnson.
``I'm not sure if these guys are ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson tried to calm Parcells. Assure him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're ready, coach,'' he said. ``We're ready.''
</P>
<P>
   What was Parcells so nervous about? The playoff game, the bundle
at stake versus Jacksonville, was certainly enough.
</P>
<P>
   But anxiety was defeated. The New York Jets beat the Jaguars by
34-24 at Giants Stadium Sunday afternoon and advanced to the
American Football Conference championship game against Denver next
Sunday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But whom had Parcells been more concerned about, his guys or the
other guys? He knew Jacksonville, with one of his pupils, Tom
Coughlin, as its coach, would be prepared. He considered that
Jacksonville featured a quarterback in Mark Brunell who displays
fancy feet and a cannon-like arm. No doubt, the Jaguars would be
feisty, score some points, light some fires, take some chances.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was concerned about Jacksonville, all right, but he was
more worried about his guys. Would they hear footsteps? Could they
handle the moment? Would they be too anxious, press, try to make it
all happen at once, fall behind and try to turn a good play into a
great play? Begin to fall all over themselves? Play catch-up all
day?
</P>
<P>
   We are talking adversity. How would the Jets respond?
</P>
<P>
   Before the Jets found out, the Jaguars did. They found out that
the Jets were much better at handling adversity.
</P>
<P>
   And at the start of the game, the Jets created it for
Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   These were two eager, spirited teams before kickoff, and early
on the Jets channeled their energy into success. The Jets took the
opening drive for a touchdown. At the start of the second quarter
they made it 10-0. They scored that field goal on a drive that
included a third-and-6 pass of 10 yards from Vinny Testaverde to
Wayne Chrebet, a daring pass that began at the Jets' 11-yard line.
They scored on John Hall's 52-yard kick.
</P>
<P>
   You are the Jaguars, a warm-weather team playing a hot team on a
chilly day on the road and getting no breaks. Hey, the other team
just scored a touchdown to start the game, tossed a successful
third-down pass from its own 11 and then made a 52-yard field goal.
You press. You add in that from the end of the first quarter to the
middle of the second quarter, for a stretch of more than 12
minutes, the other team has the ball for 24 plays and you have it
for 1 play. And your 1 play was an interception. If this had
happened to you, if you are the Jaguars, you wonder what is going
on. You press.
</P>
<P>
   You try to turn a good play, any play, into a great play.
</P>
<P>
   You try to score 10 points at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jets came out and established ball control and they kept
it for themselves,'' said Keenan McCardell, a Jacksonville receiver
who tried to explain what happened when the Jaguars finally got the
ball back in the second quarter on a turnover and then, on safety
Chris Hudson's foiled lateral, turned the ball right back over to
the Jets. That play helped the Jets keep the ball for another
4-plus minutes in the second quarter. For another 11 plays. For
another field goal and a 17-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris felt like the rest of us _ we had to put something
together,'' McCardell said. ``He was trying to get us points right
away. He was trying to make a play.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to turn a good play into a great play.
</P>
<P>
   Pressing under adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were trying to make plays in a playoff game,'' Coughlin
said. ``Just a foolish mistake. A dumb mistake, and Chris feels
very badly about that. It's the name of the game. Humans play it.''
</P>
<P>
   They certainly do.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to why Parcells, why the Jets, may have
been worried. How would they handle adversity?
</P>
<P>
   They found out. Jacksonville settled down and made a game of it,
ran at the Jets with gusto and closed to 31-24 with 6 minutes 38
seconds remaining in the game.
</P>
<P>
   How did the Jets respond? On their next drive, on third-and-14
at their own 30, the Jets passed. No running and no punting and no
playing to lose. It was all playing to win. Testaverde found
Johnson for a 20-yard gain. First down. More time milked. The Jets
would eventually punt, but then they would play to win on defense,
gambling, blitzing Brunell, getting the ball back to the Jets'
offense with 1:59 remaining. That led to the game's final points,
another Hall field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Jets have traveled so far, so fast this season in part
by playing to win in the face of adversity. Nothing stupid, but
plenty of risks that work. By getting up when knocked down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches have a comfort level with us now that they are not
afraid to call certain plays at any time of the game,'' tight end
Kyle Brady said. ``We have taken the season and developed a good
relationship between coaches and players and understand that during
the course of the game adversity is definitely coming. But how do
you deal with it?''
</P>
<P>
   You deal with it like Brady did.
</P>
<P>
   It was late in the third quarter, Jacksonville had just cut the
Jets' lead to 24-14 and Brady had just caught a 17-yard pass to the
Jacksonville 4. Safety Donovin Darius socked Brady so hard on the
tackle that the 6-foot-6-inch Brady, all 268 pounds of him, flew in
the air like a feather and crashed to the ground like concrete. He
slowly got up. Even more slowly, he trudged to the sideline.
Parcells was in his face, challenging him. Would Brady get back in
there? How would he handle adversity?
</P>
<P>
   ``He said something like we need you and get tough and some
other things,'' Brady said. ``Quite frankly, I'm still feeling
woozy. I can't remember the entire incident.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembers, though, getting up. Walking off. Walking back on.
</P>
<P>
   Handling the moment, the adversity, like all the Jets did. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 2014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
