<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6948 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MODERATES-BOS     01-10 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MODERATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN N.E. SENATORS KEY TO PRESIDENT'S FATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four moderate Republicans from New England, who
last week killed a proposal that would have swiftly concluded
President Clinton's impeachment trial, have emerged as a pivotal
force in deciding the president's fate.
</P>
<P>
   After hoping for days that these New Englanders would back a
blueprint for an abbreviated trial, Senate Democrats said they
accepted a compromise on Friday only after realizing the GOP
moderates wanted to retain the option of hearing from witnesses and
would not support the Democratic-backed plan.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the four Republicans _ who have demonstrated an ability to
go against the GOP tide _ remain crucial to the Democratic strategy
of ending the trial without permitting House managers to call
witnesses or present new allegations.
</P>
<P>
   The four members of the group are Senators John H. Chafee of
Rhode Island, James M. Jeffords of Vermont, and Olympia J. Snowe
and Susan M. Collins, both of Maine. Each has indicated an interest
in quickly concluding the trial, despite their refusal to back the
trial proposal of Senators Slade Gorton, a Republican of
Washington, and Joseph I. Lieberman, a Democrat of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they did not believe the moderates had buckled
under conservative pressure to conform to the party line, as some
believe moderate Republicans did during the impeachment process in
the House. But the Democrats fear that the moderates still need to
satisfy the conservative wing of the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting conflicting signals from them,'' said one
Democratic Senate aide.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Senate Democrats accepted that they ``can't ask them
to shut down the process up front,'' a Senate source involved in
Democratic leadership decisions said of the New England
Republicans. ``There has to be some factual basis on which they can
hang their hat. Once you get that factual basis, then you can
proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   Their positions are continually evolving. Snowe, Collins, and
Jeffords have said they would be interested in hearing evidence
from potential witnesses, but have not declared an absolute stance
on how that should occur. They have largely kept the details of
their opinions guarded, saying they are waiting to see how the
evidence unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, their views might diverge. The moderate New
Englanders are not a formal caucus, although they meet every
Wednesday for lunch _ with a fifth moderate member, Senator Arlen
Specter of Pennsylvania. Except for abortion rights, none could
recall a specific position on which all four moderates always break
from the Republican Party as a solid bloc. Usually they break away
one at a time on issues such as health care or the environment, and
members said they are even divided on some specifics in the
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they clearly share a constituency peculiar to New England _
fiscally conservative, socially more liberal, and willing to vote
for members of either party depending on the candidate. Three of
them, Jeffords, Snowe, and Chafee, must keep that constituency in
mind; they are up for reelection in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   They are no doubt considering poll numbers as well. Just days
before opening arguments in the trial, public opinion polls
continue to show overwhelming opposition to removing Clinton from
office over the sex scandal. The results of a CNN/Time poll
released Saturday showed 34 percent believe the Senate should
convict Clinton, which could automatically remove him from office.
But 62 percent said the charges do not warrant Clinton's removal.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's bipartisan agreement, which specifies how the first few
days of the trial will unfold, appears to have put the Senate on
the brink of avoiding a bitter impeachment battle. But the deal
postponed the most contentious debate _ the handling of potential
witnesses, including Monica S. Lewinsky _ and left open the
possibility of a future partisan split.
</P>
<P>
   In such an instance, senators in both parties said, moderate
Republicans would be a deciding factor.
</P>
<P>
   The four Republicans have proved a formidable force. During a
Republican conference last week, Snowe led the way in urging her 54
colleagues not to throw in the towel on a bipartisan agreement
after only a few hours' debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Olympia basically turned things around,'' Jeffords said of
Snowe, who has bucked the Republican party on issues such as tax
credits for the sick and family leave initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were rushing to a decision (Thursday) night and really
hadn't thought it out as to why, when there were definite feelers
coming from the Democrats that we ought to be bipartisan, there was
a rush on our side to get everything done,'' Jeffords said.
``Olympia said, `Wait a minute, why does it have to be done
tonight?' ''
</P>
<P>
   In his Republicans' weekly radio address Saturday, Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott said, ``All week, we had seemed
hopelessly divided. But after listening to one another, speaking
face to face, we came together in the last 15 minutes of our
meeting. It was a moment none of us will ever forget.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mississippi Republican said the framework would help ensure
that the Senate conducts the trial with ``decency and decorum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When this is all over, no matter what the outcome, you will be
proud of your Senate _ and prouder still that our system of
government is able to handle even this momentous matter with
civility, order, and fairness,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he still must contend with the New England Republicans,
who have made clear their intention to act on their own instincts
rather than their party's interests. The four privately have told
Lott that they will not be swayed by party interests on the most
crucial issues, such as whether to convict the president, but they
will try to help him ensure the trial is fair and adequately
thorough.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not necessarily votes that either side of the aisle
can count on,'' said Felicia Knight, a spokeswoman for Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to work with the majority leader on these kinds
of issues to the extent possible to make sure the process goes
forward,'' Jeffords said. ``But we have let it be known that our
votes on other matters are going to be based on conscience, not on
support for the leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is charged with lying under oath before a federal grand
jury and obstructing justice in trying to conceal his sexual affair
in the White House with former intern Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution requires a two-thirds majority, or 67 votes, to
convict the president. But only a simple majority of 51 is needed
to dismiss the charges or to approve a motion to cut short the
trial by forcing a vote on the articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans outnumber Democrats in the Senate, 55-45, so
Democrats need to pick up only six GOP votes to control the
proceedings if their 45 members remain unified.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the swing group on that side, in the sense that, when
things get out of whack, they can have a tempering effect,'' said
Senator Chris Dodd, a Democrat from Connecticut. ``But I think on
this matter, there is a sense that this is a very perilous few
weeks, that this is a court of last resort. . .in a sense I think
today we're all Democrats, we're all Republicans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
