<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS STILL SPLIT ON IMPEACHMENT TRIAL WITNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, R.I., S.D., La., Maine, Ill., Calif., Pa.)  (Eds: See also IMPEACH-POLITICS, IMPEACH-SENATE, IMPEACH-HISTORY) 
(mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two days after the Senate struck an unexpected note
of harmony with an agreement on how to conduct the impeachment
trial of President Clinton, Republicans and Democrats disagreed
anew Sunday over the one overriding question that threatens to
cleave the two parties: whether to call witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   With the Senate poised to hear opening arguments in the trial on
Thursday, Senate Republicans spanning the ideological spectrum
spoke forcefully Sunday for the need to hear from witnesses who
could clarify factual disputes in the case against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen a trial before where you had factual
disputes where you didn't have witnesses where you could watch
their demeanor on the stand, listen to them, judge one witness
versus another witness,'' said Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, on ``Meet
the Press,'' the NBC program. ``That's basically our system of
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., a moderate, echoed the sentiment of
most of his colleagues, saying, ``I do believe some witnesses will
have to be called.'' He also spoke on ``Meet the Press.'' But in a
sign that partisan displays may have been merely delayed by
Friday's agreement to postpone for two weeks a decision on
summoning witnesses, Democrats took the opposite stance.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that the existing record sufficiently lays out the
case for the Senate to make a determination on Clinton's fitness to
hold office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a body of evidence that is really phenomenal _ 60,000
pages, five volumes _ an amazing array of data that I think
probably answers virtually every scintilla of question there would
be about what happened and why it happened,'' said Sen. Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., the minority leader, on ``Face the Nation'' on
CBS. ``We know the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republican managers, who will prosecute the case against
Clinton, said Sunday that they would like to call six to 10
witnesses, among them Monica Lewinsky; Betty Currie, Clinton's
personal secretary; Vernon Jordan Jr., the Washington lawyer who is
Clinton's confidant; Sidney Blumenthal, a White House aide, and
perhaps unidentified women who have claimed that Clinton made
sexual advances toward them, including Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Senate begins in earnest the first presidential
impeachment trial in 131 years and only the second in the nation's
history. It will plunge into the details of a scandal that led to
Clinton's impeachment by the House of Representatives, along a near
party-line vote, on charges that he committed perjury and
obstructed justice.
</P>
<P>
   After edging toward a partisan divide last week, all 100
senators emerged from an unusual closed-door caucus on Friday with
an agreement on how to conduct the trial and to postpone the
question of summoning witnesses until after the House impeachment
managers and Clinton's lawyers have made their opening
presentations. The agreement was passed unanimously on the floor of
the Senate on Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's statements by Senate Republicans and Democrats made
clear that while the bipartisan agreement on Friday was a lesson in
comity, the rest of the proceedings may not necessarily engender
the same congeniality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suggested that we are in a bipartisan mode for the opening
kickoff,'' said Sen. John Breaux, R-La., on the ABC program ``This
Week.'' ``Half-time is questionable. And if we go into overtime,
all bets are off.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a view that Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, hoped would not
prevail. ``I do think bipartisanship will continue, irrespective of
the outcome, irrespective of the votes cast down the road,'' she
said on ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   The House and the White House are allowed to present a series of
motions in the early part of this week, with most of the activity
occurring behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers met all day Sunday planning their strategy
for the week. By noon Monday, they expect to file an executive
summary, similar to the one sent to the House Judiciary Committee
in December, maintaining that charges of perjury and obstruction of
justice are too thin to warrant impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, with Chief Justice William Rehnquist presiding, the
House will begin presenting its case, followed by the White House.
House prosecutors have indicated that they may need only eight to
10 session hours to make their case, and not the full 24 session
hours allocated to them by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who heads the House Judiciary
Committee, and the other 12 managers who will prosecute the case in
the Senate do not want to tire the senators _ and possibly undercut
their arguments for calling witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we went on for the full 24 hours, senators will say, golly,
are they ever going to shut up?'' a House Republican aide said.
``We're walking a very fine line here.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The White House, which was planning a double-barreled defense
strategy, one barrel focusing on the facts, the other on the
public, was also considering not using its full 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Following the two arguments, the Senate could face another
crucial vote, perhaps on Jan. 25 when it is expected to take up a
White House motion to dismiss the case. The vote would require a
simple majority, 51 votes, but with 45 Democrats and 55 Republicans
in the Senate, few expected that it would pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we want to hear this case out,'' said Chafee, ``and I
think I'd be surprised if a motion to dismiss at that early stage
prevailed.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaux cautioned the White House to avoid any ``scorched earth''
tactics that may delay the case, and he urged that the president's
lawyers defer from trying to get the case dismissed at the outset
of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would put a lot of pressure on people that are not ready to
make that decision,'' Breaux said. ``To make them vote on that
proposition before we hear the opening arguments, I think would be
a mistake on the part of the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   If the motion to dismiss fails, the Senate would take up the
more contentious issue of witnesses. Under the ground rules the
Senate adopted on Friday, senators would vote on a list of
witnesses that House prosecutors and the White House would like to
depose. The vote would provide an early indication of whether
senators would like more information.
</P>
<P>
   After depositions were taken, the Senate would decide which, if
any, of the witnesses would actually testify in the trial, voting
on each witness separately.
</P>
<P>
   Hopping from one morning talk show to the next, House Republican
prosecutors stepped up their call for witnesses Sunday by arguing
that it would turn the scandal's cast of characters into human
beings and help clear up differences or ambiguities in testimony.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ms. Lewinsky testified that Clinton never asked her
to lie, said Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., one of the House
prosecutors. But prosecutors say she could shed light on what
Clinton did ask her to do, especially as it refers to her job
search, an underpinning of the obstruction of justice case against
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan said it was possible that calling witnesses who are
sympathetic to Clinton may tarnish the prosecutors' case, but it
was a risk the prosecutors were willing to take.
</P>
<P>
   To help allay the concerns of senators who worry that the trial
will be weighted down by salacious details, House Republican
prosecutors have said they would stipulate to Ms. Lewinsky's
testimony on the perjury charge, which would avoid rehashing many
of the embarrassing specifics of the sexual relationship between
her and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth can come out through the witnesses,'' Rogan said on
``This Week.'' ``And if the witnesses aren't able to present the
case, then all you have are a bunch of lawyers standing up reading
the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, Republicans, and a few Democrats, urged Clinton to
postpone his State of the Union address, scheduled for Jan. 19, a
date that would overlap with his trial before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when we're in the middle of this kind of fact-finding,
it is very, it's almost schizophrenic then to turn around and go
that evening into the state of the union,'' Sen. Dianne Feinstein,
D-Calif., said on NBC. ``I know for me, it's going to be very
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., agreed. ``I think it would create
acrimony within the chamber that is really unnecessary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., whose daughter is married to
one of Hillary Rodham Clinton's brothers, said on ``Meet the
Press'' that the ``people deserve to hear from the president.''
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman, Jim Kennedy, said Clinton planned to
deliver his speech and had ``no intention of being diverted from
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 2018EST &QL; 
