<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-IMPEACH-RATINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL STORIES HURT RATINGS, CBS SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, CALIF. _ The television networks have created ``Monica
fatigue'' among viewers and hurt their own newscast ratings by
focusing so heavily on the White House sex scandal, according to
CBS News President Andrew Heyward.
</P>
<P>
   Heyward said the ``saturation coverage'' of the affair between
President Clinton and former intern Monica S. Lewinsky has created
a backlash that became measurable as the networks tallied their
fourth-quarter ratings, even though the story by then had moved
into the impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've covered it so much, it has turned off the public in
droves,'' Heyward said Saturday in an interview at the midwinter
meeting of television critics.
</P>
<P>
   Heyward's remarks followed a press conference during which CBS
Television President Leslie Moonves defended the network's decision
_ made over the opposition of Heyward and CBS News anchor Dan
Rather _ to broadcast an NFL game on Dec. 19 rather than the first
House of Representatives vote to impeach a president in 130 years.
</P>
<P>
   CBS was the only major network to stick with previously
scheduled programming (and was rewarded with higher ratings for the
football game than the other networks received for coverage of the
impeachment vote). Heyward and Rather acknowledged that they were
disappointed that the network chose to broadcast the football game,
though Heyward noted CBS provided seven news updates during the
game.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of a possible merger between CBS and CNN, the
subject of much speculation, Heyward and Moonves played down the
possibility, though neither ruled it out. In the interview, Heyward
acknowledged that CBS has had discussions with CNN since 1996 about
some form of alliance, but he said there are many obstacles to a
merger, including issues such as who would wield editorial control
and how the different approaches to news could be reconciled.
</P>
<P>
   He said CNN still is identified with ``generic, wire-service
news,'' adding, ``If CBS became that, there wouldn't be a reason to
exist for us.'' In addition, he said, there is ``ambivalence within
Time-Warner,'' owner of CNN, about a merger.
</P>
<P>
   Heyward also denounced as ``outrageous'' a subpoena issued to
``60 Minutes'' by a Marine Corps prosecutor who is seeking tapes of
an interview the CBS newsmagazine conducted with the pilot of a
military jet involved in a fatal accident last year in the Italian
Alps. CBS has filed a motion in military court arguing that the
subpoena for tapes that have not yet aired abridges the network's
rights under the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the outcry over a November ``60 Minutes'' broadcast that
showed Dr. Jack Kevorkian administering a fatal dose to a Michigan
man suffering from Lou Gehrig's disease, Heyward said he has had no
second thoughts about permitting the broadcast. ``It did what good
journalism is supposed to do, which is provoke debate about
important national issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves raised some eyebrows during a press conference when he
criticized the Gore Commission, of which he was a member, as ``rife
with bureaucracy,'' and said it was not ``a worthwhile exercise.''
The commission was established to draft a report to Vice President
Al Gore, the FCC, and Congress on what the obligations of
broadcasters should be in return for use of the new digital
spectrum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
