<HEADER>
A6958 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-AFC-NOTES11-COX     01-10 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hudson `should have just held onto the thing'
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The strangest event of Sunday's game,
and one cited by players from both teams as perhaps the most
significant, came in the second quarter with the New York Jets
leading 10-0 and driving to extend that margin.
</P>
<P>
   With a second-and-15 at the Jaguars' 17-yard line, Jets tailback
Curtis Martin carried on a draw play over the right side and
fumbled. The ball was scooped up by Jacksonville free safety Chris
Hudson, who raced 47 yards down the right sideline and had only New
York quarterback Vinny Testaverde between he and the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   But as he approached the quarterback, Hudson seemingly attempted
to lateral to corner Dave Thomas. The loose ball was deflected by
Testaverde and recovered by Jets wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson.
Referee Bob McElwee ruled that Hudson had not tried a forward
lateral, an infraction which would have kept the ball in Jaguars
possession. The recovery by Johnson stood.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Jacksonville having the ball at the Jets 35-yard
line, New York regained it and then drove 65 yards to Johnson's
10-yard score on an end-around play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to make a play, that's all,'' explained an
obviously brainlocked Hudson after the game. ``I guess I should
have just held onto the thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Select company
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, Johnson was not the first man in league playoff
history to score on a catch, score on a run, record an interception
and have a fumble recovery in the same contest. In the 1937 NFL
championship game, Chicago's Jack Manders made the same four plays
as the Bears lost to the Washington Redskins 28-21.
</P>
<P>
   Shared misery
</P>
<P>
   The snafu by Hudson wasn't the only foul-up by a Jacksonville
defensive back. Trailing 31-24, strong safety Donovin Darius
intercepted Testaverde's pass in the end zone with 2:24 to play.
Instead of just staying in the end zone and taking a touchback that
would have put the ball at the 20-yard line, Darius tried to run it
out. He was stopped at the 1-yard line. ``Dumb, just absolutely
dumb,'' Darius said. Almost as ill-advised was the play-call by
Jets coach Bill Parcells. He could have run the ball instead and
virtually bled the clock. ``If I had it to do over again,''
Parcells conceded, ``I probably wouldn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawg day afternoon
</P>
<P>
   The two former University of Georgia standout on the New York
defense both played well. Tackle Jason Ferguson had a team-high
seven tackles and also deflected a pass by Mark Brunell. Strongside
linebacker Mo Lewis had six tackles from scrimmage and also a
special teams tackle. ``This kind of win is something I've waited a
long time for, but all I'm going to do is get home, call for
delivery pizza and start thinking about next week and what it's
going to take to stop (Denver tailback) Terrell Davis.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Weakside linebacker Kevin Hardy played a superb game for the
Jaguars and finished with 19 tackles, including 14 solo stops. . .
. New York's 29 first downs established a new team record for a
playoff game. . . . Jets kicker John Hall had a 52-yard field goal,
the longest in Jets playoff history. . . . Jacksonville offensive
coordinator Chris Palmer is expected to interview for the head
coach opening in Baltimore this week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
