<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-POLITICS-925(     01-10 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-POLITICS-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL MEMO: MYRIAD ISSUES AWAIT THE ATTENTION OF WHITE HOUSE
AND CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Calif., N.H.)  (js) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON and JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a city that seems to be all impeachment all the
time, the question now is whether there is any hope of Congress
working with the Clinton administration to address the full plate
of other issues facing the country.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security and Medicare need to be overhauled before they
are driven into bankruptcy by the aging of the baby boom
generation. Military leaders say the Pentagon needs more money to
insure national security.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties have ideas for improving schools. Republicans are
pressing for big tax cuts, Democrats for more spending on health
and child care. The shortcomings in the laws governing political
fund-raising remain unaddressed.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans alike have powerful motivations to
prove to the electorate that they have not been consumed by the
impeachment process, especially given that the Senate trial of
President Clinton now seems likely to stretch into next month and
perhaps longer.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, some members of both parties think the White
House and the Republican leadership in Congress will be eager to
strike deals on big issues like Social Security once the
impeachment trial is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trial has obviously knocked everything off the agenda for
a period of time, but as a practical matter, this is a time of year
when Congress does very little anyway,'' said Sen. Judd Gregg,
R-N.H..
</P>
<P>
   ``It could end up having a positive impact because after we come
out of the trial there's going to be a desire on both ends of
Pennsylvania Avenue to show constructive action,'' Gregg said.
``The issue that's sitting there ready to go is Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   But such an outcome presumes that there is enough trust between
two parties who have been savaging each other for months that they
will be willing to wade hand-in-hand into issues that are easy
targets for demagoguery. Trust may prove to be an especially scarce
commodity since Republicans and Democrats are thinking as much in
terms of positioning themselves for the 2000 elections as in terms
of what they might accomplish legislatively this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bitter partisanship in the past has not prevented us from
getting things done,'' said Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz. ``We did it
with welfare reform and with the balanced budget agreement. But
both sides will have to believe they are getting something from it.
If both sides think they're better off by doing nothing and blaming
the other, we'll get nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is a complex and subtle political calculus at
work. Clinton would clearly like to leave a legacy of
accomplishment to offset the stain of impeachment. But doing so _
whether on big issues like Social Security and health care or on
specific programs like building more classrooms _ will require him
to compromise with Republicans, a prospect that is not appealing to
many congressional Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Democrats in particular think their best chance of
recapturing control of the House in 2000 is to paint Republicans as
right-wing zealots who have accomplished nothing of importance to
the American people. The dynamic could also be affected by whether
Rep. Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri, the House Democratic leader,
chooses to challenges Vice President Al Gore for the party's
presidential nomination, leading to an open battle between the
party's centrist and liberal factions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question for a lot of congressional Democrats is why we
should do anything to help build a record of accomplishment for the
Republican Congress,'' a senior Democratic aide in the House said.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans, too, there are widely varying views on how to
proceed at a time when their party's standing in the polls is
plummeting.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, 13 of the 19 Republicans up for re-election in
2000 are from states Clinton carried in 1996, suggesting some
willingness to move to the center. Senate Republicans are
increasingly eager to reach a deal on Social Security so they can
turn the agenda to an issue they believe is the most proven
political winner available to them: tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois has promised to
steer Republicans in a more pragmatic direction and to work with
Democrats. But any substantive compromises he makes are likely to
expose him to the same furious response from his right wing that
helped bring down Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denny Hastert has got to be able to tell the far right of his
party to knock it off, that he's going to govern from the center,''
Rep. Robert T. Matsui, D-Calif., said. ``It's possible, though,
that if he tries he'll get run over.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Matsui said, if the Republican leadership and
the White House prove willing to work with each other, ``the left
of our party won't be happy because then you'll see bills getting
passed.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also some question as to how much pressure the
electorate will put on Washington to get down to business. Stephen
Moore of the Cato Institute, a research organization influential
with conservative Republicans, said that with the economy humming
along nicely and the country lacking any sense of urgency about big
policy changes, the electorate may find gridlock in Washington to
be an acceptable or even appealing outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton, at least, is determined to show the voters an
activist administration at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will we rest on our laurels, become diverted in our energies,
or keep working together?'' Clinton asked in a speech in Detroit on
Friday. ``If we work together, there are no limits to 21st century
America.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   White House officials continue to work on a wide variety of
relatively small-bore policy initiatives to include in the budget
proposal Clinton will send to Capitol Hill on Feb. 1. And they are
considering whether to make a renewed push starting with the State
of the Union address, scheduled for Jan. 19, for a bipartisan
agreement on shoring up the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, White House officials have been floating the
idea of leaving the current retirement system more or less intact,
with its financial problems addressed through a package of benefit
cuts and tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   To make that approach more palatable to Republicans who have
been demanding that Social Security be remade to include private
investment accounts, the White House would then call for the
creation of retirement accounts that would not technically be
linked to Social Security but would use the federal budget surplus
to give individuals tax breaks or other incentives to save for old
age.
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans arguing that future budget surpluses will be
big enough both to fix Social Security and finance a big tax cut,
the administration is also considering whether to lay out
explicitly how it would use the surplus beyond dealing with Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the president believes is that the agenda-setting
function is vital to the presidency,'' Paul Begala, senior adviser
to the president, said. ``Last year he was quite innovative in
using the coalescence of the State of the Union and the budget and
the absence of Congress in early January to dominate the agenda and
set the policy agenda for the year. He intends to do the same thing
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Begala bristled at the idea that the policy proposals Clinton
announced last week _ long-term care, after-school programs, drug
treatment for inmates _ were intended to divert attention from
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a diversion, this is the presidency, this is our
job, it's leading the only superpower on God's earth,'' Begala
said. ``It's what we did last year before anyone had heard of
Monica Lewinsky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 2032EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990110.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6967 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-IMPEACH-RATINGS-BO     01-10 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-IMPEACH-RATINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL STORIES HURT RATINGS, CBS SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, CALIF. _ The television networks have created ``Monica
fatigue'' among viewers and hurt their own newscast ratings by
focusing so heavily on the White House sex scandal, according to
CBS News President Andrew Heyward.
</P>
<P>
   Heyward said the ``saturation coverage'' of the affair between
President Clinton and former intern Monica S. Lewinsky has created
a backlash that became measurable as the networks tallied their
fourth-quarter ratings, even though the story by then had moved
into the impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've covered it so much, it has turned off the public in
droves,'' Heyward said Saturday in an interview at the midwinter
meeting of television critics.
</P>
<P>
   Heyward's remarks followed a press conference during which CBS
Television President Leslie Moonves defended the network's decision
_ made over the opposition of Heyward and CBS News anchor Dan
Rather _ to broadcast an NFL game on Dec. 19 rather than the first
House of Representatives vote to impeach a president in 130 years.
</P>
<P>
   CBS was the only major network to stick with previously
scheduled programming (and was rewarded with higher ratings for the
football game than the other networks received for coverage of the
impeachment vote). Heyward and Rather acknowledged that they were
disappointed that the network chose to broadcast the football game,
though Heyward noted CBS provided seven news updates during the
game.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of a possible merger between CBS and CNN, the
subject of much speculation, Heyward and Moonves played down the
possibility, though neither ruled it out. In the interview, Heyward
acknowledged that CBS has had discussions with CNN since 1996 about
some form of alliance, but he said there are many obstacles to a
merger, including issues such as who would wield editorial control
and how the different approaches to news could be reconciled.
</P>
<P>
   He said CNN still is identified with ``generic, wire-service
news,'' adding, ``If CBS became that, there wouldn't be a reason to
exist for us.'' In addition, he said, there is ``ambivalence within
Time-Warner,'' owner of CNN, about a merger.
</P>
<P>
   Heyward also denounced as ``outrageous'' a subpoena issued to
``60 Minutes'' by a Marine Corps prosecutor who is seeking tapes of
an interview the CBS newsmagazine conducted with the pilot of a
military jet involved in a fatal accident last year in the Italian
Alps. CBS has filed a motion in military court arguing that the
subpoena for tapes that have not yet aired abridges the network's
rights under the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the outcry over a November ``60 Minutes'' broadcast that
showed Dr. Jack Kevorkian administering a fatal dose to a Michigan
man suffering from Lou Gehrig's disease, Heyward said he has had no
second thoughts about permitting the broadcast. ``It did what good
journalism is supposed to do, which is provoke debate about
important national issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves raised some eyebrows during a press conference when he
criticized the Gore Commission, of which he was a member, as ``rife
with bureaucracy,'' and said it was not ``a worthwhile exercise.''
The commission was established to draft a report to Vice President
Al Gore, the FCC, and Congress on what the obligations of
broadcasters should be in return for use of the new digital
spectrum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
