<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SUPEERBOMB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUPERBOMB': ARMS RACE MADNESS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
RACE FOR THE SUPERBOMB 
Produced by: Thomas Ott 
Channel: PBS 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite a dry, slow start, ``Race for the Superbomb,'' a new
edition of PBS's ``The American Experience,'' should be on
everyone's TV-viewing calendar. Is there a more chilling or
important late 20th-century story than that of the competitive Cold
War bomb-building and brinksmanship that imperiled humanity and
bequeathed to the world still-present dangers?
</P>
<P>
   It's fearful and sobering to be reminded of how close to
extinction the world may have come in the 1950s as the United
States and the Soviet Union secretly constructed and stockpiled
earthshaking weapons of mass destruction. And how both superpowers
proceeded aggressively but almost blindly, unsure about just what
to do with the unimaginably destructive forces their top physicists
were eagerly harnessing.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, ``Superbomb'' captures the mad atmosphere of
national paranoia _ fanned by historical experiences like Japan's
surprise attack on the US military base at Pearl Harbor in 1941 _
that drove the perilous arms race. Significantly, it reveals how
irresistible the advancement of knowledge was even to scientists
deeply worried about the consequences of their weapons work.
</P>
<P>
   According to the two-hour documentary, President Eisenhower
concluded privately that nuclear war was ``insanity,'' but insisted
he didn't know what else the nation could do to provide security.
His Soviet counterpart, Premier Khrushchev, had similarly deep
reservations, but also fueled the Cold War with bellicose talk and
frightening bomb-testing programs and production.
</P>
<P>
   The second hour of ``Race'' is a captivating real-life horror
story on an immense scale played out on several levels _ political,
scientific, social, and cultural. But to get there, you have to
endure the first hour devoted largely to the development of the
H-Bomb or ``Super,'' as physicist and advocate Edward Teller dubbed
it. ``Endure'' may be too strong a word, but the first half
resembles an encyclopedia entry: informative but largely colorless,
devoid of the second hour's dynamic interweaving of political and
social material.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of access to recently released civil defense and
US military films, ``Superbomb'' is able to dramatize the scope of
the government's pernicious propaganda. Although US leaders knew
about the inescapable horrors of nuclear war, the government
``educated'' citizens about how to hide under couches or flee
cities to avoid harm. The wooden civil defense footage would be
funny if it weren't also disturbingly deceptive and antidemocratic.
Another film reveals how the US military tried to dispel fear of
atomic war among infantry troops. (At the end, a relieved soldier
is seen drawing deeply on his cigarette.) ``Superbomb'' also covers
the less surprising deceits perpetrated by the USSR, whose early
bomb-construction program under Stalin was aided by slave labor.
</P>
<P>
   But the design of this literate, impressively researched film
goes beyond exposing the lies, delusions, and human losses that
accompanied the arms buildup it carefully chronicles. Often
dramatic and disconcerting, ``Superbomb'' is history bristling with
implications _ about unprecedented US peacetime militarization and
the risks sometimes inherent in scientific progress. And about not
only the awesome power of megaton bombs but also of fear itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 2035EST &QL; 
