<HEADER>
A6972 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPORT-SECURITY-2TAK     01-10 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-SECURITY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREACHING SECURITY AT U.S. AIRPORTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Va., Mo., Iowa., N.C., Texas, Ind., Fla.)   (EXCLUSIVE; 10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET
EMBARGO for electronic media.) 
(jw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ How good is airport security?
</P>
<P>
   Good enough, the Federal Aviation Administration has said
repeatedly. Even so, efforts by outsiders to assess security at
America's airports are all but fruitless, because the FAA says it
cannot provide details without giving away information that could
help terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   But FAA reports of violations by one airline show that agents
masquerading as passengers were able to smuggle guns, hand grenades
and bombs past security guards and their scanners, or send the
weapons in through exits.
</P>
<P>
   On July 11, 1993, for example, a female FAA agent entered the
departure terminal of Port Columbus International Airport, in
Columbus, Ohio, with a handgun under her waistband, in the small of
her back.
</P>
<P>
   She set off a metal detector and was ``selected for examination
by the checkpoint security supervisor using a hand held metal
detector,'' according to FAA documents.
</P>
<P>
   The security supervisor passed the metal detector over the FAA
agent, and the alarm sounded when it was over the area of the
handgun, according to the report. The wand was passed over the FAA
agent a second time, and again the alarm sounded in the area of the
handgun.
</P>
<P>
   But the security supervisor ``failed to take any further action
and the subject with the handgun in her waistband entered the
sterile area,'' and was free to proceed toward the boarding gate,
the FAA reported
</P>
<P>
   The documents also recount how an investigator strolled
unchallenged into unguarded aircraft. In another instance, federal
employees sent to ticket counters with the assignment of drawing
suspicion to themselves _ by paying cash for the next flight out,
or refusing to show identification, for example _ provoked no
special security precautions toward their bags. Others were never
asked if they were carrying packages from strangers, or if they
replied that they were carrying such packages, the airline failed
to react appropriately.
</P>
<P>
   The reports, a pile 51/2 inches thick, were on USAir, now known
as USAirways, and were given to The New York Times in response to a
Freedom of Information Act request. The documents, requested in
November 1996, were released last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Times requested the documents after the FAA made a brief
announcement in November 1996 that it would settle 84 charges
against the airline for $450,000, but would give no details on the
charges. Under the same request, the FAA released documents on
safety violations in April 1997. But 73 other alleged violations
involved security.
</P>
<P>
   Cathal Flynn, the FAA's associate administrator for civil
aviation security, said Friday that the violations summarized in
the documents were characteristic of those occurring now, and that
USAirways' security record was about the same as all big airlines'.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that these represented only the failures, and he
pointed out that of the 10,000 tests conducted by the FAA each
year, the airlines pass most.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn said the tests are getting tougher, forcing the airlines
to detect smaller smuggled objects, for example, and that generally
the airlines are improving.
</P>
<P>
   The security rules under which the airlines operate are secret
and many details of the violations were blacked out before the
documents were released. Here, though, is a sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 6, 1995: An FAA security agent posing as a passenger used a
personal credit card at the ticket counter in Kansas City to buy a
ticket to Des Moines on a flight leaving that morning. The airline
representative asked if he had been given a package by anyone
unknown to him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I replied that the night previous, I was in a pizza parlor in
Parkville, Mo., with my wife and was discussing my trip to Des
Moines,'' the security agent replied. ``A young man apparently
overhead our discussion and asked if I would take some books to Des
Moines for a friend of his. He explained that this `friend' would
come to my motel and pick up the books.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline agent ``asked me if I checked the box to see if it
really contained only books, and I replied `no,''' the FAA agent
said.
</P>
<P>
   The airline agent went to a back room to consult with someone,
according to the FAA report, and then returned to ask her customer
whether the incident in the pizza parlor had occurred that day, or
the night before. ``I replied `last night,' '' the FAA agent said.
``She then stated that everything was OK, presented me with my
ticket and accepted my checked bag with the 'unknown
person/package' inside.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA had sought a fine of $8,750, but the case was closed as
part of the general settlement in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   May 22, 1996: An FAA agent, posing as a passenger, paid $326
cash at the ticket counter at Charlotte, N.C., for a round-trip
ticket to Raleigh, and checked a bag, a combination that should
have triggered a special search of the bag. The ticket agent ``was
being assisted by a trainee employee, who in his zeal to assist,
attached the bag tag and loaded it on the belt,'' with no special
screening, according to the documents. The ticket agent said later
that she did not believe the FAA agent met the criteria for special
screening, because he had bought a round-trip ticket; two of her
supervisors agreed. But all three were wrong, the FAA said.
</P>
<P>
   USAir argued it should not be fined, partly because it suspended
the ticket agent for a week without pay and put her on probation
for 18 months. ``The severity of the discipline would serve as an
effective example to all employees of the importance placed on full
compliance with security directive procedures,'' the airline said
in a letter to the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA deleted the amount of the proposed fine.
</P>
<P>
   April 7, 1994: William Olive Jr. usually carries his 9mm Colt
handgun in the glove box of his car, but had put it in his
soft-sided briefcase and forgotten it. Then he went to the airport
in Tampa to catch a flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put the briefcase on the X-ray machine on its side as I
usually do and it passed through screening without any
interruption,'' he later told the FAA in a letter. At the gate, he
opened the briefcase to get his ticket, and saw his loaded gun. He
told the ticket agent, who told him to go back to the checkpoint,
where the screeners ran his briefcase through the machine a second
time.
</P>
<P>
   USAir told the FAA that ``due to the position of the gun during
presentation, the X-ray image produced a long, narrow bar,
resembling a curling iron or similar device.'' The company, asking
that it not be fined, said it had administered 564 tests at Tampa
in the prior 12 months, with a 97 percent pass rate, and that it
had also detected and confiscated ``31 real weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA said it reviewed its records and found eight similar
violations, none at Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 15, 1995: An FAA agent posing as a passenger arrived for a
flight from Akron-Canton Regional Airport, in North Canton, Ohio,
and checked one bag. Asked by the ticket agent for identification,
the passenger replied that ``he did not have a driver's license due
to the fact it was taken from him because of several traffic
violations.'' The ticket agent warned that the man's bag would not
be put on the plane unless the passenger himself boarded.
</P>
<P>
   But the airline put the bag on the plane and carried it to its
destination, and the ``passenger'' did not board.
</P>
<P>
   USAir had accumulated at least 22 similar violations between
July 1, 1995, and July 1, 1996, the FAA said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   June 13, 1996: FAA agents at Terminal 2W at Dallas/Fort Worth
``were able to introduce an FAA-approved test object (hand grenade)
into the sterile area using the revolving exit door without
detection. The Special Agents repeated the evaluation using a bag
containing all the following FAA-approved test objects; a hand
grenade, a dynamite bomb, a pipe bomb and an encapsulated weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At no time during the evaluations did the sensor activate,
stop the door and prevent the introduction of the test objects,''
the documents report. ``A mitigating factor to be considered is the
corrective action taken to post a guard at location of the door to
preclude further unauthorized access.''
</P>
<P>
   The agent's statement said he used a black vinyl knapsack
weighing about nine pounds. ``Several passengers observed the
testing but did not report our actions,'' the agent wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 30, 1994: A female air traffic controller was recruited by
FAA security personnel as a tester, and she walked through a metal
detector at Indianapolis International Airport with a gun, setting
off the detector. A security screener went over the controller with
a hand wand and waived her through, failing to find the gun.
</P>
<P>
   USAir said in a letter to the FAA that using the wand on the
passenger, the screener ``had unintentionally touched her chest
with the hand wand which made him very self-conscious in being
careful not to touch the tester again. In this effort, he believes
he held the wand away from her body more than the recommended 1-3
inches making the wand ineffective in detecting the test object.''
The airline said it had bought wands that worked within a 10-inch
range.
</P>
<P>
   April 9, 1996: An FAA agent carried a blue briefcase with a
``test object'' through security at Roanoke Regional Airport, and
then confronted the screener, who had missed it on the X-ray
machine's display.
</P>
<P>
   ``The image of the (word deleted) object was clearly visible as
a dark silhouette against a light background,'' the agent reported.
When the agent asked the security screener to say what she thought
the test object was, as viewed on the x-ray monitor, the screener
said ``she had thought that the round grenade was possibly a ladies
compact makeup case.''
</P>
<P>
   And on hundreds of occasions, the airline accepted packages from
unknown shippers without verifying their contents, the FAA said.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Flynn said of the incident involving the screener who
touched the passenger with the wand, ``as a human, one understands
the kind of thing that happens there. The screeners have a
difficult job to do, to be courteous, to avoid excessively
bothering people, but yet to ensure that they are no longer causing
an alarm before they proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   But the agency insists that the screeners do their job right, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
