<SLUG> BC-OBIT-POTTER-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARE POTTER, WHO SET TRENDS IN WOMEN'S CLOTHES, DIES AT 95
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Conn., Va.)   (jw) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clare Potter, a leading American fashion designer of the 1930s
and '40s known for imaginative use of color and simplicity of line,
died Jan. 5 at her home in Fort Ann, N.Y. She was 95.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Claire McCardell and Tina Leser, Ms. Potter was one
of the designers credited with inventing American sportswear, a
style that has influenced designers all over the world. She was a
featured designer at Lord &AMP; Taylor when the store was headed by the
legendary Dorothy Shaver, and received the first Lord &AMP; Taylor
Design Award in 1938 for ``distinguished designing in the field of
sports clothes for women.'' She also received a Neiman Marcus Award
in 1939 and a Coty Fashion Critics Award in 1946. In 1939, she
designed a blue wool dress for Eleanor Roosevelt to wear to meet
King George VI and Queen Elizabeth of England.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Ms. Potter's designs are in an exhibition called,
``Designing Women: American Style 1940-1960,'' at the Wadsworth
Atheneum in Hartford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was incredibly important,'' said Richard Martin, the
curator of the Costume Institute of the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
``She was one of that first group in the 1930s of designers
recognized by name. She was recognized by American women for
getting rid of ornamentation. She wasn't the boldest, like Claire
McCardell, but she was known for color and simple textures, for a
discreet style of dressing, for sophisticated sportswear.''
</P>
<P>
   An aristocratic-looking woman who loved sports, particularly
horseback riding, Ms. Potter designed for women like herself who
favored casual clothes that were simple yet sophisticated. ``Large
numbers of American women want clothes that are refined,'' Ms.
Potter said in a 1948 interview with The New York Times. ``I aim to
give them in a medium-priced, ready-to-wear costume what they would
find in custom-made styles.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the styles she was known for were the two-piece swimsuit
consisting of a bra and bloomers, the evening sweater and the
sidesaddle-draped skirt. Even for evening, her designs tended to be
as casual as a shirt and skirt or pants and a tunic. One outfit of
the 1940s combined a rose-colored blouse, a pale blue floor-length
skirt and a green belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``She did forward-looking active sports clothes, sundresses,
trousers, bathing suits and evening sweaters,'' said Valerie
Steele, the chief curator of the Museum at the Fashion Institute of
Technology. ``She wasn't influenced by Paris, but by the modern
American leisure life style.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Potter was born in Jersey City, N.J., in 1903. Her affinity
for color could be traced to an interest in art she developed while
in high school, where she was art editor of the school paper, and
continued with studies at the Art Students League. Although she did
not know how to sew, she took a draping course and produced what
she later described as ``my first weird costume,'' consisting of a
long, slinky red wool dress with huge silk sleeves that she dyed to
match.
</P>
<P>
   She went on to study at the Pratt Institute in Brooklyn, N.Y.,
and after graduation found a job with a dress manufacturer. In
1948, she went into partnership with Martha Stout, a former
magazine editor, in a ready-to-wear company called Timbertop. The
name came from the turkey farm in West Nyack, N.Y., where Ms.
Potter lived with her husband, J. Sanford Potter, an architect.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   By the mid-1950s she was in business on her own, working from a
barn on her farm with her husband drafting the patterns for her
clothing. ``It was very chic to go out there and buy things in a
lovely spot,'' recalled Virginia Wagoner Booth, who was then a
buyer for Lord &AMP; Taylor and became a lifelong friend.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1950s, Potter designed and built a Japanese-style
house in Fort Ann on Lake Nebo, where the couple grew camellias and
raised Dalmatians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept horses down in Virginia,'' Ms. Booth said, ``and
went down every weekend in the fall to hunt. Clare remained
physically active almost until the end. When she took to her
bedroom, she could look out at the lake and see the birds. She
loved to watch and feed the birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Sandy died four years ago,'' she added, referring to
Potter, ``we scattered his ashes on the property. We'll do the same
thing with hers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Potter left no survivors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
