<SLUG> BC-EXP-GORE-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS WEEK WILL HAVE A THEME FOR A PROBABLE GORE CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This article is part of TIMES EXPRESS. It is a condensed
version of a story that will appear in tomorrow's New York Times.) 
(ms) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While still months from officially declaring
himself a presidential candidate, Vice President Al Gore is
scheduled to announce a series of initiatives this week that his
aides say will be major themes of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Gore will unveil the administration's budget request
for community planning programs. On Tuesday, he will propose tax
incentives for education and job training programs. On Wednesday,
he will award Empowerment Zone grants and speak to a Jewish group
in New York in support of the Israeli peace process. On Thursday
and Friday, he will be the host for officials from 45 countries at
a conference to promote open trade.
</P>
<P>
   These issues may sound familiar, as they have been hallmarks of
the Clinton administration. But as the backbone of Gore's campaign,
they clearly define him as an extension of Clinton, a calculation
that suggests the vice president is confident voters will reward
him for the administration's successes but not blame him for the
president's personal failings.
</P>
<P>
   Two Republican presidential hopefuls, Lamar Alexander, the
former governor of Tennessee, and Sen. John McCain of Arizona, have
denounced Gore as an apologist for the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the electoral clock is ticking, we are still more
than two years away from the term of the next president,'' Gore
said Sunday in an interview. ``So while political speculation is
understandable and omnipresent, for my part, I'm going to continue
to focus on my work as vice president and put off for quite some
time into the future a formal announcement of my candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides say he is betting that with the stars aligned as
they are _ a robust national economy, an enormously popular
president and a Clinton-Gore fund-raising apparatus already tapping
Democratic donors for the $20 million Gore expects to raise by
December _ the vice president risks nothing by not stepping out
from behind Clinton, even with the impeachment trial set to begin
this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 2058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
