</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-LIGHTNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' VICTORY SETS UP A MOVE INTO PLAYOFF CONTENTION
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Except for the injury to Petr Nedved, the Rangers
emerged from Sunday's victory over the Tampa Bay Lightning with
several reasons to smile. By beating the woeful Lightning by 5-2 in
Madison Square Garden, they moved one victory from the .500 mark.
</P>
<P>
   They scored on their first shot of the game, off the rush, by
Mike Knuble. They scored on a penalty shot by John MacLean. They
got another nifty performance from Dan Cloutier, their backup
goalie, who made 22 saves. And their two offensive stars, Brian
Leetch and Wayne Gretzky, returned to the score sheet after modest
absences.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Rangers play three more last-place teams _ the Islanders
on Wednesday, Chicago on Friday and Montreal on Saturday. Like the
Lightning, all three rank at the bottom of their respective
divisions. Another hot streak, and the Rangers are quite capable of
them, could put the Blue Shirts (16-17-7) back into playoff
contention as they pass the halfway point of their 82-game
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But they will need the help of Nedved, their creative center who
helped manufacture Knuble's goal by carrying the puck with speed,
drawing the coverage toward him and then leaving a pass at the blue
line for Leetch, who set up Knuble's classy finish at the 20-second
mark.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second period, Nedved fell to the ice after his
right knee collided with the right knee of Pavel Kubina during what
Nedved called a pick play. The Rangers described the injury as a
mild knee sprain. Coach John Muckler called it a first-degree knee
sprain and added, ``If you are going to have a sprain, that's the
best to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Nedved, who has eight goals and 14 assists in 21 games, seemed
uneasy and uncertain about playing against the Islanders on
Wednesday. ``We'll see how it goes tomorrow,'' he said. ``It's
sore. Definitely, it's not 100 percent.'' Should he miss the game,
the Rangers would probably use Manny Malhotra, who moved up from
the fourth line and took Nedved's place between Knuble and Niklas
Sundstrom.
</P>
<P>
   The victory ended a two-game losing streak against a team that
leaves town with a five-game losing streak. The Rangers had beaten
the Lightning by 10-2 in Tampa in their first meeting this season.
</P>
<P>
   How bad is Tampa? Late in the first period, Wendel Clark of the
Lightning, with no one around him, lost control of his feet and
crashed into the boards. In light of his tough-guy persona, it is a
wonder Clark did not drop his gloves and start punching himself in
the head. He is but one name on a roster of discards from
everyone's recycling bins. Here a Stephane Richer, who scored one
of the goals; there a Benoit Hogue, who has feuded with Coach
Jacques Demers; here a Craig Janney, who did not dress; there a
Petr Svoboda, who left with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Leetch, without a point in his previous six games, had three
assists, although he has not scored a goal in 14 games. ``I love
day games,'' the captain said. ``I'd like to play one a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, with no points in his previous two games and no goals
in his previous nine, had a power-play goal, one assist and four
shots on goal. The goal was No. 892 of his 20-year career, the most
ever by a National Hockey League player. Gretzky, who has said ``I
wear my heart on my sleeve'' when showing emotion, now wears,
literally, a heart on his jersey. His wife, Janet, put the tiny,
red valentine on the back of his shirt, just inside the first ``9''
of his number ``99.''
</P>
<P>
   MacLean scored for the second time on two penalty shots in his
career. This one came at the 12-minute-12-second mark of the first
period, as the Rangers were killing a penalty, and it gave the
Rangers a 2-0 lead. Pulled down from behind by Drew Bannister,
MacLean was awarded the shot by Paul Stewart, who refereed in a
flamboyant style. MacLean skated in on the goal, faked back to the
forehand and beat Bill Ranford between the skates for his 14th goal
of the season. He is second on the team, behind Adam Graves, who
got his 18th at 16:25 as the Rangers decided this one early.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to jump on them,'' MacLean said. ``We knew it was
their third game in three and a half days.'' Because his goal took
place while his team was killing a penalty, it technically counted
as a short-handed goal, the first for the Rangers in 122 games.
Marc Savard scored the other Ranger goal, on the power play at 5:12
of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   For Cloutier, it was his seventh start of the season and it
raised his record to 3-3-2. Although he was one of the stars, the
spotlight was also shared by Stewart, the referee who recently
recovered from colon cancer. After awarding the one-penalty shot,
Stewart ignored another obvious penalty shot when a Tampa player
gloved the puck in the crease. He called Malhotra for a diving
infraction. Twice he penalized the Rangers by two men for two full
minutes. Once he put the Lightning two men down for 72 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   A former player who had a brawling style, Stewart is loquacious
and well liked even by those hockey folks who occasionally question
the consistency of his judgment. On Sunday, his curious
decision-making kept things interesting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
