<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PRESIDENTIAL-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EDITORIAL: THE EXPANDING PRESIDENTIAL RACE  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, Jan. 11:
</P>
<P>
   The nation's crop of presidential candidates is exploding. Sen.
John McCain of Arizona and Sen. Robert Smith of New Hampshire
recently became official Republican hopefuls. Elizabeth Dole
cleared the way for what her aides say is likely to be a
presidential bid, and former Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee
announced his intention to announce.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Vice President Al Gore and former Sen.
Bill Bradley are in the race. Sen. John Kerry is in what
politicians like to call ``testing the waters'' mode. Things are
happening so fast that other potential candidates, like Sen. Bob
Kerrey, a Democrat, and John Ashcroft, a Republican, have felt
obliged to rule themselves out of the running for nominations that
will not be formally bestowed on anyone until the summer of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The rush to run is being driven mainly by money worries. The
calendar for the next presidential primaries is so front-loaded
that both nominations will probably be decided in early March.
Conventional wisdom holds that a candidate needs to raise at least
$20 million this year to compete seriously. Every day a potential
candidate delays making a commitment is one day less to solicit
money.
</P>
<P>
   Some presidential hopefuls, like Alexander and Dan Quayle, have
been running for months without any campaign committee, raising
money through ``leadership'' political-action committees that
theoretically exist only to promote certain issues that the
candidate in question also happens to espouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have been most successful in attracting
candidates for the nomination, because the field seems so open.
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas is the man everyone has been watching.
But if Bush does intend to run, he is certainly discreet enough to
wait at least until he is sworn in for a second term this month
before he announces he wants to move on to higher office.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Mrs. Dole's ambitions are creating most of the
stir, since she could be the first woman to make a competitive bid
for her party's presidential nomination. Although Mrs. Dole has yet
to declare her candidacy, her announcement that she is quitting her
job as president of the American Red Cross is evidence that she is
serious. Giving up a good job is a far more convincing show of
intention than the creation of an ``exploratory committee.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush does run for president, there is a danger that the
Republican field will quickly dwindle. That would be too bad. The
peculiar schedule of the primaries and the loathsome state of
campaign finance could easily create a situation in which a
front-runner stumbles under the intense scrutiny of the media early
next year, but there is no other candidate with enough money to
make an effective challenge.
</P>
<P>
   It would be foolish to regard either of the early favorites as
unstoppable. Bush has never been tested in a national campaign.
Gore may look like a shoo-in now, but the events of the last few
years have demonstrated how much can happen in a short period of
time to make a strong candidate less attractive, particularly if
the candidate in question is a member of the current
administration.
</P>
<P>
   While any discussion of the year 2000 election now may seem too
much too soon to the public, the sight of all these candidates is
heartening. We hope the field still looks crowded 12 months down
the road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 2105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990110.0157 </DOCNO>
