<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7001 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-NYT &LR;      01-10 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE IMPEACHMENT TRIAL IS LEGALLY UNIQUE, LAWYERS SAY  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., N.Y.)  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-POLITICS, IMPEACH-HISTORY) 
(js) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In setting a detailed schedule to resume the
president's impeachment trial but putting off the vexing issue of
whether witnesses will be heard, the Senate demonstrated to many
lawyers and others just how different the impeachment trial was
from any other legal proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a thoroughly odd way to do business,'' said Yale Kamisar,
a professor of criminal procedure at the University of Michigan Law
School. The strangest element, he said, is to begin the trial and
only decide later in the process whether or which witnesses will be
called.
</P>
<P>
   ``In no other kind of proceeding do you have this kind of
piecemeal approach where you get started and see how things develop
and then decide what to do,'' Kamisar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really sui generis,'' a situation without exact legal
parallel, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment trial also defies description in that it is
neither a civil nor a criminal proceeding in the normal meaning of
the word. Burt Neuborne of the New York University Law School said
that it bore elements of both, but argued that it should probably
be closer to a criminal proceeding because of the gravity of the
event and the need to have the greatest protections for the
accused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the consequences are so great and the importance to
the nation is so overwhelming, there should be the most cautious
set of procedures and standards,'' Neuborne said. ``That's most
close to criminal proceedings where you have the guaranteed right
to counsel and notice of the charges as well as the right to
cross-examine witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Another distinction is that in trials, both civil and criminal,
a judge is the ultimate arbiter and is charged with ensuring that
all the proceedings conform to traditional notions of fairness and
due process.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it remains unclear whether Chief Justice William Rehnquist
will serve in the trial as anything more than a presiding officer,
as many have suggested. Any ruling Rehnquist makes may be
overturned by a majority of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Neuborne said he believed that the chief justice was obliged,
nonetheless, to try to enforce a sense of due process. For example,
he said, under the plan approved on Friday, it would be possible
for the Senate to vote to allow witnesses called by the House
prosecutors but to deny hearing witnesses offered by the
president's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   But Neuborne said that should be unthinkable and the chief
justice would have to block such an event. ``They may be able to
limit the witnesses the prosecution presents, but they cannot limit
the witnesses the president might think he needs to mount his
defense,'' he said. ``And the chief justice took an oath himself,
and it's clear he has an obligation to maintain some legal
fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the rough plan agreed to on Friday, either side may depose
the other side's witnesses before they can be called to testify
before the Senate. That feature, which is intended to prevent any
surprises, is typical of a civil rather than a criminal proceeding.
In criminal trials, lawyers may seek to question the other side but
there is no obligation to comply.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue that figures in almost all other legal proceedings
but which seems to have no place in the Senate trial is a defined
standard of proof. Criminal trials require that a conviction be
beyond a reasonable doubt, a standard of proof that legal
historians say dates from 1770, when British soldiers were put on
trial for killing civilians in the Boston Massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Civil trials have two different standards of proof: ``a
preponderance of the evidence,'' used in most proceedings, and
``clear and convincing evidence,'' a slightly higher standard used
in extraordinary proceedings like loss of citizenship, commitment
to an institution or taking custody of children.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Baron, a Washington lawyer who helped prosecute two
impeachment cases before the Senate against Alcee Hastings and
Walter Nixon Jr., both federal judges, said each senator may decide
on his or her own what the standard should be. At the time of his
trial in 1989, Hastings explicitly asked that the highest standard
of proof, beyond a reasonable doubt, be required and the Senate
rejected that, Baron said.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike all civil and criminal proceedings, which may be
appealed through the court system, the verdict in the impeachment
trial may not be taken to the courts, in the view of most scholars.
In his 1993 ruling on the impeachment of Nixon, Rehnquist wrote
that the Constitution made the Senate the sole arbiter of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David Souter filed a concurring opinion, saying that
impeachments are not generally subject to court review, but if the
Senate chose to make its decision on some outrageous standard, like
a coin toss, the courts might then step in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 2111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990110.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7004 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLLARD-CLEMENCY-NYT &LR;      01-10 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLARD-CLEMENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. NOW TELLS OF MUCH DEEPER DAMAGE BY POLLARD
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Adamant that President Clinton refuse requests for
clemency for Jonathan Pollard, an American spy for Israel, U.S.
military and intelligence officials say Pollard did more damage to
national security than the public has been told.
</P>
<P>
   An article to be published in The New Yorker on Monday cites
those officials as saying that Pollard, who was arrested in 1985
and is now serving a life sentence, gave Israel invaluable American
intelligence secrets in exchange for payments of $50,000 and
promises of $540,000 more.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, intelligence officials confirmed the gist of the
magazine article, written by the investigative reporter Seymour
Hersh.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. intelligence officials have long suspected that information
delivered to Israel by Pollard was subsequently obtained by the
Soviet intelligence services _ either deliberately handed over by
Israel in exchange for freedom for Soviet Jews or surreptitiously
obtained by Moscow's spies in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard and his supporters have contended that he did not do
real damage to American national security and should be pardoned or
paroled.
</P>
<P>
   Monday is the deadline that Clinton gave American military,
intelligence and law enforcement agencies last month for submitting
their views on the question, a response to demands for Pollard's
release made by Israel in October at the Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations held at Wye Plantation in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement and intelligence officials have said the FBI,
CIA and Defense Department will submit reports arguing against
leniency. The State Department and Justice Department are also to
give their views.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Clinton and his aides were not likely to make a
decision soon.
</P>
<P>
   Among the documents Pollard handed over to Israel, Hersh's
article said, was a 10-volume directory of the frequencies and
bandwidths of signals intercepted worldwide by the National
Security Agency, which is the United States' primary electronic
eavesdropping service and its biggest espionage entity.
</P>
<P>
   That set of data would afford a foreign intelligence service
deep insights into American techniques for spying on the world.
Pollard told the author that U.S. officials had ``consistently
lied'' about the importance of the signal intelligence he gave the
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Another set of documents divulged by Pollard, the article said,
was a computerized information retrieval system containing
intelligence reports filed by American spies, intelligence
analysts, military attaches and citizens in the Middle East. A
foreign intelligence service possessing this information could
determine the identities of intelligence agents and informers.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard also handed over more than a year's worth of reports
from a Navy surveillance station in Spain that monitored the Middle
East and North Africa, the article said.
</P>
<P>
   It said a fourth set was the daily list of telecommunications
interceptions undertaken by the National Security Agency. Such data
could help a foreign intelligence service evade detection by the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The material handed over by Pollard showed how the United States
spied on Israel, just as his arrest and conviction showed how
Israel spied on the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the magazine article strongly suggested that Pollard, whom
it described as a cocaine abuser and an inveterate liar during the
time of his espionage for Israel, had no idea of the value of what
he handed over, and no concept of the damage it caused American
intelligence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
