u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRANE-COLTEC-600&AMP;ADD-     01-10 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRANE-COLTEC-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRANE SUIT AGAINST COLTEC MAY ALTER MERGER STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.C., Ohio)  (lb) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fate of Crane Co.'s $1.7 billion unsolicited takeover bid
for Coltec Industries now rests largely in the hands of the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Crane has sued Coltec, which agreed in November to be acquired
by B.F. Goodrich for $1.4 billion and the assumption of debt, in a
last-ditch effort to derail the deal with Goodrich and force Coltec
to consider its offer.
</P>
<P>
   The battle among the three aerospace and industrial-products
companies may reach a turning point Monday, when Judge Barbara
Jones of U.S. District Court in New York is scheduled to hear
arguments on a motion by Coltec to dismiss Crane's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Crane, based in Stamford, Conn., says it wants to use its shares
for a stock-for-stock deal with Coltec in what is called a
pooling-of-interests transaction. Such transactions are less
expensive and usually tax-free. As a result, they have been very
popular in many recent mergers, including that of Daimler-Benz and
Chrysler. At the same time, the accounting has been coming under
increased scrutiny from regulators.
</P>
<P>
   But a hostile bid for Coltec would make a pooling transaction
unworkable, Crane says, because of certain provisions in the
agreement between Coltec and Goodrich that allow the companies to
take shares in each other. The Crane lawsuit is likely to focus
attention on the use of pooling transactions and the resources
companies have to ward off unwanted takeover bids.
</P>
<P>
   In its suit, Crane contends that Coltec, by agreeing to be
acquired by Goodrich of Richfield, Ohio, broke a 1995 promise to
notify Crane of any offers to buy the company. The lawsuit, filed
last month, seeks to block Coltec's deal with Goodrich and to void
the anti-takeover provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Coltec, based in Charlotte, N.C., says that the 1995 agreement
with Crane, which came after the two companies held informal talks
about a possible deal, did not require it to notify Crane if a
third party expressed interest in buying the company, nor did it
prohibit it from negotiating an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The main anti-takeover provision in the agreement between Coltec
and Goodrich gives Goodrich an option to acquire as much as 19.9
percent of Coltec stock. Coltec has a similar option to acquire
Goodrich stock. The options would be set off if their merger does
not go through. Crane contends that such ``lock-up agreements''
hurt shareholders, because they can eliminate more lucrative
counteroffers.
</P>
<P>
   Options for cross-ownership are able to thwart unwanted takeover
bids because of accounting regulations that prohibit any
significant change in the holding of a company immediately before a
merger that uses a pooling transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Such a transfer of a significant amount of stock has the same
effect as a poison pill, a provision that typically makes the stock
of a target company more expensive for a would-be acquirer, noted
Robert Willens, a tax specialist with Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Crane has said that it is interested in acquiring Coltec
only if it can use a pooling transaction, which would be less
expensive than a stock purchase. In a pooling transaction, merging
companies merely add together the book value of their assets; there
is no change from pre-merger values and no good will is created. As
a result, the transaction is tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, the purchase method of accounting assumes that
one company buys the assets of another. If the price paid for the
acquired company exceeds the market value of its assets, the
difference is recorded as good will. The good will must then be
written off over a period of years, causing a reduction in earnings
each time.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The popularity of pooling has certainly surged. In 1989, only 5
percent of the dollar volume of total transactions were
pooling-of-interests combinations. By the third quarter of 1998,
that had increased to 65 percent, according to Securities Data Co.
of Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting standards board and the Securities and Exchange
Commission have been looking more closely at such transactions in
response to criticisms that pooling allows companies to overpay for
acquisitions while leaving almost no trace on their books.
</P>
<P>
   And although poolings were intended for combinations in which
each company would own an equal stake in the other, they allow
transactions in which one company can own a majority stake in
another and still receive the preferential accounting treatment.
The accounting board is now studying whether two accounting methods
should continue to be used for mergers.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the lock-up agreements between Coltec and
Goodrich could prevent another bid from a third party should the
deal between the two collapse, some analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule is the lock-up option precludes pooling that would
trigger the exercisability of the option,'' Willens of Lehman
Brothers said. ``Apparently the only way the lock-up option can be
rescinded is if the court decides the lock-up option was illegal
from the outset and strikes it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Lucas, director of research and technical accounting at
the Financial Accounting Standards Board, said the board had not
addressed whether the elimination of the lock-up agreement would
prevent pooling with a third party.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, several Wall Street analysts said that if the deal
fell through, Goodrich would probably give up the cross-ownership
and instead take the $50 million break-up fee, which is also part
of the agreement with Coltec.
</P>
<P>
   And should Crane succeed in the courts and get the lock-up
agreements voided, acquiring Coltec in a hostile pooling
transaction would still not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, out of 11 hostile bids structured as pooling
transactions, only three have been completed. The largest was
Newmont Mining's $2.86 billion acquisition of Santa Fe Pacific Gold
Corp., announced in December 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
