<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGUARS-BRUNELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUNDERING JAGUARS PLAYED AGAINST THEMSELVES
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Jacksonville coach Tom Coughlin kept
searching for words to describe the things he had seen his Jaguars
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foolish,'' Coughlin said. ``Ill advised. Dumb mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin had complimented the New York Jets for their 34-24
divisional playoff victory Sunday at Giants Stadium. He had praised
his team for a second-half rally that fell short, adding that he
was proud of quarterback Mark Brunell, who played on a sore left
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   But standing in a quiet corner of a somber locker room, Coughlin
shook his head as conversation inevitably came back to the Jaguars'
blunders _ three interceptions of Brunell, a fumble recovery that
ended as a bizarre fumble lost, and an inexplicable misstep after a
late interception by Jaguars safety Donovin Darius that cost
Jacksonville almost 20 yards at a pivotal time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Errors, that's what they were,'' Coughlin said. ``They were
the huge factors in the game. Very, very ill advised.''
</P>
<P>
   For sheer blooper value, nothing was as entertaining as the
bobbled attempted lateral by Jaguars safety Chris Hudson in the
second quarter. Leading by 10-0, the Jets were driving in Jaguars
territory moments after their first interception of Brunell, who
would finish the game with just 12 completions in 31 passing
attempts for 156 yards.
</P>
<P>
   At the Jaguars' 18-yard line, Jets running back Curtis Martin
fumbled, the ball bouncing directly into the hands of Hudson, who
burst up the field with the recovery. Quarterback Vinny Testaverde
was the lone Jet between Hudson and the end zone. As Hudson neared
both Testaverde and the sideline at midfield, he made eye contact
with his teammate Dave Thomas and attempted a lateral.
</P>
<P>
   The ball bounced off Thomas, who never seemed to gain
possession, knocking it forward, where it was covered by Keyshawn
Johnson at the Jets' 35-yard line. Turnover had led to turnover
and, 11 plays later, the Jets went ahead by 17-0.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what Hudson was doing, Coughlin said, ``I wish I knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudson said he was trying too hard to make a big play. ``Of
course, I wish I could take it back,'' he said. ``But I can't. I
won't be haunted by it. I feel down, but we had 59 other minutes to
win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Coughlin said, ``It might have been a different game if
it's 10-7 there instead of 17-0.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said he was as startled as anyone to see Hudson heave the
ball at him. ``I thought he'd keep running,'' Thomas said. ``It was
a spontaneous decision. In the heat of the battle, things fly
through your head.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not the line of reasoning Brunell used to explain his
decision to loft an underthrown ball in wide receiver Keenan
McCardell's direction on Jacksonville's first possession of the
second half. He might have blamed his injured ankle, but he did
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a poorly thrown ball,'' Brunell said.
</P>
<P>
   Brunell's pass was 5 yards behind McCardell, who was open up the
left sideline, and was intercepted by Jets safety Corwin Brown. The
Jets scored seven plays later to take a 24-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have stepped into it and gotten more on the throw,''
said Brunell, who acknowledged that his ankle hampered him, though
he rallied the Jaguars with two touchdown passes later in the
second half. ``It got up a bit and the wind got hold of it. A
foolish thing on my part.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the Jaguars were doing wrong, they trailed the Jets by
only 7 points when Darius intercepted a Testaverde pass in the
Jacksonville end zone with 2 minutes 24 seconds remaining. After
catching the ball, Darius stepped inches over his the goal line in
a timid attempt to run back his interception. Surrounded by Jets,
he was tackled, giving the Jaguars the ball on the 1-yard line
instead of the 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I caught the ball, I collided with Keith Byars,'' Darius
said, referring to Testaverde's intended receiver. ``I jumped up
and my eyes were kind of blurred. I didn't know where I was. It was
a natural reaction to try and run.''
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin shook his head over Darius' mistake, too. ``I don't
know what he was thinking,'' Coughlin said. ``I'm sure he wasn't
thinking that he wanted to put the offense on the 1-yard line. But
I would have liked to have had the opportunity to tie the game
starting at our 20-yard line. That might have been a legitimate
chance.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
