<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yikes, it'll be the Vikes
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Memo to the Falcons: Bring your ``A'' game next
week. The Vikings are every bit what their won-lost record
suggests, and then some. Just ask the Arizona Cardinals. Catch them
on their way to vacation _ battered, bruised and thoroughly
dominated.
</P>
<P>
   Never once was Minnesota threatened Sunday by the upstart
Cardinals at the Metrodome. By the time Arizona could say,
``Brrr!'' _ game-time temperature outside was minus-1 degree _
Viking quarterback Randall Cunningham had directed two touchdown
drives that started the Vikings' 41-21 victory.
</P>
<P>
   With the win, Minnesota hosts Atlanta, winners Saturday over San
Francisco, in the NFC Championship Game next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta was 14-2, won their first (playoff) game convincingly,
we know they're going to be a formidable foe,'' Vikings coach
Dennis Green said. ``They have a great running game and a lot of
veterans who are winners. It'll be a great matchup.''
</P>
<P>
   This one was not. Minnesota compiled 416 yards of total offense.
Cunningham threw for 228 yards on 17-for-27 passing with three
touchdowns. Pro Bowl rookie Randy Moss managed four catches for 73
yards and a TD against fellow Pro Bowl defensive back Aeneas
Williams. Leader Chris Carter had five receptions for 82. Running
back Robert Smith rushed for 124 yards on 19 carries. All that, and
Cunningham still hardly was impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We weren't (clicking) on (offense),'' he had the audacity to
say. ''Our purpose is to dominate and to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the Vikings' disposition, and possess a confidence that
matches their ability.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we get the ball, every possession we can score,'' Moss
said.
</P>
<P>
   They were close to doing that Sunday. To wit: Mitch Berger only
attempted one punt.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a tough task for anyone,'' Smith said, ''because we have
so many guys who can make the big play.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Cardinals settled down Sunday, the Falcons had
already begun game-planning for the Vikings. Minnesota jumped to a
17-0 lead, and did so in diverse, scary ways. It took 7:20 to drive
80 yards on 13 plays to open the game. Then, after a Cunningham
interception to Williams in the end zone, the Vikings marched 62
yards on four plays. Leroy Hoard ended the sustained drive with a
1-yard run and Cunningham connected with tight end Andrew Glover
for a 15-yard pass play to end the other.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the defense gave up little. Nothing, in fact. Arizona
had the ball just once in the first quarter - for 56 seconds - and
had -1 net yards to the Vikings' 141. That they trailed just 7-0
after one was a significant accomplishment. But it was only a
matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what a juggernaut is,'' Cardinals coach Vince
Tobin said, ''but I know one thing: They've got a good football
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona and young quarterback Jake Plummer got the jitters
early, but played differently after the inauspicious start. The
Cardinals moved the ball well, and Plummer, after two early
interceptions, ended up going 23-for-41 for 242 yards.
</P>
<P>
   They scored on scored on three fourth-down 1-yard runs by Mario
Bates. But each touchdown was matched by a Minnesota assualt, which
was loudly celebrated by purple-wearing fans.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any team that comes in here is going to have a tough time,''
Smith said. ''It's so noisy that it's tough to concentrate. We know
Atlanta plays in a dome, too. But I'm glad we'll be at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
