<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons refuse to fear Minnesota
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons free safety Eugene Robinson sat down in front
of his TV Sunday afternoon and watched Minnesota wail on Arizona.
It didn't take long to figure out that the Atlanta's first-ever
appearance in an NFC Championship Game next Sunday will be in the
Metrodome in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   So about the time the Vikings (16-1) took a 24-7 lead on the way
to a 41-21 win, Robinson switched channels.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Gia, watched the movie, ''Armaggedon,''
instead.
</P>
<P>
   How appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   If the Falcons (15-2), are going to punch a ticket to Super Bowl
XXXIII, they'll have to win a war against the highest-scoring
offense in NFL history in a facility that is as loud as any in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   But Robinson, who was 3-1 the last two seasons against the
Vikings while he played for the Packers, didn't want to hear any
hype _ just like he didn't want to see too much of the Vikings, at
least not yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to watch a game like that, where they look like
world beaters,'' he said. ''I remember before by first game against
them in Green Bay, (Packers defensive coordinator) Fritz Shurmur
showed video of them looking just awesome.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, 'Turn it off. Show me something when they got punched
in the mouth, when they're vulnerable.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings are 13-6 all-time against Atlanta, including four
straight wins over the Falcons, the last a 23-17 victory here in
1996. In Atlanta's last trip to Minnesota, the Vikings won 43-17 in
'89.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves didn't need much film study Sunday to get to
the point. ''They're explosive, a complete football team,'' he
said. ''The question is going to be which offense can play the
best?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Reeves and his staff will take Robinson's suggestion, and
show only video of the Vikings' low points.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is there aren't many.
</P>
<P>
   They lost only one game, 27-24 at Tampa Bay on Nov. 1 when the
Buccaneers succeeded in running the ball.
</P>
<P>
   That helped keep the potent offense of quarterback Randall
Cunningham, wide receivers Cris Carter and Randy Moss, and running
back Robert Smith off the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are good at that. They led the NFL in average time
of possession (33:10 per game).
</P>
<P>
   That's what Robinson wants to hear _ positive thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't need to see them pounding the Cardinals,'' he said.
''Right now, their fans think they're the greatest thing since
sliced bread. I refuse to think that way. I refuse to think a team
can't be beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the attitude of a team that has won 10 straight
games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
