A7015 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFC-HUMMER11-COX     01-10 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-HUMMER11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons had better win the coin flip
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ To the next team entering the Minnesota Vikings
purple asylum _ and we all know who that is _ this single snipet of
advice: Win the coin toss, at all costs.
</P>
<P>
   After that, fellas, you're pretty much on your own in devising
ways to keep the ball out of the home team's hands and its wildfire
offense off the scoreboard. These guys make trips to the end zone
look so routine, it's as if they're just there to pick up a jug of
milk and loaf of bread.
</P>
<P>
   In preparing for the NFC Championship, the Falcons would have
been better off not peaking at Minnesota's 41-21 dismantling of
Arizona Sunday. What was to be gained, other than an unhealthy
respect? What exactly was there to be learned? A team that set a
record for points in a season, a team that won 15 games in the
regular season by an average margin of 17 points, is going to show
a little offense.
</P>
<P>
   No one was surprised by the ruthless character of the Vikings
offense. Least of all Minnesota. ``We have a lot of money invested
in the offense. We expect the offense to be the bellcow of this
team,'' receiver Cris Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the obvious, what the Vikings displayed in this division
playoff game was the nature to begin the landslide early and
smother an opponent in an avalanche of points. They are not of a
mood to mess around.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Cardinals made the crucial error of not winning the
opening toss. So the Vikes took the ball on the kickoff and didn't
give it back until nearly eight minutes later with Leroy Hoard
burrowing in for the first of many touchdowns. ``And they said we
can't drive the ball; that all we can do is make big plays,'' said
Carter, referring to the last few critics who remained standing.
</P>
<P>
   With this first possession, the Vikes began their campaign of
confusion. Monica Kauffman doesn't have as many looks as the
Minnesota offense. They even got cute on third-and-1, using running
back David Palmer as a shotgun quarterback while the real thing,
Randall Cunningham, split out wide left. Of course, it worked.
``And I don't think we got to everything,'' said Cunningham,
hinting there is much in reserve for the Falcons. ``We didn't even
get Jake (receiver Reed) the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue was settled quite early. While the Vikings hoarded the
ball, Arizona sputtered. For the first 19 minutes of play, the
Cardinals total offense mirrored the outside temperature _ minus-1.
These birds weren't nearly dirty enough for the job at hand.
</P>
<P>
   So, this is what awaits the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   There's a dome crowd more throaty than its own. This visitor
from Atlanta was having some bad Kirby Puckett flashbacks. The
scene can melt the unprepared. It was late in the second quarter
before young Cardinals quarterback Jake Plummer could get his game
on Prozac and under control.
</P>
<P>
   There's an offense that rolls up 416 yards and 41 points and is
dissatisfied. ``I don't believe we were really on,'' Cunningham
said.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, there's a defense that can be had, but a touchdown against
the Vikings is no more than holding serve.
</P>
<P>
   Next Sunday is going to be way too much fun. Just win the coin
toss, get the ball first, and hold on.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
