</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vikings have no liking for Falcons `Dirty Bird'
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Seems the Falcons' ``Dirty Bird'' routine doesn't
play so well up here. At least not from the words of a couple key
Vikings after their 41-21 dismantling of the Cardinals Sunday at
the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Randy Moss, the rising star rookie receiver: ``I don't
think Atlanta respects us....They see we lost one game, they lost
two. If I was in their position, I wouldn't respect us,
either...They're cocky, call themselves the 'Dirty Birds' from down
South...I guarantee they watched us play, so ...they're coming here
and we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Randall Cunningham went through great pains to not
criticize the Falcons' celebratory dance and nickname, then
proceeded to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he thought of the ``Dirty Bird,'' Cunningham
paused for several seconds before beginning a rambling statement
about a pregame message from the team's chaplin. Finally, he said,
``Let me put it this way: I wouldn't want to be called anything
dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   After a quick answer to another question, Cunningham
backtracked.
</P>
<P>
   ``About that 'Dirty Bird' thing, it's all fun and games,'' he
said. ``Everybody gets a nickname. We're 'Purple Pride.' There's
'Vinnie and the Jets.' It's good for the fans. We just play the
game and don't get caught up in that hype.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Smith A Quiet Killer
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to overlook running back Robert Smith when the offense
has three Pro Bowl players in high profile positions. But if you
don't pay attention to him, he'll go for a team-playoff-record124
yards on 19 carries like he did Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way the game developed,'' Smith said. ``Team
pay so much attention to our passing game that they have a decision
to make on who to stop: the run or the pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, neither is stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We throw in Leroy (Hoard), and he complements Robert great,''
coach Dennis Green said of his power reserve back. ``He's healthy,
fierce and a competitor. He's as good a power runner as they is in
the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   With a touchdown run of 1 yard and a 16-yard TD reception, Hoard
became the first Viking in playoff history to score in both
fashions. . .
</P>
<P>
   Etc. . .
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota used more offensive formations than in any game this
season, including using running back David Palmer at quarterback,
with Cunningham split wide left as a receiver. Moss' 2-yard scoring
reception near the end of the third quarter gave the outstanding
rookie a TD catch in each of the last eight games...At halftime,
Arizona had just 85 yards of total offense...Cardinals owner Bill
Bidwell was n the press box as the game began. When a Minnesota PR
worker passed out Vikings towels before the game, he unwittingly
placed one in front of Bidwell, who did not touch it.
</P>
<P>
   Quotable
</P>
<P>
   Chris Carter, when asked about the difference in the Vikings'
playoff attitude from last year: ``(You) get into the playoffs at
9-7 and you get in at 15-1. I mean, you figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
