<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-SHANAHAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHANAHAN RELISHES TAKING ON PARCELLS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ When Mike Shanahan arrived at his office Sunday
morning, he began studying the New York Jets. Several hours later,
the Denver Broncos' coach turned on his television to make sure he
wasn't wasting his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just going back and forth, to see if I should switch
gears,'' said Shanahan, who later kept interrupting his news
conference to check on the final minutes of the Jets' 34-24 victory
over Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   The coach stopped in midsentence in one answer. ``Excuse me, I'm
watching the game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once it became certain that Denver would be facing the Jets here
next Sunday for the American Football Conference title and a trip
to the Super Bowl, Shanahan acknowledged several things about the
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   First, he feels an extra tingle in matching wits with celebrated
coaches like the Jets' Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think you always get a little juiced up when you're
going against a coach that's had a lot of success and obviously a
couple of Super Bowl rings,'' Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he was not surprised that the Jets have improved so
rapidly under Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of this crazy business is not to get a `name' player but
a guy who's a player,'' Shanahan said. ``They've done that. I like
to think that's what we've done, too.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day after the Broncos' 38-3 trampling of the Miami
Dolphins, all but a few Denver players stayed away from the news
media glare.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback John Elway expected to do plenty of studying this
week. Denver, the defending Super Bowl champion, has played the
Jets only once in the last four seasons, a game here in 1996 won by
the Broncos, 31-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't really faced them in a couple of years, so we don't
know what they're all about,'' Elway told NBC from his home. ``So
it'll be like starting from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   The outspoken tight end Shannon Sharpe displayed his usual
cockiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jets might be the team to beat,'' he said, ``but they've
got to lay over in Denver. I don't care who we play. If they come
here, they've got to play a flawless game to beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe added: ``They're a very talented offense, no question
about it. ``They have two 1,000-yard receivers; so do we. They have
a Pro Bowl quarterback; so do we. They have a 1,000-yard runner;
we've got a 2,000-yard runner. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Marvin Washington, who played eight seasons for
the Jets, the last in 1996, seemed to have no emotional involvement
in playing his former team. ``I think I'm far enough removed from
that situation,'' he said. ``It's a whole different regime, a whole
different group of players. So it doesn't really matter to me who
we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Dolphins limped out of town, several players gave the
Jets a good chance to dethrone the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you the Jets are going to find some kind of way to
shut them down, like we did on that Monday night,'' linebacker
Robert Jones said, harking back to Miami's 31-21 victory in late
December. ``The Jets have a defense to get them, yes they do. In
big games, the Jets play. They come to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Terrell Buckley noted that the Jets under Parcells
are masters of innovation, while his teammate O.J. McDuffie guessed
that the Jets would not be fazed by having to play at Mile High
Stadium, where Denver has won 18 straight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't care where they go,'' the wide receiver said.
``They're ornery like that. They'll play anywhere and they'll play
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Shanahan went back to studying film Sunday, he tried to
defuse several inflammatory comments made by his players before the
Miami game. Besides Sharpe's statement that Denver was 10 to 14
points better than Miami, he said Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson
should clear out his office to give Denver room to study for the
Super Bowl, which will be in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a lot of people take Shannon seriously,'' Shanahan said.
``He's really a good person. He does that sometimes to fire himself
up. But that was kind of rough. I kind of cringed about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach balked at Sharpe's assertion that Dolphins quarterback
Dan Marino is a loser. ``Dan Marino is a winner and everybody knows
that,'' the coach said. ``Yeah, I was disappointed when I saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Shanahan defended linebacker Bill Romanowski's insinuation
that Johnson had lied in describing injuries to two of his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill said what he thought was the truth,'' Shanahan said. ``If
a guy feels like it's the truth, I don't think it's a slap at Jimmy
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Shanahan turned and left for a night of film study. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
