<HEADER>
A7034 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-MARINELAND-ART-64     01-10 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-MARINELAND-ART-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FADED PARK, 19 DOLPHINS STRONG, HOPES TO REBUILD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JIM CARRIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARINELAND, Fla. _ The parking lot is strewn with dead palm
fronds. Rot has invaded the bleachers. Rust dribbles down the
tanks. And the famous portholes are clouded and leaking.
</P>
<P>
   But something is roiling the water.
</P>
<P>
   As Bill Upson approaches with a pail of fish, the surface of a
huge circular pool erupts. A dozen dolphins flip, twist, squeak and
wave their tails at the empty seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Betty,'' Upson said, pointing at a 300-pound flying
dolphin. ``She throws that big, high triple twist. Here come three
jumping together _ Dazzle, Ariel, Nemo _ they learned that all by
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Marineland closed four months ago, after 60 years in the
business, but the dolphins still perform three times a day, their
mouths curved in everlasting smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found the dolphins like to keep their routine,'' said
Upson, Marineland's operations chief, adding that if they didn't
play, they could aggressively turn on each other, as Marineland's
human overseers have done.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's most popular tourist attraction in the 1950s and '60s,
Marineland says it was the world's first oceanarium and the first
to teach wild dolphins to perform. Now the park is mired in bond
defaults, years of neglect and blame-trading, and a Chapter 11
bankruptcy filing. A legion of lawyers is settling claims.
</P>
<P>
   If Marineland is to survive, tourism experts say, it must find a
niche in the shadow of Disney and Busch theme parks. Though small,
family-owned attractions fold every year, others thrive, like
Cypress Gardens in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Marineland's new manager, the nonprofit Marineland Foundation,
hopes to renegotiate the bond debt, reopen the aquarium by April
and begin fund raising to help subsidize the operation.
</P>
<P>
   The park's dreams are riding on 19 irrepressible dolphins, which
outnumber the 17 voters in the municipality of Marineland.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they go, it's down the tubes,'' said Dennis Blackburn, the
lawyer for the Marineland Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Jacoby, an Atlanta developer who has bought Marineland
property across the road from the aquarium, said, ``There is
something very spiritual about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby became interested in Marineland because of his belief
that swimming with dolphins _ as he has done with his daughter, who
suffers a seizure disorder _ can be therapeutic. He plans to build
a therapy center.
</P>
<P>
   But it's going to be a tough battle. Two developers have come
and gone in the last three years. And holders of $9 million in
bonds that are in default recently learned that the Marineland
aquarium's most valuable assets were the dolphins, which could be
sold for $100,000 each. Jacoby said that millions of dollars would
also be needed to rebuild the Marineland aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism officials stopped recommending Marineland years ago,
said Bill Puckett, president of the Florida Attractions
Association, an industry trade group, and a former marketing
director of Marineland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aquariums today _ in Tennessee, Baltimore, Tampa, the Sea
Worlds _ are these big, huge wonders with huge glass windows,''
Puckett said. ``I wouldn't want to try to revitalize it.''
</P>
<P>
   But smaller attractions have found strategies to survive:
Cypress Gardens has year-round flower shows and Silver Springs in
Ocala sells annual passes to area residents for $42, not much more
than its $30 daily fee. The tiny Alligator Farm in St. Augustine
says it has become an accredited zoological park, with every kind
of alligator and crocodile in the world.
</P>
<P>
   When Marineland was built on the Atlantic in 1938, it opened a
vista under the ocean's surface, the first such view for some.
Cornelius Vanderbilt Whitney, the owner of the park and producer of
``Gone With the Wind,'' built the tanks to film underwater, and
several movies were made here, including the 1954 science fiction
movie ``Creature from the Black Lagoon.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The park pioneered marine research, studying dolphins' behavior
and their use of sonar.
</P>
<P>
   In 1953, a Ringling Bros. circus trainer was hired to teach
Flippy, a wild dolphin, to ring a bell and jump through hoops. What
the park called ``the first educated dolphin'' drew so much
attention that Marineland became a must-see tourist stop and a
municipality.
</P>
<P>
   But attendance at the park began to shrink because Disney World
opened near Orlando in 1971, and Interstates 95 and 4 bypassed
Marineland.
</P>
<P>
   However, developers were attracted to the 125 acres adjacent to
the aquarium. The land includes a beautiful stretch of ocean and a
hammock of wild oak along the Intracoastal Waterway.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney sold Marineland in 1982 to local investors, who said
they hoped to create a village like Seaside, a planned community.
They sold it in 1996 to investors led by Barry Loughrane, a
marketing executive and co-founder of Omnicom Group in New York
City, who said he wanted to refurbish a ``golden oldie,'' and also
build condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   The investors, Marineland Ocean Resorts, spun off the park
itself, with the dolphins and oceanside tanks as a nonprofit
foundation, and persuaded the municipality to sell $9.6 million in
municipal bonds based on attendance projections. They defaulted on
the bonds a year later.
</P>
<P>
   The group also used $900,000 in maintenance funds to pay lawyers
and accountants, Loughrane said. He said he tried to sell it to
Jacoby, the developer, who pulled out at the last minute, leading
the group to file for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   After a contentious bankruptcy filing, Marineland's 125 acres,
without the tanks and dolphins, were sold to the Trust for Public
Land, a nonprofit conservation group, for $7.75 million, said Greg
Chelius, a spokesman for the trust. In turn, the trust sold 36
acres to Jacoby for his planned dolphin-therapy center, and the
remaining 89 acres to Flagler County as a park that must remain
undeveloped.
</P>
<P>
   As attendance slipped last year, the foundation cut the aquarium
staff in half, to 15, and then closed the park last October. Both
the trust and Jacoby have donated money to pay salaries of staff
members and the $100,000 annual cost of feeding the dolphins,
including Nelly, at 43 the world's oldest dolphin born in
captivity, according to Marineland.
</P>
<P>
   If the bond debt can be restructured, the foundation wants to
solicit donations and conduct research with the University of
Florida. Jacoby, on whom the foundation's hopes are riding,
envisions a nationwide children's fund-raising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've torn down a lot of green fields,'' Jacoby said. ``I'm
looking for a development where we can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Upson, the Marineland operations chief, said, ``Because we
have the animals, we are here and still fighting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 2148EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
