<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7035 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SGI-SFCHRON-SGI &LR;      01-10 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SGI-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON - SGI  
 SGI Bets It All on New Line  &HT;     By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's bet-the-company time for Silicon Graphics, the struggling
computer-maker that today unveils its first desktop workstations
based on Intel chips and Microsoft Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   SGI, which until now has relied on its own chips and Unix
operating software, hopes that the new machines _ boasting the
company's vaunted graphics technology _ will help stop a financial
slide that has seen it lose money in eight of the past 10 quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Mountain View company have doubled in value
recently, largely in anticipation of the products being introduced
today. The stock, which bottomed at $7.88 on October 8, added $1.06
yesterday to close at $16.31, a new 52-week high.
</P>
<P>
   ``These new NT workstations are potentially a company-saver,''
said analyst Rob Enderle of Giga Information Group. ``SGI was able
to take their expertise in high-performance workstations and
convert that into a strong video subsystem for the Intel platform.
On paper at least, the performance looks pretty phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   The new SGI 320 ($3,395 without monitor) and 540 ($5,995) are
intended to compete on price and performance with other powerful PC
workstations, broadening the market for the company beyond the
high-end, specialized customers it traditionally has served. For
years, SGI workstations have been favored by engineers, scientists
and the entertainment industry but have been too expensive for
small- and medium-size businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its established markets, SGI plans to go after
new areas such as publishing and education _ historically dominated
by Apple Macintoshes.
</P>
<P>
   If they catch on, the new workstations could do for SGI what the
iMac has done to reinvigorate Apple, whose earnings and stock price
have climbed sinced the introduction of the transluscent-blue
personal computer last year.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't, SGI may find it increasingly difficult to survive
as an independent company.
</P>
<P>
   Once a favorite of Wall Street and President Clinton, who in
1993 called it a paragon of successful technology, SGI made a name
for itself with sleek workstations that boasted graphics far ahead
of what anyone else could offer. SGI computers were used to pioneer
Hollywood special effects and still are responsible for most of the
dinosaurs, space ships and explosions in the movies.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, the company has been under assault.
Powerful personal computers running Windows NT have eaten into its
business at the low end, while Sun Microsystems and Hewlett-Packard
have hurt it in the market for high-end Unix servers.
</P>
<P>
   SGI decided that it no longer could survive exclusively as a
Unix vendor. To reach the mainstream market increasingly being
dominated by PCs, it said in autumn 1997 that it would shift its
line over time to the Wintel platform. It will continue selling
Unix-based systems while it phases in Wintel machines.
</P>
<P>
   The SGI 320 and 540 use the latest Pentium II chips and can run
any of the thousands of software programs developed for Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   They also incorporate SGI graphics capabilities, giving them
what could be a significant competitive advantage. SGI claims that
its system can route information six times faster than other
Intel-based systems _ resulting in blazing-fast 3-D graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts think that SGI's high-performance graphics will appeal
to people who need it to create complex animation and video. But
for most graphics tasks, a Dell or Compaq PC could be adequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If SGI's systems only really excel in high-performance areas,
that's where they may end up, and that would be a problem for SGI''
because it would not be able to significantly expand its market,
said analyst Peter ffoulkes (cq) &LR; of Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the potential market for SGI's new systems is large
enough to pull the company out of its abyss is uncertain. And it
faces stiff competition from other computer-makers who won't cede
ground graciously, such as Apple, which is well-entrenched in the
publishing business.
</P>
<P>
   Now that it's in the Windows NT arena, SGI also must contend
with the likes of Dell, Compaq and IBM. Dell, wasting no time, will
announce a workstation today that has less graphical firepower than
the entry-level SGI 320 but does sport the same advanced
flat-screen display used by SGI. (In fact, it's made by SGI.) The
Dell system will go for $4,222, far less than the $5,890 that SGI
will charge for its system with the display.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Copeland of International Data Corp. thinks the new SGI
systems will get a warm welcome from existing SGI customers. ``The
next challenge will be for them to expand by capturing other
people's imagination,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Belluzzo, who took over as SGI's chief executive a year ago
this month, isn't counting on the new Windows NT workstations to
single-handedly revive the company. But he believes they're ``a
breakthrough product that should give us a great opportunity to
grow revenue and be profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the new systems illustrate SGI's commitment ``to
lower price points and make innovative technology available to a
broader market place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By itself, this doesn't solve all the company's problems,''
Belluzzo said, ``but it's a very important part of the whole
story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
