<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia football teams land verbal pledges from top high school
picks
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia and Georgia Tech both garnered verbal
commitments after big football recruiting weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs landed Rome High defensive end Chris Hewitt, a
preseason Super 11 choice by the Journal-Constitution. Hewitt, a
6-foot-6, 250-pounder, turned down scholarship offers from Virginia
Tech, Auburn and Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really liked Georgia's coaching staff,'' Hewitt said. ``I
wanted to play in the SEC and I wanted my mom and dad to be able to
watch me play.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Georgia Tech got Rockdale County placekicker Luke
Manget and Marist defensive lineman Hugh Reilly. Manget, who was
hampered by a hamsting injury during his senior season, hit 7 of 12
field goals with a long of 48 yards. Manget put 90 percent of his
kickoffs went into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, who turned down a scholarship offer from Virginia, had
12 sacks during his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   In other recruiting news, Morrow defensive back Michael Ages
committed to South Carolina. Defensive end Clint Mitchell, who also
visited Georgia, committed to Florida. Mitchell is the younger
brother of former Gators offensive lineman Jeff Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
