<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-SIDE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cunningham grows finer with time
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The remaking of Randall Cunningham has entered the
serious stages.
</P>
<P>
   At 35, having already survived a long, at times unpleasant
career in Philly, the Minnesota Vikings born-again quarterback was
asked Sunday if this season would be the one to leave the lasting
mark on him as a player. ``I hope so,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All the improvements that have come with age were evident in the
Vikings 41-21 divisional playoff victory over Phoenix Sunday.
Cunningham was the calm leader of the NFL's most varied and
volitile offense, his endzone interception the only major flaw to a
17-of-27, 236-yard passing performance. His three touchdown passes
more than made up for the one ill-advised toss.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons behind the new Cunningham are easy enough to trace _
to a more spiritual, stable nature. ``I'm mature as far as life
goes. I look at the mistakes I made and I don't want to make them
again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poise. The poise,'' Vikings nose tackle Jerry Ball has
said. ``The control of emotion. The deliberateness of what he's
trying to do. He's a different quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Jake Plummer, who once hung a Cunningham poster on the
wall of his boyhood bedroom, looked the part of playoff newcomer.
Meanwhile, Cunningham directed the Vikings to a 80-yard, 13-play
drive with the Vikings first possession and a 24-7 lead by
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   He now is a craftsman with many tools. The three touchdown
passes each landed in a different set of hands (tight end Andrew
Glover, running back Leroy Hoard and rookie sensation Randy Moss).
Meanwhile, he benefitted from a running game that amassed 188
yards. Randall Cunningham doesn't have to do it all anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling (to have so many weapons),'' he said,
``but I don't think we really got to everyone today.''
</P>
<P>
   He also had a little fun, three times splitting out as a wide
receiver while running back David Palmer took the snap. ``I'm
wondering what the other guy is thinking. I know they don't think
that I'm going to get the ball, we have plays designed to me. . .I
had a route where I was supposed to run a crossing route, but I
don't want to go up in there too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham has signed a five-year, $28 million contract
extension. He is the NFL's highest-rated quarterback this season.
His postseason debut with Minnesota was a spectacular success. But
he warns that as of Sunday, you haven't seen the best of him or
this Vikings offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we were really on (against the Cardinals). I
hope after today we can get all our cylinders going. We know what
we're capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
