<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALT LAKE PANEL FOCUSING ON EIGHT IOC MEMBERS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An internal ethics panel of the Salt Lake City Olympic
Organizing Committee has linked eight members of the International
Olympic Committee to a scandal involving cash payments, free
medical care, tuition payments and excessive gifts during the
bidding for the 2002 Winter Games, an Olympic official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, also said
Roger Jackson, a Canadian, has emerged as a possible interim chief
operating officer of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee as it seeks
replacements for its top two organizers, who resigned last Friday.
Jackson was described as a member of the organizing committee of
the 1988 Winter Games in Calgary, Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   In the Sunday issue of The Deseret News of Salt Lake City, Tom
Welch, who headed the Salt Lake City bid committee, said he made a
$50,000 cash payment to Jean-Claude Ganga, an IOC member from Congo
Republic, and contributed $10,000 to the mayoral campaign of Sergio
Santander Fantini, an IOC member from Santiago, Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Welch also said Frank Joklik, who resigned last Friday as
president of the SLOC, knew about payments made by the bid
committee. Joklik has denied this.
</P>
<P>
   The expenditures were justified and not part of any vote-buying
effort, Welch said. Welch also denied allegations that the bid
committee had hired prostitutes for members of the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never bribed anybody,'' Welch told the newspaper. ``We
never bought a vote. We made contributions as part of the Olympic
family, as an obligation we have. It was the responsible thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Welch told the newspaper he made a $50,000 payment to Ganga when
the IOC member requested help for children in his ravaged African
nation. The New York Times reported last Saturday that Ganga had
received approximately $70,000 in a series of payments.
</P>
<P>
   Welch was reached at his condominium in Park City, Utah, on
Sunday, but he declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Other IOC members linked to tuition payments for their relatives
include the late Rene Essomba of Cameroon, David Sibandze of
Swaziland and Mohamed Bashir Attarabulsi of Libya. The names of
other members linked to the scandal are not yet known. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
