<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LONGTERM-CARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A START ON LONG-TERM CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, Jan. 11:
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's proposal on long-term care will give only
modest help to most individuals with debilitating illnesses and
family members who are caring for them, and no help at all to the
very poor. But it might do some good if it puts the long-term care
problem on the nation's political agenda and becomes a starting
point for increased federal involvement. The issue cannot be put
off for long as millions of baby boomers begin facing potentially
huge long-term care costs for themselves or their parents.
</P>
<P>
   In New York state, nursing homes charge an average of about $200
a day, or $73,000 a year. The cost in the New York City area is
close to $90,000 a year. Even three home visits a week by a nurse
can cost more than $12,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   With costs this high, few people can afford to pay the bills.
Medicare does not cover most long-term services, nor do regular
health plans, and insurance policies that cover nursing-home costs
can be prohibitively expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid is currently the major financing source for custodial
care, but it is available only to people with extremely low
incomes. Others have to deplete nearly all of their assets before
qualifying for Medicaid. But because nursing-home costs are so
high, more than half of the people entering nursing homes become so
impoverished that they qualify for Medicaid after less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton plan is tiny given these enormous needs. The
centerpiece of the proposal is a $1,000 tax credit for disabled
individuals or families that have such a person living with them.
Like other efforts by the administration to shape social policy
through tax cuts, this one has inherent problems. The credit,
expected to cost about $5.5 billion over five years, is spread so
broadly that the benefit to each individual is very small.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the credit would not help the 40 percent of America's
elderly population with incomes too low to be taxed. It would
primarily benefit middle- and upper-income groups. One way to make
the plan fairer is to make the $1,000 refundable to those who are
too poor to owe taxes. Directly financing state programs that help
the elderly and disabled would be more efficient than the tax cut,
though probably less popular in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Other pieces of the plan offer some promise. The federal
government would give the states $625 million over five years to
provide counseling and support, including respite care, to help
family care-givers. The plan would also allow federal employees to
buy long-term-care insurance policies at lower negotiated group
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Private nursing-home insurance has not been very popular because
premiums can be high. An innovative private insurance program in
New York that helps individuals pay for three years of nursing-home
costs and shields their assets if they should need Medicaid after
three years currently covers fewer than 15,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The modest Clinton proposal does not solve these problems. It
can only ease the burden a little for individuals and families who
get no help now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 2156EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
