<HEADER>
A7041 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOTECH-SFCHRON-BIOTE     01-10 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON - BIOTECH  
 BIOTECH FIRMS MEETING IN S.F. TO WOO INVESTORS  &HT;     By Tom Abate  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Biotech companies get their big chance this week to reclaim some
of the hot money that has moved into Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 3,000 investors will gather at San Francisco's St.
Francis Hotel for the Hambrecht &AMP; Quist health care conference, the
biotech industry's marquee event.
</P>
<P>
   At the four-day meeting starting today, 240 large and small
firms will do their best to wow institutional investors with their
latest scientific and financial results.
</P>
<P>
   This year's conference comes at a time when hundreds of small
and midsize biotech firms have been struggling to raise cash
because Wall Street, lured by quick returns on Internet stocks, has
shied away from smaller biotech companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in a capital-crunch situation for the companies
that are a few years away from profitability,'' said Dennis
Purcell, director of H&AMP;Q's life sciences practice and conference
host.
</P>
<P>
   Purcell said that in 1998, the combined market value of the 25
largest biotech firms grew by $37.1 billion, a 56 percent gain. But
the rest of the industry, some 360 smaller biotech firms,
collectively lost $8.7 billion, an 18 percent decrease in market
value.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, a single Internet stock, Amazon.com, gained $15.4
billion in market cap _ nearly half as much money as the entire
biotech sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small biotech firms, which had been accustomed to going back
to Wall Street for cash infusions, have been struggling,'' Purcell
said.
</P>
<P>
   He expects that many of the companies at the conference will
explain to investors their plans for getting through this dry
spell, through expense controls, partnerships, private placements
or mergers.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, Karen Bernstein, editor of the BioCentury
Newsletter in San Carlos, said last year's cash shortage may have
begun to ease. ``What we saw in the fourth quarter was that even
small biotech firms registered some gains in share price, although
they were down for the year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bennet Weintraub, chief financial officer of Burlingame
biotech firm Megabios Corp., said he doesn't believe in a quick
return to the good old days, when scientists could easily get Wall
Street backing for bright ideas that might take years to move from
the laboratory to the drug store.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too many small companies out there whose whole futures
rest on a single line of research that may or may not pay off,''
Weintraub said. ``These companies are going to have to merge or
else be forced out.''
</P>
<P>
   Megabios itself is merging with Houston's GeneMedicine, another
public biotech startup that works in the same area as Megabios _
devising new genetic tools to deliver drugs to targeted cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``These sorts of mergers rarely went on before,'' Weintraub
said. But last year's cash crunch forced biotech firms to look for
ways to become more than one-trick ponies. According to BioCentury,
27 mergers were completed or announced in the fourth quarter of
1998, up from just eight deals in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Small companies that decide to sell out should have no trouble
finding buyers. Chiron Corp., a large biotech firm in Emeryville,
is sitting on $1.2 billion it earned from selling off its
diagnostics division and has said it will use at least part of its
hoard to finance acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalist Bob McNeil of Sanderling in Menlo Park hopes
last year's cash crisis prompts biotech companies to lower their
burn rate _ the amount of money they spend before they start
generating product revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened in most of the '90s was that you had all these
raw startups, with no lab or anything, getting $6 million one day,
and thinking it has to last them two years,'' McNeil said. ``Why
not make it last four years'' by keeping staffing and overhead to a
minimum?
</P>
<P>
   He said his bare-bones philosophy has helped one of his
startups, ReGen Biologics of Redwood City, bring two products to
late-stage clinical trials for less than $12 million. The products,
which are in Phase III trials before the Food and Drug
Administration, seek to repair the knee tissue that people injure
in skiing or other sporting accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most guys would be thrilled if they could get two compounds to
that stage for $25 or $30 million,'' McNeil said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to pledging renewed allegiance to thrift, the
companies presenting at H&AMP;Q will try to assure investors that they
aren't mesmerized by science, but are focused on bringing products
through the Food and Drug Administration's approval process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, the scientific advances are there and you have
lots of small-to-midsize companies with products on the market or
about to come on the market,'' said H&AMP;Q's Purcell.
</P>
<P>
   In one 1998 survey, the Pharmaceutical Research and
Manufacturers of America Association counted 350 biotech products
moving through the various stages of human testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, investors haven't valued that,'' Purcell said. ``I
think that points to a big opportunity in the sector.''
</P>
<P>
   He named two overlooked companies with promising products:
SangStat, the Menlo Park firm that has two transplant drugs on the
market, and Coulter Pharmaceuticals of Palo Alto, which hopes to
get regulatory approval soon to market a drug to fight
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the whole purpose of the H&AMP;Q conference is to give
each company a chance to make its case to the institutional
investors who have been focusing only on the large companies.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Feldbaum, president of the Biotechnology Industry
Association, expressed the hopeful view that investors will leave
San Francisco this week ready to bet on the majority of overlooked
firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got better science and better management than we've ever
had as an industry,'' Feldbaum said. ``I think investors are ready
to take a look at some of the small companies that have not been
recognized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
