<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON - MUSIC  
 MP3s Turn Up the Volume  
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Executives at the world's five biggest record companies have
started to discuss how best to deal with Internet music pirates.
They hope to have the answer by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But a handful of companies like Audio Explosion of San Francisco
aren't waiting that long. They're ready to sell copyright-protected
MP3-formatted songs now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology is here today,'' said Arnold Brown II, Audio
Explosion's president and CEO. The year-old startup is trying to
capitalize on the growing popularity of MP3, an audio format that
can compress, play and distribute music via the Internet or on one
of a number of portable devices coming to the market.
</P>
<P>
   `'It's hard to wait,'' Brown said. ``We want to be known as the
company that provides a secure solution for MP3s.''
</P>
<P>
   Audio Explosion last week began selling a small selection of
legal, copyright-protected songs for $1 each. The songs, playable
using Audio Explosion's own Mjuice Music Player, are part of a
special promotion targeted at people who have purchased the Rio
PMP300, Diamond Multimedia Systems Inc.'s controversial portable
MP3 music player.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the company hopes to open its Mjuice.com site for the
general public sometime in February and is already is working with
a major record label that could make music from hip-hop stars like
Big Pun and Funkmaster Flex available in the MP3 format.
</P>
<P>
   Audio Explosion isn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow, AudioSoft Inc. will launch a new version of the
Internet's most popular MP3 player, WinAmp, which uses AudioSoft's
music-scrambling technology designed to prevent MP3 songs from
being illegally copied and distributed.
</P>
<P>
   AudioSoft CEO Francois-Xavier Nuttall, who founded the company
in 1986 in Switzerland, is shifting his operations to Fremont later
this month to be closer to the mainstream Silicon Valley technology
companies. One of his investors is pop star Phil Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to build on the momentum,'' Nuttall said,
referring to MP3. ``In no way shall I just sit around to wait for
the majors (recording labels) to make a move. I believe the
consumer is ready to pay a fair amount to have some quality
content.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's MCY America Inc. of New York, which plans to launch
a Web site on January 24 that also will sell protected MP3 music.
</P>
<P>
   ``The digital music revolution has begun,'' proclaimed Bernhard
Fritsch, president and CEO of MCY. ``We're not only talking, we are
ready to go. It's a fully developed system, and we'll be offering
up to 1 million songs in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Each company is trying to ride the wave that has made MP3 one of
the most popular topics on Internet search engines.
</P>
<P>
   MP3, shorthand for MPEG 1, Layer 3, is a technical standard
approved by international audio and video engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Using MP3, a song that would take up about 50 megabytes of space
on a computer hard dri &LR;   &LR; ve can be compressed to about 5 megabytes
but still retain the sound quality of a CD.
</P>
<P>
   Songs also can be ``ripped,'' or copied, from a regular CD onto
the hard drive of a personal computer using MP3. From there, the
song is played back on computer speakers using any of the widely
available software programs, including Microsoft's Media Player.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 songs grew in popularity as high school and college students
with access to high-speed Internet lines began trading songs or
posting them on Web sites for free downloads by other MP3 fans. The
popularity spread in the past year as more home and business users
gained higher-speed modems or Internet lines.
</P>
<P>
   PC Computing magazine recently reported that the Internet has
become a virtual jukebox filled with at least 20,000 free songs.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the Recording Industry Association of America
views this development as a threat. It says the distribution of
those songs, especially music by artists under contract to the
major record labels, violates copyright laws and reduces their
sales revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the MP3 phenomenon has made only a tiny dent in the
$40 billion worldwide recording industry. Analyst Mark Hardie of
Forrester Research of Cambridge, Mass., believes that it will take
another five years before there is a significant shift of
consumer-buying habits toward Internet music.
</P>
<P>
   But the Big Five labels _ BMG Entertainment, Sony Music, Warner
Music Group, EMI Recorded Music and Universal Music Group _ that
control about 80 percent of the popular music industry already
worry that MP3s are just the tip of an iceberg that could sink
their record-distribution structure.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, MP3 music has vividly demonstrated how easily songs
can be sold via the Internet directly from artist to consumer,
bypassing the traditional middlemen like retail stores, CD-makers,
music distributors, wholesalers or even record companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``MP3 represents artists' empowerment,'' said Michael Robertson,
founder of a site that has become an MP3 portal,  &LR; www.MP3.com.
 &LR; ``It's about consumer freedom. It's not just about pirate music.
It's much bigger than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Big Five, acknowledging that the Web was their
future, put aside their differences to form a rare alliance called
the Secure Digital Music Initiative to decide how to protect their
online music interests.
</P>
<P>
   The SDMI hopes to set technology standards by the end of 1999
ensuring that Internet music distribution moves forward while still
protecting copyrights and revenues. The SDMI includes companies
like Liquid Audio of Redwood City and A2b Music of New York, which
still hope the industry adopts their own secured digital music
formats, which are different than MP3.
</P>
<P>
   But companies like Audio Explosion, AudioSoft and MCY say the
Internet public has already spoken and adopted the MP3-formatted
songs, so they believe that they will be in position to sell or
license their technologies long before the SDMI makes a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Each, in fact, claims they already are negotiating with some of
those record companies on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Audio Explosion has cut an informal but potentially
groundbreaking deal to develop MP3 songs as promotional tools for
Loud Records, which has a stable of well-known hip-hop artists like
Wu-Tang Clan, Funkmaster Flex and Grammy Award-nominee Big Pun.
</P>
<P>
   That's significant because Loud Records is half-owned by BMG
Entertainment, one of the Big Five in the recording industry.
</P>
<P>
   Hardie of Forrester Research expects that the SDMI will fail
before the companies agree to a standard. He also predicted that
BMG will be the first to break ranks and embrace MP3s, with Sony
not far behind with its its own portable MP3 player.
</P>
<P>
   Loud Records' collaboration with Audio Explosion appears to be
``the first crack in the dam,'' Hardie said.
</P>
<P>
   While BMG has been publicly skeptical about MP3, it also
realizes there's a market for Web music, said Randy Weiner, Loud
Records' executive producer for new media.
</P>
<P>
   Loud wants to start with giving away a limited number of songs
on Audio Explosion to promote new albums but also sees MP3 as a
path to future music sales on the Web, Weiner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
