<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NET FILES/JON SWARTZ 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - THE NET FILES   Playboy Sues Ex-Playmate Over Web Site 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one of the highest-profile cases involving trademark
protection on the Internet, Playboy Enterprises is suing former
Playmate Terri Welles over her alleged use of a programming trick
to lure Web surfers to her site.
</P>
<P>
   The adult-entertainment publishing empire claims that Welles,
41, of San Diego is using a technology called ``meta tags'' to
confuse people into thinking her site is connected to Playboy's.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyer counters that she is just trying to make a living.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts are closely watching the case to see what impact
it will have on Internet trademark disputes _ especially as
companies invest heavily in Net sites as potential revenue sources.
</P>
<P>
   Welles' attorney, David Noonan, says his client created her
commercial site ( &LR; www.terriwelles.com &LR; ) in June 1997 with the
blessing of Playboy founder Hugh Heffner. Under the banner headline
``1981 Playmate of the Year,'' it contains photos of a scantily
clad Welles, biographical information and links to X-rated banner
ads. Nude pictures are sold separately.
</P>
<P>
   Things went well until August 1997, when Playboy started Cyber
Club, its own online den of Playmates and centerfolds. It asked
Welles to join. She refused. Playboy sued Welles in February 1998
for trademark infringement over her use of the phrase ``Playmate of
the Year'' and sought $5 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy requested a preliminary injunction. A federal judge in
San Diego ruled in favor of Welles in May 1998. The decision was
upheld in October by the U.S. Court of Appeals in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Playboy added a new claim to its lawsuit: trademark
counterfeiting. Welles countersued Playboy last week for defamation
and unfair-business practices. A final pretrial hearing on the
Playboy suit is scheduled for federal district court this spring in
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy objects in particular to the site's use of meta tags.
These are key words embedded in a site's programming code so that
the site is prominently mentioned in certain Internet search
results. They are used by many sites, especially
adult-entertainment ones.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Playboy contends that Welles illegally included meta tags for
the words ``Playboy'' and ``Playmate'' so that Web users are
directed to her site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like traveling on the freeway and seeing a sign for
Chevron, but when you pull off the road, you find other gas
stations instead,'' said Neil Smith, a San Francisco Internet
trademark attorney who has represented Playboy in unrelated cases.
``Eventually, you may find Chevron, but it is a misleading sign.''
</P>
<P>
   David Francescani, an attorney for Playboy Enterprises in
Chicago, said that once Playboy customers are ``hijacked'' to
Welles' site, they can count on getting an eyeful of unsavory ads
that Playboy ``would never be associated with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no problem with her site,'' he said, ``but we do
object to the use of meta tags. The magazine is simply trying to
protect itself against unfair competition and trademark
infringement.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
URGE TO MERGE: Acquisitions of three Bay Area Internet service
providers last week is a harbinger of major consolidation in the
crowded ISP market. Whether that's good news for consumers remains
to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Slip.Net, Netcom and the parent company of Best Internet
Communications were gobbled up by larger communications companies
that intend to blend the ISPs into their vast networking and online
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Although a bigger company might mean more and better services
for customers, less competition could hurt in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Data communications companies like us want to round out our
offerings with Internet service,'' said Sheldon Ohringer, CEO of
FirstWorlds, the San Diego company that acquired Slip.Net for
$10.45 million in cash plus 187,000 shares of stock Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Added Slip.Net President Ted Glenwright: The buyout ``gives our
20,000 customers richer service and support at the same price.''
</P>
<P>
   Other ISP customers can only hope they are as lucky.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the ISP boom in 1997, flat-rate pricing was de
riguer. America Online, Netcom and others were offering unlimited
Internet access for $19.95 per month. Today, AOL has increased its
monthly rate to $21.95. Earlier this year, IBM Internet Connection
Services eschewed the unlimited pricing model in favor of metered
rates based on time of use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are turning away from unlimited hours,'' said Greg
Tally, associate editor at Boardwatch of Golden, Colo., a magazine
that tracks ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   There currently are 5,000 ISPs in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ICG Communications Inc., which bought Netcom 14 months ago, sold
the San Jose ISP to MindSpring Enterprises of Atlanta for $245
million in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   Verio bought Hiway Technologies, parent of Best Internet, for
about $350 million in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
I'VE GOT A SECRET: To the surprise of nearly everyone _ especially
self-described iCEO Steve Jobs _ Apple Computer was able to keep a
tight lid on last week's surprise announcement of lollipop-colored
iMacs at the Macworld Expo computer show in San Francisco. For such
a notoriously loose-lipped company, the secret was as unlikely as
Ken Starr keeping his investigation under wraps.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; So how did Apple stay mum on the space-age Internet computers?
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing a page from the CIA, it allegedly covered in drapes a
portion of its Macworld Expo booth to hide the new machines and it
even sent a security force to a print shop to oversee production of
the colorful iMac posters, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
