<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-JAGUARS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS BAG JAGS, BRONCOS ARE UP NEXT 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ With the largest crowd to see a pro
football game in the New York region rattling Giants Stadium, the
New York Jets defeated the Jacksonville Jaguars, 34-24, Sunday and
suddenly found themselves 30 years and 60 minutes from returning to
a Super Bowl in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's victory, before a crowd of 78,817, put the Jets in the
American Conference championship game next Sunday in Denver, where
they will be underdogs against the defending Super Bowl champion
Broncos. The winner will play in Super Bowl XXXIII on Jan. 31, a
game the Jets have appeared in only once _ 30 years ago Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Only two seasons ago, the Jets had a 1-15 record, the worst in
the National Football League for a second consecutive season, and
they had not won a playoff game in 12 years. So Sunday was a
remarkable day for a franchise whose past three decades had been
overshadowed by its historic victory in Super Bowl III.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a remarkable day for their star wide receiver,
Keyshawn Johnson, who had said before the game, ``I want to be the
guy on every play, running, catching, blocking, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday he nearly was the guy on every play. He ran for two
touchdowns, on a reverse and on a 21-yard pass from Vinny
Testaverde; recovered a fumble at a pivotal moment by racing 60
yards in pursuit of a Jaguar player, and then moved to defense and
intercepted a desperation pass from quarterback Mark Brunell.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in 62 years that a player has managed such
accomplishments on both sides of the line of scrimmage, but he
probably was the least surprised of anyone. With anxiety keeping
him awake, he said sleeping only three hours on Saturday night was
an indication that he was going to do great things.
</P>
<P>
   His interception was no surprise. All week, the Jets practiced
with the 6-foot-3-inch Johnson in the role of extra defensive back.
Brunell's pass was a heave of 60 yards, but Johnson outjumped
everyone to haul it in at the 7-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   For the game, Johnson had nine receptions for 121 yards and
rushed for 28 yards on two carries. His big day was shared by
running back Curtis Martin and quarterback Vinny Testaverde. Martin
handled the ball 42 times, with 36 rushing attempts for 124 yards
and two touchdowns and six receptions for 58 yards. Testaverde
completed 24 of his 36 passes for 284 yards for one touchdown, with
one interception.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets statistically dominated the Jaguars, who were bidding
for their second appearance in a conference championship game in
their four seasons. At times it seemed that the Jets would rout the
Jaguars. They built leads of 17-0, 24-7 and 31-14, but Jacksonville
kept coming up with big plays to narrow the margin.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's victory also represented a personal achievement for
Testaverde, who is in his first season with the Jets after being
let go by the Baltimore Ravens and signing as a free agent in the
off season. Testaverde had lost all six of the games he had played
against Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Testaverde said he was not surprised by the success he
has had this season in leading the Jets to victories in 13 of the
14 games he has started.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Parcells, the architect of this team's unprecedented
rise from a one-victory season to the divisional title, is aware
that the Jets have to play better than they did today to beat the
Broncos, who have won 18 consecutive games at home.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was critical of several plays by the Jets, but said:
``This was a good win for our franchise. I was happy for our fans.
I'm happy about it. But there's more to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive lineman Ernie Logan was more direct. ``If we do next
Sunday what we did today, we are not going to win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, everything seemed headed toward perfection. Johnson
opened the scoring on a 21-yard pass from Testaverde. John Hall
kicked the longest field goal in Jets' playoff history, 52 yards,
and then Johnson continued his string of heroics.
</P>
<P>
   First, Martin fumbled on the Jaguars' 22. Jacksonville's Chris
Hudson recovered and dashed along the right sideline, past
midfield. From there, just as he was about to be run out of bounds,
he appeared to try to lateral the ball, although the officials
ruled that he fumbled. The ball bounced around and suddenly it was
pounced on by Johnson, who had been a potential receiver far
downfield in the other direction.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets proceeded to drive to the Jaguars' 10, where Johnson
got the ball again. This time it was on an end-around play and he
dashed into the end zone for a touchdown. It was the second time
this season that he had scored on the play.
</P>
<P>
   That put the Jets ahead by 17-0, a lead that was trimmed on the
final play of the first half when Brunell connected with Jimmy
Smith on a 52-yard score after Jerome Henderson missed the
coverage. The Jets left the field with Parcells directing a tirade
at Henderson. After controlling the ball for more than 14 minutes
in the 15-minute quarter, they had suddenly lost momentum.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jets came out for the third quarter and quickly scored,
with Martin churning out a final 1-yard dive. It was a dramatic day
for Martin, who also caught three screens, picking up good yardage
against overcommitted Jaguars. He also benefited from good blocking
from the linemen.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-7 edge, though, lasted only 65 seconds. Reggie Barlow
returned the kickoff 88 yards and a few plays later Brunell
connected with Keenan McCardell on a 3-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   If the Jets were to fold, this seemed to be the moment. Instead,
they continued to demonstrate that the six-game winning streak that
closed the season toughened them. They quickly roared back with
another Martin touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Jaguars continued to make it interesting. In the
final period, Brunell clicked on a third-and-15 with Smith for a
19-yard touchdown as Otis Smith was covering.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Chrebet fumbled on the next drive and the Jaguars
converted the turnover into a 37-yard Mike Hollis field goal. Now
the Jets' lead was down to 31-24.
</P>
<P>
   On the next drive the Jets got to the Jaguars' 14, and
Testaverde threw the ball into the end zone for Keith Byars. At
that point, with about two and a half minutes remaining, a field
goal would have put the Jets up by 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Testaverde was hit as he threw. The pass was
intercepted by Donovin Darius. Unwisely, Darius attempted to run
out of the end zone and was stopped at the one by Byars. Had he
stayed in the end zone, the ball would have come out to the 20.
</P>
<P>
   Brunell was unable to move the Jaguars and the Jets took over
and produced a 30-yard Hall field goal for a 10-point edge.
</P>
<P>
   That set up Brunell's final opportunity. After the kickoff, he
got the ball at his 41. He let his last pass fly, but Brunell never
quite expected that Johnson was back on the field, playing defense
and ready to intercept the Jaguars' hopes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
