<SLUG> BC-DIGITALBAY-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL BAY/TOM ABATE 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - DIGITAL BAY   Lotus Founder Mitch Kapor Admits Move to Boston Was a Mistake 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
In 1980, a twentysomething entrepreneur moved from Silicon Valley
to Boston and started a software company.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Mitch Kapor, founder of Lotus Development Corp.,
recalled that fateful decision, as he discussed his plan to move
back here again to join Accel Partners, a venture capital firm in
Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   ``If only I'd stayed on the West Coast, I might have made
something of myself,'' quipped Kapor, who will be bicoastal for
several months before replanting himself full time in San
Francisco's Pacific Heights.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to popularizing the Lotus 1-2-3 spreadsheet that
made the PC a fixture in the business world, Kapor co-founded the
Electronic Frontier Foundation, the San Francisco nonprofit group
that focuses on Internet policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kapor has maintained a low business profile for years,
he has been an early private investor in several ventures that paid
large dividends. In 1993, for instance, before the Internet gold
rush began, he became one of the first outside investors in UUNet,
an early Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``My history is to find the next big thing early,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kapor was coy about where he intends to look for future scores,
but he did disclose his modus operandi _ it won't include poring
through the business plans that come in over the transom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real deals that get funded come from your network of
personal contacts,'' said Kapor, whose relationships go back to the
earliest days of the PC revolution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THEY GOT MAIL?: Letters or phone calls are still a far-more
effective way to influence your congressional representative than
fax or e-mail, according to a new survey from OMB Watch, a
nonprofit political watchdog group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which pulls together a variety of recent research
into Congress' cyber-quotient, says most House and all Senate
members have some form of Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But to no one's surprise, many of those Web sites contain
outdated information. On the upside, nearly 60 percent of the sites
made it easy for browsers to e-mail comments to the member.
</P>
<P>
   But just because the e-mails are getting through doesn't mean
they're being heeded. Most members screen out and disregard
electronic messages from nonconstituents. And even when
representatives do acknowledge or reply to e-mails, the response
most likely will come by snail mail.
</P>
<P>
   The full text of the report can be downloaded at
 &LR; www.ombwatch.org &LR;   &LR; /ombw/npt/reports &LR;   &LR; /emailsurvey.pdf. &LR;   &QL; 
 &QL; 
LEGAL MYSTERY: Silicon Valley is still weighing the impact of a
California Supreme Court ruling last week. It allows out-of-state
residents to go into California courts to file class-action suits
that charge California companies with stock fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Such shareholder suits are the bane of high-tech execs, who feel
victimized by law firms that specialize in suing when a company's
stock drops unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the past three years, Silicon Valley lobbyists have
persuaded Congress to change the rules under which such suits are
filed in federal courts. The most recent change, in 1998, required
that most class-action suits for stock fraud be filed in federal
courts _ where the rules of evidence were changed in 1995 to favor
Silicon Valley defendants.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1998 law left one loophole for lawyers who might like to
file fraud class-action suits in state courts like those in
California, where fraud laws still favor plaintiffs. Even under the
1998 reform, it is still legal for 49 or fewer plaintiffs to file a
class action in state court.
</P>
<P>
   Now Silicon Valley execs wonder if the California Supreme Court
ruling can be combined with that federal provision that lets 49 or
fewer plaintiffs file in state courts. If it's possible, it will
give plaintiff's attorneys a new loophole to file in state courts
where the rules of evidence in fraud cases favor their clients.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Grundfest, a Stanford law professor who tracks this issue,
said lawyers could round up four dozen institutional investors,
even if they have offices in New York, and file class actions under
California's more-liberal fraud rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a risk here of undermining the 1998 reform, which was
to steer all these cases to the federal courts, so companies traded
on national stock markets will only have to conform to one set of
rules,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The California Supreme Court ruling was won by the San Diego law
firm of Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes &AMP; Lerach, which has long been
the most prolific filer of stock fraud suits against Valley firms.
</P>
<P>
   Milberg Weiss attorney Tom Dato said his firm has ``no
particular game plan'' to round up institutional investors to
become plaintiffs for stock fraud cases filed in California.
</P>
<P>
   But Dato noted that two state retirement funds, one in Missouri
and the other in Pennsylvania, filed friend-of-court briefs
supporting Milberg Weiss' contention that out-of-staters should be
able to file fraud class actions under California rules _ as long
as they number 49 or fewer. (Any suit with 50 or more plaintiffs
would be handled by federal courts.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we're going to have to see whether the impact of this
case is significant,'' Dato said.
</P>
<P>
   Grundfest predicted that the Silicon Valley side would ask the
U.S. Supreme Court to review the California decision, in the hopes
of getting a ruling that only plaintiffs in California should be
able to file fraud class actions in California courts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
