r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CES-SFCHRON-CES &LR;      01-10 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CES-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG, THE BOLD AND THE BIZARRE 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - CES   By Carolyn Said 
 &HT;     Chronicle Technology Editor 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR; ``Have you heard the pillow yet? You must hear the pillow,''
exclaimed Grant Nelson, a spokesman at the Pillow-Phonic booth at
the Consumer Electronics Show here.
</P>
<P>
   A pillow seems kind of, well, soft to qualify as an electronics
device, but this $59.95 ``audio-pillow relaxation system'' has more
to it than meets the eye (or ear).
</P>
<P>
   Nestled inside the hypo-allergenic fibers is a pair of digital
speakers. You plug a radio, or CD/tape player into a small jack and
_ voila _ you can listen to soothing nature sounds, subliminal
learning tapes or Counting Crows without disturbing your bedmate or
fussing with headphones.
</P>
<P>
   While the CES show has heavy-duty electronics galore _ 64-inch
rear-projection digital TVs, $16,000 stereo speakers, cars smarter
than most drivers _ it also has many products whose charm lies in
their more modest approach, such as electronic nose-hair clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Or take Freeplay Energy Group's self-powered radios ($89) and
flashlights ($69). You just turn a crank to power them. Thirty
seconds of cranking gives you an hour of use. Freeplay usually
markets them to boaters and campers, but the CES crowd had a
different use in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is perfect for Y2K,'' said two Silicon Valley engineers.
</P>
<P>
   For another variation on portable listening, there is the $99.95
Bike Jammer, billed as the first stereo for your bicycle. Shaped
like a foreshortened submarine, it snaps onto the handlebars and
includes a halogen headlight and a pair of speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the technologies at CES, the telephone is probably the
oldest, and the concept of stylized phones to match decors is
hardly new. Still, vendors managed to come up with some fresh
twists.
</P>
<P>
   Kash N Gold Ltd. seemed to have a slam-dunk with its Michael
Jordan phone. Shaped like a regular-sized basketball, it opens up
to reveal a basketball arena whenever it receives an incoming call.
Instead of a ring, you hear an announcer enthusiastically
introducing No.23, while lights flash, the crowd does the wave and
images of Jordan appear on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Uniden salespeople were proud to present the world's first
official Harley-Davidson phone, though it wasn't clear if the bulky
black-and-silver phone or the sleek black-leather-clad spokesmodel
was a bigger draw.
</P>
<P>
   Kash N Gold also has addressed the need for fun paper shredders.
There's a golf course model where you put the paper in the water
hazard, and the NFL football stadium model. It also carries remote
controls shaped like fishing reels and race cars, and boom boxes in
brushed-aluminum briefcases.
</P>
<P>
   Why so many variations on familiar themes?
</P>
<P>
   ``Many electronics are so inexpensive that manufacturers can go
ahead and make them goofy,'' said Jim Barry, a spokesman for the
Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association, the trade group
that sponsors CES. ``Twenty years ago, a calculator cost $200 and
was the size of a laptop. Now, you can literally give them away. So
everyone's looking for a way to make things appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   For people who found the Las Vegas desert heat unbearable
(although in January, you don't hear too many complaints), there is
U B Kool, a handheld gizmo that looks like an electric shaver. The
$49 ``electronic ice cube'' has a circular area slightly larger
than a 50-cent piece that gets cold _ about 40 degrees Fahrenheit _
when you press a button. ``Then you can rub it on your neck or
wrists to cool your blood,'' said the booth representative.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the brochure's claim that it utilizes
``NASA-developed solid-state chip technology,'' he ventured, ``I
think it's the same way they cool the astronauts' space suits.''
</P>
<P>
   Another health-oriented item is PolluCorp's Pollumetre Air, a
pocket-size air pollution detector. Its brochure, too, had a
problem containing its enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helps you to better protect yourself from damage caused by
atmospheric pollution. Allows you to improve your quality of life
and to adapt your behavior according to the situation,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   So what does that really mean?
</P>
<P>
   The device flashes a number indicating how much carbon monoxide
is in the air, measured in parts per million.
</P>
<P>
   If the number seems too high, you can go somewhere else. Or you
could just stop breathing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
