<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-MINORITIES--NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK AND HISPANIC LEADERS SEEK CONSENSUS ON SENATE RACE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now that the state's highest ranking black elected
official has removed himself from next year's race for U.S. Senate,
a group of black and Hispanic elected officials, political
strategists and businessmen _ led by the Rev. Al Sharpton _ have
begun meeting to discuss uniting behind a single minority
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton, who has failed twice before to win the Democratic
nomination for the Senate, said he was strongly considering trying
again. He said he would decide by April whether to seek the seat
being vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan, basing his decision on
the deliberations of the group of elected officials, which includes
legislators primarily from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Sunday, Sharpton, who has also considered a
second candidacy for mayor of New York City in 2001, said, ``Right
now, I would say there is a 50-50 chance'' he would attempt a third
Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions among the black and Hispanic officials _ all
Democrats _ come at a time when two of the party's strongest
potential contenders have decided not to run. Last month, State
Comptroller H. Carl McCall said he would not seek the Senate seat.
He made the decision after receiving what was tantamount to an
endorsement from Moynihan, who said the Senate should have a black
member. And last week, Andrew Cuomo, secretary of housing and urban
development and son of former Gov. Mario Cuomo, also said he would
not run.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's meeting at Jimmy's Bronx Cafe, which included two
dozen elected officials and an equal number of political tacticians
and business owners, was led by Sharpton and state Sen. Efrain
Gonzales Jr. of the Bronx. Gonzales said that several more meetings
were planned over the next few months. He and Sharpton said
McCall's withdrawal made it more critical that black and Hispanic
leaders focus on uniting behind a single candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that we develop a new alliance of black and
Latinos,'' Sharpton said. He said the victories of Sen. Charles
Schumer and state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer were due in large
measure to the strong turnout by black and Latino voters. ``We have
seen what can happen when we come together.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sharpton sounded very much like a candidate. ``The fact
is that I am the only African-American to have run for the Senate
nomination and there are a lot of people who are urging me to
run,'' Sharpton said. ``With Carl McCall out of the race, I don't
know any others who have the statewide recognition that I have.''
</P>
<P>
   To many New Yorkers, however, Sharpton remains a highly
controversial political figure, a result of his seemingly perennial
involvement in racially charged cases. Last summer, for example, a
jury in Dutchess County ordered him to pay $65,000 to a white
former prosecutor whom Sharpton had accused of kidnapping and
raping a black teen-ager 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In his race for the 1992 Democratic nomination for the Senate,
Sharpton placed third in a four-way race, receiving 14 percent of
the vote. Two years later, he received 26 percent of the vote
against Moynihan in the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's meeting was attended by elected officials from
throughout the city, including Assemblyman Keith Wright, who is
chairman of the state's Black and Puerto Rican Legislative Caucus;
state Sen. David Paterson of Manhattan, City Councilman Angel
Rodriguez of Brooklyn and Assemblyman Ruben Diaz Jr. of the Bronx.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
