<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990110.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7060 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     01-10 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN WOMEN COME UP ONE GUARD SHORT
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ Geno Auriemma rotated players in and out until
they looked as if they had whiplash, but he never did find the
unifying piece, or point. Against the likes of Tennessee,
Connecticut looked to be one bird short of a championship flock.
</P>
<P>
   Against Chamique Holdsclaw and the three-time defending national
champions, UConn needed Sue Bird, recruited out of Christ the King
High School in Queens, just as Holdsclaw was by Tennessee, to bring
some direction, some city savvy, to a deep but inexperienced team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking forward to playing against her, the same way
players in the NBA want Michael Jordan to stay,'' Bird said after.
``They want to get their rings through him.''
</P>
<P>
   Fate, in the form of the anterior cruciate ligament in her left
knee, ran a backdoor cut on Bird. In a practice last month, the
5-foot-9-inch freshman blew out the knee, and her one sure chance
to play against Holdsclaw, who encased four state championship
trophies at Christ the King for Bird to look at when she
transferred in the year after Holdsclaw left. Also gone with the
untimely snap, in all likelihood, is Auriemma's chance of wresting
a championship from Coach Pat Summitt before Holdsclaw takes her
summertime dreams and quick pull-up jumper to the pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said going in we were one guard short, and we were right,''
Auriemma said after the Huskies lost the game, 92-81, and the No. 1
ranking, at Gampel Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   It is much easier to beat a team like Tennessee on paper.
Auriemma's unyielding substitutions also play more to his all-court
pressure system than any one talent, but Bird, no relation to the
Indiana Birds, is a creative, offensive point guard. Conversely,
the play of her replacement and roommate, the freshman Keirsten
Walters, was tentative, to be kind about it, especially as UConn
tried to pull ahead with Holdsclaw on the bench late in the game
with four fouls.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time I took her out and said, `Go spend the next three
minutes finding your brain, and when you find it, I'll put you back
in,''' Auriemma said.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds harsh, well, this was about as big as it gets
outside the Final Four. One versus two. A sold-out arena. National
television (at least when the network had shown enough post-game
football replays). The appropriate amount of tension and passion,
even a near first-half fight as Tennessee's wonderfully aggressive
Semeka Randall fought on the floor for a rebound with Svetlana
Abrosimova, did a complete body flip and kicked Abrosimova in the
head.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of game, end to end, until Tennessee, at 76-76,
ran off 12 straight points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone want their money back?'' Auriemma said.
</P>
<P>
   Not really, but Bird did express an interest in the
reacquisition of her uniform and mobility, in time for a possible
rematch next spring. The doctors have told her not to hope too
hard. Six months, they said. Bird said she has a friend who
recovered from similar surgery in five weeks. She is drawing
inspiration from her teammate Shea Ralph, a two-time victim. Kellie
Jolly, Tennessee's senior point guard, who graciously encouraged
Bird after the game, had her knee cut as a sophomore and made it
back in time to co-star with Holdsclaw in championship game No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to get back,'' Bird said, ``just to make a foul
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   All she could do yesterday was trail her teammates to the court,
stiff-legged, in tan slacks, a white pullover shirt and sleeveless
blue sweater. She took a seat in the row behind the UConn bench,
and watched Walters force too many passes, shoot too many air
balls. She watched Holdsclaw restore the carbonation to those shots
that were so flat last week against Rutgers at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw would have fared better financially had she left
college after her junior year and leveraged the now defunct
American Basketball League for a few hundred thousand from David
Stern's women's annex. But now that she stayed, she figures she may
as well bat 1.000, win a fourth title, let the Huskies inherit the
sport after she's gone, the way Bird took over at Christ the King.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I came here, UConn owned Tennessee,'' said Holdsclaw,
who had 25 points, nine rebounds, four assists.
</P>
<P>
   Summitt, who won a few trinkets before she convinced Holdsclaw
that Knoxville was ``just like New York,'' shot her star an
oh-really look.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it is with the prime-time players, who are too busy
achieving to consider what came before, or what comes next. Bird
said the sight of those trophies at Christ the King motivated her
to want ``to outdo'' Holdsclaw. In the stands yesterday was still
another Christ the King headliner, Clare Droesch, who just last
week scored more points in one game, 48, than Holdsclaw or Bird.
</P>
<P>
   Droesch is a high school sophomore. Her time will come. Bird, a
college freshman, said she is ``rehabbing like crazy,'' but the
medical odds are that she will have to settle for next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies will wait for her. They will win many more games
this season with their talent and depth. Auriemma will keep
rotating players at his dizzying pace, but he will not find the
player he needs to beat Tennessee on his bench. She is one row
behind it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 2219EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
