<DOCNO> NYT19990110.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7063 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS     01-10 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNRAVELING SEEN IN SENATE'S BIPARTISAN ACCORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ All signs indicated Sunday that the Senate's
fragile agreement on how to conduct President Clinton's impeachment
trial faces serious obstacles, including a potential showdown over
whether to expand the case by permitting testimony by several
``Jane Does'' who have made claims about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As the president's lawyers prepared to meet a noon deadline
Monday to file a written defense to the impeachment charges, key
players sparred over several major questions the Senate left
unanswered last week in its compromise blueprint for the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the disputes, ranging from the possible Jane Doe
witnesses to whether the Senate's deliberations as jurors should be
open to public scrutiny, must be resolved before Clinton's fate is
ultimately decided, possibly in mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the controversy, the White House announced that Clinton
intends to deliver his State of the Union address to Congress next
week, despite calls from members of both parties to postpone the
annual speech until after the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no intention of being diverted from addressing the
issues that are important to the country,'' said James Kennedy, a
White House spokesman. He said Clinton will deliver the address on
Tuesday night, Jan. 19, as originally scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Under a tentative trial plan, Clinton would deliver the address
the same day his lawyers give opening statements to rebut charges
that the president lied under oath to a federal grand jury and
obstructed justice to try to conceal an extramarital affair in the
White House with a former intern, Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The House ``managers,'' or prosecutors, who must file a written
brief by 5 p.m. Monday and respond to Clinton's brief by noon on
Wednesday, are scheduled to begin their opening arguments Thursday
at 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides would debate pretrial motions on Wednesday, but
neither side would say Sunday what motions, if any, they plan to
file. The motions must be filed Monday by 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the 13 House managers who will present the case
against Clinton argued Sunday that it is crucial to compel Lewinsky
and perhaps the purported Jane Does to testify in the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Lindsey O. Graham, a South Carolina Republican,
cited a 1997 civil deposition in the Paula Corbin Jones sexual
harassment suit, in which Clinton said, ``I've never sexually
harassed anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some women out there who, if you believe them, would
make that a lie,'' Graham said on NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' ``If a
witness meets the criteria to help us explain that this is about a
persuasive, all-encompassing obstruction case, then I think, yes,
we should have the right to call any witnesses before the Senate
that can show that there's a pattern of obstruction of justice
here. This is very much the essence of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats oppose calling witnesses, particularly the Jane
Does, whose claims were never aired in the House impeachment
process.
</P>
<P>
   Under a bipartisan deal reached last week to conduct the trial,
the Senate would vote later this month on whether to grant the
House request for witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But the compromise also provides for the witness vote to follow
a likely motion to dismiss the charges, which would make the
witness question moot if the charges were dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John H. Chafee of Rhode Island, a moderate Republican,
said Sunday he will oppose a motion to dismiss the charges and
support the House request to subpoena witnesses. ``I do believe
some witnesses will have to be called,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee, who meets regularly with three other GOP moderates from
New England whom Democrats would need to help them dismiss the
charges later this month, all but closed the door on the
possibility. ``I think that we want to hear this case out,'' he
said, ``and I think I'd be surprised if a motion to dismiss at that
early stage prevailed.''
</P>
<P>
   Several House managers said they plan to seek testimony from
Lewinsky and as many as nine other witnesses. They said the list
may include Kathleen Willey, who claimed Clinton groped her near
the Oval Office in 1993, and a woman identified as ``Jane Doe
Number 5'' in a report by the independent counsel, Kenneth W.
Starr, on the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   A footnote in the Starr report says Jane Doe Number 5 signed an
affidavit on Jan. 2, 1998, in which she denied that Clinton made
``unwelcome sexual advances toward me in the late seventies.'' The
footnote adds: ``On April 8, 1998, however, Jane Doe Number 5
stated to Office of Independent Counsel investigators that this
affidavit was false.''
</P>
<P>
   Although senators in both parties said they will prevent the
trial from becoming a sexually graphic spectacle, they remained
sharply divided over the need for witnesses, even Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Monica Lewinsky can add one iota of additional
information,'' said the Senate Democratic leader, Thomas A.
Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   But several Republicans expressed strong support for calling
witnesses, increasing the likelihood the issue will be resolved on
a party-line vote, as was nearly every dispute in the highly
contentious House proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me it is hard to have a trial without witnesses,''
said Senator Orrin G. Hatch, a Utah Republican who is chairman of
the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But if the trial drags on because witnesses are subpoenaed,
``all bets are off'' on maintaining bipartisanship, said Senator
John B. Breaux of Louisiana, the chief deputy whip for the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one Democrat already appeared to have abandoned the
bipartisan spirit. Senator Tom Harkin of Iowa called the House case
against Clinton ``a sham and a pile of dung.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch accused Harkin of ``really denigrating the process.''
</P>
<P>
   If those kinds of sentiments surface in the Senate's final
deliberations, the public would not see them under the current
rules, which require the talks to be held behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin plans to file a motion to open the deliberations, a
change that would require the approval of a two-thirds majority, or
67 senators. ``The best political disinfectant is sunshine,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Senator Mitch McConnell, a Kentucky Republican who is
chairman of the Rules Committee, predicted the deliberations would
remain private. ``We are much better able to . . . reach
compromises when we are not under the glare of the camera,''
McConnell said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clinton's State of the Union address, the timing even
divided such close Democratic allies as California Senators Dianne
Feinstein and Barbara Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said it would be ``almost schizophrenic'' for senators
to sit in judgment of Clinton during the day and watch him address
the nation that night.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said: ``The people deserve to hear from their president. I
hope he will go on and do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
