   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday 1/10/98. Photo clients
will automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or
may download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Jan. 10, 1999 -- COMPUTERS-BUG-1999, 1-10 --
Environmental Systems Products, one of three companies that
supplies automobile emission-testing equipment for use in New York
state, discovered last month that equipment it was phasing out
could not produce a windshield sticker with a '00' expiration date
for drivers whose vehicles passed inspection. A crash effort to
complete the transition to newer equipment that issues 00 stickers
was undertaken immediately. (Phillip Greenberg/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Jan. 10, 1999 -- BRITANNICUS-THEATER-REVIEW,
1-10 -- Diana Rigg as Agrippina and Toby Stephens as Nero in
Racine's ``Britannicus'' at the Majestic Theater of the Brooklyn
Academy of Music. ``Britannicus'' is as entertaining a tale of
Roman decadence and cut-throat politics as Robert Graves' ``I,
Claudius,'' but it resists turning its characters into mere players
in a sinister chess game of good and evil. (Andrea Mohin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Jan. 10, 1999 -- GIOBBI-DANCE-REVIEW, 1-10
-- Dance and the circus are happily united for Lisa Giobbi and
Timothy Harling in ``Temptation,'' a New York premiere at the Joyce
Theater. ``Temptation,'' created by Ms. Giobbi for the Lisa Giobbi
Movement Theater, clearly shows off her ingenuity. (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LAS VEGAS -- Jan. 10, 1999 -- HDTV-PRICES, 1-10 --
Visitors to the annual Consumer Electronics Show getting a close-up
look at the newest HDTV sets. The least-expensive set on display
will be sold for half the cost of the cheapest set the industry was
selling in the fall. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Jan. 10, 1999 -- SUBWAY-DEATH, 1-10 --
Andrew Goldstein, the 29-year-old man accused of pushing Kendra
Webdale to her death under a subway train on Jan. 3, has come to be
known as a frustrated man in the grip of schizophrenia. Advocates
who work with the mentally ill have been quick to conclude that
Goldstein was one more person neglected by the system, that this
tragedy reinforces the notion that there is too little money and
too few programs to serve a needy population that is no longer kept
in hospitals. (William Lopez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEWARK, N.J. -- Jan. 10, 1998 -- DRUG-REPS, 1-10 -- Marie
Atkinson, a sales representative for Du Pont Pharmaceuticals,
briefing Dr. Jihad Slim at St. Michael's Medical Center on the
company's newest product. According to the Scott-Levin consulting
firm in Pennsylvania, pharmaceutical companies spent $5.3 billion
last year sending representatives into doctors' offices and
hospitals, and an additional $1 billion holding marketing events
for doctors. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Jan. 10, 1999 -- LINCOLNCENTER-ARTSALE, 1-10
-- Jasper Johns' only public artwork, the monumental ``Numbers,
1964,'' in the lobby of the New York State Theater at Lincoln
Center. Faced with increasingly heavy production and maintenance
costs, the complex is considering selling ``Numbers, 1964,'' in
hopes of raising what some people estimate could be as much as $15
million. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) HAVANA -- Jan. 10, 1999 -- CUBA-ECON-2, 1-10 -- A clerk
at a state store in Havana sells a single cigarette to a customer
paying in pesos. Some goods in Cuba can now be bought only with
dollars. Ten years after the Soviet bloc collapsed and cut off
Cuba's lifeline of subsidies and aid, Cubans struggle to survive in
a dual economy, fueled in large part by money flowing from their
greatest enemy, the United States. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) HAVANA -- Jan. 10, 1999 -- CUBA-ECON-1, 1-10 -- Julio
Cesar Hernandez, a vegetable vendor, weighing beans for a customer
at the Cuatro Caminos farmers' market in downtown Havana. The Cuban
government now allows farmers and vendors to sell their produce on
their own once they have supplied the state with its quota. (Kevin
Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 10, 1999 -- RENO-RECORD, 1-10 --
Attorney General Janet Reno, 60, in view of a portrait of a
predecessor, Robert F. Kennedy. Reno, whose longevity at the
Justice Department is notable, has earned praise and criticism in
her six years, and is set to become the longest-serving attorney
general of this century on Monday, surpassing the record set 60
years ago by Homer Cummings in the administration of Franklin
Delano Roosevelt. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) TOKYO -- Jan. 10, 1999 -- NOMA-PROFILE-MEDIA, 1-10 --
Sawako Noma, 55, had no business experience when she took over the
reins of Kodansha Ltd., Japan's largest publishing company, after
her husband died in 1987. In the decade since she has taken over,
Kodansha has solidified its position as the No. 1 publishing
company in Japan. (Stuart Isett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Jan. 10, 1999 --
FBN-JETS-JAGUARS-3, 1-10 -- New York Jets quarterback Vinny
Testaverde pitches off to running back Curtis Martin en route to a
34-24 playoff win over the Jacksonville Jaguars. The Jets earned
their first trip to the AFC title game since 1982 by controlling
the ball for 39:16 and outgaining Jacksonville 429 yards to 251.
(Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Jan. 10, 1999 --
FBN-JETS-JAGUARS-2, 1-10 -- New York Jets fans Ed Anzalone, top, a
New York City firefighter, and his brother Frank Anzalone, getting
into the spirit of things as the Jets defeated the Jacksonville
Jaguars 34-24 Sunday. Overcoming several mistakes, the Jets held on
against the Jaguars for their first postseason victory in 12 years.
They now have the opportunity to reach their first Super Bowl since
winning it with Joe Namath in 1969. (Barton Silverman/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Jan. 10, 1999 --
FBN-JETS-JAGUARS-1, 1-10 -- The New York Jets running back Curtis
Martin leaping over Jacksonville Jaguar defenders en route to a
34-24 playoff win for the Jets. The Jets combined a cold-weather,
ball-control offense with a solid defense Sunday to pull within a
victory of their first Super Bowl berth since 1969. The next stop
for the Jets is Mile High stadium and the Denver Broncos. (Barton
Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
