<HEADLINE>
GORE PLANS TO OUTLINE PLAN TO FIGHT URBAN SPRAWL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration will outline plans
Monday to fight urban sprawl and ease traffic congestion by
boosting federal spending on open-space land purchases,
transportation programs, and regional planning by $1 billion or
more next year, White House aides said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will ask Congress to fund the plans when he
submits his budget on Feb. 1 for the next fiscal year. Vice
President Al Gore will discuss details of the proposals in a speech
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who is all but certain to run for president in 2000, has
said communities that become more ``livable'' and less congested
will have the economic advantage of attracting more businesses and
workers. The November elections revealed signs of public support
for similar programs, as state and local ballots included 200
measures aimed at preserving watersheds, parks, farmland, and other
open spaces.
</P>
<P>
   According to White House aides, Gore will announce plans to seek
$700 million over five years, including about $125 million next
year, to allow cities and towns to issue bonds to protect parks,
wetlands, or farmland threatened by development. Communities could
also issue the bonds to buy land to protect drinking water or to
clean up industrial sites.
</P>
<P>
   The federal money would allow communities to issue bonds worth
$9.5 billion, White House aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will also announce plans to ask Congress for $6.1 billion
for public transit, nearly 5 percent or $300 million more than
called for under a long-term funding plan approved by Congress last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the president's budget will ask for increases in a
group of transportation planning programs. They include a plan to
spend $1.6 billion next year, or $341 million more than anticipated
by Congress, to help state and local governments improve air
quality by creating new carpool lanes, bike paths, and traffic
monitoring systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton budget will request $50 million to help communities
share information from their fingerprint, sex offender, and
domestic violence offender registries, and to automate their
criminal history records. The budget will also call for $50 million
to support regional planning projects that involve multiple cities
or towns, and for $10 million in competitive grants for communities
that want to include more citizens in their planning process for
building new schools.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will also announce plans to ask Congress for nearly $40
million to help communities buy new mapping software that the
administration considers to be an important tool in regional
planning.
</P>
<P>
   Known in the White House as Gore's ``livable communities
agenda,'' some elements of the proposal have not been settled.
Aides said the total price tag would be close to $1 billion and
possibly as much as $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, as much as $3 billion a year had been proposed but
drew opposition from the White House Office of Management and
Budget, which considered it too extravagant, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Tracie Seder-Hines of Waltham, who is working on open-space
issues in Eastern Massachusetts, will take part in Gore's
presentation Monday, a White House aide said.
</P>
<P>
   The next fiscal year does not start until October, but Congress
will begin work on the budget shortly after Clinton submits it next
month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Material from the Associated Press was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
