<HEADER>
A7071 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TCU-FRANCHIONE-TE     01-10 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-FRANCHIONE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR STATUS' SAKE, KEEP FRANCIONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The suitors are calling and, frankly,
they're getting more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, it was Colorado. Last month, Iowa and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Show me a college football coaching vacancy, especially since
the Sun Bowl, and I'll show you Dennis Franchione's name somewhere
on the must-be-interviewed list.
</P>
<P>
   For TCU, this is flattering, but the university would be wise
not to make Fran the February foldout in the alumni magazine.
</P>
<P>
   TCU can't let Franchione get away. It needs to move more than
quickly to place Fran under contractual lock-and-key.
</P>
<P>
   The news from Boulder, Colo., over the weekend prompted
Franchione's name to surface yet again. Boy-wonder, self-extoller
Rick Neuheisel, after four seasons, took the money and ran to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In Neuheisel's last two regular seasons in Boulder, he was
12-10. But that didn't stop the Huskies from offering Neuheisel a
seven-year deal at $1.5 million per year, plus a big house.
</P>
<P>
   But we'll get to the numbers later. Speculation began almost
immediately in Colorado that the Buffs might be interested in
interviewing Franchione, Gary Barnett of Northwestern, Sonny Lubick
of Colorado State and Gerry DiNardo of LSU.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Sun Bowl might prove to be a lot more
expensive to TCU than it ever dreamed. You get this vision of
athletic directors around the country seeing the Sun Bowl score
flash on their TV screens and saying, as they reach for a pencil,
``Hmm. And what exactly is the name of that TCU coach?''
</P>
<P>
   The interest is richly deserved. It is hard to imagine how, week
in and week out, any coach in the country could have done a better
job of getting his team ready to play. And he did it all while
redshirting 20 underclassmen and without a blue-ribbon quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   He is a bright and decent man, well-liked by his players, though
they were coming off an esteem-draining 1-10 season. He seems to be
exactly the kind of person that TCU needs running its football
program.
</P>
<P>
   But there's the catch. Franchione has been with the Horned Frogs
only one season _ and a 6-5 season, at that. And now the school is
forced to make a decision that might affect the next eight to 10
years _ at no small expense.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione's base salary is around $300,000, with added perks
that reportedly bring it to the $450,000 range. Based on the recent
deals signed by Mack Brown at Texas and Hal Mumme at Kentucky,
Franchione would not be out of line in asking for an eight-year,
$6.5-million deal.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does the TCU administration not have much choice, it
had better act quickly. Operators at Colorado _ and who knows where
else? _ are standing by.
</P>
<P>
   To lose Franchione would send a distressing signal to Frogs fans
and recruits. Picture the image left at Tulane, where a 12-0 record
wasn't enough to keep Tommy Bowden from bolting to Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   TCU wants to be a football destination, not just another truck
stop. It already faces the stigma of being a football orphan,
abandoned twice in the past two conferences to which it belonged.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, now that the New Year's Eve champagne and euphoria from
beating USC have worn off, the Frogs are still at the same
crossroads. They need to keep their football coach, and they need
to find a new league.
</P>
<P>
   That explosion you saw over University Drive last week wasn't
the chemistry lab. That was TCU basketball coach Billy Tubbs,
learning that the Western Athletic Conference still doesn't have a
TV contract or an automatic NCAA bid and that the league tournament
is probably going to be held in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Gee. Why not Fresno, when you get right down to it?
</P>
<P>
   When the next round of conference realignment comes _ and people
are waiting for Notre Dame to start the line of dominoes _ TCU
wants to be brandishing the image of a big-time football and
basketball program.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs stands as a neon emblem of TCU's commitment. And so could
Franchione.
</P>
<P>
   TCU can't let him get away. A big-time program calls for a
big-time splash. If their dreams are real, TCU administrators can't
be scared to offer Franchione a Mumme-sized contract, nor shy about
blabbing the financial details afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Be quick, Frogs. Operators are standing by.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
