<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WORRY FOR JONES IS FINDING A REAL TEST
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENSACOLA, Fla. _ With few viable opponents on the horizon, Roy
Jones Jr. may want to consider another sport. Bowling perhaps. He
is halfway there anyway. His promoter, Murad Muhammad, sets up
opponents and Jones knocks them down. Replace the human pins with
wooden ones, and Jones will have nearly completed the transition.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after he dispatched Richard Frazier, a 39-year-old New
York City police officer who was the No. 1 contender for Jones'
World Boxing Council light heavyweight title, here last Saturday
night, opponents were lining themselves up for Jones. The postfight
news conference at the Pensacola Civic Center was more like a
boisterous fraternity mixer than an opportunity for reporters to
talk to Jones about his second-round technical knockout.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Collins had traveled from Ireland to declare his desire to
fight Jones. David Telasco, his hair cascading down on his
shoulders, kept screaming that Jones was ducking him. But Michael
Nunn, another would-be opponent, was conspicuous by his silence. In
this case silence could be golden, because Jones, the cash cow of
the light heavyweight division, hates loudmouths who try to berate
him into matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I offered this man a fight last winter,'' Jones said of
Telasco. ``He said he wasn't ready for the fight. If he had taken
the fight then, I wouldn't be dealing with this garbage now. He had
his shot. He missed the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier was not left standing on the dock. He took a ride worth
$350,000. But his presence in the ring against a world-class boxer
like Jones left many people wondering how he even got to the pier.
Frazier's promoter, Don King, and his manager, Grant Phillips,
finagled Frazier into the top spot.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was indeed ready to fight Telasco, but all of a sudden
Frazier popped up as the mandatory WBC challenger. Jones had to
take the fight against Frazier or risk losing his WBC title belt.
To compound matters, the World Boxing Association sanctioned the
bout against Frazier, but does not believe that Jones has satisfied
its requirement for a mandatory defense. Its No. 1 contender is
Dario Matteoni.
</P>
<P>
   So Jones, who wants to keep both his titles and fight a
unification bout against Reggie Johnson, the International Boxing
Federation champion, is stuck with another bowling match against
Matteoni. And HBO, which has an exclusive contract with Jones and
broadcast the Jones-Frazier match last Saturday night, is faced
with broadcasting another Jones mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier said he was not able to determine just how good Jones is
because the bout was stopped so soon by referee Armando Garcia.
Jones had knocked Frazier down in the first round with a glancing
right hand, although Frazier said he slipped on an advertising sign
on the ring apron. So Jones clipped Frazier again in the second
round, catching him with a left to the temple that sent Frazier
down on his back with his legs raised in the air. Frazier got up to
beat the 10 count, but Garcia felt that Frazier could not continue
and stopped the bout at 2 minutes 59 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say,'' Frazier said. ``I came to fight. I
had a game plan to fight and I was never able to get into it. I
think it was stopped too early. He wasn't hurting me.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from a television replay, it did appear that Garcia
stopped the fight too soon. But he probably saved Frazier from a
severe beating and the viewing audience from having to sit through
a once-sided 12-round decision.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier said he will take a few days off from his job at the
26th Police Precinct in Harlem, in New York City, and then continue
to train for his next bout. Who knows, he could be the IBF's No. 1
contender next week.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Mosley, the IBF lightweight champion, was also in a
mismatch of sorts. But his opponent, Golden Johnson, lasted longer
than Frazier did against Jones. Mosley knocked Johnson out at 2:59
of the seventh round. Mosley dropped Johnson four times in the bout
_ three times with body shots. The final body shot sent Johnson
down to one knee and he stayed there for the count of 10. A former
short-order cook, Johnson had had his fill of Mosley chopping on
his ribs with left hooks.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley's list of future opponents is not nearly as dreary as
Jones'. There is talk that Mosley could step into the ring against
Ivan Robinson, who fought two memorable bouts against Arturo Gatti
last year. Mosley would also like to unify the lightweight division
with bouts against the other world champions: Cesar Bazan, the WBA
champion, and Jean Baptiste Mendy, the WBC champion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
