<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-FANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS FANS EXULT AFTER A DECADES-LONG VIGIL
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ At the pre-game tailgate parties in the
Giants Stadium parking lot, the New York Jets fans were intoxicated
Sunday, some on beer, many others on a home game at long last in
January.
</P>
<P>
   They have suffered so long. Not since 1991 have the Jets made
the playoffs. Under Coach Rich Kotite in 1995 and '96, the
franchise hit an all-time low with a combined 4-28 record.
</P>
<P>
   No more. The Jets are one victory from the Super Bowl after
their 34-24 victory Sunday against the Jacksonville Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   The fans came from the East End of Long Island, eastern New York
and eastern Pennsylvania and elsewhere. And Sunday all those cold,
empty, painful afternoons were forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Demorest Knapp, 60, was a fan when the team was known as the New
York Titans of the American Football League. He was in Miami for
the Super Bowl victory over the Baltimore Colts in '69. He was
there for all the losing, for the move from Shea Stadium, in
Queens, to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really been an ordeal,'' said Knapp, who makes the
two-hour commute from Shoreham on Long Island for every home game.
``In those years, I've gone from heaven to New Jersey. Now I'm
almost back.''
</P>
<P>
   In the parking lot before the game, Jason Freewell demonstrated
his joy by trying to do a backflip off his pickup truck. (He could
not.) Allen Johnson's lips looked blue as he partied in the parking
lot, his naked torso painted green.
</P>
<P>
   At the kickoff, Brian Thompson, 42, was in his seat, his lips
wrapped around a wine skin. The first play went for 17 yards; it
looked as if Bad Luck would get no playing time. But after 30
miserable years, you never know.
</P>
<P>
   Six plays later, a touchdown pass from Vinny Testaverde to
Keyshawn Johnson had the fans bubbling about a trip to Denver for
next Sunday's American Football Conference Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't imagine it, you just can't,'' said Thompson, a New
Jersey native who has never had much to root for. He does not like
baseball, or understand the lure of hockey, and the football
Giants, well, ``those guys belong to the cigar smiling button-up
types who drink Scotch at halftime.''
</P>
<P>
   There were more than 78,000 Jets fans here, and a handful of
Jacksonville fans. Two of those poor souls were showered with beer,
and it froze in the 26-degree air.
</P>
<P>
   The second half became a blur as a group of men from Queens
watched it through the bottoms of their plastic beer cups: a
Checker cab mechanic, Lou Pepe, 31; a glazier, Matt Aurigemma, 31;
a mailman, Mike Laruccia, 31, and a police officer, Paul Notholt,
35, all sat in the top tier of the western end zone. It is where
the fanatics sit.
</P>
<P>
   A fumble occurred in the fourth quarter and Laruccia screamed,
``Hold the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahead by 31-24, the Jets lined up for a field goal with 24
seconds left. Aurigemma chewed on his tongue as if it were a piece
of beef jerky.
</P>
<P>
   The kick went up. The kick was good. Jets 34, Jaguars, 24.
</P>
<P>
   Aurigemma disappeared under a pile. ``I'm buying the drinks,''
he screamed. ``I'm buying the drinks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
