<SLUG> BC-TV-TOUR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DILBERT' CREATOR GETS DOWN TO THE BUSINESS OF ANIMATED SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ There's more than a little irony in a
television network's seeking salvation from a guy who got rich
poking fun at big business. But if Scott Adams, creator of the
``Dilbert'' phenomenon, can reverse the fortunes of UPN, the
bespectacled hero of cubicle-bound working grunts may replace
Leonardo DiCaprio as king of the world, at least on the Good Ship
UPN.
</P>
<P>
   Though teensy-weensy by network standards, UPN qualifies as a
substantial corporate entity by any benchmark. Launched four years
ago at about the same time as its main rival, The WB, it is a
cooperative venture of BHC Communications (a unit of Chris-Craft
Industries Inc.) and Paramount Television Stations Group (a
subsidiary of Viacom Inc.).
</P>
<P>
   But aside from ``Star Trek: Voyager'' and a couple of other
shows, UPN has a lot of stink bombs that nobody watches. At the
moment, it loses more money in a week than, say, Mike Holmgren will
make in a year as an employee of Seattle Seahawks owner Paul Allen.
Lacking a high-tech tycoon's billions, UPN is hoping a low-tech
former bank teller/computer programmer/phone company engineer will
show it the way to prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he senses no desperation among UPN executives, no
indication that the jig is up if its new animated ``Dilbert''
series doesn't do for UPN what ``The Simpsons'' did for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just working on the show,'' Adams said, ``and if it's
good, good things will happen for everybody involved, and that's
all we can concentrate on.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams gets to see his creation come alive Jan. 25.
</P>
<P>
   More sound sound bites from the ``Dilbert'' creator:
</P>
<P>
   On why Dilbert looks the way he does: ``It's for more simple
reasons than you'd think. I'm just a really bad artist.''
</P>
<P>
   On the corporate world of TV: ``Nothing down here is like the
real world. `Dilbert' exists because it's about common experiences
exaggerated. ... Everything down here starts out exaggerated and
gets worse.''
</P>
<P>
   On his effect on corporate America: ``The only effect that I
hear about is that people use the comic strip to mock their boss.
... You clip it out and slide it under the door and run away, kind
of like putting the poop in the flaming bag on the porch.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS anchor Dan Rather heads the new ``Sixty Minutes II'' team,
which goes into action Wednesday. But even though he's 67 and the
managing editor of ``CBS Evening News,'' Rather knows his place.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there might be some spirited competition for juicy
stories with the members of the venerable Sunday version of ``60
Minutes,'' Rather said: ``Here's the way it works. Mike Wallace
gets what he wants. ... The ones he doesn't want to do or doesn't
know about, then the rest of us have the right to squabble over
it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Rather's new teammates is longtime CBS correspondent Bob
Simon, a regular contributor to the Sunday show who is
comparatively boyish by ``60 Minutes'' standards. Only 57, Simon
said, ``For the last several years, my two favorite places in the
world have been `60 Minutes' and the nursing home where my
father-in-law stays, because they're the only places where I'm
occasionally called `young man.'''
</P>
<P>
   We say we want more channels, but will we actually watch them?
According to ABC's research department, when a household has 26 to
30 channels, the average number of channels watched is 11.3. When
the choices are 71 channels and above, the average number of
channels watched increases to only 15.3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
