<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: AMERICAN FOLK ART EXHIBITION; WOODY ALLEN AND TV;
DUKE ELLINGTON CENTENNIAL; EARLY PHOTOGRAPHY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., The Netherlands)   (js) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vibrant, color-saturated works on paper, photographic
collages, dolls, chewing-gum sculptures and installations of found
objects. All are the work of the self-taught African-American
artist Nellie Mae Rowe (1900-1982), the subject of a major
exhibition from Saturday through May 16 at the Museum of American
Folk Art on Columbus Avenue between 65th and 66th streets. The
show, ``Nellie Mae Rowe: 99{ Won't Do,'' a title derived from a
gospel song played at her funeral, comprises some 90 works.
Information: (212) 595-9533.
</P>
<P>
   EARLY ALLEN
</P>
<P>
   Beginning on Friday, it's back to the days of rampant neurosis
and offhand references to Dostoyevsky and the meaning of life and
sendups of ``Bonnie and Clyde.''
</P>
<P>
   At its branches in New York and Los Angeles, the Museum of
Television and Radio is opening ``Woody Allen's Television Days,''
a two-part screening series. The first part, ``Sketches and
Kvetches,'' including an appearance by Allen on ``The Tonight
Show'' in 1962, until Feb. 18; the second, ``Tell It Again,
Woody,'' including his only television special, seen on CBS in
1969, runs from Feb. 19 through March 21. Information: (212)
621-6600 in New York and (310) 786-1000 in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   DUKE'S DOMAINS
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He was born on April 29, 1899, but nobody is waiting
till spring to begin the celebration of the centennial of Duke
Ellington. A yearlong acknowledgment by Jazz at Lincoln Center of
his contributions to jazz begins at 7 p.m. on Thursday at Alice
Tully Hall, where Ellington Orchestra alumni will participate in a
round-table discussion called ``Happy Reunion: Memories of Duke,''
followed by a party and jam session in the Stanley H. Kaplan
Penthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (212) 721-6500. On Jan. 21 the Carnegie Hall Jazz
Band weighs in at Carnegie Hall with a concert featuring
Ellington's rarely performed tone poem ``Black, Brown and Beige.''
Information: (212) 247-7800.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTURED MOMENTS
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1840s, at the dawn of the invention of photography,
Eduard Isaac Asser, a well-to-do lawyer in Amsterdam, the
Netherlands, bought a camera in Paris and taught himself to take
pictures of his family and still lifes. Cleaned and restored, these
remarkable examples of early photographic art will be exhibited at
the Rijksmuseum in Amsterdam from Saturday through March 14.
Information: 011-31-20-674-7000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
