</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-CARDINALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIKINGS SPRINT INTO THE NFC TITLE GAME
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Jake Plummer's first four passes in the biggest
game of his life were something out of a nightmare. Passes No. 1
and No. 2: badly overthrown incompletions. Pass No. 3: a
beautifully thrown ball to Minnesota safety Robert Griffith.
Plummer, the Arizona quarterback, liked Griffith so much, he found
him again on the next series on his fourth pass.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer would recover from his disastrous start and Arizona's
minus-1 yard of total offense in the first quarter Sunday _ the
only place to go after that kind of start is up _ but it would be
too late. Minnesota took a second-quarter lead of 17-0, and then a
halftime lead of 24-7.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer, the comeback kid, had the Vikings right where he wanted
them, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not this time. Playing the Vikings is like being in the Olympic
200-meter sprint, with Minnesota the equivalent of Michael Johnson.
For an opponent to have any chance of winning, staying close early
is a necessity; otherwise, on this slick artificial turf, the
Vikings will blow past as if they are on jet-propelled roller
skates.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota beat the Cardinals, 41-21, before 63,760 at the
Metrodome and advanced to the National Conference title game
against Atlanta because the Vikings were again successful with
their three-pronged formula: smart coaching, speed and big plays.
</P>
<P>
   The smart coaching came when the Vikings used 15 different
formations in their first 15 plays, adding brilliant wrinkles like
a direct snap to running back David Palmer with quarterback Randall
Cunningham playing decoy wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   The speed was evident in a defense that smothered Plummer,
chasing him all over the field. At times he looked slower than the
270-pound linemen trying to ruin his day.
</P>
<P>
   The big plays? Where else: Randy Moss, the Vikings' Pro Bowl
wide receiver, beat Aeneas Williams, the Cardinals' Pro Bowl
cornerback, for a 45-yard completion in the second quarter. That
play led to Minnesota's second touchdown, a 15-yard pass from
Cunningham to tight end Andrew Glover. In the third quarter, Cris
Carter caught a pass for 45 yards, leading to a 20-yard field goal
by Gary Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   With their dominating performance against Arizona, the Vikings
gave the Atlanta Falcons lots to think about when the two teams
meet here next Sunday in a game that will feature two of the best
offenses in football. But it is the Vikings that are the most
dangerous team in the conference and, perhaps, all of football.
When they are on a roll, the Vikings, who are 16-1 this season,
cannot be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, that's true,'' Vikings cornerback Jimmy Hitchcock said.
``Once we get into our groove, playing our A-plus game, you can't
beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Glover: ``In 20-something games, we've only lost once. When
we're at home, we're impossible to beat. Only the Vikings can truly
beat the Vikings.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota players are not being cocky with those statements _
they are factual. This team is built so that if the offense gets
ahead, the defense comes hard, as it did against Plummer, who
completed 23 of 41 passes for 242 yards, and the two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   And the Vikings' offense always seems to get ahead because it
has more weapons than any other team in the league. Beyond Moss
(four catches for 73 yards), Carter (five catches for 82 yards) and
Cunningham (17 of 27 for 236 yards and three touchdowns), there are
other weapons in the arsenal. Robert Smith had 19 carries for 124
yards, a post-season team rushing record. Glover had several key
catches. Fullback Leroy Hoard had touchdown runs of one, 16 and six
yards, becoming the first Viking to score three touchdowns in a
playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we couldn't stop their offense,'' Arizona safety
Tommy Bennett said. ``If you can't stop the run, it opens up the
pass. They have four outstanding receivers. Cunningham has a lot of
go-to guys, and it's hard to stop all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The place-kicker Mitch Berger had five touchbacks, breaking Fred
Cox's team playoff record of three against Dallas in 1973. Those
kicks into the end zone were important because Arizona's Eric
Metcalf, one of the game's most dangerous return men, did not
become a huge factor.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer tried to revive the Cardinals, but he was too excited
early and bothered by the crowd noise. ``It was loud, you know, it
was a different situation,'' he said. ``We have not been in a
situation this loud. The first interception was a case of me being
young and hyped up and wanting to make a big play when I should
have been patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Several times Plummer wanted to check with the offensive
coordinator Marc Trestman about changing a play, but Plummer could
not hear what Trestman was saying, even though Trestman's voice was
piped into Plummer's helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer still made the game interesting in the third quarter. He
cut the score to 24-14 after leading the Cardinals on an 80-yard,
14-play drive. Plummer was 7 of 8 passing for 57 yards during the
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was Minnesota's turn. The Vikings scored on Anderson's
20-yard field goal, and after Plummer fumbled a snap that was
recovered by Antonio Banks at the Arizona 20-yard line, Cunningham
went to Moss on a crossing pattern in the end zone for a 2-yard
score.
</P>
<P>
   In less than six minutes, the Vikings had scored 10 points to
take a 34-14 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes a week of speculation about whether the Falcons can
stop perhaps the best offensive football team ever. The Cardinals,
with a good defense, did not come close. Arizona coach Vince Tobin,
who wore a stunned look on his face after the game, was asked if he
had just played a juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what a juggernaut is,'' he said, ``but I know one
thing, they've got a good football team.''
</P>
<P>
   The understatement of the week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
