<SLUG> BC-NY-READING-TEST-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK STATE TEST SETS SCHOOLS TO CRAMMING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For weeks, the new New York state reading, writing
and listening test has spurred a frenzy of cramming more often
associated with getting into law school than with passing fourth
grade. Schools have virtually suspended their normal curriculums to
administer practice tests and help pupils brush up on concepts like
``the main idea,'' ``topic sentences'' and ``supporting details.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a hurricane is coming,'' Gary Lincoff, the father of
a fourth-grade boy on Manhattan's Upper West Side, said last week,
shaking his head ruefully.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the three-day test begins Tuesday in New York
City's school districts, and most others, and while many educators
fear scores will be low, State Education Commissioner Richard Mills
said that outcome would not necessarily be a bad thing. The test is
part of a long-term state plan to shake up and transform the
education system by returning to the basics, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that scores will be low,'' Mills said last week. ``The
standards are deliberately higher.'' But he added: ``These are the
basics that all fourth graders and other children need to have.
It's one of the strategies to change things for the better. I am
expecting superintendents and boards, principals and teachers to
examine these results and examine their practices and make
appropriate changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, New York has become a leader in the
national movement to establish stronger curriculums and to create
tests to measure their effectiveness. Only last week, a national
survey by Education Week magazine ranked New York first in the
country in holding students accountable to rigorous academic
standards and testing.
</P>
<P>
   The old fourth-grade test required pupils to read sentences or
short passages and fill in missing words using a list of
multiple-choice answers. The new test moves from a focus on simple
reading to an expectation that by the middle of fourth grade,
pupils can understand and write about complex passages and about
themselves, using correct spelling. This puts the test at odds with
much of progressive-education theory and the whole-language
movement, which assume that students will eventually pick up the
mechanics of writing at their own pace.
</P>
<P>
   It also puts a burden on New York City schools, which have
historically lagged behind the statewide average on basic test
scores. In addition, many city schools have been struggling to meet
the easier standards of the old test. In New York City, the failure
rate on the old test was 35 percent in 1998, compared with an
average of just 6 percent in the rest of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a philosophical level, I think it's a good test,'' said
Robert Riccobono, superintendent of Community School District 19 in
East New York, Brooklyn, an impoverished district in which 53
percent of the pupils failed the old test in 1998, scoring at least
a year behind grade level. ``But on a practical level, it scares
the hell out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills said the fourth-grade test was the first step of a drive
toward higher standards statewide. In June, fourth graders will
begin taking a new state math test, and eighth graders will begin
taking a new state math and English test.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Beginning with the class of 2003, all high school students in
New York state will be required to pass five subject exams, called
Regents tests, with a score of at least 55 percent before they can
receive a diploma, said Alan Ray, a spokesman for Mills. In 1997,
only 24 percent of high school students in New York City who
graduated within four years had earned Regents diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   At Public School 165, a school with a largely immigrant
population on the Upper West Side of Manhattan, information about
the skills demanded by the new test has quickly filtered throughout
all grades. Almost every class, from kindergarten on up, is filled
with exercises in spelling and grammar that once would have been
dismissed as stultifyingly old-fashioned. ``I came in with a much
more liberal, open-ended approach to things,'' said Evangeline
Avlonitis, a fourth-grade teacher. ``But I think we need to get
back to a lot of these basics.''
</P>
<P>
   One of her pupils, Jennifer Peguero, agreed. Last week her class
took a series of timed practice tests. After listening to a fable
about a miser, Jennifer had to explain the maxim ``Without wisdom,
wealth is worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer carefully wrote 17 lines, printing neatly, indenting
her two paragraphs, beginning sentences with capital letters and
ending them with punctuation marks, including two emphatic
exclamation points after the sentence ``What a selfish old man!!''
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I was kind of, like, stuck,'' Jennifer said. ``Now I
feel proud because I worked so hard, and what I wrote came from my
heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 2237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
