<DOCNO> NYT19990110.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7086 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVISIONS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-10 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVISIONS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMO TO ACTORS: LEARN TO MASTER THE ESSENTIALS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We like to talk about actors in terms of clean, well-lighted
oppositions. When Willa Cather was a stern, very smart young drama
critic, she compared the flamboyant (and to her narcissistic) art
of a Sarah Bernhardt with the luminously self-contained (and to her
transcendent) art of Eleanora Duse. Display vs. mystery; the force
of the lurid vs. the force of the pure.
</P>
<P>
   When Gilbert Seldes wrote about performers in his kinetically
intelligent book ``The Seven Lively Arts,'' he called the
difference between those who lose every identifiable part of
themselves in a role and those who dominate it with their
personality the difference between actors and players.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is still true. Maggie Smith is all display;
Vanessa Redgrave courts mystery. Meryl Streep is an actress; Goldie
Hawn is a player. But thinking about some of the young film
actresses getting attention, awards or awards nominations right
now, let us consider some other essentials.
</P>
<P>
   THE BODY. Yes, we've been in the age of the talking picture
since 1927, and yes, the beauty of an actor's face in close-up will
never die. Nevertheless, we need more actors who use their bodies
with total skill and utter abandon, actors (and players) who bring
a complete physical language to every role.
</P>
<P>
   Any director knows the evocative power of an object or a
landscape (a certain slant of light on a street corner, a plate of
half-eaten food on a table). How often do you feel the same power
from watching something as simple as the way an actor strikes a bed
with her leg when she is speaking?
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking of Patricia Clarkson in ``High Art,'' the dark
little film written and directed by Lisa Cholodenko for which Ally
Sheedy just won a best actress award from the National Society of
Film Critics. She earned it. She is spooky, cynical, childish and
jaded all at once.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a movie about lethal entanglements. It depends on
ensemble work, and Ms. Clarkson and Radha Mitchell are uncannily
good as the two women bound up with her through heroin, sex and art
that longs to be cutting edge. When Ms. Clarkson, playing a skinny
Teutonic junkie _ a kind of sub-Marlene Dietrich, sub-Nico actress
who once worked for Fassbinder _ hits the bed with her thin,
feral-looking leg, it's as if she is saying: ``I'm spoiled. I'm in
a rage. I'm hopeless, and don't you ever forget that you are,
too.'' The gesture is as strong as anything she actually does say.
</P>
<P>
   It's a predictable cultural fact that in roles for women, social
lawlessness, sexual rebellion and emotional despair are the best
incentives for physical expressiveness. We're talking about drug
addicts, prostitutes and thieves, even spirits: not just the
actresses in ``High Art,'' but Thandie Newton as the devouring
ghost in ``Beloved'' or Courtney Love as a rabble-rousing heroin
addict in ``The People vs. Larry Flynt'' and Queen Latifah as an
Uzi-loving bank robber in ``Set It Off,'' both 1996 films. (It's no
accident that Ms. Love and Queen Latifah come from the world of
rock and rap, where you don't have an act if you don't have a body
that flaunts itself as much as your voice does.)
</P>
<P>
   But it was not ever thus. What's a better medium for canny
physical abandon than comedy? It's our bad luck to be in a thin and
anxious age when it comes to film comedy. Meg Ryan is pert and
predictable enough to have come out of a little music box. Cameron
Diaz is the comic equivalent of a pleasing backup singer. Julia
Roberts needs better material. And someone should look at ``Jerry
Maguire'' and ``The Whole Wide World'' again, then start writing
full-bodied romantic comedies for Renee Zellweger. Her limbs and
nerve endings are always in readiness. When they move, they take
you by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   THE VOICE. Give actors a text, and some will play it with
perfect grace and propriety, while others will insist on finding
riskier ways through and into it. It's a question of rhythm,
phrasing and range. Take Gwyneth Paltrow in ``Shakespeare in Love''
and Cate Blanchett in ``Elizabeth.'' Both play women of privilege
and at least surface propriety in Elizabethan England, women who
are also at odds with conventions of power, duty and love. Ms.
Paltrow is lovely to look at and offers pleasant easy listening.
All of the notes adding up to a character are struck cleanly and
gracefully. But couldn't passion and romantic grief profit from
more daring, less awareness that one must look one's best at all
times?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Blanchett's performance is moodier and wilder; there are
rhythmic ruptures, pauses and rushes in her interpretation, which
bring darkness as well as light to her character. And don't tell me
this difference depends on the fact that ``Shakespeare'' is a
romantic comedy and ``Elizabeth'' a romantic melodrama. Romantic
comedy is supposed to be built on rhythms and emotional shifts that
take the audience as well as the other characters by surprise. We
know the basic story of Queen Elizabeth's life, and melodrama
thrives on forcefully struck emotional poses, but Ms. Blanchett
gives us the intimacies behind them and lets our feelings toward
her character keep changing.
</P>
<P>
   STILLNESS. What an underrated quality stillness is. It is partly
the ability to listen and make listening an action that has
consequences for the speaker. (Listening can seduce, soothe, repel,
enlighten or condemn, after all). And it is partly the ability to
ground a scene, to help the other actors stay aligned and
concentrated, whatever goes on.
</P>
<P>
   When an actor really knows how to be still, we feel her taking
in all the other emotions on screen and holding onto them for us,
clarifying their meaning. Think back to Susan Sarandon in in
``Thelma and Louise'' and ``Dead Man Walking.'' Return to the
present and watch Radha Mitchell as she picks her way through
cynicism and desperation in ``High Art.''
</P>
<P>
   If you savor lessons from older masters, watch Judi Dench in
``Shakespeare in Love'' and Mary Alice in ``Down in the Delta.''
And if you failed to see ``Beloved'' (you probably did), wait for
the video release, then watch the painfully acute receptivity of
Kimberly Elise as a young woman who sees so much and can do so
little.
</P>
<P>
   The actress who seems to possess these qualities in the greatest
abundance right now is Emily Watson. Watch her in Lars von Trier's
``Breaking the Waves,'' as a young Scottish woman in the grip of
religion, eros and sacrifice, or in Anand Tucker's ``Hilary and
Jackie,'' as the English cellist Jacqueline du Pre, trying first to
live with a great and burdensome talent, then with a murderous
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Watson is blessed to be offered and smart to choose such
good scripts and directors. (Von Trier is more than good, he is
extraordinary.) She joins her physical and vocal resources to naked
feeling in a way that is astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   It comes down to the willingness to push yourself into emotional
territory that may scare you as much as it scares your audience.
It's the most mysterious and the finest quality an actor can have.
Let's call it fearlessness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
