<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ANTI-SEMITISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWS CONDEMN ANTI-SEMITIC STATEMENTS BY RUSSIAN OFFICIALS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Most are old enough to have defied Hitler, either as
Soviet soldiers or soldiers' wives. By keeping their heads down,
they survived the anti-Semitism that became government policy
during Stalin's last yers. They silently endured the subtle
discrimination against Jews that permeated modern Soviet society
and even the blossoming of overtly anti-Semitic movements during
the years of perestroika.
</P>
<P>
   Now safe in new lives in the United States, some 1,000 Jewish
immigrants from the former Soviet Union gathered Sunday in Brooklyn
to warn of a rising tide of officially tolerated anti-Semitism in
Russia that could threaten those left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you still have relatives there, have them come,'' said
Bella Zelkin, the community liaison for the New York Association
for New Americans, one of more than a dozen New York City Jewish
and Russian organizations that called the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The situation, she said, resembles the atmosphere in Eastern
Europe during the rise of Nazism in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who say, `It's not affecting me personally' are
like those who were holding on before the war,'' Ms. Zelkin said.
``They all were killed. The ones who closed their eyes and went
ahead and got out, they survived.''
</P>
<P>
   During the last few months, prominent figures in the Russian
Communist Party have joined nationalist politicians in openly
blaming their country's troubles on Jews, specifically on people of
Jewish ancestry who have worked in the government of President
Boris Yeltsin. While Yeltsin has condemned such statements,
Communist leaders have blocked efforts to censure parliamentarians
who make statements that criticize Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Groups that provide assistance to immigrants from the former
Soviet Union said they had not yet seen an increase in the number
of Jews seeking to emigrate in response to the political atmosphere
in Russia. The exact number of Jews or people of Jewish ancestry
remaining in Russia and the former Soviet republics, like Belarus
and Ukraine, is not known, but some Jewish agencies estimate the
number is somewhere around 700,000. About 400,000 Jews from the
former Soviet Union have immigrated to the New York region in the
last decade.
</P>
<P>
   The immigrants at the gathering _ most elderly and bent by
arthritis, some wearing rows of faded World War II military medals
on their coats _ demanded that the United Nations, the White House
and Congress respond more forcefully to those officials responsible
for making or tolerating anti-Semitic statements.
</P>
<P>
   A resolution drawn up by the organizers of the meeting said
Russian political figures who fail to condemn anti-Semitism, like
Gennadi Zyuganov, the leader of the Communist Party, should not be
allowed to enter the United States. The resolution also calls for
linking American aid to Russia to its observance of religious
freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have learned a lesson from the past,'' said Leonid Stonov,
president of the American Association of Jews From the Former USSR,
at the standing-room-only gathering in the heavily Russian Brighton
Beach section of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of the lesson was 6 million lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
