A7089 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JAGUARS-EVALUATE-     01-10 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JAGUARS-EVALUATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAGUARS LIKE JETS' BALL CONTROL AND THEIR CHANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Having upset the Denver Broncos two
years ago, the Jacksonville Jaguars know what it's like to win a
playoff game at Mile High Stadium. After losing Sunday to the New
York Jets, 34-24, several Jaguars said they liked the Jets' chances
against the Broncos in next weekend's American Football Conference
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think the Jets can beat them,'' said offensive
tackle Tony Boselli, whose Jaguars won at Denver, 30-27, two years
ago but lost, 37-24, in the 1998 regular season. ``The Broncos are
beatable, there's no doubt in my mind. We played pretty good today,
especially in the second half, and the Jets still held us off. I
think the Jets are playing with a lot of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Kevin Hardy said the Jets' offense could make it hard
on the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they hold the ball in Denver for as long as they did
against us today,'' Hardy said, ``it would be hard for anyone to
beat them. Denver is good, but I'm not going to count the Jets out.
You've got to stop them and get them off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``At all the crucial times, we couldn't stop the Jets. They
moved the ball up and down the field all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars coach Tom Coughlin would not take sides in the
Jets-Broncos matchup, but he recognized in the Jets a self-assured
team playing a dominating style of football. And Coughlin praised
the Jets' coaching staff, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out in the first half and were almost
mistake-free,'' Coughlin said. ``That's when they took some control
of the game. They had a fumble, but they converted seven of nine
third downs in the first half. That's a good football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second quarter, we couldn't get the ball back from
them.'' The Jaguars had the ball just 51 seconds in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``To beat them, you have to stop them,'' Coughlin said. ``I was
standing there saying, `Somebody stop them.' And we couldn't. Their
offensive balance gives them a tough attack to stop. They prove
they can run it, and then they throw it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's also a good bunch of coaches. They prepare well. They
showed us a number of new things today. We adjusted, but there were
some new wrinkles.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Taylor, the Jaguars' star running back, rushed for 86 yards
on 20 carries, but he had just 26 yards on nine first-half carries
as the Jets sprinted to a 17-0 lead. Taylor said the Jets would
probably have to do something similar against Broncos running back
Terrell Davis to win next Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jets today didn't give up many big plays on the ground,''
Taylor said. ``They cut you off before you could cut back. They'll
probably try to do the same thing against Denver. If they can get a
big lead like they did today, maybe they can make Denver
one-dimensional. That's what they did to us for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the Jaguars, however, liked the Jets' chances in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would give the Broncos the advantage,'' cornerback Dave
Thomas said. ``Whenever you can run the football as well as Denver
runs the football, you have the edge. The Jets played well, but
they had an advantage on us today.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were well-rested and you could tell. We came out a little
flat and made mistakes. Plus, Denver will have its crowd with them.
Playing at home always helps.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
