A7091 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MERCEDES-CHAMP-NY     01-10 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MERCEDES-CHAMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL PADS HIS REPUTATION AS THE WORLD'S BEST GOLFER
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAPALUA, Hawaii _ He dominated this weekend. He has been the PGA
Tour's biggest winner over the last 15 months. And after watching
David Duval win Sunday for the eighth time in his last 27 starts,
even more of his peers were convinced that Duval is the world's
best player.
</P>
<P>
   Duval played at a different level during the season-opening
Mercedes Championships, as the rest of the field played for second
place. Starting today's final round with a five-shot lead, Duval
was never threatened. People wondered not whether Duval would win,
but by how much he would win.
</P>
<P>
   So as Duval began 1999 with a virtuoso performance, others
marveled at a player who keeps adding to both his reputation and
his bank account. Shooting a final-round five-under-par 68, Duval
finished at 26 under for the tournament (266) and cruised to a
nine-stroke victory at the Kapalua Plantation Course, well ahead of
Mark O'Meara and Billy Mayfair, who tied for second place at
17-under 275.
</P>
<P>
   Duval's current winning pace is the best since Nick Price won
nine events in 15 months during the 1993 and 1994 seasons. By
winning, Duval opened the season by winning the $468,000
first-place check, plus a new Mercedes-Benz SL 500 roadster. There
are worse ways to spend a week in Maui.
</P>
<P>
   But while Duval will surely enjoy the car and the money, nothing
seems to alter his determination to be the best player he can be.
And many are convinced he is already the best there is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there's no question he's the best in the world,''
said Fred Funk, who finished tied for fifth place. ``I really don't
think David feels pressure anymore. He's just going to beat you
with pure talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at his game, there's absolutely no weaknesses.
He's tremendously long, he's tremendously straight, a great iron
player, great wedge player, really good chipper, and a really good
putter. He's in a different league.''
</P>
<P>
   The tour's opening event featured an elite 30-man field, limited
to players who won at least once last year. By winning Sunday,
Duval became the first player to qualify for next year's Mercedes
Championships, but Duval has bigger goals in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Since winning his first event at the 1997 Michelob Championship
at Kingsmill in Williamsburg, Va., his appetite for victory has
been insatiable. Duval won his final three starts in 1997, he won
four events in 1998, he won last year's money title, and he started
this year by picking up where he left off. A major championship is
the biggest piece missing from Duval's resume, but tying for second
place at last year's Masters only made Duval hungrier to achieve
that goal. And in the meantime, he seems intent on winning as much
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obviously playing quite well,'' said Duval, in an early
candidate for the understatement of the year. ``Poor shots or
mis-hits never really enter your mind. The confidence just kind of
feeds on itself.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the case all weekend, as Duval showed the completeness
and coolness that make him so consistent. Duval rarely hits poor
shots, and it is more rare for him to lose his temper. While Duval
is one of the game's longest hitters, he spends more time working
on his short game, intent on saving strokes even when he makes a
mistake. Duval makes the game look easy, but his talent is the
residue of hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the off season, all I ever do is hit 50 or 100 balls a
day, then I chip, hit wedges,'' said Duval. ``It can just save you.
Everybody talks about how important it is, but I don't think you
can emphasize it enough. I'm pretty handy with a wedge, and I can
putt well. So what if I have to pitch out 80 yards? I have a pretty
darn good chance of getting up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara shot a five-under-par 68 Sunday, while Mayfair shot a
71, but Duval turned the tournament into a runaway by shooting a 67
in the first round, tying the course record with a 63 in the second
round, and shooting a splendid 68 in the third. Funk played with
Duval in Sunday's final group, and he came away impressed, calling
Duval the best driver in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to put Greg Norman in that category, but he's longer
than Norman, and just as straight,'' said Funk of Duval. ``I think
total driving, he's probably the best in the game right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The thought of starting Sunday with a huge lead only made Duval
more relaxed. He almost lost a seven-stroke lead at Tucson, Ariz.,
in the final round last year, falling into a tie with Justin
Leonard, before winning by a stroke. But Duval learned from that
experience, just as he seems to learn from everything. ``I feel
more comfortable in that position now,'' said Duval. ``Actually, I
wish I could have led by more.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval will not play at the Sony Hawaiian Open this week, and he
plans to take a week off to go skiing and snowboarding in Idaho. It
was a vacation well earned. And it was an impressive start to the
new year for a player who only seems to get better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
