<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-TENN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LADY VOLS END CONNECTICUT'S REIGN
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ Connecticut had floated above the women's
college basketball universe for almost two months. Since the middle
of November, the Huskies woke up each day knowing that they were
the top-ranked team in the country. At least technically.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Huskies rampaged past opponents by an average of 40
points, they understood that their ranking would really be
validated by defeating Tennessee. That luscious opportunity finally
came Sunday. Time for UConn to make it official by beating the
school that has won the last three national championships. Time for
UConn to throttle the No. 2 team, technically, and continue dancing
toward March.
</P>
<P>
   But the Huskies stumbled and staggered in the final minutes of a
captivating game and lost to the Lady Vols, 92-81, before 10,027
fans at Gampel Pavilion. UConn will not wake up on Monday morning
as the No. 1 team in the country after Semeka Randall, Chamique
Holdsclaw and Tamika Catchings combined to stop the Huskies, erase
Connecticut's 54-game home winning streak and surely swipe the top
ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying all along that until you beat Tennessee and
beat them in March, they're the best team in the country,'' said
UConn coach Geno Auriemma. ``The only reason we were No. 1 is
because they lost their second game. We got a chance to see the No.
1 team. We stared them in the eyes for 37 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not enough. UConn blinked and Tennessee's eyes bulged.
With the score tied, 76-76, and a wonderful finish seemingly about
to unfold in a wonderful game, Teresa Geter made a 10-foot jumper
to put the Lady Vols ahead with 3 minutes 16 seconds remaining.
Shea Ralph could not handle a pass on UConn's next possession and
then Catchings made a huge shot by nailing a 3-pointer over a
tentative Swin Cash that widened the bulge to 81-76.
</P>
<P>
   It was only Catchings' sixth 3-pointer of the season. It
bewildered the Huskies, who never recovered as Tennessee reeled off
12 straight points and, suddenly, a tight game that had been tied
eight times had turned into another rout for Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the late minutes of the game, we stepped up and we made big
plays,'' said Tennessee coach Pat Summitt. ``In order to win big
games, you have to make big plays. I felt we had the players who
did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Catchings (18 points) made the biggest shot of the afternoon,
but Holdsclaw and Randall split 50 points and also split time in
guiding the savvy Volunteers (13-1) over the younger Huskies
(13-1).
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw, her body hunched over and her mouth slightly open,
had 10 points before the game was 4 minutes old and, unlike the
UConn guards, always played under control. Randall, who plays like
a pit bull and who was booed every time she touched the ball after
she wrestled with Svetlana Abrosimova for a rebound, celebrated
more on the court than most people do on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's emotional when she gets on the bus,'' Summitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Randall had reasons to be emotional in a game that was the
marquee contest of the women's season, a game that was nationally
televised and caused Connecticut to distribute 214 news media
credentials. That was Randall with a jumping kick that would have
made David Carradine proud after giving the Lady Vols all of a 4-2
spread. That was Randall enjoying the booing she received after
tussling with Abrosimova (11 points), who played sluggishly after
hitting her head on the floor. Ralph was also held to 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to let go and she didn't want to let go,''
Randall said of her scuffle with Abrosimova. ``We rolled over for a
few. It guess it was a WWF match.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game was close to it. It was fierce, frenetic and
physical and, most of the time, it resembled a game in New York's
Greenwich Village. Summitt decided to run with the deeper Huskies
and the strategy worked. The Huskies shot just 41 percent from the
field, inexplicably missed at least 10 layups and swished five of
18 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always disappointing to lose a game at home,'' Ralph
said. ``At the same time, it's only January. We don't play here for
the national championship. Honestly, that's all we're worried
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours before the game, some fans circled Gampel Pavilion
holding signs that read ``I Need Tickets.'' One man told a
desperate teen-age girl that he would sell her two tickets for
$1,000. The girl gasped and walked away. Connecticut even imported
the ring announcer Michael Buffer to introduce the Huskies and
shout, ``Let's get ready for round ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were ready, but Tennessee was a little better when it
mattered most. Stay tuned. Summitt hinted that the Lady Vols and
UConn could meet for the national title in two months. Auriemma
pondered a different script.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we will get another chance to play in a game like
this in March,'' Auriemma said. ``Hopefully, someone will kick
their behind and we won't have to play them.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
