<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALF MAKES BRUINS HAPPY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the second half of their victory at Oregon, the Bruins shot
43.3 percent from the field. They made two shots outside of 10
feet. They scored just 28 points, and _ get this _ they made 1 of 5
free throws.
</P>
<P>
   But in one important respect it was their best half of the
season. Against a stingy man-to-man defense in a raucous arena, the
Bruins executed their halfcourt offense with unprecedented poise
and efficiency. And that, not their size or depth or athleticism,
is the most important ingredient to surviving on the rugged Pac-10
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win here in the clutch is a character-builder for the young
guys,'' said the old guy, sophomore Baron Davis, who led the Bruins
with 22 points. ``Now we can go back on the road with the same
mentality. When we go to a better place, like Stanford or Arizona,,
we've got to play halfcourt, and (Saturday) we showed we could.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were impatience incarnate Thursday at Oregon State,
mistaking open shots for good shots. Saturday, they played with a
``Hoosiers'' mentality _ i.e.: when coach Gene Hackman orders five
passes before a shot _ and bypassed open 15-footers to get open
five-footers.
</P>
<P>
   Of their 13 second-half field goals, nine came in the halfcourt
offense. In addition, they committed just two turnovers in the
second half. It was as close to Stanfordesque precision as UCLA is
likely to get.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half, we executed well under pressure
circumstances,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Board work: Freshman forward JaRon Rush continues to struggle
with his jumper. He made 4 of 23 shots over the weekend and was 0
of 10 from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   But Rush is compensating for poor shooting with hustle _ at
Oregon, he made two diving deflections in the second half that led
to Davis baskets _ and superb rebounding. At 6-6, he has become
UCLA's most effective rebounder, averaging 10.7 in three Pac-10
games and corralling 24 rebounds in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the shots Baron and Earl (Watson) put up, somebody's
got to rebound,'' Rush said with a slight smirk. ``I put up a lot,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Downs and ups: Freshman big men Dan Gadzuric and Jerome Moiso
typified UCLA's inconsistent weekend.
</P>
<P>
   At Oregon State, they made 1 of 13 shots (combined), grabbed 10
rebounds and scored three points. At Oregon, with improved patience
and settled nerves, they made 10 of 19 shots, grabbed 13 rebounds
and scored 20 points. Gadzuric also made the winning basket, a
tip-in of Moiso's miss with 1:28 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking too much about what I should do when I get the
ball,'' Gadzuric said of the Oregon State game.
</P>
<P>
   Calming down: Watson moved from point guard to wing guard when
Davis returned from his knee injury a month ago and the adjustment
hasn't been easy.
</P>
<P>
   Watson isn't a pure wing guard; he doesn't have the size or
shooting skills. When he plays with a scorer's mentality _ as he
did at OSU, taking 17 shots _ the offense sputters. When he waits
for opportunities in the flow of the offense, he's a solid wing
player.
</P>
<P>
   Watson played one of his most controlled games of the season at
Oregon. He did not force shots or passes, made 3 of 8 field goals
and had one turnover, matching a season low.
</P>
<P>
   Watson has committed three turnovers or less in five games this
season: Kentucky, Oklahoma State, Loyola Marymount, Arizona and
Oregon. It's no coincidence those are UCLA's five best games.
</P>
<P>
   Reason to worry: In style, if not talent or environment, the
UCLA coaches were more concerned with Oregon State than Oregon. The
Beavers employ a compact zone defense and prefer a dull, grinding
tempo _ two things that have always confounded the go-go Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``With coach (Eddie) Payne, they're so deliberate,'' Bruins
assistant Michael Holton said. ``We spent time preparing for that
and trying to do things to force the tempo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
