<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7231 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIT-RULES-NYT     01-10 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIT-RULES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDITORS GIVEN NEW RULES TO PREVENT BIAS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beginning in July, auditors must disclose any relationships they
have with the public companies they audit that could weaken their
independence, according to new rules approved by the Independence
Standards Board.
</P>
<P>
   The rules, approved last Friday, were the first to come from the
board, which was created by the Securities and Exchange Commission
in 1997 because of concerns about the growing number of ties
between some auditors and their clients.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors must be independent because they are expected to give
unbiased opinions on whether companies' financial statements are
fair and accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, an accounting firm must write a letter to a
company's audit committee describing any relationship that could be
considered a possible conflict of interest. Examples might be
consulting work for the company, employment of former auditors at
the company, or any financial interest that auditors have in the
company. The auditors must explain why the relationships have not
affected their objectivity.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules apply to the audits of companies that have fiscal
years ending after July 15.
</P>
<P>
   The standards board is now considering a proposal to prevent
auditors from going to work for their audit clients for a period of
time. An alternative proposal would let an auditor accept a job
with a client immediately but require the former employer to
increase its safeguards to insure that its audit work was not
affected by the job change.
</P>
<P>
   Securities regulators have been pressing the standards board to
move quickly to tighten the independence rules. The regulators say
they are concerned about the growing amount of consulting work that
the accounting firms are doing for their audit clients.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators say they have found more cases recently in which
accountants have violated the current independence rules. For
example, at some companies, accounting firms' consultants have
determined how much value should be assigned to certain assets. The
same firms' auditors have then reviewed those values during annual
audits, so that they are reviewing their own work, which is a
violation of the rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 2310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
