<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER TAKES SENATE OATH FOR A SECOND TIME
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a day of pomp and celebration by a political party
that has little to cheer about this decade, thousands of New York
Democrats assembled at Lincoln Center Sunday to whoop and cheer as
Charles E. Schumer was sworn in _ for a second time _ as New York
State's new junior Senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Chuck Schumer _ doesn't that have a nice ring to it?''
said Vice President Al Gore, who flew to Manhattan to administer
the oath to Schumer at Avery Fisher Hall for an audience that
commemorated the moment with a 30-second burst of flashbulbs. The
state's Democratic leaders, many of whom are beginning to consider
Gore's own political future as he steps up his presidential bid
this year, responded to the vice president with warm applause as
Schumer's wife, Iris, and daughters, Jessica, 14, and Alison, 9,
laughed and clapped on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   There was a certain familiarity to the event for anyone who has
been following the recent career of the former nine-term
congressman from Brooklyn. Schumer was sworn in at a ceremony in
Washington last week _ placing his left hand on the same Bible,
which he had saved from his bar mitzvah, as he used Sunday, and
taking the oath from the same vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The event's moderator, Robin MacNeil, the retired television
journalist, referred to it as Schumer's ``second annual
inauguration.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were differences. Last week's event on Capitol Hill
was attended by 50 or so people and was sponsored by the National
Soft Drink Association. Sunday's was attended by more than 2,000,
and was sponsored by the state Democratic Committee. The crowd
heard performances by the Boys Choir of Harlem, T.S. Monk Jr. (the
son of the jazz pianist and composer), and Itzhak Perlman, the
violinist, who played American standards. William Kennedy, the
Albany novelist, gave a reading.
</P>
<P>
   And Schumer, speaking to an audience that clearly was unhappy
with events in Washington _ Rep. Jerrold Nadler, among President
Clinton's most public defenders on the House Judiciary Committee,
received a standing ovation as he walked into the room _ warned
against what he described as a ``corrosive partisanship'' that he
said was making young voters cynical.
</P>
<P>
   ``What began 25 years ago with Watergate as a solemn and
necessary endeavor to restore the public trust has now grown beyond
our control,'' Schumer said. ``We are in danger of criminalizing
our differences _ of using scandal and innuendo to win at the gavel
what we can not settle at the ballot box. Instead of great debates
about the future of our Republic we have new politics of fear and
smear, where the loyal opposition is too often bent on personal
destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer made only an indirect mention of Alfonse M. D'Amato, the
three-term Republican he handily defeated last year, and the Senate
campaign. It came when, in listing his priorities as senator, he
stressed the need to unify the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upstaters must not let politicians demonize downstate _ such
attacks do not create one new job,'' Schumer said. D'Amato sought
to portray Schumer as hostile to upstate interests.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer went out of his way in the speech to telegraph his
concern about the problems of upstate New Yorkers. ``I know the
pain you feel because the nation's economic boom has left you
behind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The swearing in drew a wide representation of Democrats from
across the state, including most of the congressional delegation,
with the exception of Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, and even some
Democrats who had not supported Schumer, including Edward I. Koch,
the former mayor of New York. ``They invited me, so I came,'' Koch
said on Sunday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
