<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-SPRINKLERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SAFETY COLLIDES WITH REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vina Drennan's impassioned plea to the City Council
on Friday made the evening news and the morning papers. But her
testimony at the public hearing on fire sprinklers was perhaps not
as instructive as what she said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Drennan, a board member of the National Fallen Firefighters
Committee, has devoted herself to the cause of fire safety since
1994, when her husband, firefighter John Drennan, was burned in an
apartment building in the SoHo neighborhood of Manhattan and died
40 days later. In her testimony, she recalled the long vigil with
him at the burn unit of New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center
and spoke of the ``twisted bodies'' and ``melted skin'' she had
seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I challenge anyone who says we cannot afford a sprinkler
system law to visit the burn unit,'' she angrily told the council.
``We can change this. I hope you have the courage to stand up to
the forces that have blocked sprinklers in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   After testifying, Mrs. Drennan patiently explained to reporters
outside the chamber that sprinklers could save lives not only in
high-rises but also in houses. ``I suggest it very strongly for
homeowners,'' she said. ``For the same cost as wall-to-wall
carpeting you can have a sprinkler system.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she was asked another question: Had she installed
sprinklers in her own home?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she said, ``I gave it some thought after what happened
four years ago.'' But by the time of her husband's death, Mrs.
Drennan said, the last of her children were nearing college age,
and she expected to move out of their house on Staten Island within
a few years, so she decided not to spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house was emptying out, and there were tuition bills to
worry about,'' she said. ``But when I sold it this fall, I
recommended that the buyer install it.'' Mrs. Drennan herself moved
into a Manhattan apartment without sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   How could a passionate advocate of sprinklers choose to risk
living without them? Why couldn't she stand up to the ``forces''
blocking them in her own house? Because sprinklers are fine in the
abstract _ hailed by experts, rewarded by discounts on homeowner
insurance policies _ but problematic in the real world, especially
in old apartments and houses that require expensive retrofitting.
</P>
<P>
   Some esthetes find sprinklers hideous. Some people worry about
their going off accidentally or being set off by vandals (a
particular concern in New York's landlord-tenant war zones). And
some, particularly those who already pay for an array of
only-in-New-York requirements for fire safety, would rather spend
their money on other things, like college tuition bills.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most zealous fire-safety expert couldn't fault Mrs.
Drennan for investing in college rather than sprinklers. One of the
many advantages of being a college graduate is that you're less
likely to die in a fire. The two chief distinguishing features of
fire victims _ the two risk factors more important than anything
else _ are poverty and lack of education.
</P>
<P>
   As a homeowner, Mrs. Drennan considered the kind of tradeoff
that tends to be ignored by safety advocates, particularly ones who
rent. The tenants who testified on Friday _ survivors of the fire
in an Upper West Side high-rise that inspired the furor over fire
safety _ demanded a sprinkler system in their building, but
afterward they bristled when told of estimates that it might
increase their rent by $50 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already paying enough rent that the landlord can afford
to install the sprinklers,'' said one tenant, Anna Bager. Others
insisted that the cost wouldn't be more than $5 a month. Obviously,
they had not written many checks to contractors lately. Those
accustomed to such bills dread the prospect of tearing up old
buildings to put in sprinklers. Landlords and developers say the
most reasonable approach would be to mandate the sprinklers only in
new construction, and then only if the city offsets the new cost by
eliminating some of its old fire-safety requirements that would
become superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   The more Mrs. Drennan talked about her own home, the more
sympathetic she sounded to the building owners' position. ``I'd be
happy if we can just get a law for sprinklers in new
construction,'' she said, ``and maybe offer some voluntary
incentives to put sprinklers in other homes. I'm pragmatic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of saying, thou shalt have a sprinkler in every home,
let people choose for themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
