<SLUG> BC-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CIVIL ACTION' WINS JUDGMENT AT BOX OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- ``A Civil Action'' scored a winning verdict at
the nation's multiplexes with an estimated $14.5 million at 1,802
theaters during the Friday-Sunday period, studio sources said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney release, starring John Travolta as an attorney
battling corporations over tainted drinking water, performed better
than expected during what is often a slack time for moviegoing. The
drama posted the third-best January weekend numbers, behind the
1997 re-release of ``Star Wars'' and last year's sensational
``Titanic'' grosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Audiences responded well to a serious, well-done movie,'' said
film analyst Arthur Rockwell. ``It's also amazing that Travolta
continues to draw like this after having been in so many films with
such a diversity of roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney marketing executive Chuck Viane said the audience for ``A
Civil Action,'' a co-production with Paramount, was split evenly
between males and females with 75 percent over 24 years old. ``We
think word of mouth is going to broaden the audience
significantly,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source tracking service,
called the performance ``very promising'' and predicted ``A Civil
Action'' would take in $88 million by the end of its run. ``It's
rare for films that aren't holiday holdovers to perform well at
this time of year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Civil Action,'' which opened on Christmas at two theaters to
qualify for Academy Award consideration, will face serious
competition next weekend from the widened release of 20th Century
Fox's war drama ``The Thin Red Line,'' another Oscar contender. The
latter performed well over the weekend with $1.1 million at only 61
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's third weekend of ``Patch Adams'' led the rest of the
pack with $12.8 million at 2,770 theaters to top $83 million after
17 days. `` `Patch Adams' has terrific legs,'' Rockwell said. ``Put
Robin Williams in the right vehicle and he's unstoppable.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros.' fourth weekend of ``You've Got Mail'' delivered a
third-place finish with $8.3 million at 2,749 sites and has crossed
the $90 million mark. It edged Sony's third weekend of ``Stepmom''
with $8 million at 2,358 screens, which gave the family drama $62
million overall.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks SKG's fourth weekend of ``The Prince of Egypt'' came
in fifth with $5.8 million at 2,947 theaters for a 46 percent
decline. Grosses for family films fell off significantly with
children back to school following the holiday break.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's third weekend of ``Mighty Joe Young'' took in $4.7
million at 2,559 sites, down 42 percent, and its eighth weekend of
``A Bug's Life'' followed with $4.5 million at 2,500 screens, off
49 percent. The latter has totaled $142.7 million, making it the
68th highest domestic grosser ever.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax's third weekend of ``The Faculty'' came in eighth with
$4.2 million at 2,365 theaters, followed by its widened release of
critical favorite ``Shakespeare in Love'' with $4 million at only
632 screens. ``Shakespeare,'' a major contender for Oscar
nominations, has nearly $15 million after a month in limited
release.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount's fifth weekend of ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' took
the 10th spot with $3 million at 2,161 theaters, edging Disney's
eighth weekend of ``Enemy of the State'' with $2.9 million at 1,576
locations, although those slots could be reversed when final
figures are released today. ``Enemy'' crossed over the $100 million
mark Saturday, becoming the 13th movie released in 1998 and 180th
of all time to reach the milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount showed sneak previews of football drama ``Varsity
Blues'' on Friday at 880 theaters and reported strong responses for
the film, which opens Friday at 2,100 theaters. ``We think `Varsity
Blues' will surprise a lot of people,'' Bucksbaum, noting that it
is the first of about 20 films targeted at the teen-young adult
audience due out in the next 16 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That many films for that audience could be a little bit of
overkill,'' Bucksbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Also opening Friday will be MGM's drama ``At First Sight'' with
Val Kilmer and a pair of thrillers -- DreamWorks' ``In Dreams''
with Robert Downey Jr. and Universal's ``Virus'' with Jamie Lee
Curtis. Paramount will also expand Oscar contender ``A Simple
Plan'' to 600 screens.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's overall business totaled $87 million, down 19
percent from the same weekend last year when the fourth weekend of
``Titanic'' topped $28 million.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
