<SLUG> BC-TOYOTA-PRESIDENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYOTA PRESIDENT IS CHOICE TO LEAD TRADE GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In a development that surprised corporate Japan, the
Japan Federation of Employers' Associations made clear its
intention late Friday to elect Hiroshi Okuda, the dynamic president
of Toyota Motor Corp., as its new chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota moved quickly to say that Okuda would continue to have a
significant role in its operations. ``He should not retire from the
company management,'' Shoichiro Toyoda, Toyota's chairman, said on
Saturday, according to the Kyodo News Service. ``We need him.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is difficult to see how Okuda will wear both hats. The
federation, known here as the Nikkeiren, faces its biggest
challenge since World War II, with Japan's unemployment rate
climbing as the nation's recession persists. Last month, the
unemployment rate reached 4.4 percent, not high by global standards
but almost double the rate Japan is accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   And Toyota, while one of the most financially sound and
efficient companies in the world, is confronting a persistently
weak domestic car market at home and an ever more competitive
market abroad, thanks to global overcapacity in the auto industry
and the unexpected strengthening of the Japanese yen against the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The company is pushing its auto-body manufacturing affiliates to
cut capacity, opening a major new production plant in France and
realigning its domestic sales network.
</P>
<P>
   Okuda, who is currently vice chairman of the Nikkeiren, has
expressed his willingness to take the top position from Jiro
Nemoto, the current chairman, who is expected to leave the job this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Toyoda told reporters on Saturday that since the company
intended to adopt a holding-company structure later this year,
Okuda might become chairman of Toyota Motor. He characterized that
job as more akin to the role a chief executive plays in an American
corporation. In Japan, that role is usually taken by the president,
the title Okuda now holds.
</P>
<P>
   Any suggestion that Okuda, whose candor is the bane of his
public relations staff and the delight of the global investment
community, will have less of a hands-on role at Toyota is likely to
shake investor confidence. He has pushed the hidebound company hard
to be at the forefront of new automotive technologies and trends
and has worked to increase its return on equity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 2330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
