<SLUG> BC-STRATUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASCEND TO SELL STRATUS UNIT TO INVESTCORP
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ascend Communications Inc., a maker of advanced data
communications equipment, will formally announce on Monday that it
is selling its Stratus Enterprise Computer Division for more than
$100 million to a group led by Investcorp, the Middle East
investment group.
</P>
<P>
   The division was acquired by Ascend when it bought Stratus
Computer Inc. for about $800 million in October. Ascend, of
Alameda, Calif., announced then that it would sell all
non-telecommunications business units, including enterprise
computing and software operations. The new company, which will
restore the name Stratus Computer and be based in Marlboro, Mass.,
provides servers to large businesses.
</P>
<P>
   While the sale does not rival recent huge mergers, it is
noteworthy because it is one of the few times a financial buyer
like Investcorp has invested in the often treacherous world of
technology. Financial buyers, renowned in the 1980's by the likes
of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co., take stakes in troubled
companies, shore them up and either take them public or sell them.
But these buyers have often shied away from technology producers
because product life cycles are quite short and earnings
unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher J. Stadler, a member of Investcorp's management
committee, said his company was interested in the division because
of its 18-year history and its dependable customer base, which
includes banks, brokerage firms and airlines. But the deal does not
signal a wholesale push by Investcorp into the technology arena.
``This falls into a specific case,'' he said. Investcorp has
previously bought into prominent companies including Saks Fifth
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Still, enough financial buyers looked at Stratus to suggest that
technology is an area they are now more willing to explore. Ken
Fehrnstrom, vice president for business development at Ascend, said
several financial buyers were interested in the division, along
with others who wanted the technology but not necessarily the
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Fehrnstrom said his company expected to announce the sale of two
other software divisions received in the Stratus acquisition by the
end of this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
