<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOURCE: FORD IS CLIPPERS FAVORITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Make a wish and blow out the candles, Chris Ford.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're wishing to become coach of the Clippers, be
prepared to supply your own icing. Ford couldn't be reached for
comment Sunday, so he avoided the threat of a jinx.
</P>
<P>
   According to a source close to Ford, the former Milwaukee Bucks
coach who turned 50 today has become the heavy favorite to replace
the fired Bill Fitch and inherit a 17-65 team. The Clippers, who
promised to hire a new coach at the ``beginning'' of this week,
could make it official today. Or Tuesday. Or Wednesday. The fat
lady's schedule is of little consequence to Clippers owner Donald
T. Sterling, who shut down the Danny Manning-for-Glen
Rice-and-Willie Burton deal at the last minute five seasons back.
</P>
<P>
   A similar maneuver in the imminent Ford hiring would please Jim
Brewer, the ex-Clippers assistant whose name had been prominent
around NBA campfires as the leading candidate to replace Fitch. The
third name on the Clippers' rapidly maturing short list is that of
Eddie Jordan, whose efforts in Sacramento got him canned at the end
of last season.
</P>
<P>
   When contacted Sunday at his home, Brewer said the Clippers
still hadn't communicated their intentions to him over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer spent part of Saturday night watching his son, Jim, play
in a game for Long Beach City College's unbeaten team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good about my chances,'' Brewer, who assisted
Fitch the last four seasons, said then. ``But we'll just have to
wait and see. I would relish the opportunity to coach the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the Clippers hire someone else?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even want to think about that. Obviously, I'd be very
disappointed. But I've gone through the process, and I understand a
little more about what is involved in making a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   That would put him way ahead of most Clippers observers and some
of their players.
</P>
<P>
   One Clipper, who preferred keeping a low profile on the issue,
said Brewer would be a popular choice with the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows the guys, and with a short time to prepare for the
season, bringing him in would make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time to quit recycling some of the usual coaches
and give someone new a chance,'' said another Clipper, firing under
the cloak of anonymity. ``The game has changed from when they first
started.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford became available for the Clippers gig when he was fired
after the Bucks finished 36-46 last season. During two seasons in
Milwaukee, Ford's teams were 69-95. But he does have a history of
success. In five seasons as coach of the Boston Celtics ('90-'95),
Ford was 222-188. His first two Celtics teams won Atlantic Division
titles but lost in the Eastern Conference playoff semifinals.
Thanks to career-ending back problems, Larry Bird played in only
105 games over that two-year span, while injuries limited superstar
Kevin McHale to 124 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   In seven seasons as an NBA head coach, Ford's record is 291-283,
a winning percentage of .507.
</P>
<P>
   He has pursued the Clippers job even though he completed only
two years of a three-year deal with the Bucks, who would be
obligated to compensate an idle Ford for this season.
</P>
<P>
   Ford didn't have enough ideas to prevent the Milwaukee purge,
even though the Bucks' starting lineup included Terrell Brandon,
once accused by Sports Illustrated of being the NBA's premier point
guard, scoring fiend Glenn ``Big Dog'' Robinson, and Jesus, a.k.a.
Ray Allen, co-star of Spike Lee's joint ``He Got Game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford had some game in his day as well. He teamed with Howard
Porter to lead Villanova into the 1971 NCAA championship game,
which it lost to UCLA. He averaged 9.2 points per game in a 10-year
NBA career that began in Detroit and ended in Boston. Ford helped
the Celtics win the NBA title in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The coach of that team was Bill Fitch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
