<DOCNO> NYT19990110.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7255 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STREET-PHONES-880(     01-10 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STREET-PHONES-880(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRESH FACE FOR THE CURBSIDE CHAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They came from Long Island City.
</P>
<P>
   Hooded figures of stainless steel _ 7{ feet tall, with tapered
legs and rounded flanks _ began to multiply on the sidewalks of
Manhattan last year. Most had telephones inside. A few did not.
</P>
<P>
   Their arresting design won both admirers, who thought them
sturdy and innovative, and detractors, who thought them bulky and
intrusive. They also left a lot of New Yorkers wondering what had
become of street phones.
</P>
<P>
   First, directories disappeared from the booths. Then the booths
disappeared. Operating companies multiplied. Enclosures turned into
billboards. Phones sprouted from the sides of delis. And new
designs emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're springing up like mushrooms, and some of them look
like portobellos,'' Elizabeth Starkey, a member of Community Board
7 on the Upper West Side, said of the stainless steel enclosures,
installed by Telebeam Telecommunications Corp. of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   More changes are in store as city regulators fashion a new
franchise system that would affect what phones look like, where
they stand, who runs them and how they are used for advertising.
Applications are pending for 19,965 new phones, in addition to the
32,239 already on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The art is balancing our top priority _ improvements in
operability and cleanliness _ while at the same time keeping a
vibrant, diverse industry that will service all areas of the
city,'' said Allan Dobrin, the commissioner of the city's
Department of Information Technology and Telecommunications, which
regulates the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the city should also pay more attention to
aesthetics, planning and the public environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am quite concerned about telephone booths,'' said Reba White
Williams, who resigned last month as president of the New York City
Art Commission, which reviews the design of structures on public
land and approved the Telebeam enclosure. ``It seems as though
wherever there is a vacant spot, anybody can put up a telephone
booth without any consideration of how it looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the city does not have aesthetic guidelines for
street telephones, although the telecommunications agency is
considering the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Municipal Art Society worries about the proliferation of
street phones, said Vanessa Gruen, the director of special projects
at the civic group. ``It's purely a method of getting advertising
on the sidewalks,'' Ms. Gruen said, ``especially when you have cell
phones. The public service is really to be questioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth to tell, street phones were entrepreneurial from the
start.
</P>
<P>
   New York Telephone Co. installed the first outdoor booths in
1960. (Yes, 1960. Those phone booths you recall from
black-and-white movies were indoors: nightclubs, train stations,
drugstores.) The company figured that pedestrians were a lucrative
market. ``One in every two telephone calls is made on impulse,'' a
phone company executive, Robert Simpson, explained at the time.
``With millions of people walking the streets, we were sure there
was a use for curbside phones.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times was less sure. ``People are not used to
telephoning in the street,'' the newspaper observed cautiously in a
news article on May 3, 1960.
</P>
<P>
   They got used to it.
</P>
<P>
   Glass-and-metal curbside booths with folding doors quickly
became as familiar a fixture in New York as the red cabins once
were in London. But the booths did not last long. They were
vandalized and turned into shelters, urinals and drug dealers'
offices. In the 1970s, New York Telephone began replacing them with
an open-air enclosure known as the Adco 120, made by Acoustics
Development Corp. of St. Joseph, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Kent learned this the hard way in ``Superman'' (1978),
when he dashed out of the Daily Planet building and found a skimpy
enclosure that was unusable as a changing room.
</P>
<P>
   After the breakup of American Telephone &AMP; Telegraph Co. in 1984,
independent companies installed thousands of phones on the sides of
buildings. The performance and maintenance of these phones went
largely unregulated until 1996, when the city began to require
registration. There are now nearly 24,000 registered independent
phones, in addition to nearly 8,600 operated by Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   All public pay phones in New York are soon to be governed by
franchises, which the telecommunications agency expects to award
this year. In the meantime, it has issued about 500 interim
permits, including those to Telebeam.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure the contract is as fair as it can be to a
diverse industry _ from Bell Atlantic with 8,600 phones to Joe
Telcom with one phone,'' said Larry Allison, assistant commissioner
of the telecommunications agency.
</P>
<P>
   Among the questions are these: Will companies pay a flat rate or
a percentage of revenue to the city? How will advertising be
managed? What level of maintenance and service will be required?
How can the city guarantee that phones are installed in poorer
neighborhoods? And should the city impose design standards?
</P>
<P>
   Of particular concern is the appearance of enclosures near
designated landmarks or within historic districts. Jennifer Raab,
the chairwoman of the Landmarks Preservation Commission, said the
agency is discussing the development of rules for these situations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That the design question is being asked at all is a tribute to
Telebeam, which opened New Yorkers' eyes to the idea that phone
enclosures can cut a high profile in the streetscape, although
Telebeam's chief executive, Raymond Mastroianni, said that was not
his goal.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 of the structures, designed by Rudy Fabiano, have been
installed. They bear the AT&AMP;T logo because that is the carrier
Telebeam uses. Enclosures without phones await a dial tone, which
can be supplied only by Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have put up Adcos and heard nothing from the
community,'' Mastroianni said, ``but we went out of our way to put
something nicer on the street. I wanted to do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   The structure is wide enough for a caller in a wheelchair. It
can accommodate a public-access computer terminal, which
Mastroianni hopes to install in the future. The legs are strong
enough to support ad panels without buckling, as some enclosures
do. And stainless steel is used to resist graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   Street phone design has to take into account maliciousness and
carelessness. That is why, for example, the shelves in enclosures
are slanted or made of widely spaced bars. ``Anything that's a flat
surface in New York, people think, `This is my new counter,''' said
Gerard Doolan, director of sales in the public communications
division of Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   One form of vandalism for which there is no design cure yet is
the pasting of stickers on enclosures, mostly by towing companies
and escort services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to sue these people in small-claims court,''
said Larry Ginsburg, the chief operating officer of New York City
Public Telephone Co. of Brooklyn. Its enclosure across the street
from St. Patrick's Cathedral, at Fifth Avenue and 51st Street,
recently carried the illegally pasted-on message: ``Gorgeous!!
Models drop their undies for you!!!'' A phone number followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a war out there,'' Ginsburg said.
</P>
<P>
   The battle has been joined by Commissioner Jules Polonetsky of
the city's Consumer Affairs Department. He sent letters to
towing-company owners last year warning that illegal stickers would
subject them to fines and possible suspension or revocation of
licenses.
</P>
<P>
   But in the campaign against more aggressive vandalism, such as
coin-box robbery and destruction of street phone equipment, Doolan
conceded that it could be difficult to engage the authorities in an
all-out effort. He said he cannot quite imagine a police officer
coming home and boasting: ``You know what I did today, honey? I
arrested a guy for beating up a phone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
