<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7259 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-10 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MINNEAPOLIS _ They come at you with an arsenal as frightful as the
weather outside, a blue norther dressed in purple but with more
shivers, chills and bone-numbing gusts.
</P>
<P>
   They come at you as if these were not the tense times of the NFL
playoffs, nor even football. They come at you and make your head
spin with their tricks, their high-flying acrobatics and all that
magic.
</P>
<P>
   You forget about the glory days of the grunt-and-grind Minnesota
Vikings _ those bygone times when the most popular players were
defensive linemen and the coach was Bud Grant, an expressionless
man with an expressionless team. The game was three yards and a
cloud of ice shavings.
</P>
<P>
   These Vikings make you believe the Lakers decided to return to
Minneapolis, bringing Showtime along for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   They come at you with wiry quarterback Randall Cunningham
running the break, his knees popping up and down, up and down, like
a kid running through high grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so much fun,'' Cunningham gushed. ``Because of the
guys on this team, the way we can do things, I just play. I just
have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   They come at you with Randy Moss, Jake Reed and Cris Carter,
spectacular receivers running all over the place and making
defenders look like a bunch of 12-year-olds at a rodeo calf
scramble, trying to figure out just which way to run.
</P>
<P>
   They come at you with Robert Smith slicing back and forth,
churning up yardage behind an offensive line that doesn't so much
slice as it does puree.
</P>
<P>
   They make it all look so careless and free, like Magic Johnson
pitching an alley-oop or Mary Tyler Moore tossing her beret into
the Minneapolis skyline.
</P>
<P>
   They make you think it couldn't possibly get any better or more
fun. It couldn't possibly become more creative for them or
dangerous for opposing defenses.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday afternoon, it did. While everyone was watching
Showtime, the Arizona Cardinals got Kurt Rambised.
</P>
<P>
   That was Leroy Hoard scoring three touchdowns. That was Andrew
Glover catching a big early touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a team decides they want to defend one part of our offense,
they can't do it for long,'' Minnesota coach Dennis Green said.
``We have some weapons and things we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The 41-21 final score of the Vikes' NFC playoff semifinal win
over the Cards might look like just another Minneapolis Lakers
ho-hummer: Moss going deep. Carter going deep. Smith going long.
</P>
<P>
   And, well, those guys did all those things.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinals clearly tried to shut down Moss and Carter.
And at least early on, they did it with some success as All-Pro
cornerback Aeneas Williams gave Moss a rough time and deep safeties
cut off Carter at the post.
</P>
<P>
   The Cards' defense also tried to keep Cunningham in the pocket
and Smith inside the tackles.
</P>
<P>
   But when the game was being won _ we're talking the first half
here _ it was Hoard scoring two of the Vikes' first three
touchdowns and Glover registering the third on a beautiful
third-down catch between defenders.
</P>
<P>
   And twice during those three drives, utility back David Palmer
lined up at quarterback as Cunningham split wide like a receiver,
with Palmer converting a first down both times.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a team tries to overlook anyone on our offense,'' Glover
said, ``they could be in big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, you have the scouting report for next week's Vikings
conference final against the Atlanta Falcons, which will be played
here in the land of arctic blasts outside and Miami mambos in the
Metrodome. The Dirty Birds could be in big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have playmakers, and they're not always the same guys,''
Green said. ``Sometimes, you never know who's going to get the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Cardinals never did. They fell behind 17-0 before
Moss, who eventually wound up with four catches, 73 yards and a
touchdown, even touched the ball once.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals ace quarterback Jake Plummer also threw a pair of
interceptions in the first half, and nothing hurt the Cards' cause
more than a running game that read like the local weather forecast
_ minus-two, minus-four, minus-six.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody on this team can honestly say that
they've been on a better offensive team than this one,'' Hoard
said.
</P>
<P>
   But one player in the locker room did say something that might
be even more frightful than the weather and the Vikings were on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't believe we were on today,'' Cunningham said.
``At least not all the way on. I think we can play better. I know
we can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
