<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7260 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-HNS &LR;      01-10 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ As much as the New York Jets dominated
the Jacksonville Jaguars, they had trouble putting away the
underdogs Sunday at the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the Jaguars appeared down and out, they kept springing
up with improbable plays to bounce back into their AFC divisional
playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, this was no contest. New York led in rushing
yardage 151-95; passing yardage 284-156; time of possession
39:16-20:44; and takeaways 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the final score was Jets 34, Jaguars 24. And the difference
was only seven points until John Hall kicked a 30-yard field goal
with 24 seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we put them away at times, but it turned out we
didn't,'' Jets offensive tackle Jumbo Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   Jets coach Bill Parcells prides himself on maintaining
discipline, and he was critical of ``stupid plays'' that allowed
the Jaguars to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave them too much room to breathe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And that was after the Jets had the Jacksonville defense panting
for breath on the game's first drive.
</P>
<P>
   The gale-like wind that had been forecast did not materialize.
The temperature was 26 degrees, but the sky was mostly sunny and
the wind moderate most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   With conditions conducive to passing, the Jets took to the air.
Vinny Testaverde completed all four throws on a 70-yard drive that
ended with a 21-yard scoring pass to Keyshawn Johnson, who beat
cornerback Dave Thomas cutting across the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second quarter, a 52-yard field goal by Hall gave
the Jets a 10-0 lead. Seconds later, Jets cornerback Otis Smith
made a leaping sideline interception off Mark Brunell, and the Jets
appeared ready to bury their opponent early.
</P>
<P>
   New York drove to the Jacksonville 22, but Curtis Martin
fumbled, and safety Chris Hudson recovered and returned it 47
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson then showed that the Jets did not have a monopoly on
stupidity. He tried to lateral the ball, and Johnson, who had
hustled downfield to follow the play, recovered it. The Jets
capitalized, with Johnson scoring on a 10-yard end around for a
17-0 lead with 33 seconds left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   As time was about to expire, Brunell lobbed a bomb down the left
sideline. Jimmy Smith pulled down the 52-yard pass for a touchdown,
and Parcells was furious with safety Jerome Henderson for his late
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there was no excuse for that,'' Parcells said. When
reporters asked what he told the player, the coach said: ``You
couldn't repeat it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, Corwin Brown intercepted to set up another
Jets touchdown. Johnson, who had nine receptions for 121 yards,
made an over-the-shoulder catch for 23 yards to the one-yard line.
On third down from the one, Martin scored for a 24-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But again, the Jaguars resurrected themselves, with Reggie
Barlow returning the ensuing kickoff 88 yards to the four.
</P>
<P>
   On fourth-and-three, the Jaguars went for the touchdown. The
gamble worked, as Brunell threaded a pass to a double-covered
Keenan McCardell, pulling the Jaguars to 24-14.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville could not sustain momentum, however, because Martin
(36 carries for 124 yards) kept grinding. The Jets went up 31-14
with a second one-yard touchdown by Martin.
</P>
<P>
   But again, the Jaguars came back. Jimmy Smith scored on an
artful 19-yard comeback reception in the end zone on third-and-15.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big play,'' Parcells said. ``It kept them in the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   After a fumble by receiver Wayne Chrebet, the Jaguars' Mike
Hollis kicked a 37-yard field goal to cut the lead to 31-24 with
6:38 left in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets drove to the 14-yard line before committing another
costly error. Testaverde, on second-and-seven, sailed a ball into
the hands of Jaguars rookie safety Donovin Darius, who was on his
knees just inside the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Then came another mental miscue. Darius hesitated, coming out of
the end zone, then backing into it and finally getting tackled at
the half-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got up, I couldn't see,'' Darius said. ``A guy in
green was running at me, and I didn't know if I was in the end zone
or on the one. I wanted to make a play, so I started running.''
</P>
<P>
   With 2:24 left, the Jaguars had time, but they had no field
position, and they lost the ball on downs, effectively ending the
game.
</P>
<P>
   So now, for the first time since the 1982 season, the Jets
advance to the AFC Championship Game, in Denver on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jets have a very sound offense and defense,'' Jaguars
All-Pro offensive tackle Tony Boselli said. ``I think they can beat
Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells sounded less optimistic. ``The way Denver played
yesterday (blasting Miami 38-3),'' he said, ``it would be hard for
us to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jets skeptics wonder if the team is too inexperienced. Before
Sunday's game, only 19 of their players had appeared in a
postseason game. The nervousness showed, but Parcells said, ``I
don't think it was inexperience. It was stupid plays.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
