<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7261 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-STERN-HNS &LR;      01-10 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-STERN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
When he became NBA commissioner in 1984, David Stern had a vision
of what the league could be.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not long before that, the league had been mired in drug
scandals, and the NBA Finals, now one of the premier showcase
events in professional sports, were tape-delayed on late-night TV.
</P>
<P>
   But Stern looked at players such as Magic Johnson, Larry Bird
and Isiah Thomas _ players whose flair for the game could be
packaged and sold _ and saw a sport fans around the world could
embrace. More important, Stern thought it was a game corporate
America could embrace.
</P>
<P>
   And they did.
</P>
<P>
   Stern sold the league, and he did it by selling the players.
Johnson, Bird, Thomas, Julius Erving and later Michael Jordan,
Grant Hill and Shaquille O'Neal became icons, not only on the court
but off the court as well _ on billboards, magazines, movies and
TV.
</P>
<P>
   Stern understandably took pride in his creation, not only
because of the phenomenal success it enjoyed but also because it
had been untouched by the labor problems that seemed to plague
every other professional sport in the '80s and '90s.
</P>
<P>
   But it was just a matter of time before the players began to
believe the hype Stern was selling. They understandably began to
believe they were the game, and Stern's creation suddenly became
Frankenstein's monster.
</P>
<P>
   The league's partnership with the players began to erode, coming
to a head last year, when the NBA locked out its players July 1.
The work stoppage would last six agonizing months before Stern and
Billy Hunter, executive director of the National Basketball Players
Association, hammered out an agreement mere hours before the
remainder of the 1998-99 season was to be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   So with the league gearing up to play an abbreviated schedule of
approximately 50 games, Stern is almost back where he started _
having to sell the NBA to a public that doesn't seem to care much
for it. And he might have to sell the NBA without its biggest star,
should Jordan retire after winning his sixth championship last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Can Stern work his magic again? He thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how big of (an image) hit we've taken,'' Stern
said. ``I know we've taken a big hit, but (compare it to) a serious
illness _ some people are up and walking very soon in robust health
on short term, and some it takes much longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a variable that is not preordained. I think it (the
NBA's recovery) depends on whether what we achieved in this is
viewed by our fans as having been worth the sacrifice, and whether
we use the opportunity to reconnect in serious ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Will fans believe the lockout was worth the sacrifice?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only going to be a question of time,'' Stern said. ``I
can tell them that if they're really fans of sports, they know that
the notion of a few players making all the money, and the rest
being extras, like it would be in Hollywood, is not a sports model,
because sports is about teamwork and value down the line, and
that's what we tried to do here, once and for all, and we wanted to
give teams the opportunity to succeed, not guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think with this fine-tuning we're into now we have a system
that has done that. If teams can't do well, don't blame their
heavenly stars. Our fault lies not in our stars but ourselves. Over
a period of time, if a team doesn't succeed under this system, then
management has to answer for the failure.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest challenges Stern envisions is reconnecting
with the players, many of whom might distrust the league for what
they consider to have been hardball negotiating tactics. Stern says
he is distressed when he thinks about how the partnership between
the league and the union has eroded, and he intends to rebuild that
partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, interestingly enough, one of the things Billy Hunter
and I talked about during breaks in the negotiations was that we
would, in fact, get through this eventually,'' Stern said, ``and
when we did, there were many things the union and the league were
going to be much more aligned on than opposed on, and that has to
do with marketing, globality, and player conduct and player
interaction with fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I take Billy at his word on this, that we're going to do
some things _ I don't know what they are and can't say what they
are _ but I just know that if we can reaffirm the partnership, it's
not going to be a marketing ploy. Our fans are going to see some
fundamental shifts in attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Which apparently means the NBA is cleaning up its act. Stern
hopes there will be fewer stories about poor player conduct, on and
off the court, and more instances of players cooperating with fans,
helping to rebuild the fan base.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important issue now is to use the depths of our
despair at losing the season to lead the way in changing the
attitudes of teams and players toward each other and toward the
fans,'' Stern said. ``I believe that our teams are complicit in
setting standards. I don't mean in punishing players, as little
kids, but in level of expectation of what the product is, and what
your obligations and commitments are to your fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those obligations and commitments come from players and teams
working together, and the union and the league. For reasons I can't
quite divine, for the last few years we've been stepping back from
that. Part of it, I think, was attributable to the union
necessarily trying to build its base and rally the players. In so
doing, it portrayed the teams and the league as the enemy. They
were the adversary in a collective-bargaining sense, but when you
focus on it you see that that has its own corrosive effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get together and say this is the right way for us,
collectively, to behave toward the fans, and we'd better make sure
it gets done. We are going to sit down with Billy Hunter, and we're
going to be on the same side of the issue. We're going to say,
`Let's talk about what responsibilities come with being a player in
the NBA, what commitments and responsibilities come with being an
employee of the NBA or a team or a commissioner, and let's define
those.'''
</P>
<P>
   That would depend on players being willing to cooperate, which
hasn't always been the case.
</P>
<P>
   And should Jordan retire, that would leave precious few players
who are willing to assume the role of ambassador or _ dare we say
it? _ role models. Hill, Tim Duncan, Keith Van Horn and Kobe Bryant
are a few who are being groomed, but Stern said there will be more.
There always are.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of players (could be role models), a lot,'' Stern said.
``When one looks out there, it's not even fair to mention names,
but when you look at a number of our players, you're looking at
solid citizens. What happens is the media focuses on people who are
different, because they make better copy. People think that becomes
the norm, but it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   And what is his message to NBA fans?
</P>
<P>
   ``Step back a little bit, give us some room, and judge us
harshly if we don't win you back,'' Stern said. ``But at least give
us the opportunity to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
