<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7262 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-HNS &LR;      01-10 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Before the New York Jets travel to Denver this week for
Sunday's AFC Championship Game against the Broncos, there are a few
statistics they should know about the defending Super Bowl
champions:
</P>
<P>
   In their 38-3 divisional playoff victory against Miami on
Saturday, the Broncos tied a team record for most points scored in
a playoff game and set a team record for fewest points allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Counting the playoffs, the Broncos have won 18 consecutive games
at Mile High Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos are 3-0 in AFC Championship Games at Mile High
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not done yet,'' Broncos safety Tyrone Braxton said
Sunday. ``We have to look at the big picture. This is one piece of
the puzzle. This is not it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets and coach Bill Parcells will bring a seven-game winning
streak into Mile High Stadium. When Parcells coached at New
England, the Broncos obliterated the Patriots 37-3 and 34-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you always get a little juiced up when you are going
against a coach who has had a lot of success, a coach who has a
couple of Super Bowl rings,'' Denver coach Mike Shanahan said about
Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Broncos watched the Jets' victory over Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a great man leading them,'' Braxton said. ``Parcells
has won everywhere he's gone. There's no reason to think he
wouldn't win there, but it's surprising that he did it so quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as they did in 1997 when they won their first Super Bowl,
the Broncos lost two of the last three regular-season games but
excelled when the playoffs began. Their conquest of Miami removed a
lot of doubt about their ability to refocus and play as well as
they did before they got caught up in becoming the first 19-0 team
in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an empty bandwagon,'' Pro Bowl center Tom Nalen
said. ``There weren't a lot of people who gave us a chance to play
a game like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos have their sights set on Super Bowl XXXIII at
Miami's Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they play the next two games like they played this one,
they'll win the Super Bowl,'' Dolphins linebacker Zach Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos scored on their first three possessions against the
Dolphins. They outgained Miami 424 yards to 252, including a
rushing advantage of 250-14. Running back Terrell Davis, voted the
league's Most Valuable Player on Saturday, carried 21 times for 199
yards and scored two touchdowns. Naturally, Davis doesn't expect to
average 9.5 yards a carry every week.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback John Elway completed 14 of 23 passes for 182 yards
and a touchdown and was not intercepted. He beat Miami quarterback
Dan Marino for the first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Win and we're in,'' cornerback Darrien Gordon said about
reaching a second consecutive Super Bowl. ``With Terrell carrying
the load and with John playing the way he is, it's going to be
tough to beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Denver was so dominant in the 35-point victory _ the
largest in franchise history _ over Miami that Shanahan should
preserve his game plan and use it again against the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every week, we have a different game plan,'' Shanahan said.
``We change our schemes and formations from game to game. We'll put
in a few new wrinkles for the (Jets) game.''
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising thing about the Broncos' performance wasn't
the explosiveness of the offense. It was the way their
much-maligned defense smothered Miami, especially against the run.
The Dolphins averaged 1.1 yards a carry.
</P>
<P>
   Marino was 26-of-37 for 243 yards and no touchdowns. He was
intercepted twice. Denver's defense forced three turnovers,
including end Neil Smith's 79-yard fumble return for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the season,'' Denver linebacker Bill Romanowski
said, ``it seemed like people were saying, `Well, the defense is
the weakness.' Together in the room last week as a defense, we said
if we lose it, it's not going to be the defense that does it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who took the field had a certain attitude. We were
going to attack them, we were going to hit them, and we were going
to get them off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Romanowski promises a similar effort against the Jets and
quarterback Vinny Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to play physical; we're going to knock the
you-know-what out of anybody who touches that football,''
Romanowski said. ``That's the mentality we have. It was just
awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Added receiver Rod Smith, who had a 28-yard touchdown catch,
``We won't rest until we've got another Super Bowl ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the bad blood between the Broncos and Dolphins, there
wasn't any sympathy for Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them (Dolphins) how it felt to have a Super Bowl at
your house and not be invited,'' Denver tight end Shannon Sharpe
said. ``They didn't take too kindly to that. I also told them to
tell Jimmy (Johnson) to have his office (at the Dolphins' practice
facility) ready because we're going to need to break down film.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
