<DOCNO> NYT19990110.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7263 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VIKINGS-CARDS-HNS     01-10 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-CARDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MINNEAPOLIS _ For an entire regular season, the Minnesota Vikings
fired warning shots at the rest of the NFL in machine-gun fashion.
On Sunday, they took a different approach in sending a red alert to
folks in Atlanta.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quick-striking Vikings? Not this time. The team that set a
single-season scoring record and became notorious for its quick and
painless conquests instead took its sweet time against Arizona,
controlling the ball and, ultimately, the Cardinals with a 41-21
victory at the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The point total again was impressive. But how the Vikings got
there was vastly different from the bombs-away mentality that has
been their calling this season. In this win, Minnesota had three
drives that each knocked more than seven minutes off the clock,
including the opening thrust of the game that used half of the
first quarter. It proved that the Vikings have a little smash-mouth
to go with their Showtime reputation as an explosive offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only know one way, and that's to try to put the pedal to
the metal,'' said running back Robert Smith, who had 124 yards on
the ground and combined with Leroy Hoard to make life miserable for
the Cardinals. ``But today, we ran the ball better than we have in
a long time. And that was a big key in this win.''
</P>
<P>
   One of many. With the Cardinals intent on slowing the Vikings'
vaunted receiving threats, the running game was opened up.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota took what the defense allowed it, and as a result the
Vikings will try to get back to the Super Bowl for the first time
since 1976 when they host the Atlanta Falcons next Sunday in the
NFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, any fans holding out hope that the Dallas
Cowboys actually were a great team this year and just got beat by a
charmed-life bunch of Cardinals could forget it.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals simply got outclassed. Minnesota had more players
who made more plays. And it started in the trenches, where the
Vikings are very good but receive little recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I've been here (six years), we've never had a
better performance by our offensive line,'' said Vikings offensive
coordinator Brian Billick. ``Not in any game, much less a playoff
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Billick, the architect of the Vikings' scoring machine, got no
argument from his adversary, Arizona defensive coordinator Dave
McGinnis.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got great athletes on their offensive line who are
big,'' McGinnis said. ``That's exactly what you look for in a line.
We couldn't get them into any third-and-long situations. And any
time it's third-and-short, it's hard to stop an average team, much
less a very good team like this one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings left no doubt they are a very good team. They
approached their playoff opener with some trepidation. After a 15-1
regular season and a bye week while the Cardinals beat the Cowboys
20-7 in the wild-card round, the Vikes weren't exactly sure what to
expect from themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long to get the answer. They took the opening
drive and stuffed it down Arizona's throat, going 80 yards in 13
plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first drive was really crucial,'' said Vikings safety
Robert Griffith. ``When our offense takes more than seven minutes
off the clock, and we (the defenders) get that much rest, it's a
big advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Minnesota coach Dennis Green: ``If you look around the
NFL, the teams that can run the ball usually win. The teams that
can play good run defense normally win, too. Running the ball in
crucial situations _ we did it. And we prevented them from doing
it. So that was a key part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, who came into the game as 16-point underdogs,
knew they had to keep Vikings receivers Randy Moss and Cris Carter
under wraps to have a chance of pulling off an upset. They
succeeded at times. But with their attention affixed on the
wideouts, Smith and Hoard had easy pickings busting through the gut
of the Arizona defense.
</P>
<P>
   Hoard had three touchdowns _ two rushing and one on a 16-yard
pass from Randall Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   With the running game working so well, Cunningham didn't have to
force the aerial attack. He was an efficient 17-for-27 for 236
yards. The longest of his three touchdown throws was 16 yards to
Hoard, who put the Cards in a 24-7 hole just 24 seconds before
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The first half was nearly flawless for the Vikings. In the first
quarter alone, they ate up 14:06 of the clock with two long drives.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of them resulted in points; the second was aborted when
Cunningham was intercepted by Aeneas Williams in the end zone.
Cunningham was trying to hit Moss on a slant pattern, but Williams
outpositioned Moss and returned the pick to the Cardinals' 46.
</P>
<P>
   That outburst was the only thing the Cardinals did right in the
early going. And it merely delayed the onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Arizona tried to flex a little muscle and heart by
drawing within 34-21 early in the fourth quarter, the Vikings
responded by keeping the ball for 7:12 on the ensuing drive,
effectively suffocating the Cardinals' last gasp with a six-yard TD
run by Hoard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed they were able to run the ball as well as
they were, because I think that's where your defense has to start
every game you're going to play,'' said Arizona coach Vince Tobin.
``No matter how good of skilled receivers people have, you have to
stop the run, because that's going to dominate the line of
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when we were making some scores and getting back into the
game, they were able to run the football. And we tried everything
that we had in our defensive arsenal. None of it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving the Atlanta Falcons another thing to worry about in the
NFC Championship Game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-10-99 2347EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990110.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7264 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-HNS &LR;      01-10 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ It may be too soon to label it a changing of the guard,
but Atlanta's divisional-playoff victory over San Francisco on
Saturday ensured the NFC will have some new blood in the Super
Bowl.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dallas and Green Bay were eliminated over the wild-card weekend.
Since Washington represented the NFC after the 1991 season, either
the Cowboys, Packers or 49ers reached the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell by this locker room that there's somewhat of a
train-wrecked feeling,'' 49ers quarterback Steve Young said. ``I
don't think there's anyone in here that didn't think we were going
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta knows San Francisco's rsum well, having played perennial
division doormat for the 49ers to trample over. But Saturday's
20-18 Atlanta win soothed 32 years of frustration, sending the
Falcons to the NFC Championship Game for the first time in
franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beating the team that has been the bane of our existence is
just incredible,'' Falcons defensive end Lester Archambeau said.
``I think it's fitting that the road to the championship game had
to go through San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only two years ago that coach Dan Reeves entered the
picture in Atlanta to take the reins of a 3-13 team. And like the
corporate raider who guts dying companies and then rebuilds them,
Reeves eliminated the dead weight and restructured from the core
out.
</P>
<P>
   The results have come more quickly than even he imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dreamed about it a lot, but we were not sure it was a
reachable goal,'' quarterback Chris Chandler said of getting this
far. ``It's been a season of modifying goals all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game was only the third playoff victory in Falcons
history. They had reached the playoffs only five times previously
and hadn't won a postseason game since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the old Atlanta. Under Reeves, the Falcons have a
10-game winning streak and a 15-2 mark this season. They are 21-4
since the midway point of last season, when the turnaround began,
and 22-11 overall with Reeves at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fun is just starting around here,'' tight end O.J.
Santiago said. ``When you're 14-2, you expect to win the first
playoff game. The real test will come next week.''
</P>
<P>
   The test will come in Minnesota against the Vikings, who became
only the third team in NFL history to go 15-1 in the regular
season. The other two, the 1984 49ers and 1985 Chicago Bears, both
won the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Each playoff game this season has come down to which team runs
the ball more effectively, which should give Atlanta a solid chance
against Minnesota's high-powered offense. The Falcons have the No.
2 run defense in the league and held the 49ers' No. 1-ranked
offense to only 46 yards rushing, an impressive feat even though
Garrison Hearst was in for only one play before breaking his
fibula.
</P>
<P>
   With Jamal Anderson starring in their ground attack, the Falcons
managed 136 yards rushing Saturday. Anderson, who finished second
in the league in rushing to Denver's Terrell Davis this year, had
his 13th 100-yard game of the season, netting 113 yards and
Atlanta's only two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never get enough of this feeling,'' said Atlanta
linebacker Cornelius Bennett, who played in four Super Bowls with
Buffalo. ``You look at the other teams that are at home. Those guys
would give their whole salary to be where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   If they don't go any further, it would still go down as an
amazing season for the Falcons and a huge building block for the
future. But there's only one future the Falcons are pondering right
now, and it would culminate Jan. 31 in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a remarkable turnaround for this team,'' running back
Gary Downs said. ``This team has been building for two years. We
learned how to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
