<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-10 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7265 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-COLUMN-HN     01-10 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DENVER _ Pick a play, any play.
</P>
<P>
   There is Terrell Davis gathering in the ball on a toss to the
right side from John Elway, and then the fun starts. He takes a
lightning-quick stutter-step in one direction, and suddenly the
Miami defense is skidding out of control like 11 cars with bald
tires trying to stop on a patch of ice.
</P>
<P>
   Davis sees an opening and moves to it. Never mind the Dolphins.
On this afternoon, the sea life that comes to mind is an eel, as
Davis slithers quickly through the crack. Safety Calvin Jackson
grabs nothing but air, then one last juke and cornerback Sam
Madison is so faked out that you half expect the rest of his body
to tear loose from his ankles, and Davis finishes up his 20-yard
sprint in the end zone, giving the fans the Mile High salute.
</P>
<P>
   There is Rod Smith, the quieter contrast to Shannon Sharpe's
constantly moving mouth, running under key passes thrown by Elway.
This one is also in the first quarter, and it's an out pattern to
the left side of the field, a frozen rope but just slightly short
of its mark.
</P>
<P>
   Smith sees the ball and comes back to it. Or more accurately, he
launches himself straight up into the air and seems to hover above
the spot like one of those traffic helicopters over a freeway.
Madison, the tough corner, almost runs straight through him. But
Smith simply bends his body in half, drapes over Madison's left
shoulder and hauls in the catch for a 15-yard gain and a first
down.
</P>
<P>
   There is Neil Smith bending over and picking up a ball fumbled
by Dolphin Oronde Gadsden at the Miami 21-yard line, turning,
pausing and seeming to think to himself: I have to run that far?
</P>
<P>
   So he did. Though calling it running would be an inaccuracy for
every living member of the animal kingdom this side of the
hippopotamus family. Smith lumbered and he labored and he struggled
and he staggered. He seemed to stop for a lunch break near the
Miami 30, then finally left equally slow Dolphins center Tim Ruddy
in the thin air and completed his 79-yard Marco Polo overland
journey for the outrageous cap on Denver's 38-3 flogging of the
Dolphins on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The point isn't that Denver held a mile-high fish fry or that
Miami traveled to the Rockies and played like a collection of
sea-level sissies. This was, as coach Jimmy Johnson admitted
afterward, a Dolphins team that was beat up and bruised and entered
the game with a tank that was already empty from its wild-card
struggle a week earlier with Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   What's important is that after losing their bid for an unbeaten
season and going through what has become their now-customary
December swoon, the Broncos are back and clearly the team to beat
for the Super Bowl XXXIII title.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind Vinny and the Jets or any of that Big Tuna mystique.
Forget about the air raids by the Vikings' Randall Cunningham and
Randy Moss or the ground game of Atlanta's Jamal Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   When the Broncos are on top of their game, they are like a trip
to the circus. There is always something incredible going on, and
nobody can keep up with the action in all three rings and the
overhead trapeze, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos are 10-2 in home playoff games and never have lost
in three previous AFC Championship Games played at Mile High.
What's more, after using the week off from the wild-card round to
get themselves rested and get their confidence readjusted, they are
once again looking like a road grader, capable of flattening
everything in sight. They are also on a revenge tour, of sorts.
First, it was getting back at Miami for that Dec. 21 loss. Now,
it's the Jets and their Noo Yawk accents who'll serve as stand-ins
for the perfection-breaking Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Elway took the Broncos on touchdown drives on each of their
first three possessions of Saturday's game and quickly ended any
wild notion the Dolphins might have had of an upset. This was as
complete, as dominant as the Broncos may have looked since Week 2
of the season when they went 5-for-5 on first-half drives and hung
up 35 points on the Dallas Cowboys before the intermission.
</P>
<P>
   John Elway vs. Dan Marino. Dan Marino vs. John Elway. Want to
know who's better? Terrell Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the 2,000-yard rusher and the 1998 Most Valuable Player,
is the one who separates the Broncos from everybody else. He pounds
and he slashes and he makes jaws _ and defenders _ drop and he
gives all of the other parts of the Denver attack a chance to
shine. He also allows the offense to control the ball so much that
Denver's only weak spot _ its secondary _ is never exposed for too
long.
</P>
<P>
   Pick a play, any play.
</P>
<P>
   They are, loose, confident and at home on their own ranch, the
Broncos galloping toward another Super Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
