<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDSKINS-SALE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDSKINS SAID TO BE SOLD FOR $800 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Rewrites 1st 4 grafs.)   (jw) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Washington Redskins and their new stadium were sold Sunday
to a group headed by Howard Milstein, co-owner of the New York
Islanders hockey team, for $800 million, a record price for a
domestic sports franchise, according to two people involved in the
sale.
</P>
<P>
   The sum to be paid to the estate of the late Jack Kent Cooke,
the former owner of the team, by Milstein and his partner, Daniel
Snyder, exceeds the $530 million paid by Al Lerner last August for
the expansion Cleveland Browns football team, the previous record
sales price. The Browns' price tag included a $54 million
contribution toward building the team's new municipally owned
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The price paid for the Redskins reflects the cash flow generated
by Jack Kent Cooke Stadium, which just completed its second season
of operation. Cooke stadium has 15,044 club seats, which cost $995
to $2,500 each annually, and 280 luxury suites that rent for
between $45,000 and $160,000 each per season. The Browns' stadium
will have fewer luxury suites and club seats.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins receive revenue from all tickets sold, parking and
concessions. Their sale will be formally announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Milstein, who bid unsuccessfully for the Browns, will have to
sell all or part of the 45 percent stake in the Islanders that he
owns with his brother, Edward, to comply with the National Football
League's cross-ownership rules.
</P>
<P>
   When he sought to buy the Browns, Milstein said that if he got
the team, he would sell his family's ownership in the Islanders to
the team's co-owner, Steven Gluckstern. He is expected to follow
that course now.
</P>
<P>
   Milstein's family is worth billions of dollars, from New
York-based real estate and banking empires. Snyder owns a
Washington communications firm.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to reflecting the cash flow at Jack Kent Cooke
Stadium, the $800 million purchase price was influenced by the
Browns' sale price, the $700-million-a-year guaranteed to each NFL
team owner from the new television contracts, and the size and
influence of the Washington market, which is nearly one-third
bigger than Cleveland's.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of money produced by a stadium is the economic factor
that divides the richest teams from the rest and makes franchises
leap in value. It was why a successful team like the Minnesota
Vikings, which does not generate huge wealth from the municipally
owned Metrodome, sold for a modest $250 million last year to Red
McCombs.
</P>
<P>
   The Milstein-Snyder group defeated three others, including one
formed by John Kent Cooke, the son of the late owner, that was
described as very strong by the people involved in the sale
process. Other bidders included John McMullen, the owner of the
Devils, and Charles Dolan, chairman of Cablevision Systems and Sam
Grossman, an Arizona shopping center magnate.
</P>
<P>
   By the terms established by the Cooke estate, Milstein and
Snyder are acquiring the team's stock, a transaction that will
funnel the proceeds tax free to a charitable foundation set up by
the estate.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns' sale, by comparison, was an asset purchase. The
Redskin process, compared with that of the Browns, was quiet. The
estate imposed severe confidentiality restrictions, rules that were
stern enough so that bidders like McMullen and Dolan denied they
were bidding.
</P>
<P>
   With the Browns, the league controlled the process, inviting the
bidders to meetings covered by the news media.
</P>
<P>
   League approval of Milstein and Snyder should take 60 to 90
days, but the time span could be shorter because NFL owners are
already familiar with Milstein. It is not known whether that time
frame will preserve the job of Redskins coach Norv Turner, whose
team went 6-10 last season. Had John Kent Cooke acquired the team,
Turner's future was believed to be more secure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
